 \\l "toc96"}}{\fldrslt{\fs20\cf2\par\bullet\tab \uc2  Who's who of authors will grace book festival}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK \\l "toc97"}}{\fldrslt{\fs20\cf2\par\bullet\tab \uc2  Obama renews call for Dream Act OK}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK \\l "toc98"}}{\fldrslt{\fs20\cf2\par\bullet\tab \uc2  Captured crossers returning less often}}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK \\l "toc99"}}{\fldrslt{\fs20\cf2\par\bullet\tab \uc2  Once welcoming, borderlands now forever divided}}}\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc0}{\*\bkmkend toc0}\b \uc2 Fear of \u8216\'20\'18criminal aliens\u8217\'20\'19 rhetoric again moves to forefront of Trump campaign\b0\par\par\uc2 3,486 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 November 2020\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A01\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2020 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 As Nov. 3 nears, President Trump is reprising 2016 rhetorical strategy of hyping migrant dangers\par \par \uc2 As Election Day nears and polls suggest he\u8217\'20\'19ll lose the presidency, \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  has started hammering \u8220\'20\'1Ccriminal aliens\u8221\'20\'1D again.\par \par \uc2 For Trump, it\u8217\'20\'19s a return to form. When he rode down that golden escalator on June 16, 2015, to announce his run for president, he knew how he would separate himself from the 16 other Republican candidates.\par \par \uc2 He would go hardcore on immigration, talking tougher and more crudely about migrants and the border than any other candidate. He did it that day, setting a pattern for his presidency.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThey\u8217\'20\'19re bringing drugs,\u8221\'20\'1D Trump said of undocumented migrants that day, in his infamous refrain. \u8220\'20\'1CThey\u8217\'20\'19re bringing crime. They\u8217\'20\'19re rapists. And some, I assume, are good people.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 To justify his harsh border and immigration policies, Trump and allies repeatedly associated immigrants, especially undocumented ones, with crime. He would pound that linkage home until his policies seemed necessary to keep Americans safe.\par \par \uc2 Migrants and crime, crime and migrants.\par \par \uc2 Trump mostly laid off that tactic in this year\u8217\'20\'19s campaign, preferring to highlight American rioters as a threat, but he has suddenly begun raising the specter of foreign criminals again.\par \par \uc2 Late Friday night, Trump issued a proclamation declaring Sunday, Nov. 1, a \u8220\'20\'1CNational Day of Remembrance for Americans Killed by Illegal Aliens.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The problem is, the association he\u8217\'20\'19s making is not born out by research. The presence of foreign-born, and even specifically of undocumented, people is not associated with higher crime rates in the United States.\par \par \uc2 Some studies even show that the more immigrants in a given area, including undocumented ones, the lower the crime rates.\par \par \uc2 But of course, some foreign-born people do commit crimes, and Trump has used those cases. He made an argument that was not based in statistical probabilities but on alarming anecdotes.\par \par \uc2 To understand why, go back to the 2015-2016 Republican race. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s team knew the appeal would work with a significant part of the Republican primary electorate, who were angry about the mealy-mouthed ways that candidates like \uc2 Marco Rubio\uc2  and Jeb Bush were talking about immigration.\par \par \uc2 One of Trump\u8217\'20\'19s top advisers early in the campaign, \uc2 Sam Nunberg\uc2 , told me Trump tried to contrast his views with the \u8220\'20\'1Cchamber of commerce\u8221\'20\'1D idea that even migrants illegally in the country are good and a net benefit.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAll we hear is people saying, \u8216\'20\'18These are good people. They\u8217\'20\'19re here for a good life. They want to do jobs others don\u8217\'20\'19t do.\u8217\'20\'19 And we wanted to say, \u8216\'20\'18Oh, yeah? What about the other ones?\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D Nunberg said.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CYou want to go into generalities, well what about these specifics? What about this murderer? What about this rapist? What about this drug dealer?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Bolstering their point, a killing occurred just two weeks after Trump\u8217\'20\'19s announcement that featured all the fears Trump raised. A Mexican man \u8212\'20\'14 in the country illegally after having been deported and rearrested in a sanctuary city, San Francisco \u8212\'20\'14 was accused of shooting and killing a young white American woman, \uc2 Kate Steinle\uc2 . The crime, of which the migrant was acquitted in 2017, became a flashpoint.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThis senseless and totally preventable act of violence committed by an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  is yet another example of why we must secure our border immediately,\u8221\'20\'1D Trump said in a statement days after Steinle\u8217\'20\'19s death. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is an absolutely disgraceful situation, and I am the only one that can fix it.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \{\{tncms-asset app="editorial" id="c2825f88-1ae4-11eb-82d1-00163ec2aa77"\}\}\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAngel Families\u8221\'20\'1D take center stage\par \par \uc2 Much of the Republican electorate was thrilled by Trump\u8217\'20\'19s promise. That showed as he rolled through state after state in the 2016 primary elections.\par \par \uc2 The rest of the country, though, was not as receptive. Just as there is a persistent strain of anti-immigrant sentiment in America that rises and falls with the times, there is a persistent strand of pro-immigrant sentiment.\par \par \uc2 Then the so-called Angel Families entered the political scene. These were the parents and relatives of people killed by people in the country illegally. They heard Trump\u8217\'20\'19s message, and they reached out.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThey contacted the campaign organically,\u8221\'20\'1D Nunberg said.\par \par \uc2 The alliance that resulted between Trump and those victimized by \u8220\'20\'1Ccriminal aliens\u8221\'20\'1D colored the rest of his campaign and much of his presidency.\par \par \uc2 He upheld the stories of people like Steinle and family members like Mary Ann Mendoza as what results when you don\u8217\'20\'19t impose strict policies on the border and on immigration generally.\par \par \uc2 \{\{tncms-asset app="editorial" id="339f3704-1ae5-11eb-830a-00163ec2aa77"\}\}\par \par \uc2 At the Republican National Convention in 2016, Trump introduced the country to victims\u8217\'20\'19 parents, like Mendoza.\par \par \uc2 Her son, Brandon Mendoza, was a Mesa police officer. In 2014, a man in the country illegally, Raul Silva Corona, was drunk and high when he sped recklessly for a half-hour around Phoenix-area highways, finally striking Mendoza\u8217\'20\'19s vehicle head-on. Both of them died.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CMy son\u8217\'20\'19s life was stolen at the hands of an illegal alien,\u8221\'20\'1D Mary Ann Mendoza said at the convention. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s time we have an administration that cares more about Americans than about illegals. A vote for Hillary (Clinton) is putting all of our children\u8217\'20\'19s lives at risk.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Anecdotes, not data\par \par \uc2 In rhetoric, there\u8217\'20\'19s a name for the sort of argument Trump was making through these examples. \u8220\'20\'1Csynecdoche\u8221\'20\'1D (pronounced \u8220\'20\'1Csuh-NEK-duh-kee\u8221\'20\'1D) means \u8220\'20\'1Cthe part that stands for the whole.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Jennifer Mercieca, a professor of communication at Texas A&M University, told me about that and other rhetorical strategies Trump used in interviews in late 2019 and early 2020. Since then, she has published a book called \u8220\'20\'1CDemagogue for President: The Rhetorical Genius of \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 This was one of his more effective, ingenious campaign communication strategies, she said.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe reason for that is that at first he made a very general claim \u8212\'20\'14 \u8216\'20\'18They\u8217\'20\'19re all rapists, they\u8217\'20\'19re all drug dealers and some I assume are good people,\u8217\'20\'19 \u8221\'20\'1D Mercieca said. \u8220\'20\'1CThen he started using examples from testimonials from the affected families.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CA synecdoche is really powerful. It\u8217\'20\'19s a representative anecdote. You can mislead an audience by making it seem like the anecdote is more representative than it really is,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1CHe\u8217\'20\'19ll provide you with three or four examples, so it seems like an accumulation of evidence.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 That, she said, allowed Trump \u8220\'20\'1Cto paper over the differences between what the data show and what the examples show. It\u8217\'20\'19s not that the stories weren\u8217\'20\'19t true. The stories were true, but they weren\u8217\'20\'19t representative.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The Trump White House saw the power of those stories, asking the Border Patrol sectors to provide them and the \uc2 Department of Homeland Security\uc2  to publicize them.\par \par \uc2 David Lapan, the first DHS spokesman under Trump, told me presidential adviser \uc2 Stephen Miller\uc2  wanted Lapan to spotlight crimes by immigrants.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI was in a meeting with him where he said, \u8216\'20\'18We need to get more stories out about immigrants harming Americans, killing people,\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D said Lapan, who was in the job for the first seven months of Trump\u8217\'20\'19s term. \u8220\'20\'1C\u8216\'20\'18We need more stories to highlight the criminal activities of immigrants.\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe came out of the meeting with \uc2 Stephen Miller\uc2  and said, \u8216\'20\'18We aren\u8217\'20\'19t going to do that.\u8217\'20\'19 It wasn\u8217\'20\'19t our role to cherry-pick stories to highlight.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Research undermines crime claims\par \par \uc2 The foreign-born population, whether in the country legally or illegally, does not have a greater propensity for crime, numerous studies have shown.\par \par \uc2 In fact, research published in 2018 reviewed 51 studies of the linkage between immigration and crime published from 1994 to 2014 and found a very weak negative association. In other words, the presence of immigrants in any given area is weakly associated with less crime, not more.\par \par \uc2 The researchers doing these studies note they\u8217\'20\'19re talking about correlation, not causation. In other words, they can\u8217\'20\'19t say the presence of more foreign-born people causes less crime \u8212\'20\'14 just that their presence at greater degrees is not associated with more crime.\par \par \uc2 The most recent research, published Oct. 3 in the Journal of Crime and Justice, zeroed in on the relationship between undocumented residents specifically, not just the foreign-born generally, and crime in metro areas. It came up with the same result: More undocumented people in a metro area means the same amount of or even less crime.\par \par \uc2 Robert Adelman, the chair of the sociology department at the University at Buffalo, led that study as well as another one, published in 2017, that analyzed the effect of the presence of foreign-born people on crime rates over decades.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s pretty clear from the data that with both the foreign-born population and, in the latest study, the undocumented population, we don\u8217\'20\'19t find an effect on violent crime rates,\u8221\'20\'1D Adelman told me Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 With respect to property crime, they found a weak negative effect \u8212\'20\'14 in other words, more undocumented people in a given area was mildly associated with less property crime.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19re not saying immigrants or undocumented immigrants don\u8217\'20\'19t commit crimes. That\u8217\'20\'19s not what the study is about,\u8221\'20\'1D Adelman said. \u8220\'20\'1CPeople from all groups commit crimes, including undocumented immigrants.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Pima County Sheriff Mark Napier said sheriffs in other parts of the country assume the jail in this border county must be filled with people in the country illegally, but that\u8217\'20\'19s not true.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt usually runs about 5% to 6% of the population of the Pima County jail at any given time (that) is comprised of people that are undocumented,\u8221\'20\'1D Napier said.\par \par \uc2 \{\{tncms-asset app="editorial" id="2cbfbcfe-1ae7-11eb-bd95-00163ec2aa77"\}\}\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAbout 3% of the population of the jail at any given time are subject to ICE detainers,\u8221\'20\'1D he said, meaning \uc2 Immigration and Customs Enforcement\uc2  has identified them as subject to removal.\par \par \uc2 The probabilities, of course, are no solace to those who are victimized. Members of the Angel Families often make the argument that their victimized relative would still be alive if it weren\u8217\'20\'19t for insecure borders. That\u8217\'20\'19s true, as far as it goes.\par \par \uc2 But the same reasoning applies to almost any crime: It wouldn\u8217\'20\'19t have happened but for the circumstances that allowed the perpetrator to do it. Border insecurity, in that sense, is like drug use or drunk driving or lax gun laws or even parental neglect and abuse. Without them, the criminal wouldn\u8217\'20\'19t have done what he did.\par \par \uc2 Trump turns to gangs\par \par \uc2 Trump\u8217\'20\'19s initial focus on Angel Families gradually transitioned into a fixation on the idea that members of criminal gangs, especially Mara Salvatrucha, or MS-13, were embedding themselves with asylum seekers from Central America.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CMany Gang Members and some very bad people are mixed into the Caravan heading to our Southern Border,\u8221\'20\'1D he tweeted on Oct. 29, 2018.\par \par \uc2 There\u8217\'20\'19s much to unpack in Trump\u8217\'20\'19s claims. For example, there are the facts that MS-13 is a U.S.-born gang exported to El Salvador from California, and that it never had been a significant player in transnational crime, contrary to what Trump claimed.\par \par \uc2 But perhaps the most important aspect of his focus on MS-13 was that it justified building border barriers and clamping down on asylum seekers at the Mexican border.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19re here today to discuss the menace of MS-13,\u8221\'20\'1D Trump said May 23, 2018, at an event on Long Island, N.Y., where he introduced parents of children killed by the gang. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s a menace. A ruthless gang that has violated our borders and transformed once-peaceful neighborhoods into bloodstained killing fields.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Twice in 2018, caravans of asylum seekers began walking toward the United States from Central America, which renewed Trump\u8217\'20\'19s use of the rhetoric of migrants as criminals.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe needed the plot points to move the narrative along,\u8221\'20\'1D Mercieca said. \u8220\'20\'1CThe caravan provided him with an opportunity to talk about this as an imminent threat in 2018. \u8216\'20\'18These caravans full of people are attacking the nation.\u8217\'20\'19 That was really helpful.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 His rhetoric suggested gang members were pouring across the border in the caravans, claiming asylum, but that was hyperbole.\par \par \uc2 In the last six years, 2019 was when U.S. Border Patrol agents caught the most people they labeled as gang members: 976. That was one-tenth of 1% of the total number of people the Border Patrol apprehended that year, 859,501.\par \par \uc2 In other words, in the worst recent year, only 1 out of 1,000 Border Patrol apprehensions was, by the agency\u8217\'20\'19s designation, a gang member.\par \par \uc2 After Trump took office, Customs and Border Protection began announcing the arrest of gang members much more regularly. In fiscal year 2018, the Border Patrol arrested 5% fewer gang members than it had in 2015, but CBP put out five times as many press releases announcing in their titles the arrests of \u8220\'20\'1Cgang\u8221\'20\'1D or \u8220\'20\'1CMS-13\u8221\'20\'1D members.\par \par \uc2 \{\{tncms-asset app="editorial" id="b16d3bc0-1ae7-11eb-b556-00163ec2aa77"\}\}\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s probably not a coincidence that 2018 was also the year President Trump focused his rhetoric most sharply on gang members crossing the Mexican border. That year, he tweeted 22 times about gangs, or MS-13 in particular, as compared to 14 times in 2017, eight times in 2019 and zero times so far in 2020.\par \par \uc2 Victims of immigrants\par \par \uc2 As Trump and his allies have pushed to link migrants with crime, he has received steady pushback and mixed results on that narrow issue.\par \par \uc2 But the rhetoric has helped him justify and enact broader immigration changes, such as forcing asylum seekers to remain in Mexico while awaiting their asylum cases; separating migrant parents from children; slashing refugee admissions; and, of course, building border wall.\par \par \uc2 Through a variety of maneuvers, he has also succeeded at cutting annual legal immigration levels from about 1 million in 2015-2016 to about 600,000 in 2018-2019.\par \par \uc2 As one of his first acts, on Jan. 25 2017, Trump issued an executive order that included a crackdown on sanctuary cities and the establishment of an office serving the victims of crimes committed by \u8220\'20\'1Cremovable aliens.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It was named the Victims of Immigration Crime Engagement (VOICE) office and served dual purposes. One was the defensible aim of providing information to victims of crimes by undocumented people about the perpetrator\u8217\'20\'19s status in the immigration system. The other was to make that familiar rhetorical linkage: immigration and crime, crime and immigration.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe rationale that made sense of it to me was, because the immigration system wasn\u8217\'20\'19t the same as the criminal justice system, having a way for victims\u8217\'20\'19 families to be kept apprised of what was happening,\u8221\'20\'1D said Lapan, the former Homeland Security spokesman.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1COn the flip side, what I wasn\u8217\'20\'19t comfortable with was elevating this to make it seem like immigrants were committing crimes above the levels of nonimmigrants, which we know is not the case.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Democrats pushed back on the establishment of the VOICE office, but it has persisted quietly, not posting a report on its activities since the first quarter of fiscal 2019.\par \par \uc2 They had more luck with Trump\u8217\'20\'19s efforts against sanctuary cities, from which the same 2017 executive order aimed to withhold federal grants. Cities targeted by the measure sued and have so far won their cases in federal appeals courts, blocking Trump from withholding money.\par \par \uc2 Iowa murder\u8217\'20\'19s aftershocks\par \par \uc2 In the middle of Trump\u8217\'20\'19s busiest year of linking migrants to crime, July 2018, 20-year-old Mollie Tibbetts disappeared while jogging near her small Iowa hometown.\par \par \uc2 A month later, police arrested a young Mexican man, illegally in the country and working at a nearby farm. Prosecutors charged him with Tibbetts\u8217\'20\'19 murder.\par \par \uc2 \{\{tncms-asset app="editorial" id="2cb27f2a-1ae8-11eb-8b7d-00163ec2aa77"\}\}\par \par \uc2 The outcry was immediate and predictable. Trump blamed her death on Democrats, a \u8220\'20\'1Cparty that puts criminal aliens before American citizens.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhat happened to Mollie was a disgrace,\u8221\'20\'1D Trump said. \u8220\'20\'1CWe mourn for Mollie\u8217\'20\'19s family.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 But Mollie\u8217\'20\'19s family wasn\u8217\'20\'19t having any of it. In an op-ed, her father decried those who were trying to use her as a \u8220\'20\'1Cpawn\u8221\'20\'1D in promoting a \u8220\'20\'1Cracist\u8221\'20\'1D agenda.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe person who is accused of taking Mollie\u8217\'20\'19s life is no more a reflection of the Hispanic community as white supremacists are of all white people,\u8221\'20\'1D Rob Tibbetts wrote.\par \par \uc2 Her mother, who was separated from Mollie\u8217\'20\'19s father, went further. Authorities had raided the farm where the accused killer lived and worked, and other Mexican farmworking families living there had fled. Mollie Tibbetts\u8217\'20\'19 mother, Laura Calderwood, took in the son of one of those families, a 17-year-old who wanted to stay and graduate from high school in the town that was his home.\par \par \uc2 It was part of a persistent pushback in society toward Trump\u8217\'20\'19s immigration and border policies.\par \par \uc2 The breadth of that point of view became evident this year in a Gallup survey about immigration, which has been asking Americans the same questions since 1965.\par \par \uc2 During Trump\u8217\'20\'19s presidency, public opinion of immigrants has been improving. In June, for the first time in the history of that poll, more Americans said they think the number of immigrants to the United States should increase than said it should decrease, by 34% to 28%.\par \par \uc2 One more time with migrant crime\par \par \uc2 Trump\u8217\'20\'19s focus on \u8220\'20\'1Ccriminal aliens\u8221\'20\'1D waned somewhat after 2018. This year, he\u8217\'20\'19s stopped tweeting about migrant gang members, and instead of attacking sanctuary cities for their immigration policies, he found another angle.\par \par \uc2 The new big threat Trump cites is antifa. After the unrest over police violence this summer, Trump designated New York City, Portland and Seattle as anarchist cities and threatened to remove funding for this new reason.\par \par \uc2 The Wall Street Journal reported immigration dropped far down the list of issues Trump talks about. Some of Trump\u8217\'20\'19s allies began asking, what happened to immigration?\par \par \uc2 But as the campaign winds down, the siren song of the criminal alien is inevitably drawing Trump and his allies back.\par \par \uc2 Trump said of Democrats, during a rally in Florida on Oct. 23, \u8220\'20\'1CThey want to unleash the violent rioters, criminal aliens, MS-13 killers.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In his new proclamation, he declared that \u8220\'20\'1CAmericans who are killed by illegal aliens are no longer forgotten, and we are ensuring that they will not have died in vain.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 Department of Homeland Security\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s top officials have been crisscrossing the country, brazenly campaigning for the president on the taxpayer dime. The acting commissioner of Customs and Border Protection, Mark Morgan, warned of an \u8220\'20\'1Cillegal invasion\u8221\'20\'1D if \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2  is elected.\par \par \uc2 Immigration and Customs Enforcement\uc2  even put up six billboards showing the mugshots of men along with a criminal charge like \u8220\'20\'1Cburglary\u8221\'20\'1D or \u8220\'20\'1Cassault.\u8221\'20\'1D Each person is labeled a \u8220\'20\'1Ccriminal alien\u8221\'20\'1D and each sign carries the slogan \u8220\'20\'1CSanctuary policies are a REAL DANGER.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The billboards went up, of course, in a state Trump won in 2016 and is struggling to win again this year \u8212\'20\'14 Pennsylvania.\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s one late test of whether the threat of the foreign criminal can still win elections.\par \par \uc2 'Rhetorical genuis' \u8212\'20\'14 How Trump manipulates public opinion\par \par \uc2 Jennifer Mercieca considers President Trump a dangerous demagogue and a rhetorical genius.\par \par \uc2 Mercieca, an associate professor of communication at \uc2 Texas A & M University\uc2 , spelled out Trump\u8217\'20\'19s main communications strategies in her book published this year, \u8220\'20\'1CDemagogue for President: The Rhetorical Genius of \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Here are the main strategies she says Trump uses:\par \par \uc2 Ad populum \u8212\'20\'14 appealing to the wisdom of the crowd against established leadership. Used especially against \u8220\'20\'1Cpolitical correctness\u8221\'20\'1D and the \u8220\'20\'1Celites.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Ad baculum \u8212\'20\'14 threats of force or intimidation. Used especially against the news media.\par \par \uc2 Reification \u173\'00\'AD\u8212\'20\'14 treating people as objects. Used especially against refugees\par \par \uc2 Ad hominem \u8212\'20\'14 attacking the person instead of the argument. Used to trivialize or mock critics.\par \par \uc2 Paralipsis \u8212\'20\'14 \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m not saying it; I\u8217\'20\'19m just saying it.\u8221\'20\'1D Used to spread rumor and innuendo but not take responsibility for it.\par \par \uc2 American exceptionalism \u8212\'20\'14 Promoting the idea of\u160\'00\'A0America\u8217\'20\'19s unique status in the world. Used to evoke nostalgia and nationalism.\par \par \uc2 Immigration manipulation\par \par \uc2 This is the fifth column in an investigative project by Arizona Daily Star opinion columnist Tim Steller about how government actors in the U.S. and other countries try to mold public opinion about immigration and the U.S.-Mexico border. It is funded by a fellowship from the Society of Professional Journalists Foundation. The Star is publishing the columns periodically this year.\par \par \uc2 The previous installments were titled:\u160\'00\'A0 "Mexico does little as thousands flee violence for US border," "Border hysteria misrepresents, hurts border towns," "Border wall, touted as health protection, was useless as COVID-19 surged in region," "US backs Honduran gov\u8217\'20\'19t that migrants blame for their flight," and "Defense of family separation policy is built on lies." They are\u160\'00\'A0 posted with this article on Tucson.com.\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: Arizona Daily Star\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020201101egb100015\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Metro\par {\*\bkmkstart toc1}{\*\bkmkend toc1}\b \uc2 Border Patrol agents set up checkpoint outside migrant aid camp in Arivaca\b0\par\par\uc2 Curt Prendergast \par \uc2 830 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 August 2020\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par B01\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2020 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents set up a checkpoint just outside the No More Deaths camp near Arivaca and are searching vehicles as they leave.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents have surrounded a humanitarian aid camp in Arivaca after entering the property without a warrant on Thursday and arresting an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who sought medical care, aid volunteers said.\par \par \uc2 At least a half-dozen Border Patrol trucks, along with agents on ATVs, are set up outside the camp, according to Paige Corich-Kleim, a volunteer with Tucson-based No More Deaths. The surveillance started around 9 a.m. Thursday and was ongoing as of early Friday afternoon. Agents set up a checkpoint just outside the camp and are searching vehicles as they leave.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19re viewing this as likely retaliatory, based on the documents we released,\u8221\'20\'1D Corich-Kleim said.\par \par \uc2 \{\{tncms-asset app="editorial" id="129024f0-d36f-11ea-9236-00163ec2aa77"\}\}\par \par \uc2 Emails released\par \par \uc2 On Wednesday, No More Deaths released a pair of emails they obtained through a Freedom of Information Act request that showed agents discussing a similar incident in June 2017 at the same camp in Arivaca.\par \par \uc2 In June 2017, agents said they tracked four sets of footprints for 18 miles until they led into the camp, which is on private property. Agents waited for two days outside the camp, but could not get consent to enter the property. They then obtained a search warrant, entered the property and arrested four men suspected of crossing the border illegally.\par \par \uc2 In one email released Wednesday, an agent who No More Deaths volunteers believe is a high-ranking member of the Border Patrol agents union, asked the head of Customs and Border Protection to end \u8220\'20\'1Cdiplomacy\u8221\'20\'1D with No More Deaths during the June 2017 raid.\par \par \uc2 The second email indicated two agents with the Border Patrol\u8217\'20\'19s tactical unit, known as BORTAC, \u8220\'20\'1Chelped out in an advisory capacity\u8221\'20\'1D to \u8220\'20\'1Chit the No More Deaths/No Mas Muertes camp\u8221\'20\'1D in June 2017. That unit has come under increased scrutiny after they clashed with protesters in Portland, Oregon, in recent days.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol\u8217\'20\'19s Tucson Sector has released few details about the ongoing incident in Arivaca.\par \par \uc2 \{\{tncms-asset app="editorial" id="3741bcaa-d36f-11ea-8570-00163ec2aa77"\}\}\par \par \uc2 Roy Villareal, chief patrol agent for the Tucson Sector, said in a Friday afternoon tweet that agents \u8220\'20\'1Cdetected a group of suspected border crossers moving north from the international border southeast of Arivaca\u8221\'20\'1D on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAgents followed tracks from the group to a camp operated by No More Deaths,\u8221\'20\'1D Villareal said. \u8220\'20\'1CWithin minutes, agents encountered one illegal border crosser just outside the perimeter of the camp.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 A Border Patrol EMT evaluated her and the Arivaca Fire Department took her to a local hospital for medical treatment, Villareal said, adding the health and safety of agents, border crossers, and humanitarians is always \u8220\'20\'1Cparamount.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CLaw enforcement operations occur in the area around the No More Deaths camp regularly as this is a key smuggling route for both undocumented migrants and drug traffickers,\u8221\'20\'1D Villareal said.\par \par \uc2 He did not address the ongoing surveillance of the camp. The public affairs office did not respond to a follow-up inquiry .\par \par \uc2 Camp aids migrants\par \par \uc2 The camp was set up more than a decade ago to help migrants recover from exposure to high temperatures, dehydration, blistered feet and other maladies common to trekking through the desert. A recreational vehicle serves as the office, solar panels power a refrigerator, and a couple dozen beds, some of which are supported by green milk crates, are tucked inside large tents.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol\u8217\'20\'19s position has been that the camp encourages illegal border crossings and smuggling.\par \par \uc2 \{\{tncms-asset app="editorial" id="4665f106-d36f-11ea-953e-00163ec2aa77"\}\}\par \par \uc2 The timing of agents targeting a No More Deaths aid station so soon after the group released documents critical of the Border Patrol is reminiscent of the January 2018 arrest of No More Deaths volunteer Scott Warren and two Central American men at an aid station in Ajo.\par \par \uc2 Those arrests came hours after No More Deaths released video showing Border Patrol agents destroying water bottles left for migrants in the desert. Warren was charged with human smuggling, but he was acquitted in November after a high-profile trial at Tucson\u8217\'20\'19s federal court.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThis seems like blatant intimidation, from what I\u8217\'20\'19ve heard,\u8221\'20\'1D said Francisco Cant\u250\'00\'FA, a former Border Patrol agent who worked at various posts in the Tucson Sector and El Paso from 2008 to 2012.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents generally have \u8220\'20\'1Cdismal training\u8221\'20\'1D in investigative methods, including how to conduct a search of a property, Cant\u250\'00\'FA said.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIf you can\u8217\'20\'19t get a warrant, it doesn\u8217\'20\'19t mean you can keep riding around a property on ATVs,\u8221\'20\'1D Cant\u250\'00\'FA said.\par \par \uc2 The ongoing incident in Arivaca was \u8220\'20\'1Ckind of predictable,\u8221\'20\'1D Cant\u250\'00\'FA said. He had been \u8220\'20\'1Cwondering when the other shoe was going to drop\u8221\'20\'1D after Warren was acquitted.\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: By Curt Prendergast Arizona Daily Star\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020200801eg810000b\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Metro\par {\*\bkmkstart toc2}{\*\bkmkend toc2}\b \uc2 Arizona leaders lookto Congress to take up DACA legislation, provide some certainty\b0\par\par\uc2 Howard Fischer \par \uc2 715 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 June 2020\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par B01\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2020 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Some have linked a permanent solution for DACA recipients to border security issues.\par \par \uc2 PHOENIX \u8212\'20\'14 The 5-4 decision by the \uc2 U.S. Supreme Court\uc2  to let young immigrants remain in this country \u8212\'20\'14 at least for the time being \u8212\'20\'14 got one bit of largely universal response in Arizona: Congress needs to do something.\par \par \uc2 Both those who agreed with the decision to keep the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program in place and those who did not acknowledged it is far from a permanent solution. But the question of what to do now \u8212\'20\'14 there are about 24,120 \u8220\'20\'1Cdreamers\u8221\'20\'1D in Arizona \u8212\'20\'14 is less than clear.\par \par \uc2 Gov. Doug Ducey\uc2  would not weigh in on whether the justices got it right.\par \par \uc2 But Ducey, a Republican, said this isn\u8217\'20\'19t the end of the issue.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHe continues to believe that Congress needs to do its job to address this issue and ensure DACA kids do not have the rug pulled out from under them,\u8221\'20\'1D said press aide Patrick Ptak.\par \par \uc2 In previous remarks, however, Ducey has put some conditions on all of that, saying a deal would require a compromise.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI think it\u8217\'20\'19s an opportunity for border security and immigration reform,\u8221\'20\'1D the governor said in 2019, saying he wanted to \u8220\'20\'1Cstart with border security.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe governor\u8217\'20\'19s position has not changed,\u8221\'20\'1D Ptak said Thursday.\par \par \uc2 Martha McSally\uc2 , the state\u8217\'20\'19s Republican senator, expressed a similar viewpoint in a \uc2 Twitter\uc2  post.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CToday\u8217\'20\'19s DACA ruling gives the White House and Congress the opportunity to do what is right and solve this issue with thoughtful legislation,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 But that, McSally acknowledged, involves more than simply providing legal status for the \u8220\'20\'1Cdreamers.\u8221\'20\'1D She said any package also means \u8220\'20\'1Cenhancing border security, closing loopholes in our laws, and modernizing our legal immigration system.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In some ways, her position is little different than that of Kyrsten Sinema, Arizona\u8217\'20\'19s Democratic senator.\par \par \uc2 In her own post, she said she is looking to find a \u8220\'20\'1Cbipartisan, common-sense solution to permanently protect dreamers, fix our broken immigration system, and secure our border to keep Arizona communities safe and secure.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 By contrast, Democratic U.S. Rep. Raul Grijalva said he wants the Senate to approve the Dream and Promise Act that already has cleared the House. It would provide \u8220\'20\'1Cconditional permanent resident\u8221\'20\'1D status for up to 10 years for DACA recipients, with a possible path to becoming lawful permanent residents if they meet certain conditions .\par \par \uc2 Fellow Democrat Ann Kirkpatrick issued a statement telling dreamers \u8220\'20\'1CI stand with you, and I promise to keep fighting for you.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Republican Congressman Andy Biggs had a different take, saying he was \u8220\'20\'1Cextremely disappointed\u8221\'20\'1D not only in the decision but with Chief Justice \uc2 John Roberts\uc2  \u8220\'20\'1Cfor continuing to side with our liberal justices and against the rule of law.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1COur nation is a nation of laws, and those laws must be upheld in order to maintain order throughout our union,\u8221\'20\'1D Biggs said in a prepared statement. \u8220\'20\'1CDACA obliterates that order and serves to incentivize more \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  to cross into our nation with hopes of receiving some reprieve from the federal government.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Biggs is not alone in that sentiment. The ruling did not go the way that Attorney General \uc2 Mark Brnovich\uc2 , also a Republican, had hoped.\par \par \uc2 He contended that President \uc2 Obama\uc2  never had the legal authority to create the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals programs in 2012. And that, he argued in a 2019 legal brief with 11 other Republican attorneys general, meant President Trump was free to abolish it.\par \par \uc2 Brnovich told Capitol Media Services in 2019 he believes \uc2 Obama\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s unilateral action was illegal. But he also said it isn\u8217\'20\'19t necessary for the justices to reach the same conclusion in deciding whether the current president can abolish the program.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s a matter of simple logic,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CIf President \uc2 Obama\uc2  can create a substantive program by himself using the executive power, then why can\u8217\'20\'19t President Trump rescind that using executive action?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 On Thursday, Brnovich was sticking with his legal position.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhile the Supreme Court says DACA can remain in place for now, the temporary program has never provided a lasting solution,\u8221\'20\'1D he said in a prepared statement.\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: By Howard Fischer Capitol Media Services\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020200619eg6j00034\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Metro\par {\*\bkmkstart toc3}{\*\bkmkend toc3}\b \uc2 Guilt by association: Strategy morphs for border prosecutions\b0\par\par\uc2 Curt Prendergast \par \uc2 1,809 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 August 2019\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par B01\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2019 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The last two years saw a rash of criminal charges against border aid workers in Southern Arizona, raising questions about the future of humanitarian aid in a deadly border-crossing area.\par \par \uc2 A road map to that future may be found by looking back on how the U.S. Attorney\u8217\'20\'19s Office went after cartel scouts and then expanded their pursuit to the variety of roles needed to support the scouts, according to an analysis of cases and trends in U.S. District Court in Tucson by the Arizona Daily Star.\par \par \uc2 As the U.S. Attorney\u8217\'20\'19s Office pursued charges against nine volunteers with Tucson-based humanitarian aid group No More Deaths, prosecutors in Tucson also expanded the scope of cases involving cartel scouts.\par \par \uc2 Those scouts spend weeks on mountains west of Tucson and act as \u8220\'20\'1Cair traffic controllers,\u8221\'20\'1D as one Border Patrol agent put it, for marijuana backpackers in the valleys below.\par \par \uc2 Prosecutors broke new legal ground in 2015 when a judge ruled a man working as a scout on a mountaintop near Ajo could be charged with conspiring to smuggle marijuana, despite not having any marijuana when he was arrested.\par \par \uc2 Since then, scout cases have grown to include scout \u8220\'20\'1Chelpers\u8221\'20\'1D who cook and fetch supplies for scouts, drivers who drop off supplies, homeowners who store supplies, people buying groceries or wiring money to pay for supplies, and other roles.\par \par \uc2 If a jury were to convict Scott Warren, a volunteer with No More Deaths, at a retrial in November, he would be the first border aid worker convicted of felony human-smuggling charges in Tucson\u8217\'20\'19s federal court in more than a decade.\par \par \uc2 Judging by what the U.S. Attorney\u8217\'20\'19s Office in Arizona has done when breaking new legal ground with scout cases, any future trials of border aid workers potentially could see nurses, doctors, volunteers, or even donors to No More Deaths sitting at the defense table instead of in the courtroom gallery.\par \par \uc2 In the gallery\par \par \uc2 During Warren\u8217\'20\'19s trial in June, Susannah Brown bowed her head and pinched the bridge of her nose as she sat in the gallery of a federal courtroom in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 A federal prosecutor was telling jurors that Brown, a 67-year-old nurse who works with humanitarian aid groups in Southern Arizona, conspired with Warren and others to smuggle two Central American men across the U.S.-Mexico border in January 2018 and help them get to Phoenix.\par \par \uc2 Brown regularly treats migrants for a number of ailments and injuries at a shelter in Sonoyta, the Mexican border town south of Ajo. She and her fellow volunteers also bring a truck with a big tank of water to the shelter, which has an unreliable hookup to the municipal water system.\par \par \uc2 In January 2018, Brown attended to the two Central American men at an aid station in Ajo, known as The Barn, and Dr. Norma Price gave a medical consultation by phone.\par \par \uc2 Prosecutors at Warren\u8217\'20\'19s trial also said Irineo Mujica, the operator of the migrant shelter in Sonoyta, arranged to help the two Central Americans get to Ajo.\par \par \uc2 Brown, Price and Mujica were not charged with any offenses, but they remained in the crosshairs of the U.S. Attorney\u8217\'20\'19s Office as Warren\u8217\'20\'19s trial ended.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CSo what the evidence shows in this case is that the defendant, Irineo Mujica, and Susannah Brown and the others conspired to further Kristian and Jose\u8217\'20\'19s illegal journey into the United States,\u8221\'20\'1D federal prosecutor Anna Wright told the jurors in her closing arguments, according to a court transcript.\par \par \uc2 Wright also referred to two No More Deaths volunteers when she told jurors that in the days after the arrest, \u8220\'20\'1Cat least two people intentionally went to The Barn and took things out, and they took those things out to help the defendant, and they handed those things over to the defendant.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Rather than make money, Warren \u8220\'20\'1Cgets to further the goals of the organization that he is a high-ranking leader in, and one of those goals, although never stated outright, is to thwart Border Patrol at every possible turn, to further the entry of illegal aliens,\u8221\'20\'1D Wright told jurors.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol also viewed No More Deaths as a smuggling organization, according to Agent John Marquez\u8217\'20\'19s report detailing Warren\u8217\'20\'19s arrest.\par \par \uc2 No More Deaths \u8220\'20\'1Cwas long suspected of illegally harboring and aiding illegal aliens and a search warrant for their illicit activities was recently executed at their humanitarian station near Arivaca, Arizona,\u8221\'20\'1D Marquez wrote.\par \par \uc2 He was referring to the raid of a No More Deaths camp near Arivaca in June 2017. Agents had followed the footprints of four people suspected of crossing the border illegally.\par \par \uc2 No volunteers were arrested, but they later said the raid and the surveillance that preceded it signaled a heightened level of tension between No More Deaths and the Border Patrol.\par \par \uc2 Warren\u8217\'20\'19s trial ended with a mistrial after the jury split 8-4, favoring acquittal.\par \par \uc2 After more than a year of arguing that Warren was part of a conspiracy, prosecutors dropped the conspiracy charge when they announced in July their plan to retry Warren on harboring charges.\par \par \uc2 Circumstantial connections\par \par \uc2 Marijuana backpackers have trekked through the desert west of Tucson for many years, often led by scouts using binoculars and encrypted radios to keep the backpacking groups spread apart, as well as to let the groups know if Border Patrol agents were approaching.\par \par \uc2 Until 2015, prosecutors would charge scouts only with crossing the border illegally.\par \par \uc2 But a judge\u8217\'20\'19s ruling in Tucson\u8217\'20\'19s federal court in 2015, followed by two 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals decisions in 2017, opened the door for scouts to face conspiracy charges.\par \par \uc2 In the years that followed, prosecutors have charged at least 100 scouts with conspiring to smuggle marijuana, court records show.\par \par \uc2 As time went on, agents and prosecutors started targeting not only scouts, but the network of people who supported the scouts.\par \par \uc2 In one ongoing case, Border Patrol agents arrested Jose Angel Felix Ramirez, the suspected head scout for a drug-trafficking organization, in late 2017, and more than a dozen people accused of conspiring to smuggle loads of marijuana through the mountainous areas of the Tohono O\u8217\'20\'19odham Nation.\par \par \uc2 In that case, agents arrested scouts and backpackers; helpers who picked up groceries, batteries and other supplies at the base of mountains; drivers who brought supplies to the mountains; a man who let the scouts use his house in a nearby village to store supplies; a woman in Phoenix who bought supplies; and a woman who loaned her car to supply drivers and paid people to buy supplies, according to plea agreements.\par \par \uc2 As prosecutors expanded the roles that could be included in the conspiracies, they also expanded how much marijuana a scout could be held responsible for conspiring to smuggle.\par \par \uc2 Initially, scouts were accused of conspiring to smuggle the equivalent of one backpack of marijuana. As time went on, prosecutors started accusing scouts of conspiring to smuggle all the marijuana backpacks that were caught in the scouts\u8217\'20\'19 \u8220\'20\'1Cview sheds,\u8221\'20\'1D or line of sight, while the scouts were on the mountain.\par \par \uc2 In the Felix case, members of the conspiracy were connected to about 4,300 pounds of marijuana, prosecutors said.\par \par \uc2 Humanitarian conspiracy?\par \par \uc2 Under the prosecution\u8217\'20\'19s theory of Warren\u8217\'20\'19s case, he acted as part of a criminal conspiracy.\par \par \uc2 That theory is in many ways analogous to theories put forth by prosecutors in scout cases.\par \par \uc2 From that prosecutorial line of thinking, if an aid volunteer cooked for a migrant who came into an aid station from the desert, how different would that be from helpers cooking for scouts on a mountaintop?\par \par \uc2 If a volunteer drove jugs of water, beans, socks, or gear to an aid station in Ajo or Arivaca, how different would that be from a person driving bags of food, batteries and gear to the base of a mountain where a scout worked?\par \par \uc2 If a Tucson resident donated money to No More Deaths to buy water and aid for migrants, how different would that be from people in Phoenix buying supplies for scouts?\par \par \uc2 If a volunteer said they had worked at an aid station for a week, could they be charged with aiding the illegal border crossings of however many migrants were caught in that area in the previous week?\par \par \uc2 U.S. Attorney Michael Bailey, who took the position in May, declined to be interviewed but issued a statement to the Star.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThose who want only to give water to the thirsty should be commended,\u8221\'20\'1D Bailey said. \u8220\'20\'1COn the other hand, when one\u8217\'20\'19s true goal is to assist an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in getting in without getting caught, such conduct is subject to prosecution.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Nine No More Deaths volunteers, including Warren, were charged with misdemeanors related to leaving water and food on the Cabeza Prieta National Wildlife Refuge in 2017. The charges included driving on unauthorized roads and abandoning property on the refuge.\par \par \uc2 The \u8220\'20\'1Cbottom line\u8221\'20\'1D is that prosecutors could not convince a jury that Warren was guilty of any charges, said Paige Corich-Kleim, a No More Deaths volunteer.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CProsecutors could try to cast a wide net, but they\u8217\'20\'19d essentially be arguing that keeping people from dying is \u8216\'20\'18furthering illegal presence,\u8217\'20\'19 and I doubt any jury would agree with that,\u8217\'20\'19 Corich-Kleim said.\par \par \uc2 Aid workers, Border Patrol agents, hunters and others in Southern Arizona have recovered nearly 3,000 sets of human remains believed to belong to migrants since 2001.\par \par \uc2 Andy Silverman, a law professor at the University of Arizona and a member of the No More Deaths legal team, said the difference between the scout cases and Warren\u8217\'20\'19s case is that Warren was not involved in illegal activity.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CAs they say, humanitarian aid is never a crime,\u8221\'20\'1D Silverman wrote in response to an inquiry from the Star.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHowever, charging Scott and trying him for serious offenses \u8212\'20\'14 even though ultimately he should be found not guilty \u8212\'20\'14 has a chilling effect on people considering doing humanitarian work along the border,\u8221\'20\'1D Silverman wrote.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CBut it will not stop such work,\u8221\'20\'1D he wrote. \u8220\'20\'1CHelping others in need has been part of our culture and the threat of criminal charges will not stop good folks from trying to save lives in our desert regions.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Silverman said he would expect a \u8220\'20\'1Clarge public backlash\u8221\'20\'1D if prosecutors start charging all people who do humanitarian work.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe have seen it in the Warren case and it would even be greater if the government starts to go after, for example, health professionals, shelter operators and others helping people in the deadly deserts along the border,\u8221\'20\'1D Silverman said.\par \par \uc2 A status conference in Warren\u8217\'20\'19s case is scheduled for Monday, Aug. 5. His retrial is scheduled to start Nov. 12.\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: By Curt Prendergast Arizona Daily Star\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020190804ef840000b\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc4}{\*\bkmkend toc4}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 2,201 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 May 2019\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A35\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2019 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Catchy phrases will help Democrats win in 2020\par \par \uc2 The 2020 presidential election is really significant, threatening four more year of overbearing, lies, damaged America, at home and abroad, etc. Democrats must seize and define the moment or Trump will. His battalions include a core of voters, a Republican Party in lock-step with him, and his daily tweets and threats. Can he be beaten? Of course. But not by complacency and namby-pamby, lengthy policy explanations. One of my favorite columnists, Pulitzer Prize winner Eugene Robinson, recently said it well: To beat Trump we must use simple statements of fact and catchy phrases. He coined the phrase \u8220\'20\'1CDepartment of Pithy Phrases\u8221\'20\'1D to outline how Trump invokes fealty, using repeated familiar wording. Who doesn\u8217\'20\'19t remember \u8220\'20\'1CNo Collusion, No Obstruction,\u8221\'20\'1D \u8220\'20\'1CWitch Hunt,\u8221\'20\'1D \u8220\'20\'1CFake News\u8221\'20\'1D?\par \par \uc2 Which President said \u8220\'20\'1CThe only thing we have to fear is fear itself!\u8221\'20\'1D Or \u8220\'20\'1CMr. Gorbachev\par \par \uc2 , tear down this wall?\u8221\'20\'1D Short, pithy phrases persist in memory (even into the voting booth). It\u8217\'20\'19s important Democrat hopefuls adopt this posture, to sell our message. Candidates, please take note.\par \par \uc2 Paul Rees\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Thanks to Gregory School students for gifts\par \par \uc2 I accompanied my 106-year-old neighbor to the 32nd annual Centenarian luncheon held at TMC. It\u8217\'20\'19s a collaborative event founded by my friend and colleague, Robin Klaehn-Quilliam, who wanted a way to honor our Tucson elders. There were 52 centenarians attending the luncheon\par \par \uc2 , and it was made extra special by several students from The\par \par \uc2 Gregory School presenting handmade memory boxes to the honorees. Their thoughtfulness and artistic talents were so wonderful to receive. Thank you.\par \par \uc2 Stephanie Frederick\par \par \uc2 North side\par \par \uc2 Give credit where credit is due\par \par \uc2 Re: the April 30 letter \u8220\'20\'1CLet\u8217\'20\'19s be fair.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 If President Trump thinks he is not getting the credit he should for the economy, he has only himself to blame. He can\u8217\'20\'19t give President \uc2 Obama\uc2  any credit for the economy being in better shape when he left then when he started. If any economic news is not helpful to President Trump he calls it fake. The news is accurate if it helps him. He gets in his own way with his tweets.\par \par \uc2 I have no problem giving President Trump credit for the economy after he took office. What I will not give him credit for is the starting line that President \uc2 Obama\uc2  gave him, 4.9% unemployment rate, 75 straight months of job growth, Dow over 19,000, that was at about 8,000 when \uc2 Obama\uc2  started.\par \par \uc2 We should give President \uc2 Obama\uc2  a break and give him credit for the unemployment rate starting line he gave President Trump. President \uc2 Obama\uc2  earned the credit considering the state the economy was in when he started. Fair is fair.\par \par \uc2 Penny Zacharias\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Why is it called\par \par \uc2 Operation Stonegarden?\par \par \uc2 I have no idea what Operation Stone garden\u8217\'20\'19s title is supposed to imply. Usually these government names are intended to convey some meaning related to their mission. Well, I will fill in the blank. Cemetery. Where else are so many stones intentionally, proudly or humbly arranged, tended in perpetual care?\par \par \uc2 Is this where the officer intended to send young Mr. Torres\u8217\'20\'19 hopes and dreams when he courageously arrested and detained this 18-year-old and dispatched him to some holding tank for \u8220\'20\'1Cillegals\u8221\'20\'1D instead of letting him graduate with his senior class? Is this \u8220\'20\'1CTo serve and protect\u8221\'20\'1D?\par \par \uc2 This is law enforcement run amok.\par \par \uc2 Susan Vonkersburg\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Column misses point: Deputy doing his job\par \par \uc2 Re: the May 8 article \u8220\'20\'1CTeen\u8217\'20\'19s case shows regular traffic stops need monitoring.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It is interesting that even though Tim Steller states that there was no evidence of racial profiling in this case, he then proceeds to bring up numerous questions regarding the manner in which Mr. Torres was questioned, intimating that there was a racial tint to this case and also bringing up issues with the Stonegarden funds. Mr. Torres is not only an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , but he was driving without insurance and without a driver\u8217\'20\'19s license, it\u8217\'20\'19s not as if he were an upstanding person who was not doing anything wrong. This deputy was doing his job. And where do the Desert View students come off protesting his detention, does the law not matter anymore?\par \par \uc2 Helge Carson\par \par \uc2 Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 Imagine what could have occurred without arrest\par \par \uc2 Re: the May 8 article \u8220\'20\'1CTeen\u8217\'20\'19s case shows regular traffic stops need monitoring.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mr. Steller has to explain and help me understand where we are now as a local society. A plate is run for reasonable cause, no current registration, no insurance and no operators permit. But once again, the crime seems to be that the perpetrator was handed over to process for breaking federal law.\par \par \uc2 Well, it is a good thing he did not cause a massive injury accident uninsured and under the influence of drugs, or he could have missed out on all that entails for all involved, which is the real issue.\par \par \uc2 Maybe Mr. Steller would have him elected class president, who knows? It may happen still.\par \par \uc2 David Cabbage\par \par \uc2 Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 Work together\par \par \uc2 for good of the nation\par \par \uc2 For all you people who want to rant and rave about President Trump, you need to read Romans 13:1.\par \par \uc2 Instead of pounding nails into a coffin, work for the good of the nation. We need to put this country together and make it strong. I bet if our people who put this country together were here, you who are against it would get a piece of mind. During WWII we gave up a lot for this country and now you people are trying to destroy it.\par \par \uc2 Sharlie Deschaines\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 A vote\par \par \uc2 for nonpartisanship\par \par \uc2 As our state wrestles with the ongoing struggles related to border enforcement, recently it was refreshing to see a bit of nonpartisan agreement at the Pima County Board of Supervisors. After weeks of posturing, the Supervisors voted 3-2 in favor of accepting $1.8 million dollars in federal funds in Operation Stonegarden grants for the Pima County Sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s Department. Supervisor Sharon Bronson (D) joined Steve Christy (R) and Ally Miller (R) in the vote. The county has a record of accepting the grants over a dozen years amounting to almost $16 million. The Tucson Police Department has also used Stonegarden grants for overtime, equipment and other important supplemental funding.\par \par \uc2 Both sides of the aisle in all levels of government have become increasingly more divided, entrenched in ideology that precludes honest discussion about issues.\par \par \uc2 To continue moving our community forward we need something different. On municipal issues of governance and leadership, our elected officials should demonstrate nonpartisan cooperation more often.\par \par \uc2 Ed Ackerley\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 No real concern\par \par \uc2 for those in flight paths\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 9, 2018, article \u8220\'20\'1CAir Force hopes F-16 use will rise in Tucson.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Now that this article is nearly a year old you may ask yourself why is someone now just commenting on it. Well I will tell you why. Mr. Gary Hunter commented in the article regarding the noise issue, and that is exactly why I am writing you today. Apparently this proposed move has since taken place as the Air Force air traffic over my home has increased greatly. I don\u8217\'20\'19t normally keep abreast of what\u8217\'20\'19s going on in the news locally, or otherwise, unless it affects me directly.\par \par \uc2 It seems there was not enough opposition by the residents here in South Tucson against this proposed move. I must admit that there is good cause to believe the ruling officials had no real concern for the residents in the immediate flight path of Tuscon International Airport. Besides they\u8217\'20\'19re just lower class Hispanics, Native Americans and some elderly retired folk, who are probably mostly deaf anyway, that live down that way anyhow. It seems we have no say down here.\par \par \uc2 David Ogburn\par \par \uc2 South Tucson\par \par \uc2 Teach sex education at home\par \par \uc2 Re: the May 21 article \u8220\'20\'1CBoard of Education ditches requirement that heterosexual marriage be extolled.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Just stop teaching sex ed all together. Put it in the home where it belongs teaching respect in a loving relationship. End of problem.\par \par \uc2 Lillian Fitzpatrick\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Kudos for front page with good news\par \par \uc2 I want to commend the Star on the stories that appeared on the front page of its Monday, May 20 paper. The two above the fold stories were about the Reid Park Zoo renovation and a possible $26 million in the Pima County budget for road repairs. It\u8217\'20\'19s nice to wake up to some good news for a change. And the best part: Trump wasn\u8217\'20\'19t mentioned once on the entire page. Keep up the good work.\par \par \uc2 Douglas Maul\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Contempt \u8216\'20\'18of\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 and \u8216\'20\'18for\u8217\'20\'19 Congress\par \par \uc2 As the elected threaten more \u8220\'20\'1Ccontempt of\u8221\'20\'1D charges, the electorate harbors more \u8220\'20\'1Ccontempt for\u8221\'20\'1D Congress.\par \par \uc2 Steve Bernhardt\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Impact of printing change now being felt\par \par \uc2 The first clear result of the Star\u8217\'20\'19s printing change to Phoenix is evident. Since that occurred we no longer can view baseball scores or box scores from most previous evening games. Oh well, there is always MLB.com. But just wait until next fall\u8217\'20\'19s U of A football and basketball coverage. The complaints may be deafening.\par \par \uc2 Robert Hutchens\par \par \uc2 Marana\par \par \uc2 Pima County should fund preschool\par \par \uc2 Re: the May 17 editorial cartoon.\par \par \uc2 Fitz nails it again. His cartoon about funding early childhood education is right on point. Potholes can be fixed at any time, but when children are lost, they are lost for good. I have worked in both the public and private sectors, and know that we need an educated workforce in order to grow and prosper. We know what to do and how to do it, we must give kids the start they need to succeed in school and throughout life. This is how I want my taxes to be spent, so I am sharing the cartoon and my support for PCPIP with my friends and neighbors.\par \par \uc2 Rob Stansfield, Ph.D, MBA\par \par \uc2 Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 Missing box scores another sign of decline\par \par \uc2 It appears that the printing of the Arizona Daily Star in Phoenix now means publishing of overnight baseball box scores is no longer possible. While this item may seem insignificant to non\par \par \uc2 sports fans this is sadly another signal of a rapidly declining trend for our local daily newspaper and its long time loyal readers.\par \par \uc2 Michael Bolchalk\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Terms used by media are incorrect\par \par \uc2 The news media, including the Arizona Daily Star, refer to those coming here illegally as migrants. They also refer to them as undocumented immigrants or immigrants. None are legally correct. Migrant conjures up someone moving from one place to another looking for work. Or animals in the wild that migrate from one place to another searching for food, or birds migrating south to escape the winter, then returning in the spring. These human \u8220\'20\'1Cmigrants\u8221\'20\'1D are not doing any of this. They come here with the intent to permanently stay. They are not \u8220\'20\'1Cundocumented immigrants,\u8221\'20\'1D nor are they \u8220\'20\'1Cimmigrants\u8221\'20\'1D as that is an affront to those who went through the lengthy legal process to come here. These terms are intended to blur and extinguish the line between legal and illegal immigration. The correct and legal term used by the USDOJ, federal courts\par \par \uc2 and federal immigration law for those who enter the country illegally is \u8220\'20\'1Cillegal alien.\u8221\'20\'1D But you will never hear any in the liberal news media use this term.\par \par \uc2 A Reed\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 A narrow road, a flat tire and a positive story\par \par \uc2 My wife and I decided to drive up to Pinetop a week ago. We made it as far as a rock in the road 6\par \par \uc2 miles north of the town of Winkelman\par \par \uc2 where the rock destroyed our tire. The road is narrow just there with no shoulder. I pulled as far off as I could but it was a dangerous spot. Then I discovered that there was no cellphone service. A short time later, a couple in a big pickup truck stopped. Their truck was actually a tow truck for their business in Pinetop. They hooked us up and towed our car 6\par \par \uc2 miles down the road to Winkelman. They unhooked the car in a gas station where we could call AAA to change the tire for us. They would not accept any money and then drove on toward Tucson where their daughter was having a baby, They were real g\par \par \uc2 ood Samaritans and I just want to thank them.\par \par \uc2 Michael Kennedy\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Abortion activists\par \par \uc2 Re: the May 22 letter \u8220\'20\'1C\par \par \uc2 Forced-birthers heedless of quality-of-life issues.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 For years I have waited and watched for pro-abortion activists to descend into utter depravity. Now it has happened, and in the letters section of the Daily Star. The writer suggests that Alabama must approve abortion services for the primary purpose of avoiding payments for \u8220\'20\'1Cadoption services, foster homes, education, health care, school lunches, etc.\u8221\'20\'1D In other words, these unborn children must be killed because we cannot afford to support them. That\u8217\'20\'19s a mighty bloody approach to maintenance of the bottom line. Perhaps we should call it the Gosnell Track (Kermit Gosnell).\par \par \uc2 Glenn Perry\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020190524ef5o0000f\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Metro\par {\*\bkmkstart toc5}{\*\bkmkend toc5}\b \uc2 Teen\u8217\'20\'19s case shows regular traffic stops need monitoring\b0\par\par\uc2 Tim Steller \par \uc2 1,026 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 May 2019\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par C01\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2019 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 For two hours Tuesday, dozens of Pima County residents argued before the Board of Supervisors that accepting Operation Stonegarden money from the federal government makes the county complicit in racial profiling and family separation.\par \par \uc2 Thomas Torres was not available for comment.\par \par \uc2 Torres, as you may have read, is the 18-year-old Desert View High School senior who was stopped in a car by a sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s deputy on patrol Thursday night, then handed over to the Border Patrol. The nearly lifelong Tucson resident, brought here as a young child, was being held in immigration detention as his May 22 graduation date approaches. Late Tuesday, though, he was released from detention after a five-day stay.\par \par \uc2 What Torres\u8217\'20\'19 experience shows is, you don\u8217\'20\'19t need Operation Stonegarden to have family separation. You also don\u8217\'20\'19t need Stonegarden for racial profiling to occur, though there\u8217\'20\'19s no evidence that happened in Torres\u8217\'20\'19 case. In fact, the approval Tuesday by county supervisors of the Stonegarden funding came with new conditions, meaning those federally funded patrols are more scrutinized and therefore probably less likely to result in problematic enforcement than the routine patrols and investigations that make up most of any department\u8217\'20\'19s activity.\par \par \uc2 Like the patrol that Deputy Jeffrey Creller was on Thursday night. He was working in the unincorporated area where Torres was driving, near South Alvernon Way and East Drexel Road. Creller saw a 2006 Kia Spectra and didn\u8217\'20\'19t detect any traffic violations, but he called in the license plate and found the car had an expired registration and an insurance suspension, so he pulled it over.\par \par \uc2 Creller details in his incident report that he had trouble getting Torres to identify himself. Torres acknowledged driving without a license and gave an inaccurate Social Security number, but then he produced a high school ID with his name on it. Creller viewed it as evidence of further deception, but it more likely was evidence of cultural confusion on the deputy\u8217\'20\'19s part.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThomas was able to produce a high school identification card from (Desert) View High School. On this card was the name Thomas Torres Maytorena. At this time Thomas clarified with me, when I pointed out to him the misinformation, that he goes by Thomas Torres; however, his legal surname is Maytorena,\u8221\'20\'1D Creller\u8217\'20\'19s report says.\par \par \uc2 Anybody who is from Mexico or the rest of Latin America, or has even spent much time there, could likely have explained the confusion to Creller. In those countries, the common convention for last names is that each person has two of them: The father\u8217\'20\'19s last name first, and the mother\u8217\'20\'19s last name second, without a hyphen. Often people go by both last names, but sometimes they just use the father\u8217\'20\'19s last name.\par \par \uc2 Football rosters from Torres\u8217\'20\'19 high school career show he went by Torres then, too. So calling himself Torres, not Maytorena, was not evidence of deception, or \u8220\'20\'1Cmisinformation,\u8221\'20\'1D as the deputy called it. That appears to have played some role in Deputy Creller suggesting Torres was in the country illegally.\par \par \uc2 The report goes on, \u8220\'20\'1CAgain, I very firmly but politely indicated to Mr. Maytorena, as I had now come to know him at this time, that he needed to be completely honest as to his true identity. I then began to indicate that regardless of the reasons he may be attempting to hide his identity and not be upfront, to include but not limited to him having a warrant, being an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  or having a suspended license, none of which would be acceptable to conceal his identity from me.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Then, the report says, \u8220\'20\'1CMr. Maytorena indicated to me that he is an undocumented \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Would it have made a difference to the deputy if he had known that Thomas Torres is his real name, not a deceptive one? I suspect so.\par \par \uc2 Torres was also arrested in early April. He was cited for misdemeanor possession of marijuana and released. The court filing on his arrest lists his name as Thomas Antonio Torres. Pima County Sheriff Mark Napier noted there was not confusion about his name in that arrest, and if there hadn\u8217\'20\'19t been the second time, \u8220\'20\'1CIn all probability he would have been cited and released.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 With the renewed acceptance of Operation Stonegarden money, there will be a series of conditions that Napier has accepted. Each contact by a deputy taking part in Operation Stonegarden will be registered and explained. No deputies will participate in Border Patrol checkpoints. Deputies will never be cross-deputized as federal immigration agents in the program previously known as 287(g). Each contact by the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s department with the Border Patrol will be tracked. And of course, \uc2 Immigration and Customs Enforcement\uc2  has been removed from the jail.\par \par \uc2 These are significant concessions the sheriff has made related to the acceptance of Stonegarden money. But what about the day-to-day, routine patrols that have nothing to do with Stonegarden? The sheriff, when I asked him about Creller\u8217\'20\'19s stop of Torres, approved of his handling of it, and noted that it was the Border Patrol\u8217\'20\'19s decision, not the sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s department\u8217\'20\'19s choice, to take Torres away.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIf a person admits to being in violation of federal immigration law, I don\u8217\'20\'19t expect them to look the other way,\u8221\'20\'1D Napier said. \u8220\'20\'1CI believe our deputy did exactly what he should do and acted in a reasonable and appropriate manner.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I\u8217\'20\'19m not so sure. I have no problem with the deputy citing him for driving without a license and other vehicular violations. But by his own report, the deputy asked Torres to say if he was in the country illegally, prompting the admission by an undoubtedly intimidated teen. And the deputy may have misinterpreted Torres\u8217\'20\'19 responses as being misleading. This didn\u8217\'20\'19t have to lead to a Border Patrol call.\par \par \uc2 Now that Stonegarden funding has been re-approved, but with conditions that will keep it monitored, it\u8217\'20\'19s these run-of-the-mill stops we really need to watch.\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: \uc2 Tim Steller\uc2  Arizona Daily Star\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020190508ef580000g\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc6}{\*\bkmkend toc6}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 2,101 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2019\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A05\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2019 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 A halting\par \par \uc2 State of the Union\par \par \uc2 When Trump speaks ... he can\u8217\'20\'19t put together ... more than a few words ... at a time. Pause. Even if he could ... put together ... a whole sentence ... I could not believe a single word he said.\par \par \uc2 Deb Childers\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Concertina wire\par \par \uc2 on wall is not the answer\par \par \uc2 Reading about concertina wire being put at the base of the \u8220\'20\'1Cwall\u8221\'20\'1D in Nogales and, for that matter, any city along the border is not only unsafe but morally wrong. You create an unsafe environment for families with young children who live along the border just to appeal to your political base.\par \par \uc2 A wall in itself is not the answer to illegal immigration and adding this unsafe environment for those along the border just helps to create more animosity and anger towards the USA. Have we forgotten that we are nation of immigrants? The political atmosphere in this country has become so divisive that we seem to have forgotten our roots. Let\u8217\'20\'19s get back to using common sense to resolve the real issues and not let partisan politics send us down a path of no return.\par \par \uc2 Frank Flasch\par \par \uc2 North side\par \par \uc2 Dangerous razor wire?\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 6 column \u8220\'20\'1CPointless razor wire makes border unsafe for residents.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Here is a suggestion: Stay away from it!\par \par \uc2 Currie Clement\par \par \uc2 Southeast side\par \par \uc2 Ignoring intelligence\par \par \uc2 reports is unacceptable\par \par \uc2 The Constitution says a president can be impeached and convicted for \u8220\'20\'1Ctreason, bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors.\u8221\'20\'1D I would hope most Americans are looking toward the Mueller investigation to see if any of those charges are warranted.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, the president\u8217\'20\'19s latest tweets malign the intelligence of his own hand-picked intelligence chiefs regarding their reports to the Senate about North Korea, Iran and ISIS. This, to me, already suggests he is guilty of treason. For what is treason? Again, according to the Constitution, it\u8217\'20\'19s \u8220\'20\'1Cgiving aid and comfort\u8221\'20\'1D to the enemies of the United States.\par \par \uc2 By denigrating and refusing to accept the intelligence reports of the directors of the FBI, CIA and national intelligence, Trump is trying to neutralize them as monitors of and safeguards against our enemies. Perhaps one of those directors might be mistaken. But all three? I think not.\par \par \uc2 Karen Schickedanz\par \par \uc2 SaddleBrooke\par \par \uc2 Star is better than mindless speculation\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 5 article \u8220\'20\'1C\uc2 Yahoo\uc2  cites \u8216\'20\'18expectation\u8217\'20\'19 of Miller subpoena.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 What a garbage article. I usually come to Tucson.com for Wildcats news since I stopped visiting \uc2 ESPN\uc2 , which is obviously trying to smear Sean Miller without any factual evidence. I didn\u8217\'20\'19t think your site/paper would even put lame, speculative stories like this one on your site, much less as a top story with \uc2 Yahoo\uc2  as the source. It\u8217\'20\'19s the dumbest thing I have ever read.\par \par \uc2 Vijay Patel\par \par \uc2 North side\par \par \uc2 Sanctuary proposal won\u8217\'20\'19t make us safer\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 2 guest column \u8220\'20\'1CProposal would make Tucson a place of safety, refuge.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Unlike previous news releases about this organization, Saturday\u8217\'20\'19s opinion by the People\u8217\'20\'19s Defense Committee failed to mention that part of the group\u8217\'20\'19s proposal prohibits local law enforcement from turning convicted illegal alien criminals over to federal authorities. Saturday\u8217\'20\'19s headline continues to claim that the People\u8217\'20\'19s Defense Committee proposal will make Tucson a safer place.\par \par \uc2 Are we to believe that releasing convicted criminals into the city instead of turning them over to ICE makes our city safer? I wonder if the widow of Newman, California, police officer Ronil Singh and his 5-month-old son buy this idea. Last December, officer Singh was shot and killed by an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  during a routine traffic stop. Local authorities say California\u8217\'20\'19s sanctuary law prohibited the killer from being turned over to ICE.\par \par \uc2 Alan Kohl\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Electoral College\par \par \uc2 is antiquated and unfair\par \par \uc2 The spate of recent letters about the Electoral College on this page is healthy. A serious discussion about this method of voting for president is long overdue, particularly since in two of the last four elections the candidate with the most votes lost.\par \par \uc2 Those who defend the Electoral College cite the intention of the founding fathers to have equal representation for less populated states vis-\u224\'00\'E0-vis the more populated ones; a remedy to the \u8220\'20\'1Ctyranny of the majority.\u8221\'20\'1D The \uc2 U.S. Senate\uc2 , a powerful body, fills that role. Texas has 46 times more people than Vermont and California has a population 70 times that of Wyoming, yet all of those states are equally represented with two senators each. That is what levels the playing field for the smaller populated states.\par \par \uc2 The Electoral College is an antiquated and unfair way of electing our president. If it cannot be entirely eliminated, its influence should be mitigated in as many ways as possible.\par \par \uc2 Peter Bourque\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Women should never lose right to an abortion\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 1 guest column \u8220\'20\'1COn abortion, let each woman make her own decision in peace.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I was delighted to read Kendra Gaines\u8217\'20\'19 rebuttal and rejection of the Jan. 27 Ren\u233\'00\'E9e Schafer Horton column. I wholeheartedly agree that women should be left in peace to make their own decisions about abortion. I likewise am tired of hearing the debate on abortion. Roe v. Wade is settled law, though pro-life advocates and the religious right continue to defend the rights of the \u8220\'20\'1Cunborn,\u8221\'20\'1D throw road blocks through state legislatures to prevent women from having abortions and place undue burdens on women seeking them.\par \par \uc2 There are many reasons women seek abortions. It is not the right of pro-lifers to question these reasons nor to stop them from having an abortion. And it is certainly not the right of government, politicians or religion to interfere in any way with a woman\u8217\'20\'19s right to choose.\par \par \uc2 Beth Allen\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Please give blood\par \par \uc2 These days, only 1 in 10 people donate blood, yet the need is constant and critical. If you call yourself a citizen and patriot, get moving. Your fellow citizens are depending on you. This is a real national crisis. If you are eligible, please donate. You will feel so good! Take action. Get er\u8217\'20\'19 done!\par \par \uc2 David Keating\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Make America wait again\par \par \uc2 Nancy Pelosi\uc2  and \uc2 Chuck Schumer\uc2  have once again successfully led the Democratic Party down the lonely road against immigration reform. Their unwillingness to negotiate with the president over substantial improvements in border security makes me wonder if the Democrats really want immigration reform or if the status quo is good enough for them?\par \par \uc2 Americans by and large support improved border security and true immigration reform; but year after year nothing gets done. The can gets kicked down the road and Americans wait again.\par \par \uc2 I stand with our president and his attempt to get moving on border security and true immigration reform. I\u8217\'20\'19m appalled that some Republicans and moderate Democrats are hiding and hoping the whole thing blows over.\par \par \uc2 Members of Congress were elected to be the voice of those who voted for them. When you let your party leaders dictate to you how to vote; you have failed yourself and those who you promised to serve.\par \par \uc2 Robert Guth\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Remembering four brave chaplains\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 2 article \u8220\'20\'1CWWII chaplains who gave their lives to save others will be honored here.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 My uncle lived in Tucson when he entered the war and was on the SS Dorchester being transported to Greenland when they were torpedoed by a German sub. The kindness in the hearts of the four chaplains will never be forgotten.\par \par \uc2 My Uncle Johnny was the recipient of a life vest from the Catholic chaplain. Thank you for writing the story about the four chaplains and the ceremony at Kino Memorial Park. Hopefully my cousin will be there. It was his dad who was on the Dorchester. I plan to attend also.\par \par \uc2 Mike Cable\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Tucsonans missed\par \par \uc2 the game of the year\par \par \uc2 The women\u8217\'20\'19s basketball game at \uc2 Pima Community College\uc2  Saturday had everything except attendance. Everyone should have been there. After a triple overtime, several players fouling out, a few injuries and spectacular play, fast breaks and clutch 3-pointers, PCC won 116-114 \u8212\'20\'14 and you weren\u8217\'20\'19t there. The gym should have been packed, as it sometimes is. The gym is easy to get to and there\u8217\'20\'19s plenty of parking. Tickets are $5 and kids are free.\par \par \uc2 Ned Russell\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 State leaders putting tax returns in limbo\par \par \uc2 I am a tax preparer and I cannot believe that the fight between Gov. Ducey and the Legislature is still going on to come to a conclusion on which tax rate and deductions will be used for 2018. It is now February 2019 and we cannot process clients\u8217\'20\'19 tax returns because of the infighting that should have taken place before the end of 2018.\par \par \uc2 The other problem is that there seems to be a lack of information in the Star as to what is taking place each day on this issue. It is extremely hard to get any information on whether the Legislature will try to override the veto that Gov. Ducey instituted last week. Come on now!\par \par \uc2 Lawrence Sanders\par \par \uc2 Southeast side\par \par \uc2 Wash cleanup volunteer\par \par \uc2 deserves recognition\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 5 article \u8220\'20\'1CVolunteers step up to keep Alamo Wash free of debris.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I live next door to the Alamo Wash in Old Fort Lowell and happily join the wash cleanup crews. I was gratified to read the article regarding our volunteer efforts and most particularly to hear well-deserved praise for Bob Lindrub. He works tirelessly to clean up the wash, contributing many hours every week.\par \par \uc2 Working alone, Bob toils year-round, in grueling desert sun and the chill of winter. Bob\u8217\'20\'19s dedication to his community should be formally recognized by the city of Tucson. People like Bob are few and far between. I recommend that Mayor \uc2 Jonathan Rothschild\uc2  present Bob with a formal certificate of commendation on behalf of the city at a public reception well-covered by local media.\par \par \uc2 Jon Dorschner\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Trump cannot tell truth\par \par \uc2 Negotiating with a liar is like trying to catch an eel in a vat of oil, blindfolded. I pity \uc2 Nancy Pelosi\uc2  and \uc2 Chuck Schumer\uc2  for having to deal with President Trump. How other countries can trust him on treaties I don\u8217\'20\'19t know.\par \par \uc2 He constantly lies even about things he must know can easily be checked or are simply common sense. His daily tweets are a national joke. According to a nonpartisan fact-check, he has told 8,000 lies since his inauguration. That comes to about 10 a day. It seems that America has come full circle. We started with a president who \u8220\'20\'1Ccannot tell a lie\u8221\'20\'1D to one who cannot tell the truth.\par \par \uc2 Don Vandine\par \par \uc2 Sierra Vista\par \par \uc2 We didn\u8217\'20\'19t vote for more taxes\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 5 article \u8220\'20\'1CTaxpayers in limbo, along with AZ tax law.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Gov. Ducey has overstepped his authority to raise taxes on hardworking Arizona people. No tax increase was approved through the legislative process, so this is basically taxation without representation. A tax increase would not have been approved by the voters or their representatives.\par \par \uc2 The word needs to get out to more people so they will hold the governor to task. Even high-tax California is making adjustments so they don\u8217\'20\'19t collect more tax due to the federal tax-law changes. This is shameful, especially for a Republican.\par \par \uc2 Christine Olson\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Young wrestler, father deserve understanding\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 5 article \u8220\'20\'1CSafford police, AIA investigating CDO wrestler who \u8216\'20\'18aggressively tackled\u8217\'20\'19 Salpointe coach.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Our entire community would benefit from understanding frustration levels and having effective and accessible strategies for anger management, including coping skills.\par \par \uc2 1) Expulsion and punitive actions are likely to have long term negative results, especially considering that he is 18, and probably ready to graduate. 2) This may be the last chance to teach this young man appropriate ways to be a man. 3) I am purposely NOT using his name, because he should not be labeled and stigmatized. 4) He and his dad need support with anger management and self-control. 5) We as the community can make things better or worse, depending on how we choose to respond.\par \par \uc2 No, it was not OK for him to attack the coach. No, it was not OK for his dad to cross into the ring. No, it is not OK for us to be judgy. Yes, it is OK and necessary for the community to help him and his dad be accountable to themselves and our community.\par \par \uc2 Felicia Chew\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020190207ef2700036\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc7}{\*\bkmkend toc7}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 2,547 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 January 2019\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A05\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2019 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Let\u8217\'20\'19s all be nicer out there\par \par \uc2 I was having lunch at a northwest-side chain restaurant the other day and needed to use the \u8220\'20\'1Cfacilities.\u8221\'20\'1D I left that area to tell the hostess that there was no more toilet paper in the two stalls. She thanked me profusely for letting her know and for being so calm and nice about it. What? It\u8217\'20\'19s only toilet paper.\par \par \uc2 I suggested to her that I detected that because the restaurant was having a low-staff day due to illness, that checking the restrooms was lower on the focus. But again, it was only toilet paper. And then the thought came: It\u8217\'20\'19s just another symptom of the angry society in which we live now. She was expecting a tantrum from me. People have stopped being calm and being nice, even in minor situations. \u8220\'20\'1CYou are more than welcome,\u8221\'20\'1D Ms. Hostess. And \u8220\'20\'1Ccalm down, people,\u8221\'20\'1D it\u8217\'20\'19s just not that urgent. Be nice/kind/calm. It gets the job done.\par \par \uc2 Nancy Tepper\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Ignore Venezuela,\par \par \uc2 focus on US\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 13 article \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s time for a new government in Venezuela, US says.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In the article, I read some disturbing comments from State Department spokesman Robert Palladino. He spoke about their need for freedom and to live in a democratic society and how the U.S. needs \u8220\'20\'1Cto begin the orderly transition to a new government.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 As a student of foreign policy since the mid-1970s, I must say that our imperialism agenda has not worked in places like Iran, Vietnam, Iraq, etc. Our CIA involvement since 1960 has had serious blowback involving negative sentiment toward the U.S. Is it any of our business if Venezuela is run poorly? We should be more concerned about establishing democracy here, rather than trying to assure it in foreign lands.\par \par \uc2 Steve Rasmussen\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Sanctuary policies can be dangerous\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 12 article \u8220\'20\'1CPetition seeks to make Tucson a sanctuary city.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The most striking sentence in this article is: \u8220\'20\'1CThe campaign effort is to \u8216\'20\'18build what somebody might call a sanctuary for all, to build a Tucson that is a safe place for everybody to thrive,\u8217\'20\'19 Livier said.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 What is striking is that the campaign, or Zaira Livier, or both, must be unaware (or worse yet, don\u8217\'20\'19t care) that such cities are not only NOT a \u8220\'20\'1Csafe place for everybody,\u8221\'20\'1D but in fact have resulted in deaths to innocent people including U.S. citizens and other LEGAL residents.\par \par \uc2 The most recent example is in California (again) where a released \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  killed one and injured six. Any effort for Tucson to adopt deadly sanctuary city policies should be soundly rejected \u8212\'20\'14 for the safety of everybody. Everyone can only thrive if they are alive!\par \par \uc2 Matthew Scully\par \par \uc2 Sahuarita\par \par \uc2 Indigenous language speakers get raw deal\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 13 article \u8220\'20\'1CMigrant kids\u8217\'20\'19 deaths highlight language barriers along border.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Many thanks to reporter Perla Trevizo for her informative and insightful article about the challenges indigenous language speakers face as they cross the U.S.-Mexico border. My colleagues at the End Streamline Coalition and I witness daily the impact of the lack of a comprehensive language assessment system to which Trevizo refers, particularly for those migrants seeking asylum.\par \par \uc2 First-time border crossers prosecuted in Streamline court typically have their cases dismissed if they speak neither English nor Spanish fluently. They are quickly transferred to ICE custody for deportation, but are unable to understand the application process nor advocate for their asylum claims.\par \par \uc2 As a result, these migrants, who have a legal right to apply for asylum, are wrongly deported back to life-threatening danger in their country of origin.\par \par \uc2 This practice is a travesty and must be changed.\par \par \uc2 Elizabeth Jaeger\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Don\u8217\'20\'19t blame Trump\par \par \uc2 The president does not know what he is doing, but the GOP leadership should know better. People like \uc2 Chuck Grassley\uc2 , \uc2 Mitch McConnell\uc2  and Lindsey Graham, et al., should know better. They seem to be acting in their own interest and a political agenda, not in the best interest of the country.\par \par \uc2 Creating chaos and dividing us weakens our country. Look for the truth, not a cover-up!\par \par \uc2 Pat Manion\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Asphalt jungle, part 2\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 16 letter to the editor \u8220\'20\'1CThe asphalt jungle is ruining Tucson.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I concur heartily with the observations about the proliferating malady of ever more and wider traffic lanes throughout the city at the great expense of historic urban scale, landscapes, livability, walkability and, most painfully to this observer, historic buildings, landmarks and streetscapes that have, to this point, defined and characterized much of what was an attractive desert community.\par \par \uc2 I have recently returned to my adoptive hometown after a 45-year professional sojourn in the West and am equally dismayed at the scope and impact of these destructive trends. Growth, development, and redevelopment are all part of the renewed vitality essential to the life and health of the new organism known as Tucson. But I urge, and hope deeply, that city officials and planners will insist upon a more balanced, user-friendly and life-sustaining policy and philosophy to guide future decisions about the health and welfare of our shared urban environment and home. I am wiling to help.\par \par \uc2 Richard Bierce\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Small-state pandering\par \par \uc2 Re: the 1/16/19 letter \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s about the election.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The writer suggests that President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s handling of the government shutdown is nothing but pandering to the smaller states that helped him get elected. We\u8217\'20\'19re reminded that he was not elected by the people, but rather that evil Electoral College, and his solution is that Congress must move swiftly eliminate it.\par \par \uc2 Our Founding Fathers realized the tyranny of the majority and that\u8217\'20\'19s why America is a republic rather than a democracy. The college is the reason why the executive must always pander to the small states.\par \par \uc2 And by the way, Congress can only pass bills (legislate) and the bills become law only if the executive approves. To change the Constitution, you will have to pander to those annoying small states.\par \par \uc2 Jeffrey McConnell\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Pelosi sells out to far left\par \par \uc2 In order to retain her job as speaker of the House, \uc2 Nancy Pelosi\uc2  had to promise the far left she would resist Trump. So at the age of 78, when most people have taken to doing activities that benefit their communities, she has sold out her country for $223,500.\par \par \uc2 Bruce Dockter\par \par \uc2 Sierra Vista\par \par \uc2 Kudos to federal workers\par \par \uc2 All of us should express our thanks to the federal workers who have been working without pay during the government shutdown. They are doing this to keep our services operational, and to keep our country safe. They are as much heroes as our military. I don\u8217\'20\'19t know how many of our soldiers would be willing to fight for us, if their families would have to lose their homes because they couldn\u8217\'20\'19t pay their bills and end up in soup kitchens, because their checks were not forthcoming. How many of us would be willing to put in a full day\u8217\'20\'19s work because it was ordered by our boss that we work without being paid?\par \par \uc2 Esther Blumenfeld\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Walls don\u8217\'20\'19t guarantee anyone\u8217\'20\'19s safety\par \par \uc2 My residential wall keeps me safe and secure, ergo, the same will happen once we build a wall from Texas to California, is a logical fallacy. From my experience, walls don\u8217\'20\'19t keep burglars out of a house, sometimes not even a dog does, and security systems may not either (although they might help catch the thief post-burglary). And unless you have a wall in the front of your house you are probably just as vulnerable as everyone else. I built a wall to keep the \u8220\'20\'1Ccritters\u8221\'20\'1D out of my backyard. So far I have seen hawks, packrats, prairie dogs, bobcats, coyotes, fox, rattlesnakes, king snakes, roadrunners and other wildlife in my yard after the wall was constructed. A lot of good that wall did for me.\par \par \uc2 So you\u8217\'20\'19d better reinforce that wall with steel, put concertina wire around the top, get yourself a 24-hour surveillance system, a big dog and leave a gun ready on every table in your house.\par \par \uc2 Oh, and never leave home.\par \par \uc2 Richard Harper\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Back-pay problems\par \par \uc2 There is a lot of talk about people on furlough, and President Trump said they will be paid once the government is back to work. The questions I have are \u8211\'20\'13 How many are hourly employees? This means since they are not working any hours they will get no back pay. They are just out of a paycheck. If they are on salary, will they get a \u8216\'20\'18lump sum\u8217\'20\'19 paycheck? This means that it will throw them into another tax bracket and they will take a hit on their paychecks. Why should working for the \uc2 United States government\uc2  become a liability? Why do lawmakers and the president still get a paycheck when people working paycheck to paycheck don\u8217\'20\'19t?\par \par \uc2 Sandra Gassan Joubert\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Are video games appropriate at library?\par \par \uc2 I recently stopped at the library located near Craycroft and River to use the internet. Seated next to me was a young man, possibly a middle school or early high school student. He was playing a video which involved pursuing and shooting people. I brought this activity to the attention of library staff, who assured me the child\u8217\'20\'19s choice was legal. This situation raised several questions for me.\par \par \uc2 Is it appropriate for public funds to be used to entertain a child with this type of video game? Is it appropriate for library resources to be used by a minor for something other than research or scholarly achievement? Are parents aware their children are using the library to play games that involve hunting and killing?\par \par \uc2 Tony Urbanski\par \par \uc2 Southeast side\par \par \uc2 Living the spiritual life\par \par \uc2 Responding to \u8220\'20\'1C35 Ways to Live Your Life So You Can Be Happy.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I love the author\u8217\'20\'19s optimism and heartfelt words. I\u8217\'20\'19m 70 years old. I\u8217\'20\'19ve lived out most of my \u8220\'20\'1Cfuture.\u8221\'20\'1D Many ups and downs. As I have grown older, my spiritual life has taken on more importance. My relationship with God has grown stronger and is the reason for my well-being. I fear for people who only stay in the \u8220\'20\'1Chuman\u8221\'20\'1D box for happiness. Man was born with eternity in his heart.\par \par \uc2 Read God\u8217\'20\'19s word to mankind. Focus on the spiritual aspects of your life as well as the human. Enjoy the happiness your creator desires for you have.\par \par \uc2 Bradford Soland\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Wall solutions\par \par \uc2 I have a two solutions to getting Trump\u8217\'20\'19s wall built.\par \par \uc2 First, let Trump pay for it with the back taxes he owes to the \uc2 IRS\uc2 . Second, let Congress build the wall. They aren\u8217\'20\'19t doing anything else anyway. Of course it would take quite a while, since they only work three days a week, 26 weeks a year at the most.\par \par \uc2 Ann Akers\par \par \uc2 Southeast side\par \par \uc2 Majority didn\u8217\'20\'19t\par \par \uc2 vote for Trump\par \par \uc2 In response to the letter writer in Sunday\u8217\'20\'19s Star who urges us to support The Donald because \u8220\'20\'1Cthat\u8217\'20\'19s why the majority voted him in,\u8221\'20\'1D let me remind everyone that the majority did NOT vote Trump. He won through the Electoral College. The majority of the voters didn\u8217\'20\'19t want to support a lying predator.\par \par \uc2 Brian Johnson\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 TUSD should focus\par \par \uc2 om going small\par \par \uc2 TUSD need to focus on the path of being a small school district. Times have changed, and we need to look forward to taking care of the students we have in TUSD.\par \par \uc2 There are many small school districts that are very successful in educating the students without trying to expand. It\u8217\'20\'19s not necessary to be big anymore to be successful.\par \par \uc2 Education has proclaimed that a larger district is \u8220\'20\'1Cbetter\u8221\'20\'1D for so long that many have become believers in a doctrine which they have not truly examined. Indeed, the largeness of TUSD may be one factor contributing to declines in test scores and increases in behavior problems among students.\par \par \uc2 Having fewer schools in TUSD is more manageable. Scheduling is much more flexible than in a large district, and schedules can be easily altered to accommodate instructional activities.\par \par \uc2 Currently, there are many studies comparing district and school size to student achievement. Many of the studies indicate that students, especially lower income, perform much better in smaller districts.\par \par \uc2 Don Cotton\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Trump, his supporters damage America\par \par \uc2 First of all, I am not a radical, left-wing liberal. I am, however, an 80-year-old retired business owner who loves this country more than anyone can imagine. I am well-educated, law-abiding and financially independent. I am proud to say I served my country in the \uc2 U.S. Navy\uc2  for six years.\par \par \uc2 My children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren love this country as I do. However, I greatly fear they will not continue to enjoy the blessings America has always offered and represented. I fear it is very close to all going away.\par \par \uc2 The current resident of the White House (who some call president) is destroying all we hold dear.\par \par \uc2 Even more alarming are the number of people (in and out of government) who continue to believe his distorted viewpoints and support his destructive agenda.\par \par \uc2 Wake up America ... before it\u8217\'20\'19s too late!\par \par \uc2 Ken Easton\par \par \uc2 Marana\par \par \uc2 Criminalizing humanity\par \par \uc2 I just read about the arrest and prosecution of the water carriers of No More Deaths.\par \par \uc2 I wonder \u8212\'20\'14 If trespassing on public land and \u8220\'20\'1Clittering\u8221\'20\'1D in order to save human lives is a criminal offense, does that mean that you should not break into and enter a burning house to save a life? Is it a punishable offense to crush the windshield of an overturned vehicle in order to rescue the victim of a car accident, especially if it turns out to be a drunk driver or a red-light runner? Should you leave an injured person lying in the street until you find out whether or not they have committed a crime, and if they have, should you leave them to die? If we gather up a lost child, are we going to be arrested on kidnapping charges?\par \par \uc2 Is crossing the U.S. border illegally now a capital offense? Is cruel and unusual punishment, like death by starvation or dehydration, now legal and morally acceptable in this country?\par \par \uc2 SHAME .\par \par \uc2 Julianna Elias\par \par \uc2 Nogales\par \par \uc2 Make Trump, Congress pony up for back pay\par \par \uc2 Once this ridiculously long federal government shutdown is finally over, I have no issue with my tax dollars being used for back pay for those federal government employees who have had to work without pay during the shutdown.\par \par \uc2 But Congress and the president have also approved using tax dollars to back pay all the furloughed government employees for the days they did not work.\par \par \uc2 Why should my tax dollars be used to pay more than one month (and counting) of wages for hundreds of thousands of government employees who did not work only because Congress and the president did not do their job of funding the government? That back pay should come right out of the paychecks and bank accounts of Trump and Congress.\par \par \uc2 Roy Goodman\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020190122ef1m0000r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc8}{\*\bkmkend toc8}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 2,594 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 January 2019\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A09\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2019 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Why the whining?\par \par \uc2 As a reader of the Arizona Daily Star for nearly 20 years, I am baffled by the ongoing spate of letters complaining the Star has no conservative content. Is this a coordinated push to change the paper into something most of its readers don\u8217\'20\'19t want to see? The content of the editorial page has changed significantly over the past several years to include contributors who are definitively conservative.\par \par \uc2 I read this content. It provides me with insight into the viewpoints of conservative Americans without having to watch Fox News or go on websites I prefer not to frequent. I certainly hope the Star will not move away from its strong voice for progressive values in Southern Arizona. Condemning fact reporting as \u8220\'20\'1Cfake news\u8221\'20\'1D is as worrisome as it is tiresome. Your readers need your objective focus on state and local issues as well as fact-checking national issues.\par \par \uc2 Margaret Nichols\par \par \uc2 Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 Women\u8217\'20\'19s sports demand equal coverage\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 9 letter to the editor \u8220\'20\'1CA tale of two games.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Thank you, Phil Bentley, for supporting women\u8217\'20\'19s sports. I appreciate your letter regarding lack of fair and equal coverage of women\u8217\'20\'19s basketball. I have been addressing this issue for several years with the Star regarding \uc2 UA\uc2  women\u8217\'20\'19s sports.\par \par \uc2 When Jon Gold was assigned to softball the articles were accurate, interesting and you did not have to search the Sports section to find them. Last year, softball had some decent coverage but it was not consistent. It is way past time for the Star to correct their unequal coverage, especially when the teams are ranked and winning. Men\u8217\'20\'19s sports get front page coverage whether they win, lose and sometimes even when they don\u8217\'20\'19t have a game.\par \par \uc2 Kathy Gabhart\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Nice words, bad facts\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 7 letter to the editor \u8220\'20\'1CTrump attack unwarranted.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Kudos to the letter writer on his language usage and/or copy of the dictionary, but he needs to do some serious research of the known facts. While his use of \u8220\'20\'1Cad hominem,\u8221\'20\'1D \u8220\'20\'1Cdiatribe,\u8221\'20\'1D and \u8220\'20\'1Celegiac\u8221\'20\'1D required me to break-out my Wikipedia, his logic and grasp of facts are \u8221\'20\'1Dsad.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 While it is true there has been no indictment yet of the Don or his co-conspiratorial familia, his consigliere Cohen, and many others have been already convicted of crimes related to the investigation. There is so much smoke that this fire is obviously raging. Once Mr. Mueller pulls his final rabbit out of the hat, the whole Trump Tower of cards will come tumbling down upon them all.\par \par \uc2 When that happens, Trump/Boris can only look for help from his \u8220\'20\'1Cfearless leader.\u8221\'20\'1D Melania/Natasha, should be safe however, as God knows she has suffered enough. Let\u8217\'20\'19s hope this all ends soon and we can \u8220\'20\'1CMake America sane again.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Robert Kunz\par \par \uc2 Sierra Vista\par \par \uc2 Gun rights and STOP legislation\par \par \uc2 Dear Gov.\par \par \uc2 Ducey: Is it the tool, or the mind behind it that matters?\par \par \uc2 Take for example a 4,000- pound sedan capable of 120 mph. In the hands of a madman, what is more lethal; this car or a handgun? If the car, then let\u8217\'20\'19s extend STOP \u8220\'20\'1Cred flag\u8221\'20\'1D laws to motor vehicle confiscation under court order.\par \par \uc2 Stephen Hansen\par \par \uc2 Southeast side\par \par \uc2 Already a \u8216\'20\'18de facto\u8217\'20\'19 sanctuary city\par \par \uc2 A group called the People\u8217\'20\'19s Defense Initiative, \u8220\'20\'1Cpeople\u8221\'20\'1D meaning illegal immigrants, is seeking signatures to put a ballot on the next election officially making Tucson a \u8220\'20\'1Csanctuary city.\u8221\'20\'1D The Tucson City Council has already deemed Tucson as an \u8220\'20\'1Cimmigrant welcoming\u8221\'20\'1D city, meaning de facto \u8220\'20\'1Csanctuary.\u8221\'20\'1D They have curtailed the Tucson Police Department from fully enforcing the AZ SB 1070 law requiring police officers to notify immigration authorities when making lawful contact with a suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The Pima County Board of Supervisors, due to their hate for President Trump and his immigration enforcement policies, has rejected a federal $1.4 million grant to cover the Pima County Sheriff\u8217\'20\'19s Office assistance of Border Patrol. Sheriff Napier was essentially intimidated by these people into pulling a lone ICE agent from the Pima County Jail. We recently observed the effects of \u8220\'20\'1Csanctuary\u8221\'20\'1D California, wherein a legal immigrant police officer was shot and murdered by an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , who had previous arrests and could have been deported.\par \par \uc2 David Burford\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 More, not fewer, should pay property taxes\par \par \uc2 The idea that senior citizens should be excluded from property taxes is wrong. We need to help fund the roads, public safety\par \par \uc2 and the schools. Who wants to end up in the hospital with unqualified health-care workers? Or find out your mechanic can\u8217\'20\'19t read the instructions to repair your car? Or having to drive over potholes because the county lacks funding to fill them.\par \par \uc2 What also needs to be done is to charge nonprofits property taxes on property they lease to businesses. For instance, while the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2  doesn\u8217\'20\'19t pay local property taxes on its business park, in Illinois, \uc2 Northwestern University\uc2  does voluntarily. Churches often inherit land from estates of members which is often taken off the tax roles. This is a problem for all states.\par \par \uc2 Pamela Farris\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Treason becoming more plausible\par \par \uc2 The egregiousness of the current shutdown of the \uc2 U.S. government\uc2  and the latest news relating to the \uc2 FBI\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s investigation into President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s Russian dealings could potentially result in charges of treason. The first definition of treason is: \u8220\'20\'1CThe betrayal of trust\u8221\'20\'1D and it is not a stretch to identify the aforementioned actions a betrayal of national trust.\par \par \uc2 To make matters worse, the Senate majority leader and numerous other Republican senators are complicit in supporting Trump\u8217\'20\'19s actions or lack thereof. This country is in the throes of its worst national crisis since Watergate and it is imperative that someone with former Sen. Howard Baker\u8217\'20\'19s skill of compromise and ethical behavior (exhibited during Watergate) rise up to restore order before the very foundation of our Democracy is shattered.\par \par \uc2 Chuck Cabrera\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Every vote counts\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 13 column \u8220\'20\'1CVoting process deserves respect: Cast your ballot at polls, not mailbox.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I vehemently disagree with columnist Jonathan Hoffman\u8217\'20\'19s assertion that the delivery method of a vote determines its value. Every eligible citizen\u8217\'20\'19s vote has the exact same value the Constitution assigns it. The only way to affect the value of a vote is any effort to negate it.\par \par \uc2 Arizona has a history of voter suppression that is a blatant attempt to skew the value of a vote and the suppression method most often used is to make voting difficult. I feel we are better served by making it easier to legally cast a ballot. A well considered vote demonstrates the intrinsic value of citizenship, regardless of legal delivery method.\par \par \uc2 John Sartin\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Better measures than a wall\par \par \uc2 We here on the southern border know that the most recent wave of immigrants from Central America does not constitute a national emergency. They are not all drug runners. They are not all criminals. They are mostly people who wish to live in peace and will be welcome additions to our workforce and tax base.\par \par \uc2 Please write or call our senators, Kyrsten Sinema and \uc2 Martha McSally\uc2 , to prevail upon \uc2 Mitch McConnell\uc2  to allow the bill already passed by the House of Representatives to come to a vote in the Senate. We don\u8217\'20\'19t need a wall. We need that $5.7 billion to hire more immigration judges, to hire more Citizenship and Immigration Services staff to process applications, to fund more modern methods of patrolling our border and to build better facilities to house immigrants during processing.\par \par \uc2 Finally, we need more compassion for those less fortunate than ourselves.\par \par \uc2 Cindy Soffrin\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Don\u8217\'20\'19t worry, it\u8217\'20\'19s safe\par \par \uc2 Visitors to Southern Arizona, please don\u8217\'20\'19t be worried by alarmists who don\u8217\'20\'19t live here. In spite of claims of an emergency, things are quite peaceful. We have no gangs roaming the hills or green valleys. When shopping in the summer in Green Valley I leave my windows down. We only lock the doors to our home when it gets dark. No scary hordes here.\par \par \uc2 We have lots of law enforcement. If an accident should happen, there will be an abundance of emergency personnel on site in no time. Fall and you can\u8217\'20\'19t get up? The fire department will be there to upright you in a few minutes.\par \par \uc2 Oh, did I mention we have lots of law enforcement personnel? We have Boarder Patrol bumper-to-bumper.\par \par \uc2 Ray Omdahl\par \par \uc2 Green Valley\par \par \uc2 Scolding the consumer\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 12 column \u8220\'20\'1CDon\u8217\'20\'19t blame Trump for increase in carbon emissions, it\u8217\'20\'19s on all of us.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Los Angeles Times writer Scott Martelle is an irrational scold on consumers who don\u8217\'20\'19t buy electric vehicles (EVs) or gas sippers and then admits that EVs are expensive, that there aren\u8217\'20\'19t enough charging stations and \u8220\'20\'1Cthat technology has yet to come up with batteries that give cars the range that a tank of gas can provide.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 So, all of a sudden, we the consumers are responsible for the expense and technological shortcomings of EVs. Please. As for gas-sippers, try taking any one of them (Prius, Yaris, Elantra and the like) on a family road trip and similar multiperson vehicle excursions (hunting, fishing, golf, etc.) and tell me how that works out. Not well. I guarantee it.\par \par \uc2 Steve Sollenberger\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Helping US citizens and asylum seekers\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 11 letter to the editor \u8220\'20\'1CWhat about homeless US citizens?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In response to the letter writer, I would like to inform him that there are people and organizations in Tucson who are providing meals for local homeless shelters and at the same time providing for the needs of the asylum seekers. Why? Because both are the right thing to do.\par \par \uc2 Americans will provide money and aid to tsunami and earthquake victims overseas as well as to the victims of a wildfire in California. Why? For the same reason. It is this generous volunteer spirit of Americans who care about people in need, regardless of who they are or where they are in the world, that has made America great and continues to do so, long before Mr. Trump appeared on the scene.\par \par \uc2 Tom Henderson\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 How can we help bring the Raiders?\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 11 column \u8220\'20\'1CJust win, baby: Tucson has much to gain if Raiders come for 1 season.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I really hope Tucson can make this happen. I completely agree, it\u8217\'20\'19s a great opportunity for Tucson in a huge way. How can we try to further our great city in the run for the Raiders?\par \par \uc2 Carlos Canedo\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Typical responses expected\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 13 column \u8220\'20\'1CNaysayers aside, much of what Trump said was right.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I couldn\u8217\'20\'19t help but chuckle after reading Jay Ambrose\u8217\'20\'19s piece in which he defended Trump when he wrote that much of what Trump said in his address to the nation about border security was right, especially after he slammed the Pelosi/Schumer response, fact-checkers who would never check the Democrat\u8217\'20\'19s response, and the holier-than-thou liberal media.\par \par \uc2 My amusement didn\u8217\'20\'19t come so much from what he wrote, with which I happen to agree, but from the anticipation of the torrent of responses that you will be printing in the following week from your far-left readership as they try to shout down, drown out, and abase anyone who presents an opinion opposite from their own holier-than-thou view of the world. The Star will probably even get a few letters from people who are insulted you ever printed such \u8220\'20\'1Cdrivel.\u8221\'20\'1D The left is so predictable.\par \par \uc2 Kevin Kaatz\par \par \uc2 Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 Remembering Jan. 8\par \par \uc2 Re: the Jan. 8 column \u8220\'20\'1CWe shouldn\u8217\'20\'19t need a shooting to come together.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Sarah Garrecht Gassen is right. We shouldn\u8217\'20\'19t have needed it, but we did come together. Gabby\u8217\'20\'19s Congress on Your Corner in front of my \uc2 Safeway\uc2  is where I was going to be with granddaughters in tow so they could meet her; a make-up guitar lesson kept us away. I knew nothing of the shooting until my daughter called to \u8220\'20\'1Cmake sure we were all accounted for.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I also learned that there is only one degree of separation between us. Judge John Roll was one of my husband\u8217\'20\'19s first students. All of the memories of that day flooded back at the Jan. 8 Memorial Foundation annual remembrance. I shivered as Mayor Rothschild rang a bell for each of the victims after Ron Barber, victim and president of the foundation, read their names. Hearing Ron read his own name was heartbreaking.\par \par \uc2 Equally heartbreaking was seeing a photo of Ron\u8217\'20\'19s family embracing each other on the front page of the Star the next day. Gabby wasn\u8217\'20\'19t there. She was in Congress supporting passage of a gun control bill.\par \par \uc2 Billie Kozolchyk\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Cartoon off base about Ocasio-Cortez\u8217\'20\'19s proposal\par \par \uc2 Lisa Benson\u8217\'20\'19s Jan. 8 cartoon depicting Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez picking the pocket of the average wage earner is a mischaracterization of her suggested tax changes. Ocasio-Cortez does not have a proposed tax plan. In her Jan. 6 \u8220\'20\'1C60 Minutes\u8221\'20\'1D interview, she suggested a top marginal tax rate of 70 percent that would be applied only to the wealthiest of taxpayers, after $10 million of income. This is a far cry from\par \par \uc2 Benson\u8217\'20\'19s portrayal of Ocasio-Cortez.\par \par \uc2 Warren Buffett\uc2  has admitted his secretary pays more in taxes than he does and reportedly \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  hasn\u8217\'20\'19t paid income tax for many years. Many major corporations do not pay any federal income tax, yet they reap many benefits from the government and the tax payers. Perhaps the cartoon should have portrayed Uncle Sam picking the pockets of the average wage earner, and the corporations and billionaires picking the pocket of Uncle Sam.\par \par \uc2 Chuck Kirkpatrick\par \par \uc2 SaddleBrooke\par \par \uc2 Shutdown and smaller government\par \par \uc2 I am surprised that Trump has not embraced the Tea Party mantra of smaller government by claiming the current shutdown is good for the country. Trump has accomplished the call for a government based on military spending, his continued salary and curtailed federal services.\par \par \uc2 Why do we need air traffic controllers, food inspectors, federal law enforcement personnel and small-business loans? Air traffic can be handled by private or state-sponsored control. Food inspections should then be the responsibility of the factory farm growers. Don\u8217\'20\'19t we have enough guns in our citizens\u8217\'20\'19 hands to ensure an orderly militia protecting our borders?\par \par \uc2 Everett Rockwood\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Missing leadership\par \par \uc2 We vote to elect candidates to lead our national government. In essence, \u8220\'20\'1Cwe the people\u8221\'20\'1D hire our legislative members and expect them to perform. I applaud \uc2 Sen. Martha McSally\uc2  for forgoing her Senate salary during the shutdown, but what about the other members of Congress? It appears that it is Congress that caused the shutdown and therefore, like the suffering government employees, they too should be going without pay.\par \par \uc2 The response I anticipate is that the president shut down the government. I know closing the government has been set in precedent and used as a political ploy, but I question why one person is allowed to cause all the members of Congress to be derelict in their duties. As previously stated, it is the responsibility of Congress to lead and serve. Please do so in order that we as a nation of citizens may concentrate on kindness and human decency.\par \par \uc2 Whittley Anne Gibson\par \par \uc2 Vail\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020190118ef1i0008k\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc9}{\*\bkmkend toc9}\b \uc2 How Congress can start to fix our broken immigration system\b0\par\par\uc2 David Inserra The Heritage Foundation \par \uc2 835 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 November 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A14\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Immigration is always a hot topic, but the migrant caravan has really brought it to a boil. Many have seen pictures of women and children fleeing to the U.S. or men throwing rocks and other projectiles at the U.S. border patrol.\par \par \uc2 What should Americans make of this chaos? Why are there now caravans of \u8220\'20\'1Casylum seekers\u8221\'20\'1D and increasing numbers of women and children crossing the border illegally?\par \par \uc2 Surprisingly, the total amount of illegal immigration is significantly down from where it was a decade ago. In 2008, the U.S. apprehended just over 1 million individuals trying to cross the U.S. border illegally. In fiscal year 2018, it was just under 400,000 \u8212\'20\'14 and fewer illegal aliens are slipping through undetected.\par \par \uc2 Yet certain types of migration are increasing. Specifically, unaccompanied children and family units are up. Fewer than 20,000 unaccompanied children crossed the border in 2010, but that number topped 68,000 in FY 2014. It has dipped since then, but was around 50,000 in FY 2018.\par \par \uc2 The number of family units has also surged from just over 11,000 in FY 2012 to over 100,000 in FY 2018.\par \par \uc2 The number of requests for asylum and subsequent \u8220\'20\'1Ccredible fear\u8221\'20\'1D interviews has also spiked. In 2008, just over 5,000 credible-fear referrals were made. In 2016, it was almost 92,000.\par \par \uc2 Why? Largely because multiple U.S. laws have glaring loopholes that encourage the illegal immigration of children and families and the use of asylum claims as the preferred method to enter the U.S.\par \par \uc2 When \u8220\'20\'1Cunaccompanied alien children\u8221\'20\'1D (UACs) from countries other than Mexico or Canada cross the border illegally, the well-intentioned Trafficking Victims Protection Reauthorization Act of 2008 demands not that we quickly return them to family in their home country, but that we essentially treat them as victims of human trafficking. This is true even if a parent illegally in the U.S. paid for them to be smuggled .\par \par \uc2 The result is that they are connected with family in the U.S. or placed in foster care while they await an immigration court hearing that could be years away. Of course many of these children never show up for their hearing. As a result, less than 5 percent of UACs are removed from the U.S.\par \par \uc2 Similarly, when an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  family crosses the border, the \uc2 U.S. government\uc2  is not allowed to detain the child. The 1997 Flores Settlement mandates that unaccompanied children can\u8217\'20\'19t be detained for more than 20 days. But in 2016, the 9th Circuit Court decided that this applied to all children, even those accompanied by parents.\par \par \uc2 When the parents claim asylum, as many now do, it takes more than 20 days to adjudicate their cases. So the \uc2 U.S. government\uc2  has a choice: Do they release the child but detain the parents who have broken the law by illegally entering the U.S. and not had their asylum claims adjudicated? Or release the entire family?\par \par \uc2 The U.S. would prefer to keep families together in custody awaiting the outcome of their cases, but it is simply not allowed to.\par \par \uc2 But wait, some say \u8211\'20\'13 asylum-seeking isn\u8217\'20\'19t illegal. There is a legal way to do it (at a port of entry) and an illegal way (sneak into the U.S. and then, after being arrested, claim asylum). With the right words and a little coaching, many asylum-seekers pass the credible-fear screening, but fewer than 10 percent of Hondurans, Salvadorans, and Guatemalans end up qualifying for asylum.\par \par \uc2 Society-wide violence, jobs or reuniting with family are not grounds for asylum. Knowing this, many never show up for court. They simply live illegally in the U.S. once released.\par \par \uc2 To discourage illegal immigration, the U.S. must change these incentives. Congress should make it much harder for those crossing the border illegally to claim asylum.\par \par \uc2 Lawmakers should first adjust the asylum-claim process. One way is to first require asylum-seekers traveling to the U.S. southern border to have their asylum claims heard at a U.S. consulate in Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Interviewers should also ask the asylum-seekers why they did not assert asylum in other countries, such as Mexico. If they fail to explain why, immigration officials should consider this a factor in their decisions.\par \par \uc2 Second, Congress must close the loopholes. That means rejecting the Flores settlement and instead allowing accompanied children to remain with their parents while they await adjudication of their asylum claims or prosecution for having violated immigration law.\par \par \uc2 Congress should also reform the Trafficking Victims Protection Reauthorization Act to allow unaccompanied children from countries that are noncontiguous with the U.S. to be quickly repatriated to their home countries.\par \par \uc2 Yes, other enforcement reforms are needed. But the above fixes would go a long way toward securing the border and deterring illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: By \uc2 David Inserra\uc2 The Heritage Foundation\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020181130eebu00037\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc10}{\*\bkmkend toc10}\b \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s time for US to end birthright citizenship\b0\par\par\uc2 Tribune Content Agency \par \uc2 689 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 November 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A16\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 In 2004, nearly 80 percent of Irish voters decided to end birthright citizenship. In its coverage the BBC said, \u8220\'20\'1CThe government said change was needed because foreign women were traveling to Ireland to give birth in order to get an EU passport for their babies.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In 1986, the Australian Citizenship Amendment provided that a child born in that country must have at least one parent who is an Australian citizen.\par \par \uc2 While Portuguese citizenship laws are more complicated due to the existence of former colonies, the laws of that country state that children born to \u8220\'20\'1Ctourists or short-term visitors\u8221\'20\'1D do not automatically acquire citizenship.\par \par \uc2 According to worldatlas.com, 30 countries, including the United States and Canada, offer birthright citizenship, most of the other 28 are either small or like Venezuela where the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  predicts inflation could top 1 million percent by year\u8217\'20\'19s end, and where people are more likely clamoring to leave than to get in and give birth.\par \par \uc2 Clearly a magnet for pregnant women to step over our border and give birth is the instant citizenship their child acquires. When older, that child can then bring in relatives who can also receive all sorts of benefits, including free education and health care.\par \par \uc2 Who wouldn\u8217\'20\'19t want a deal like that? It\u8217\'20\'19s almost as good as the benefits Congress votes itself.\par \par \uc2 American citizenship should not be like a Cracker Jack prize. Read the Senate debate over what became the 14th Amendment to the Constitution and learn about the intentions of its architects, which was to guarantee equal rights for recently freed slaves and their children. It was also a rebuke to the Dred Scott decision, which declared that African-Americans were not and could not be citizens of the United States and to Article 1, Section 2 of the U.S. Constitution of 1787, which said that for purposes of representation in Congress, enslaved blacks in a state would be counted \u8220\'20\'1Cas three fifths of all other Persons.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 This is why \u8220\'20\'1Coriginal intent\u8221\'20\'1D is important. The words concerning the 14th Amendment \u8212\'20\'14 one from a Republican, the other from a Democrat \u8212\'20\'14 are instructive in understanding its purpose and meaning.\par \par \uc2 Sen. Jacob Howard (R-Mich.), who wrote the citizenship clause, said of the amendment: \u8220\'20\'1CThis will not, of course, include persons born in the United States who are foreigners, aliens, [or] who belong to the families of ambassadors or foreign ministers.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Sen. Lyman Trumbull (D-Ill.), who chaired the Judiciary Committee, concurred, saying of the clause \u8220\'20\'1Csubject to the jurisdiction thereof\u8221\'20\'1D that it meant \u8220\'20\'1Cnot owing allegiance to anybody else and being subject to the complete jurisdiction of the United States.\u8221\'20\'1D This was understood to also include Native Americans who were then subject to the jurisdiction of their own tribal laws.\par \par \uc2 Sen. Howard responded: \u8220\'20\'1CI concur entirely with the honorable senator from Illinois in holding that the word \u8216\'20\'18jurisdiction,\u8217\'20\'19 as here employed, ought to be construed so as to imply a full and complete jurisdiction on the part of the United States \u8230\'20\'26 that is to say, the same jurisdiction in extent and quality as applies to every citizen of the United States now.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 If you prefer a more recent opinion, here is Sen. Harry Reid (D-Nev.) in 1983: \u8220\'20\'1CIf making it easy to be an illegal alien isn\u8217\'20\'19t enough, how about offering a reward for being an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 ? No sane country would do that, right? Guess again. If you break our laws by entering this country without permission and give birth to a child, we reward that child with U.S. citizenship and guarantee a full access to all public and social services this society provides. And that\u8217\'20\'19s a lot of services. Is it any wonder that two-thirds of the babies born at taxpayer expense at country-run hospitals in Los Angeles are born to illegal alien mothers?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I concur with Trumbull, Howard and Reid and so should the rest of us, if we are to keep America\u8217\'20\'19s culture from being overwhelmed and destroyed.\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: Tribune Content Agency\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020181107eeb70000g\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc11}{\*\bkmkend toc11}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 921 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 October 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A07\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Kavanaugh fails his stress test\par \par \uc2 In America, many products are stress-tested before consumers are allowed to use them. Thursday we watched \uc2 Brett Kavanaugh\uc2  undergo a stress test by the Senate Judiciary Committee. When hard questions were asked of him he grew belligerent, defiant and disrespectful. When nominee Kavanaugh sarcastically asked Sen. Amy Klobuchar what she liked to drink so that he didn\u8217\'20\'19t have to answer her question about his drinking, I thought to myself, \u8220\'20\'1CYou are not doing well on this stress test.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 When he blamed the Democrats for the circus and brought the Clinton name into his diatribe I knew he had failed the test. He was partisan, angry and unreasonable. He seemed like a very smart but controlling personality who is used to getting his way and not being questioned, which is bad for women and not a great characteristic for a justice of the Supreme Court.\par \par \uc2 Chris Held\par \par \uc2 Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 Hoping Flake has another surprise\par \par \uc2 Jeff Flake\uc2  has one of the best minds in the \uc2 U.S. Senate\uc2 , until he makes it up. He anguishes in public, dripping thoughtfulness, balance and a judicious approach, rising above the usual party drivel. It is an Academy Award performance, since, inevitably, he votes with his conservative colleagues.\par \par \uc2 The charade was at its best \u8212\'20\'14 or worst \u8212\'20\'14 on the \uc2 Brett Kavanaugh\uc2  confirmation hearing. Days of deliberation were followed by a predictable \u8220\'20\'1Cyes\u8221\'20\'1D vote. But then Flake surprised us. After conferring with both Democratic and Republican colleagues he stipulated an \uc2 FBI\uc2  investigation before a full Senate vote. If \uc2 Jeff Flake\uc2  more often followed his conscience, not his party\u8217\'20\'19s worst knee-jerk instincts, he would deserve our respect and \uc2 John McCain\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s blessing.\par \par \uc2 Beth Isabelle\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Flake must listen to his conscience\par \par \uc2 I appreciate Sen. Flake\u8217\'20\'19s request for an \uc2 FBI\uc2  investigation into the serious allegations against Judge Kavanaugh. But I wish he had listened to his serious concerns and doubts, and the multitude of constituents who do not believe Kavanaugh is entitled to a lifetime appointment on the Supreme Court. I wish he had voted \u8220\'20\'1Cno.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Sen. Flake still has the opportunity to do the right thing. Judge Kavanaugh does not have the temperament, impartial view, or integrity to sit on our highest court and make decisions that affect generations of people.\par \par \uc2 Women must be heard on this matter. All those who have serious complaints about Judge Kavanaugh must be heard and each allegation must be investigated.\par \par \uc2 Sen. Flake must listen to his conscience, not political agendas, and vote \u8220\'20\'1Cno\u8221\'20\'1D on Kavanaugh.\par \par \uc2 Jennifer Peters\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Republicans \u8216\'20\'18Flaked\u8217\'20\'19 by sell-out senator\par \par \uc2 Pride is a bad thing, but vengeance might be worse.\par \par \uc2 I watched the hearings on \uc2 Brett Kavanaugh\uc2 . The takeaway: she said, he said (and three people said, \u8220\'20\'1Cnever happened\u8221\'20\'1D and a day planner said \u8220\'20\'1Cnever there.\u8221\'20\'1D) So, why did Sen. Flake ask for a \uc2 FBI\uc2  investigation? The same \uc2 FBI\uc2  of \uc2 James Comey\uc2  and a special counsel run amok.\par \par \uc2 Well, he said, \u8220\'20\'1CThis country is being ripped apart.\u8221\'20\'1D But senator, who is doing the ripping? Did Dick Durbin or your buddy Chris Coons say, \u8220\'20\'1CIf you go with us on an \uc2 FBI\uc2  investigation and it turns out well, we\u8217\'20\'19ll vote for him?\u8221\'20\'1D Of course not!\par \par \uc2 Flake can now walk over to Annapolis and shout, \u8220\'20\'1CRest in peace, I got that prideful president good!\u8221\'20\'1D A real modern day Benedict Arnold destroyed an excellent judicial candidate. Jeff, you sold your party to the Democrats and our country has been \u8220\'20\'1CFlaked.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Scotti Madison\par \par \uc2 Downtown\par \par \uc2 TEP inadvertently veers into the truth\par \par \uc2 I see TEP has signs everywhere saying \u8220\'20\'1CNo on 127. Higher electric bills.\u8221\'20\'1D I commend them for telling the truth. If you vote \u8220\'20\'1Cno\u8221\'20\'1D on Prop. 127, you will get higher electric bills.\par \par \uc2 Buddy Gill\par \par \uc2 Marana\par \par \uc2 McSally overlooks fact that Trump didn\u8217\'20\'19t serve\par \par \uc2 In \uc2 Martha McSally\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s ads she proudly refers to her military career while decrying the fact that Kyrsten Sinema has never served. McSally has every right to be proud of her accomplishments in the military. If, however, military service is so important to her, how does she justify her strong support of President Trump who, as we all know, obtained multiple deferments in order to avoid serving during the Vietnam conflict?\par \par \uc2 Can it be that lack of having been in the military is only a bad thing if the person in question is a Democrat but it is not so bad if the person is a Republican?\par \par \uc2 Martin Greene\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Carrasco gives free pass to detained kids\u8217\'20\'19 parents\par \par \uc2 Re: the Sept. 23 column \u8220\'20\'1CUS lays trap for immigrants who would care for kids.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The Star\u8217\'20\'19s Latino-centric columnist, Luis Carrasco, blasted Trump and immigration authorities for their alleged \u8220\'20\'1Ctrap\u8221\'20\'1D set for those attempting to obtain the release of \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children at shelters. He has a problem with the vetting of these adult people to determine if they are in the country illegally. Why would immigration authorities knowing turn over a child to someone here illegally, even if that person was the parent?\par \par \uc2 Doing so fulfills the parent\u8217\'20\'19s scheme of bringing their children into the country illegally, knowing eventually they will take possession of them. Carrasco writes about the costs to the American taxpayer to shelter these \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children as a reason to release them. He does not place any blame or responsibility for this mess on their parents who committed child endangerment by either sending them here unaccompanied or brought them here illegally.\par \par \uc2 Alice Moreno\par \par \uc2 North side\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020181003eea30000j\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc12}{\*\bkmkend toc12}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 1,023 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 August 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A07\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Help those you leave behind: Write your will today\par \par \uc2 Like many, Aretha Franklin died without a will. Now the courts will get involved, at a cost. This is so needless.\par \par \uc2 In addition to coping with their loss, her survivors will be caught up in a public legal issue that could have been private. My late sister Suzy was right: A will is not about you. It is about those who survive you and who will have to clean up your mess. It varies by state, yet Arizona permits a hand-written (holographic) will. If you care about those after your exit, write a will today.\par \par \uc2 Tim O\u8217\'20\'19Connor\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Conservative writers no fans of Trump, either\par \par \uc2 No question, the present occupant of the White House has come in for considerable press criticism. By framing the First Amendment, the Founding Fathers ensured that presidents \u8212\'20\'14 from Washington on down \u8212\'20\'14 would be the target of criticism, rather than the press constituting the president\u8217\'20\'19s private cheering section. And this president \u8212\'20\'14 through unsavory actions, words, and countless falsehoods \u8212\'20\'14 has managed to become a very large target indeed.\par \par \uc2 But reverse roles for a second: Had \uc2 Barack Obama\uc2  engaged in the same type of behavior, would he have gone unscathed at the hands of the press? Reporting negative events certainly comes across as negative. One can argue whether the press is \u8220\'20\'1Cleft-leaning\u8221\'20\'1D or not; proof of the proposition is difficult to come by. But an intriguing question remains: Obama was the target for eight years of conservative columnists and commentators. Now Michael Gerson, Jonah Goldberg, George Will, Steve Schmidt, Nicole Wallace and others are criticizing the Republican occupant of the oval office. Why?\par \par \uc2 Edward Pokorney\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Democracy requires compromise\par \par \uc2 Recent letters to the editor regarding politics have become increasingly angry and hateful \u8212\'20\'14 reflecting a national trend. When politicians and their actions stir things up to the point where we turn on each other, it\u8217\'20\'19s time to pull back and hit the pause button. It\u8217\'20\'19s one thing to discuss the pros and cons of public policy, but quite another to attack each other like rabid dogs when our views diverge.\par \par \uc2 Democracy is messy. It requires mature, thoughtful discussions and painful compromises. The laws of nature instruct us that for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction. As much as we might wish it to be so, there are no perfect solutions. To get you have to give. If we\u8217\'20\'19re not mature enough to handle the complexities of a democracy, we can always abdicate our responsibility to act like mature adults and hand things over to a dictator.\par \par \uc2 Jay Quick\par \par \uc2 North side\par \par \uc2 Allegiant safety record is troubling\par \par \uc2 As a frequent customer on two airlines that serve Tucson, I read with great interest the article about the forthcoming entry of Allegiant Airlines into the Tucson market. I think that potential consumers would be well advised to search online for the \uc2 CBS\uc2  \u8220\'20\'1C60 Minutes\u8221\'20\'1D video about the safety and reliability record of this airline. I will not be a customer.\par \par \uc2 Robert Couch\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Where\u8217\'20\'19s the outrage over Iowa slaying?\par \par \uc2 Just wondering where the protesters, outrage, media madness and \u8220\'20\'1Cprogressive\u8221\'20\'1D politicians and their supporters are about the permanent family separation that has taken place for an Iowa family at the hands of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 . Temporary separations of those who enter illegally are bad, but even worse are deaths of U.S. citizens at the hands of illegal (oh, excuse me ... undocumented) immigrants, don\u8217\'20\'19t you think? Good thing it didn\u8217\'20\'19t happen in San Francisco or some other \u8220\'20\'1Csanctuary city.\u8221\'20\'1D They might not have honored the immigration hold that was put on the guy by ICE and released him.\par \par \uc2 Matthew Scully\par \par \uc2 Sahuarita\par \par \uc2 Help the first lady\par \par \uc2 It seems to me that we owe it to Melania Trump to see that \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s time as president comes to an end quickly, so she can start her divorce proceedings.\par \par \uc2 Kay Van Houten\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Responsible development needed\par \par \uc2 Re: the Aug. 26 article \u8220\'20\'1CBLM, enviros ask high court to reverse San Pedro decision.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 At least since the \u8217\'20\'1980s, Arizona has grappled with the issue of groundwater. Our state environmental commission, no longer in existence, brought developers like Roy Drachman to the table with water-resource experts and environmentalists and we enacted the 1980 Groundwater Act.\par \par \uc2 A travesty will be committed if this development in Southern Arizona is allowed to move forward, depleting our precious aquifer resources. An entire rural way of life, ranching, recreation, tourism and unique habitat for wildlife will be wiped out. We have seen the science fiction stories of vast deserts where inhabitants hoard water; is this what we are to become?\par \par \uc2 I for one pray that federal judges understand that unwise growth and development is not always in the best interest of the public. I hope that wise judges will ask the hard questions and consider the negative impact of depleting our San Pedro River. I am not against planned development, but be responsible!\par \par \uc2 Alicia Bristow\par \par \uc2 Oracle\par \par \uc2 In search of the truth? Check out media bias chart\par \par \uc2 I applaud the editorials the Star and many other newspapers ran on Aug. 16. The cries of \u8220\'20\'1Cfake news\u8221\'20\'1D are just a diversionary tactic used by the president and his supporters when the facts are not in their favor. Every American should be appalled by this assault on the truth.\par \par \uc2 Are there biases in the media? Absolutely!\par \par \uc2 But there are two kinds of biases. One is political bias \u8212\'20\'14 conservative versus liberal, which belongs on the editorial page. We do see the political bias of a media source creep into factual reporting from time to time and to varying degrees, which is unfortunate.\par \par \uc2 The other bias is how factual the reporting is. Here we see a spectrum from fact-based, multi-sourced reporting to stories based on misleading information or outright fabrications.\par \par \uc2 The media bias chart available at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.adfontesmedia.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.adfontesmedia.com}}}\uc2  illustrates this nicely. Local newspapers are near the top on the fact scale, while our president\u8217\'20\'19s favorite news source, Fox News, is near the bottom!\par \par \uc2 Lee LaFrese\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020180829ee8t00038\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc13}{\*\bkmkend toc13}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 1,028 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 August 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A15\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 This isn\u8217\'20\'19t the America that I know\par \par \uc2 Re: the Aug. 22 article \u8220\'20\'1CMexican woman not allowed to visit dying husband in US.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 When reading about the denial of our government to not allow a woman to visit her dying husband, I had to read it twice. Is this really happening in America, the land of the brave and the home of the free?\par \par \uc2 I have been privileged to work with Bill, the woman\u8217\'20\'19s son, and his family when I was a counselor at Pueblo Magnet High School. Bill was our valedictorian, a great scholar and a role model for other students.\par \par \uc2 The decision to deny a wife the opportunity to say goodbye to her dying husband and to comfort her children is wrong, un-American and mean-spirited. I always thought the United States was the beacon of hope and compassion.\par \par \uc2 Sa\u250\'00\'FAl Ostroff\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Republican disappointment\par \par \uc2 Re: the Aug. 19 guest column \u8220\'20\'1CWe expected better from Republicans in Congress.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Thank you to Pete and Pat Likins for expecting better from Republicans in Congress. My family\u8217\'20\'19s allegiance to the Republican Party flowed from my great grandfather, who fought under Gen. Grant during the Civil War.\par \par \uc2 Recently, after 61 years, I left the party due to the inability of Republicans in Congress to take action on the separation of children from their parents at the border, presidential failure to support our international allies while leaning toward dictatorships, and tearing apart our society on demographic issues affecting our children\u8217\'20\'19s future.\par \par \uc2 The last straw, as so well articulated by Pete and Pat Likins, was the unwillingness of the Republican-led Congress to take action on these and other issues.\par \par \uc2 June Webb-Vignery\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Bruce Wheeler is best option in CD2\par \par \uc2 Re: the Aug. 14 letter to the editor \u8220\'20\'1CAn alternative in CD2.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I, too, feel that the attacks by Ann Kirkpatrick and Matt Heinz have reduced their prospects for winning the Democratic primary. However, the candidate that I am voting for is Bruce Wheeler. He is not involved in any negative attacks. More importantly, he is for common sense policies concerning climate change, health care, regulations that affect consumers, and a sound public education system. He has had legislative experience both on the Tucson City Council and in the Legislature. Bruce is a candidate that will have his constituents\u8217\'20\'19 best interests at heart.\par \par \uc2 Ellen Shenkarow\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 We teach entitlement not work ethic\par \par \uc2 There is no free lunch. This old saying is negative today, where free lunches are a good thing. Today, a huge percentage of young people\u8217\'20\'19s thought process is of entitlement. Society fosters entitlement. The fact is someone has to pay for excessive spending and giveaways in schools and government. How many of us today choose between needs and wants? Do we need or want \uc2 Starbucks\uc2  coffee instead of McDonalds?\par \par \uc2 The new honors housing tower at the U of A is a great concept and has merit. Is it worth the expenditure versus lower tuition for all students? We say give certain students free tuition, but who helps the working middle class who save and struggle?\par \par \uc2 Pretty buildings produce students with years of debt. The money needs to go to learning. Teaching logical thought and unbiased views furthers decision processes. Abraham Lincoln, Stephen Hawking and our astronauts didn\u8217\'20\'19t need luxuries to learn. What are our values?\par \par \uc2 Ethel Maloney\par \par \uc2 SaddleBrooke\par \par \uc2 Fitz took vacation, I got a break\par \par \uc2 I hope David Fitzsimmons enjoyed his vacation, I know I did. I\u8217\'20\'19m sorry he\u8217\'20\'19s back. It was refreshing to pick up the paper each morning and see submissions by professional cartoonists such as Jeff Stahler, Lisa Benson and Mike Lester. I can\u8217\'20\'19t remember Fitz writing about anything except riding his one trick pony of vitriol toward President Trump since he started running for office. It\u8217\'20\'19s not healthy and I fear for his mental health if the president is elected for a second term.\par \par \uc2 Andrew Gullo\par \par \uc2 Southwest side\par \par \uc2 Keep Fox News, I\u8217\'20\'19ll take real news\par \par \uc2 The right-leaning people complain that the mainstream media is biased to the left. They say that their viewpoints are not represented in equal amounts as the left\u8217\'20\'19s. I can say that Fox News is biased to the right. You\u8217\'20\'19ll say that \uc2 Fox\uc2  invites guests from the left to be on their show, but then they talk over and ridicule their guests. That is hardly a chance to have your side heard.\par \par \uc2 Each side needs an outlet to have their views heard. You have Fox News, we have real news.\par \par \uc2 Real news will never shout you down or talk over you when you\u8217\'20\'19re trying to make a point.\par \par \uc2 Daniel Poryanda\par \par \uc2 Southeast side\par \par \uc2 Well-deserved arrest\par \par \uc2 An article in the Star last week spoke about an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  detained in California while taking his pregnant wife to the hospital. It was a tear-jerking missive that outlined just how cruel and unfeeling law enforcement is to honest persons breaking no laws.\par \par \uc2 I\u8217\'20\'19m positive that every liberal within shouting distance unleashed diatribes about that sorry state of affairs. So sad.\par \par \uc2 But wait a minute, today\u8217\'20\'19s Star revealed that he actually was wanted on a warrant from Mexico for murder. I guess he isn\u8217\'20\'19t such a pure individual after all. His wife\u8217\'20\'19s attorney \u8212\'20\'14 notice that he already has one \u8212\'20\'14 said, \u8220\'20\'1Cthe issue is not so much the arrest, but the total disregard for the health and well-being of the mother.\u8221\'20\'1D Yes, you read that right. We are now expected to release law breakers because it might possibly cause the family some stress.\par \par \uc2 Phil Reinecker\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Bring in a grown-up\par \par \uc2 To those Democrats in CD2, I hope you send the squabbling toddlers Ann Kirkpatrick and Matt Heinz back to the nursery and put an adult presence in the room, like Mary Matiella. I am ashamed of the Democratic Party for supporting either Kirkpatrick or Heinz. Neither seems to want to give us reasons to vote for them, only to hurt the other candidate. We need better judgment and greater integrity from people running for office.\par \par \uc2 Caren Smith\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020180824ee8o0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc14}{\*\bkmkend toc14}\b \uc2 Letters to the editor\b0\par\par\uc2 755 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 July 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A08\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Migrants put their kids in harm\u8217\'20\'19s way\par \par \uc2 I am tired of hearing all the hoopla over reuniting \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  families. Those parents made a conscientious decision to put their children\u8217\'20\'19s life in danger when they decided to cross the border illegally with them.\par \par \uc2 We have child-endangerment laws in this country designed to protect children from harm. If you or I were to put our children into a car and drive while intoxicated, we would be guilty of child endangerment. The same applies here. These parents endangered the lives of their children. They knew the risks and decided to do it anyway. What kind of parent does that and why should we reward them?\par \par \uc2 Debra Jackley\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 US is responsible for immigration crisis\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 1 column \u8220\'20\'1CImmigrant child crisis at border is Obama\u8217\'20\'19s fault.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 In response to Joseph Morgan\u8217\'20\'19s column, this claim was made by many pundits in 2014 and was rated as \u8220\'20\'1Cmostly false\u8221\'20\'1D by Politifact. The facts are that in June 2012, four months before the Obama administration implemented DACA, the rate of arrivals nearly doubled. That means the trend was already heating up. It\u8217\'20\'19s foolish to suggest that only one incident caused this most recent influx.\par \par \uc2 The other fact to consider is that Republicans refused to address the issue of these children\u8217\'20\'19s path to citizenship, their typical head-in-the-sand response. Immigration has a long history and consists of many complex angles and factors. The U.S. as a whole is responsible for this crisis. U.S. trade policies that have wreaked havoc on Central America\u8217\'20\'19s economy. It\u8217\'20\'19s very disingenuous to suggest Obama alone, in one stroke of a pen, created this massive humanitarian crisis.\par \par \uc2 Barbara Jones\par \par \uc2 Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 Suicide leaves deep scars\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 1 article \u8220\'20\'1COlder men who end their lives commonly haven\u8217\'20\'19t sought help.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Thank you for publishing this article. I relate well to widows Diane Dail and Laura McGaffey, and offer my condolences and support in their grief.\par \par \uc2 My circumstances were somewhat different. My husband was in treatment with a psychiatrist and on medication at the time he died in July 2015. Firearms were not involved, and we thought he was progressing.\par \par \uc2 My husband suffered lifelong depression that he learned to conceal well. The suicide itself leaves deep scars that are long in healing. I did not feel guilty about the event. I had done everything possible that I could. It was his decision alone. But I suffer again every time I hear about anyone ending their own life.\par \par \uc2 Margaret Drugay\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Improve Speedway west of the \uc2 UA\par \par \uc2 Re: the June 27 guest column \u8220\'20\'1CTucson offers visitors a crummy first impression.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Maybe we\u8217\'20\'19re too familiar with our streets to notice or rarely take the Speedway exit. That doesn\u8217\'20\'19t change the fact that block after block offers views of weeds along curbs and sidewalks (when there are sidewalks), dirt lots and shabby buildings. But visitors do notice. And their children notice.\par \par \uc2 While we were living away for seven years, we met many \uc2 UA\uc2  alums along the way who occasionally returned for games, reunions or academic events.\par \par \uc2 Two comments stand out: \u8220\'20\'1CTucson is a good example of an ugly city in a beautiful setting\u8221\'20\'1D and \u8220\'20\'1CWhen I proudly brought my 10-year-old son to his first \uc2 UA\uc2  basketball game and we got off at Speedway, he asked \u8216\'20\'18Dad, are we in a ghetto?\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 There are signs of economic improvement and downtown looks like a miracle to a returning Tucsonan. Surely we can find a way to revitalize this stretch of road leading into the heart of a beloved city.\par \par \uc2 Patrice Busch\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Human beings aren\u8217\'20\'19t illegal\par \par \uc2 Elie Wiesel, a social activist and Nobel laureate, once gave a talk in Tucson that brought many in the audience to tears. In it, he challenged the phrase \u8220\'20\'1Cillegal aliens,\u8221\'20\'1D still widely used today to refer to people who have immigrated to the United States without proper documentation. He said: \u8220\'20\'1CHow can a human being be illegal?\u8221\'20\'1D \u8220\'20\'1CHow can a human being be an alien?\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 As a psychologist, I am aware that descriptions like these are dehumanizing and can encourage racism and violence. We saw a similar dehumanization by the Nazis who referred to concentration camp prisoners by the numbers they tattooed on prisoners\u8217\'20\'19 arms. Immigrants are people and not \u8220\'20\'1Cillegal aliens.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Let us dispense with pejorative descriptions and refer to them properly and respectfully as undocumented immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Hal Arkowitz\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020180708ee7800038\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc15}{\*\bkmkend toc15}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 984 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 July 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A11\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Have Russia join \uc2 NATO\par \par \uc2 Although not a new idea, President Trump ought to invite President Putin to bring Russia into the \uc2 NATO\uc2  alliance during their upcoming summit. By joining \uc2 NATO\uc2 , Russia\u8217\'20\'19s perceived threat from the West and Eastern Europe would be neutralized and have no basis. Additionally, it would neutralize Putin\u8217\'20\'19s paranoia and re-invented cold-war hegemony while also hypothetically ending our 70-year nuclear standoff. An honest offer of permanent friendship.\par \par \uc2 After the fall of the USSR, and fumbling by Gorbachev and Yeltsin, Putin dragged Russia back to a quasi-communist no-man\u8217\'20\'19s land, and he may see this idea as a way to solve a multitude of problems and gain in popularity \u8212\'20\'14 especially if the Russian people embrace the friendship and transformative economic ties with the West. The United States would make obvious gains \u8212\'20\'14 the most significant being the addition of a powerful ally to help offset the very troubling actions and aims of China.\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s an idea worth trying, especially by President Trump.\par \par \uc2 Jim Terry\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 It\u8217\'20\'19s difficult to justify separation of families\par \par \uc2 President Trump, the U.S. attorney general and several letter writers to this paper have made the argument that the \u8220\'20\'1Czero-tolerance\u8221\'20\'1D policy being used, which separates children from parents, is justified to protect the U.S. and its citizens. This is really an \u8220\'20\'1Cend justifies the means\u8221\'20\'1D argument that has been used to justify immoral, illegal and tyrannical offenses for eons.\par \par \uc2 An extreme example was the Nazi extermination of the German Jews in order to protect the Germanic people and their bloodline. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s policy is certainly nowhere near that extreme but to many Americans and American clergy it is immoral. The vast majority of the anti-policy people do not advocate for open borders but for humane enforcement of just laws, two factors that the situation seems to be completely lacking for now.\par \par \uc2 John Kuisti\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Column that blamed Obama is indefensible\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 1 column \u8220\'20\'1CImmigrant child crisis at border is Obama\u8217\'20\'19s fault.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Trump\u8217\'20\'19s policy of separating \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  families is despicable and will likely cause lasting psychological damage to the children. Joseph Morgan\u8217\'20\'19s column defending Trump and blaming President Obama \u8212\'20\'14 who left office 18 months ago \u8212\'20\'14 was rubbish, and far below the normal editorial standards of the Star.\par \par \uc2 Joe Reiman\par \par \uc2 SaddleBrooke\par \par \uc2 Trump is no Boy Scout\par \par \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  is no Boy Scout. A malignant narcissist incapable of performing a selfless act, he embodies the antithesis of the scout law. Trump is unpredictable, faithless, belligerent, hostile, rude, malicious, defiant, morose, wasteful, craven, vile and decadent.\par \par \uc2 Like all bullies, this depraved miscreant delights in gratuitous cruelty, which explains his merciless policy of \u8220\'20\'1Czero tolerance\u8221\'20\'1D for the most vulnerable targets anyone could find (small children). As for his deplorable sycophants, they would be wise to heed the words of King Solomon: \u8220\'20\'1CHe who justifies the wicked, and he who condemns the just, both of them alike are an abomination to the Lord.\u8221\'20\'1D (Prov. 17:15)\par \par \uc2 John Balsbaugh\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Vote in November to protect our environment\par \par \uc2 For the last two days, the national news has aired segments about the damage being done to our environment by plastics \u8212\'20\'14 bottles, straws and bags. The harm it is doing to our waterways and wildlife is horrendous. And yet, our esteemed lawmakers in Arizona have passed a law to prohibit any city or county from banning any of these products. How is this in our best interest? You have to know they are getting some kind of perk for passing this legislation and they are in it to line their own pockets. When are we going to start voting them out? November is not that far away. Let\u8217\'20\'19s make it count this year!!\par \par \uc2 Sue Walker\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 The circus comes to town; don\u8217\'20\'19t complain\par \par \uc2 Some hard-working Tucson families took their children to the circus last night. They were met with protesters shoving signs of hurt elephants in their faces. These tired, old pictures have never been proven to be true. Our hard earned tax dollars were spent on extra police who let the protesters get very close to the children.\par \par \uc2 I believe in freedom of speech yet believe our children should be left out of the fray. The fact that any show would go to the tattered convention center is beyond me, but why discourage activity there? By the way, it was a great circus. Filled with hard-working, smiling performers. Lighten up, Tucson, and smile more.\par \par \uc2 Ellen Hundshamer\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Poor traffic control in Sahuarita after event\par \par \uc2 I attended a show at Desert Diamond Sahuarita on June 30. Upon leaving the event we were not allowed to turn left onto West Pima Mine Road to head home to Green Valley. To compound the issue, at the time we were ready to turn onto the road, there was NOBODY coming from either direction, the officer was in dark clothes and hard to see, with a flashlight that was barely visible, and not wearing a fluorescent or light colored vest.\par \par \uc2 All of us wanting to go to GV went down to the overpass, made a U-turn, then came back east on West Pima Mine Road so we could get to Nogales Highway and head home. It\u8217\'20\'19s like the Sahuarita police forgot that the southbound on-ramp to I-19 was closed. In all my years of driving, this was the most confusing traffic control I have run across. Wonder if Sahuarita PD would like to comment?\par \par \uc2 Warren McBride\par \par \uc2 Green Valley\par \par \uc2 Don\u8217\'20\'19t miss \u8216\'20\'18Big Fish\u8217\'20\'19\par \par \uc2 Once again, the Arts Express team has produced a top quality production; this time it\u8217\'20\'19s \u8220\'20\'1CBig Fish.\u8221\'20\'1D With only six weeks of rehearsals, this group of talented young people will make you smile, laugh and cry. Don\u8217\'20\'19t miss it.\par \par \uc2 Ethel Haber\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020180706ee7600005\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc16}{\*\bkmkend toc16}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 1,009 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 June 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A13\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 A veiled attack against president\par \par \uc2 Re: the June 10 article \u8220\'20\'1CLabor shortage, uncertainties over steel costs halt work on senior community in Oro Valley.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 An Oro Valley senior community will not be completed, allegedly because of the shortage of labor. This article was nothing but a cloaked effort in support of illegal immigrants and to criticize President Trump! Those interviewed in the article cite mostly the lack of construction labor here for the senior community\u8217\'20\'19s woes. They blamed that on the recent hikes in the minimum wage making entry construction jobs less attractive than working in indoor \u8220\'20\'1Ccooler\u8221\'20\'1D jobs paying the same.\par \par \uc2 One person interviewed blamed the shortage on the lack of \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  labor. Then, there is an ongoing construction boom that taxes available labor. As for President Trump\u8217\'20\'19s tariffs on steel, could not the construction firm have just used more lumber? Why did they not examine the current labor market before breaking ground?\par \par \uc2 Alice Moreno\par \par \uc2 North side\par \par \uc2 Road to nomination wasn\u8217\'20\'19t certain for RFK\par \par \uc2 Re: the June 5 guest column \u8220\'20\'1C50 years after assassination, still occupied by RFK what-ifs.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Mourning Robert Kennedy\u8217\'20\'19s assassination is worthy and beyond partisanship; 1968 was an awful year and he brought excitement to a dreary time, hope for peace instead of mayhem at home and death far away. But when the Jim Lipson says, \u8220\'20\'1CI have no doubt that he would have won the nomination and election as well,\u8221\'20\'1D he should speak with less certainty.\par \par \uc2 Several weeks before the California primary, Kennedy had come to Hubert Humphrey, acknowledged he didn\u8217\'20\'19t have the votes to be nominated, and without a dramatic victory in California, couldn\u8217\'20\'19t possibly get them. He also told Humphrey that he would quickly endorse him as Humphrey had done in 1960 when he lost to John Kennedy in West Virginia. Had Bobby Kennedy somehow won the nomination, he might have been elected, but it didn\u8217\'20\'19t seem so then. He did not carry the Vietnam/LBJ baggage Humphrey did, but he had plenty of his own. I have no doubt. I was there.\par \par \uc2 Norman Sherman\par \par \uc2 Southeast side\par \par \uc2 Puerto Rico treated as a nuisance\par \par \uc2 When Hurricane Maria struck Puerto Rico, it did catastrophic damage to the island, much more than was initially reported by our media. According to recent estimates, the storm killed several thousand people and destroyed hundreds of homes. Puerto Ricans have lost electric power and have little access to food and fresh water. Yet President Trump finds their pleas for help annoying. Why should he listen to them? Those Puerto Ricans may be U.S. citizens, but most of them speak Spanish, and they have darker skin than his. If they want to survive, perhaps the leader of some other country will show more concern for their plight.\par \par \uc2 Richard Coan\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Reimburse US for taking in refugees\par \par \uc2 By freely accepting migrants who claim refugee status, we only encourage foreign countries to use America as a dumping ground. There is no incentive for them to improve conditions so that their citizen remain home. America is only reducing the burden the sending countries should shoulder. It is the old pocketbook issue. America should \u8220\'20\'1Ccharge\u8221\'20\'1D these countries for the cost of accepting their citizens. There are a number of ways America could extract a price and when the cost exceeds whatever benefit the sending country realizes, then they will act to improve conditions.\par \par \uc2 Warren Joblin\par \par \uc2 Green Valley\par \par \uc2 Racial privilege is subject of protests\par \par \uc2 Re: the June 8 letter to the editor \u8220\'20\'1C\uc2 NFL\uc2  players, owners are disrespecting flag.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 I am so happy the letter writer is proud to live in a wonderful, free country with all its beauty and privilege thanks to those who gave their lives. However, if she were a citizen of African descent, she would need to constantly worry about being shot by law enforcement officials just for being black because of the shoot first, ask questions later mentality. If she were a citizen of Hispanic descent in Arizona, she could be stopped without cause because she must be an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Those overinflated egos are not protesting those who gave their lives for this country. They are protesting because much of that beauty and privilege that she enjoys is constantly denied to people of color in this country. They are exercising their right to freedom of speech, and protecting that right was another reason our soldiers gave their lives.\par \par \uc2 Craig Whaley\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Destroy the stigma; talk about suicide\par \par \uc2 Thanks to the Star for the columns and articles about suicide. This is an issue that needs to be discussed openly. For too long the deathly silence around the word itself has caused stigma that lessens the chance desperate people will get help. The act itself can be a result of diagnosed or undiagnosed mental illness or the hopelessness an individual feels at a particular stage of life.\par \par \uc2 Whatever the reason, we as a society need to speak about it, ask if a person is considering suicide when there is indication they might be, and not judge. We will all be touched at some time by someone\u8217\'20\'19s suicide. We all need to know how to intervene and where to get help.\par \par \uc2 No one should be ashamed and have to hide. Let\u8217\'20\'19s help each other in whatever way we can. National Suicide Prevention Lifeline is 1-800-273-8255.\par \par \uc2 Diane Wilson\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Water surcharge a bad idea then and now\par \par \uc2 Re: the June 10 article \u8220\'20\'1CUnincorporated areas facing rate hike not sought by Tucson Water.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 As a former Tucson Water employee I was on duty during the 1976 rate hike fiasco. It was an ill conceived idea then and even more ridiculous today. The concept that the city manager and council can add a tax to county water customers is a half-baked idea and their justification does not hold water. Before wasting city staff time and taxpayer money, spend a few minutes reading the newspaper and talk to Tucson Water.\par \par \uc2 Jim Littleton\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020180614ee6e00031\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc17}{\*\bkmkend toc17}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 1,017 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 April 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A.13\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Teachers walking out for, not on, kids\par \par \uc2 I am a parent and taxpayer and support the vote of Arizona educators to walk out on April 27 unless there is a plan by the governor and Legislature to address the education funding crisis. Gov. Ducey has made an unsustainable proposal that would provide teachers with the potential of a 20 percent raise over three years. Arizona might be able to pay for a 10 percent raise through budget gimmicks, one-time sweeps and shifting resources away from other areas, but we cannot count on funding increases without a sustainable revenue source.\par \par \uc2 There is $1.1 billion less in funding than in 2008. We are 47th in per-student funding. We have the second-largest class sizes in the nation. We are close to last in teacher pay. Educators across the state united and demanded that our students deserve more. They are not walking out ON kids, they are walking out FOR kids. I care about students, educators and Arizona's future --that's why I am RedForEd.\par \par \uc2 Montserrat Caballero\par \par \uc2 Southwest side\par \par \uc2 What happened to service animal law?\par \par \uc2 Re: the April 19 article "AZ makes misrepresenting pets as service animals illegal."\par \par \uc2 People with service dogs have to go through a class and be certified and the dogs have to wear a backpack or other identifier while they are doing their job so people know not to bother them. What happened to that law?\par \par \uc2 Donna Vasquez\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Education issues aren't being reported\par \par \uc2 As a teacher transplant from Minnesota, I am struck by Arizona educators' lack of a voice and the systemic underfunding of public schools here. I am also amazed at the free press, which isn't fully explaining why teachers have decided to strike.\par \par \uc2 The superintendent in our district believes teachers would be "abandoning" our students if they participated in the walkout. No, that blame lies at the feet of the governor and the Legislature who have abandoned education time and time again.\par \par \uc2 Where are the stories about the sleight of hand and duplicity our elected officials use in their drive to cripple public education? Does the public really know about the multiple federal rulings that have come down on the side of education which continue to be ignored (illegally) by our elected officials? Dark money is winning and the press is complicit through its inability and/or unwillingness to make the voting public aware of the entire story.\par \par \uc2 Kris Killian\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Old bracero program left many wanting\par \par \uc2 Regarding the suggestion to return to the bracero program to help solve \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  "problems," I taught kindergarten in Fresno County, Calif., during the era of bracero programs on the '50s and early '60s. It may have been good for the farmers, but it was not a "win" for children and other humanistic priorities. Families were not covered in the law, and instead of having at least minimal housing provisions, unauthorized and unrecognized families were sleeping in culverts under the highway.\par \par \uc2 I, perhaps naively, believed that learning English would contribute to the children's "way out," and I have done what I could to promote that end. But there is still the same problem. Yes, it is an educational one, and economic, but above all, moral. I keep the belief that the welfare of children and families (not of entrepreneurs and political parties) should be our priority when deciding whom to vote for this fall.\par \par \uc2 Muriel Saville-Troike\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Judge was following the law\par \par \uc2 Re: the April 18 letter to the editor "Judge's decision sends wrong message."\par \par \uc2 The letter asked why a defendant in a criminal case would be permitted to travel outside of Arizona. It is important to recall that a person accused of a crime is innocent until proven guilty, and also that the purpose of pretrial supervision by the court is not to impose punishment. Judges do not take requests to travel lightly, and when the accused dutifully appears in court , lives responsibly in the community without causing problems and demonstrates through his conduct that the court can trust him to travel outside the state, it is appropriate to approve such a request.\par \par \uc2 Undoubtedly, Judge Teresa Godoy considered these factors and many others presented by both the prosecution and the defense in reaching her decision. Judge Godoy is a well-respected Superior Court judge who acted within her discretion and followed the law in permitting the requested travel. Any criticism for doing what the law provides is unfair and unwarranted.\par \par \uc2 Louis Fidel\par \par \uc2 Downtown\par \par \uc2 Enjoy outdoor sculptures at JCC\par \par \uc2 Re: the April 18 letter to the editor "Tucson needs a sculpture park."\par \par \uc2 The crowds at Brandi Fenton the other weekend demonstrated Tucsonans' interest in seeing sculpture. Readers of the Star should know about the wonderful sculpture garden they can visit at the Tucson Jewish Community Center, 3800 E. River Road. It is open without charge, Sunday-Friday, to JCC members and nonmembers alike.\par \par \uc2 The garden has dozens of sculptures, 2-feet to 40-feet tall, realistic and abstract, metal and stone. Stop at the JCC reception desk to get directions to the garden and a free booklet giving background on the artworks. Free tours can be arranged for groups of six or more.\par \par \uc2 Neil Weinstein\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 South side needs some fun, too\par \par \uc2 Re: the April 20 article "Arcade bar set to open this summer in downtown Tucson."\par \par \uc2 I think this is really awesome and Tucson definitely deserves something so cool. However, what I am not happy with is the way something was worded in the article. I grew up on the southwest side of Tucson, and compared to all the other sides of the city, there was nothing to do. So to say that the Dave and Busters came to town BUT on the south side makes me really, really mad. You know how often I had to drive to the northeast side of town to do something fun? Almost every other weekend. More things should open in southern Tucson; those families deserve fun things, too.\par \par \uc2 Carolyn Averts\par \par \uc2 Southwest side\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020180423ee4n00004\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc18}{\*\bkmkend toc18}\b \uc2 'Lawful status' definition may decide tuition for 'dreamers' immigration status'\b0\par\par\uc2 Howard Fischer \par \uc2 661 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 March 2018\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A.2\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 PHOENIX -- The question of how much it will cost "dreamers" to get a higher education in Arizona could turn on who the state Supreme Court decides is in this country with "lawful immigration status."\par \par \uc2 In new legal filings, the attorney for the Maricopa community colleges told the justices that phrase is the same as "lawful presence." Mary O'Grady said those in the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program fit that definition because the \uc2 Department of Homeland Security\uc2  has -- at least for the moment -- allowed them to not only remain without fear of deportation but also to work.\par \par \uc2 But Attorney General \uc2 Mark Brnovich\uc2 , in new legal briefs, contends that acceptance into the DACA program does not translate into being in this country legally.\par \par \uc2 All that is important because Proposition 300, approved by voters in 2006, specifically says that anyone who is not a citizen or legal resident or who is "without lawful immigration status is not entitled to classification as an in-state student."\par \par \uc2 Brnovich contends -- and the Court of Appeals agreed -- that does not entitle dreamers to pay the lower tuition being charged by the Maricopa colleges, some other community colleges and the state university system. The Supreme Court has agreed to hear arguments early next month and reach its own conclusion.\par \par \uc2 In some ways the fight is less about the law and more about who gets to define what some words mean.\par \par \uc2 O'Grady points out that Prop. 300 doesn't define "lawful immigration status."\par \par \uc2 Instead, she said, it makes a reference to the 1996 federal \uc2 Illegal Immigrant\uc2  Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act. And that law talks about those who are not "lawfully present" in this country.\par \par \uc2 She also noted that another provision of Prop. 300 requires colleges and universities to report students who are denied financial assistance because they were "not lawfully present."\par \par \uc2 What makes that significant, O'Grady argues, is DACA.\par \par \uc2 That program, approved by the Obama administration in 2012, specifically allows those in the program to not only remain without fear of deportation but also to be issued Employment Authorization Documents (EADs) entitling them to work here.\par \par \uc2 "Because DACA recipients' stays in the United States are authorized by the \uc2 Department of Homeland Security\uc2  while they are in the DACA program, they are lawfully present under this statutory definition," O'Grady wrote. And that, in turn, allows them to attend community colleges and universities paying only in-state tuition if they meet other residency requirements.\par \par \uc2 Brnovich, for his part, urged the justices to reject what he sees as a stretch in verbiage.\par \par \uc2 He told the justices that the key elements of the 2006 law limit in-state tuition to only those with "lawful immigration status." And Brnovich said they should not accept O'Grady's bid to conflate that phrase "lawful presence."\par \par \uc2 "If Prop. 300 is to be rewritten in the name of absurdity, the substantive provisions should control the reporting provisions -- not the other way around," he said.\par \par \uc2 What the justices decide ultimately will affect more than the Maricopa colleges, which were sued in 2013 by Tom Horne, Brnovich's predecessor, after the board concluded that DACA recipients, by virtue of the EADs they possess, are entitled to the presumption of being here legally.\par \par \uc2 Two years later, Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Arthur Anderson sided with the colleges. That, in turn, spurred the \uc2 Arizona Board of Regents\uc2  to establish a similar policy.\par \par \uc2 At last count, about 300 dreamers are attending one of the state's three universities while paying in-state tuition.\par \par \uc2 The difference in costs is significant.\par \par \uc2 At the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2 , for example, current tuition and mandatory fees for new students this year is $12,228 for those who qualify as residents. The figure for new out-of-state students is $35,658.\par \par \uc2 Pima Community College\uc2  also now offers in-state tuition to DACA recipients.\par \par \uc2 Credit: Howard Fischer Capitol Media Services\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020180307ee370008m\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc19}{\*\bkmkend toc19}\b \uc2 Letters to the editor\b0\par\par\uc2 975 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 September 2017\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2017 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Learn to keep litter in its place\par \par \uc2 Please dispose of your trash properly. Please don't litter -- it's that easy. Downtown Tucson and our surrounding communities are beautiful. What possesses someone to litter? Like so many things, this bad habit is learned by example. We're not born with a littering gene. Kids learn by watching their parents and their friends litter. It wasn't that long ago that anti-littering campaigns were common in communities. Have we given up and are now willing to live with the trash?\par \par \uc2 Many wonderful volunteers invest their own time in cleaning up after their trashy neighbors. Imagine what those volunteer hours could accomplish if put to work advancing our community instead of picking up after others. Would education in our schools help break the cycle? If children question their parents and friends when they litter, would those litterers think twice before doing it again? There has to be an answer. We're better than this, Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Guy Brunt\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Bishop's belonging aren't 'baubles'\par \par \uc2 Re: the Sept. 9 article "Biblical baubles: Bishop to hold yard sale."\par \par \uc2 I found the words "Biblical baubles" used in reference to the upcoming sale of personal items belonging to Bishop Gerald Kicanas of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Tucson to be disrespectful and condescending.\par \par \uc2 I would feel this way no matter what religion was being addressed. The word "bauble" means something frivolous and without value. These religious items are held dear by many Roman Catholics and any reference made to them deserves to be respectful, not ridiculous.\par \par \uc2 Patsy O'Brien\par \par \uc2 Downtown\par \par \uc2 Ground subsidence still occurring\par \par \uc2 Re: the Sept. 4 article "Pumping rules cited as Tucson ground subsidence slows."\par \par \uc2 Maybe subsidence has slowed for the entire city, but you'd never know it to see my house! Sections of the garage floor are sunken an inch, the center of the house is sinking so that cracks are appearing in the tile in several rooms. We are one subdivision from the Tanque Verde Wash, but I don't know if that's the reason. What to do!?\par \par \uc2 Helen Lindberg\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Fitz's retirement can't come soon enough\par \par \uc2 I remember when editorial cartoonist David Fitzsimmons started at the Star 30-odd years ago. Up to that time, I had been an avid reader of the editorial page cartoons for decades. Back then, you published cartoons from many different sources. It was enjoyable and helped soak a wee bit of politics into my non-political brain. That all ended when you hired Fitz.\par \par \uc2 I found his artwork and topics unappealing -- unreadable, actually. So I guess I owe him a "thank you" for 30 years of not ever looking at the editorial cartoons in the Star. And when I run across an article written by him, I would never read it.\par \par \uc2 Thad Appelman\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Border wall puts US on USSR's page\par \par \uc2 Re: the Sept. 6 letter to the editor "Berlin Wall holds forgotten lessons."\par \par \uc2 As I read the letter, my eyes teared up. In 1968, I walked through Checkpoint Charlie for the first time. It was one of the most horrifying experiences of my life. As a librarian and history/geography teacher, my students learned of the wall through my experience. I cannot believe my country would follow the actions of the former USSR.\par \par \uc2 Ginny Berkey\par \par \uc2 SaddleBrooke\par \par \uc2 Trump and Arpaio are bullies\par \par \uc2 Re: the Sept. 5 letter to the editor "Complainers should read the Constitution."\par \par \uc2 The writer points out that President Trump had pardon power, so that should be the "end of discussion." I say, baloney! Just because the president can pardon federal crimes, as in the case of Joe Arpaio, we must speak out until the president's ears ring with the sounds of our indignation. If we sound off enough, maybe he will find his moral compass and act in the true spirit of the Constitution and let the law take its course in the future.\par \par \uc2 Some call Trump and Arpaio heroes, but heroes don't break laws. Heroes don't demean people. Heroes don't let their petty prejudices overrule their knowledge of right and wrong. We should continue to speak out and reaffirm that we know Trump and Arpaio for what they are -- mean-spirited bullies and bigots.\par \par \uc2 David Pear\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Blame the parents for DACA debacle\par \par \uc2 There is outrage by some -- including the Star -- at President Trump for rescinding President Obama's DACA executive order, which was likely unconstitutional, circumventing the legislative process. But the blame here is neither on Trump or Obama, but rather on the parents of these "Dreamers," who either brought their children with them when being smuggled into the U.S. or later placed them alone in the hands of violent Mexican smugglers.\par \par \uc2 Either way, the parents committed felony child endangerment. It is a known tactic used by the adult \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  population to bring their children into the country, believing that they become safer from deportation. Any new immigration legislation related to DACA needs to contain future punishment for the parents, acting as deterrent, so this mess does not repeat itself!\par \par \uc2 David Michael\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 If not gun control now, then when?\par \par \uc2 Re: the Sept. 7 article "City ends policy on smashing firearms."\par \par \uc2 Thank you to the Tucson Police Department and Tucson City Council for fighting the good fight. At least some guns were put out of commission. We can only hope that sanity will prevail someday. But, as Rabbi Cohen has said over and over again at the annual memorial services to honor those killed and wounded on Jan. 8, 2011, if we do not do something about guns now, when? Thank you to everyone who speaks so clearly, honestly and sanely on the gun issue. Truly, if not now, when?\par \par \uc2 Sally Evans\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020170912ed9c0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\bkmkstart toc20}{\*\bkmkend toc20}\b \uc2 TPD denies politics at play in decision to halt aid in BP search\b0\par\par\uc2 Caitlin Schmidt \par \uc2 638 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 March 2017\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2017 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The Tucson Police Department's decision not to continue searching for a suspect who escaped from Border Patrol agents is being criticized as a political move. A man matching the suspect's description was spotted in the area of North First Avenue and West Elm Street, and TPD officers immediately responded to help find the suspect, as they would in any situation where a law enforcement agency asks for help, said Bay. [...]my concern is that if...\par \par \uc2 The Tucson Police Department's decision not to continue searching for a suspect who escaped from Border Patrol agents is being criticized as a political move.\par \par \uc2 TPD refused to further assist in the Friday night pursuit of a "fleeing felon" due to the political climate, the president of National Border Patrol Council said Saturday.\par \par \uc2 However, TPD officials said the department pulled out of the search after being unable to find the suspect in the specified area and that staff was needed to address other calls.\par \par \uc2 Carlos Erazo-Velasquez, 37, from Honduras, escaped from agents at Banner-University Medical Center Tucson after previously attempting to evade arrest and assaulting a Border Patrol agent, officials said.\par \par \uc2 Tucson police received a call from the Border Patrol shortly after 5 p.m. Friday, apprising them of the situation, said Sgt. Kimberly Bay, a TPD spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 A man matching the suspect's description was spotted in the area of North First Avenue and West Elm Street, and TPD officers immediately responded to help find the suspect, as they would in any situation where a law enforcement agency asks for help, said Bay.\par \par \uc2 Seventeen officers, including three K9 officers and the TPD air unit, helped in the search for more than two hours, she said.\par \par \uc2 As the evening progressed, protesters heard about the search and came to the hospital, believing that Erazo-Velasquez was being pursued for illegal entry into the country, Art Del Cueto, president of the National Border Patrol Council, told the Star on Saturday.\par \par \uc2 "This (the search) had nothing to do with immigration," he said. "This wasn't an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  loose in the desert; he was in the city and near the university."\par \par \uc2 The protesters blocked a Border Patrol vehicle, Del Cueto said. Agents moved their command center to the TPD west-side substation parking lot on Miracle Mile, roughly four miles away, after protesters arrived at the hospital.\par \par \uc2 Later Friday night, TPD told Border Patrol agents they could no longer help, Del Cueto said.\par \par \uc2 And TPD management asked agents to leave the substation, saying they'd received a number of calls for service that they needed to respond to, Del Cueto said.\par \par \uc2 "With Border Patrol agents and vehicles searching the alleys and streets, I understand why citizens were calling in," Del Cueto said.\par \par \uc2 "But my concern is that if this man attacked a federal agent with a gun, what would he do to an average citizen he encountered in the streets?"\par \par \uc2 Del Cueto said agents were told that TPD couldn't assist because of the current political climate.\par \par \uc2 TPD said its actions were about resources, not politics.\par \par \uc2 "TPD officers determined, based on their experience of conducting thousands of urban-area searches, that the subject was most likely not within the contained area and further searching was futile," Bay said.\par \par \uc2 "Given the time of night, busy call volume and a lack of the staff necessary to manage a demonstration at the substation, we were unable to accommodate this request and asked USBP to relocate to their own facility," Bay said.\par \par \uc2 TPD's current policy is to provide assistance as needed or requested and if the staffing level allows based on the totality of the circumstances of the situation or incident, Bay said.\par \par \uc2 Credit: Caitlin Schmidt Arizona Daily Star\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020170306ed350000o\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\bkmk