int that is becomes a crisis for us to finally act. I think we are there now."\par \par \uc2 "Securing the border has a new meaning now, and not just because of illegal immigration or drug cartels that we've really focused on," he said. "With the advent of ISIS and terrorists, it stands to reason that if this volume of people are crossing undetected with military training and all of the financial resources at their disposal, that they can get in just as easy, if not easier."\par \par \uc2 "My values haven't changed. This is what I've done all along," he said. "What has changed is the party I was with."\par \par \uc2 The race for Congressional District 1 is considered one of the most competitive in the nation, with both the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee and the National Republican Congressional Committee trying to boost their party's candidate to victory.\par \par \uc2 Republican Pinal County Sheriff Paul Babeu and Democratic former state Sen. Tom O'Halleran both want the open seat, vacated when Democrat Ann Kirkpatrick decided to try to unseat long-serving Republican \uc2 Sen. John McCain\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 A fixture in Pinal County politics, residents in other parts of the district might know Babeu best for walking side-by-side with then-presidential candidate McCain in a political ad when McCain uttered the phrase, "Complete the danged (border) fence."\par \par \uc2 O'Halleran is better known in the northern part of the state. He is a former Republican state lawmaker who lost his seat in 2008 when he was challenged by Prescott rancher and businessman \uc2 Steve Pierce\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Two years ago, O'Halleran attempted to get his Senate seat back by running as an independent. He now identifies as a Democrat, and easily defeated his Democratic rival in the August primary.\par \par \uc2 The Cook Political Report, a nonpartisan online newsletter that analyzes elections and campaigns says the race is too close to call, labeling it a "Democratic toss-up."\par \par \uc2 THE DISTRICT'S\par \par \uc2 BIG ISSUES\par \par \uc2 Shortly after learning he had won the Republican primary last month, Babeu shifted his focus to what he called the single largest issue in the district -- coal.\par \par \uc2 Less understood in the southernmost part of the vast district, Babeu said the \uc2 Environmental Protection Agency\uc2  has overstepped its mandate by announcing mandatory cuts in the use of coal for power generation.\par \par \uc2 Such proposals could close the coal-powered Navajo generating station, putting thousands out of work, constricting regional energy supplies and likely fueling increases in energy rates.\par \par \uc2 Speaking out against the \uc2 EPA\uc2  has solidified a Republican base wary of federal mandates and has served as an attack against O'Halleran, who once served as a consultant to environmental groups.\par \par \uc2 "There are 3,000 jobs directly connected to the four coal-fired generating stations in Arizona," Babeu said. "They are all in District 1."\par \par \uc2 O'Halleran also opposes the \uc2 EPA\uc2 's mandates, saying they were made without being part of a national energy policy and without concern to how they would affect rural communities.\par \par \uc2 "This is not that competitiveness is taking us out, this is government coming in ... without any concern about you, the school district, the fire district or the community around these power plants," he said. "Some of our best jobs in the district are either at the power plants or at the mines on the Navajo Reservation."\par \par \uc2 Both men believe in climate change, with O'Halleran saying he pressured the \uc2 Bureau of Reclamation\uc2  to include climate change in its modeling system for the Colorado River more than a decade ago.\par \par \uc2 Babeu says he wants to see the coal industry adopt new technology to cut pollution. However, he believes it would take more than a decade to bring new energy sources like natural gas to rural Arizona.\par \par \uc2 O'Halleran notes that even \uc2 Hillary Clinton\uc2  has an energy plan using coal.\par \par \uc2 "Everybody has talked about it," he said.\par \par \uc2 BABEU: TIME TO ACT\par \par \uc2 ON IMMIGRATION\par \par \uc2 On the campaign trail, Babeu still gets questions about getting comprehensive immigration reform through Congress. He remains optimistic that Congress will tackle the issue next year.\par \par \uc2 "So many people have asked me that same question, 'Is this ever going to get resolved?'" said Babeu. "The most important issues in this country seem to percolate to the point that is becomes a crisis for us to finally act. I think we are there now."\par \par \uc2 The biggest issue, for him, continues to be securing the border against possible terrorists sneaking into the country.\par \par \uc2 "Securing the border has a new meaning now, and not just because of illegal immigration or drug cartels that we've really focused on," he said. "With the advent of ISIS and terrorists, it stands to reason that if this volume of people are crossing undetected with military training and all of the financial resources at their disposal, that they can get in just as easy, if not easier."\par \par \uc2 He stopped short of saying how often he believed such people were crossing into Arizona from Mexico.\par \par \uc2 "I am not saying that there is a mad rush of these individuals. What I am saying is that it should raise eyebrows," Babeu said. "All of us should want a sovereign, secure border because of that."\par \par \uc2 Babeu has had his share of political scandals, including allegations that abusive disciplinary practices were used on students at a private school he once ran in Massachusetts and media reports that the fierce opponent of illegal immigration had a romantic relationship with an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Babeu has dismissed the attacks as thinly veiled political hit pieces, going so far as to file a bar complaint against Democratic Massachusetts Rep. Katherine Clark for her allegations that Babeu attempted to thwart an investigation into the school.\par \par \uc2 Babeu ran the school 15 years ago.\par \par \uc2 The primary was also hard on Babeu, as two of his sisters endorsed one of his Republican rivals, Wendy Rogers.\par \par \uc2 "Paul thinks only of himself and his political career at the expense of others. He does not care about the people whom elected officials are called to serve," sister Veronica Babeu Keating said in a prepared statement.\par \par \uc2 O'HALLERAN: I HAVEN'T CHANGED; THE GOP HAS\par \par \uc2 O'Halleran's break from the Republican party happened years ago.\par \par \uc2 "My values haven't changed. This is what I've done all along," he said. "What has changed is the party I was with."\par \par \uc2 His core issue is how GOP leadership slashed education funding in 2009 when facing a state budget crisis.\par \par \uc2 O'Halleran said he was devastated that the Legislature was willing to sacrifice K-12 education as well as money to community colleges and the state universities rather than making cuts elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 "It is short-sighted and not the direction our country should be going in," O'Halleran said.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, the Legislature dismantled reforms he helped to enact regarding Child Protective Services by gutting funding.\par \par \uc2 "Tearing apart families is not leadership," he said.\par \par \uc2 He said he ran for Congress once learning that his friend Ann Kirkpatrick, with whom he served in the Legislature, was running for another office.\par \par \uc2 "I ran because I feel that Congress has let people down," he said.\par \par \uc2 Topping his political priorities is a jobs plan that focuses on education, job training and improvements in infrastructure -- particularly broadband internet service -- in rural parts of the state.\par \par \uc2 He believes high-speed Internet access is essential for education and small businesses to survive and to allow rural Arizonans to compete in the 21st century.\par \par \uc2 Credit: Joe Ferguson Arizona Daily Star\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020161026ec9p006k4\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\bkmkstart toc23}{\*\bkmkend toc23}\b \uc2 Letters to the editor\b0\par\par\uc2 995 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 March 2016\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2016 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 You may not get who you want, but this isn't "America's Got Talent" or "Dancing with the Stars." It is a right, obligation and responsibility as an American citizen.\par \par \uc2 Re: the March 17 letter "Here's what's offensive about the rich guy."\par \par \uc2 I am disgusted in the GOP trying to railroad the Republican nomination. I cannot even believe that as poor performance, leadership and low support as the Republican Party has had, that the GOP would try and derail their front runner. That shows America how corrupt the Washington establishment is, as well as their disavowing the people's voice.\par \par \uc2 Voting is important part of being American\par \par \uc2 A few words to the voting public. Please, just vote, vote, vote!\par \par \uc2 You may not get who you want, but this isn't "America's Got Talent" or "Dancing with the Stars." It is a right, obligation and responsibility as an American citizen.\par \par \uc2 We don't want to lose that right. Grit your teeth and mark your ballot or pull the lever.\par \par \uc2 Stan Boren\par \par \uc2 Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 Classes of stocks were misstated in letter\par \par \uc2 Re: the March 17 letter "Here's what's offensive about the rich guy."\par \par \uc2 This letter was very opinionated and had several misstatements. Some publicly-traded corporations have class A and class B shares.\par \par \uc2 The difference in the classes is usually in the voting rights. It's a way for the founders of the business to continue to control it. No classes of stock are guaranteed to receive every penny back in liquidation. If the corporation goes bankrupt all classes of stock could get wiped out.\par \par \uc2 A balance sheet depicts the assets, liabilities and capital of an entity at month or year-end. If some people pay less for things than others it has nothing to do with a balance sheet.\par \par \uc2 Douglas R. Holm\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Legislature is not acting in our interest\par \par \uc2 Some of our legislators seem to believe that in a republic, the Legislature should have more power than the people they represent; therefore, the advance of HCR 2043. It currently requires three-fourths of each house to change a successful initiative.\par \par \uc2 We must not support HCR 2043 in November. Successful initiatives represent the direct will of the people.\par \par \uc2 Let us remember that it was our representatives who completely ignored an initiative measure to devote additional tax money to public education.\par \par \uc2 We cannot trust the state Legislature to always act in our expressed interest, so we should not make it any easier to change or repeal an approved initiative simply because lawmakers did not like what the people approved.\par \par \uc2 Our system of a republic also believes in the idea of government of, by, and for the people. At times this requires direct representative in government through an initiative.\par \par \uc2 Craig Whaley\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Public education must be maintained\par \par \uc2 Kudos for outstanding editorial content on March 17. Fitzsimmons' cartoon made me laugh until I realized the horrible prospect of a Trump presidency.\par \par \uc2 Reading the article by Michael Gerson, one gets a view of the unenviable options of honorable Republicans: to accommodate Trump, sitting out the election, supporting a third party candidate, or contemplating a difficult vote for Clinton. What a dilemma!\par \par \uc2 As a first generation American I enjoyed reading and related to Raymond Farrish's article on immigration and education. It is no small miracle that I live comfortably in Tucson, Arizona of the United States.\par \par \uc2 My grandparents and my parents were immigrants, my father was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 I did not speak English until a dedicated teacher named Miss Christman taught me to read, speak, and write English in first grade in a public school.\par \par \uc2 Fortunate to have been born here, I was entitled to receive a free public education and in the process became a full-fledged citizen. Public education is the vehicle that must be maintained.\par \par \uc2 Angel Voyatzis\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 GOP disgusts in its attempt to derail Trump\par \par \uc2 I am disgusted in the GOP trying to railroad the Republican nomination. I cannot even believe that as poor performance, leadership and low support as the Republican Party has had, that the GOP would try and derail their front runner. That shows America how corrupt the Washington establishment is, as well as their disavowing the people's voice.\par \par \uc2 The media and corrupt politicians have done their best to discredit one of their own to save their pocket-lining positions.\par \par \uc2 Afraid of Trump? Yes, because they are afraid their scam is up. If they derail the nomination, I believe they will have a huge problem.\par \par \uc2 The people are speaking and will not give up this time. I do not have much faith in the GOP establishment. If they continue to railroad, I'm done with the GOP.\par \par \uc2 Melissa Rogers\par \par \uc2 Marana\par \par \uc2 Lawmakers should be ashamed, not angry\par \par \uc2 Re: the March 15 article "Historic status for mining site provokes anger from lawmakers."\par \par \uc2 I stand with the San Carlos Apache tribe in solidarity.\par \par \uc2 I learned about this political injustice last August and was appalled to learn about the midnight rider that \uc2 Sen. John McCain\uc2  sneaked into a must-pass national defense spending bill transferring Oak Flat to a foreign-owned mining company for the largest copper-mining project in North America.\par \par \uc2 I started researching. The more I learned, the angrier I became. I couldn't believe that \uc2 John McCain\uc2 , Sen. Jeff Flake and Rep. Ann Kirkpatrick could do something so wrong on so many levels.\par \par \uc2 I went to Oak Flat to see for myself what this place was all about. The moment I arrived, I knew it must be protected. I've been back every weekend since.\par \par \uc2 I camp, hike, and learn by talking to the Apache people, the ones most affected.\par \par \uc2 I talk to the elders. I ask questions and listen intently. I've seen archaeological sites, swam in the waters, explored caves, played with the children. I pray in unity with the Apaches, and know the truth.\par \par \uc2 Leslie Glass\par \par \uc2 Marana\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020161026ec3l0027e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\bkmkstart toc24}{\*\bkmkend toc24}\b \uc2 Letters to the editor\b0\par\par\uc2 1,074 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 February 2016\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2016 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 If he got over his fixation on [Obama], he might have found the source of the malaise in the Supreme Court's \uc2 Citizens United\uc2  decision, or in Bush Junior's unleashing of chaos in the Middle East, or the Clinton-era repeal of Glass-Steagall , which began the slow motion destruction of the economy, or Reagan's explosion of the federal budget deficit, or Nixon's abrogation of the Bretton Woods currency exchange system. Explanations abound. History is complicated, but the stench is undeniable.\par \par \uc2 I read your opinion piece about \uc2 Hillary Clinton\uc2  where you say she has become "The Man." I'm 68 and don't know many young women. I am glad to see young men and women getting invested in politics. I think it is great that Bernie Sanders is exciting the democratic youth. \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2 's excitation of the Republican base is frightening to me.\par \par \uc2 Your Feb. 16 headline on Obama's possible choice for Antonin Scalia's replacement was hilarious: "Obama could lean to the left on court nominee." What a shock. I suggest you follow up with an equally startling story with the headline "Pope could possibly be Catholic."\par \par \uc2 Why American politics are corrupt\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 13 column "Sanders and Trump soar by defying logic and history."\par \par \uc2 Poor Charles Krauthammer. He seems unable to get over his dismay at the wrong-headedness of the American electorate who are enamored with candidates that lash out at the corrupt political system. His explanation: it's all about Obama. He should have fixed things by now.\par \par \uc2 If he got over his fixation on Obama, he might have found the source of the malaise in the Supreme Court's \uc2 Citizens United\uc2  decision, or in Bush Junior's unleashing of chaos in the Middle East, or the Clinton-era repeal of Glass-Steagall , which began the slow motion destruction of the economy, or Reagan's explosion of the federal budget deficit, or Nixon's abrogation of the Bretton Woods currency exchange system. Explanations abound. History is complicated, but the stench is undeniable.\par \par \uc2 Steve Hahn\par \par \uc2 Downtown\par \par \uc2 Immigrants should try to become Americans\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 13 letter "Immigrants work, support their families."\par \par \uc2 I ran across the letter about "dehumanization" of immigrants. That's quite a statement to make in the land of the free.\par \par \uc2 Having been a legal immigrant many years ago myself, I must say that I have never experienced inhumane or, as the writer suggests, "dehumanizing" behavior toward me. An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  may be frowned upon as their status is against the law. No doubt many work hard but many get government handouts, and remember, we are the government. I raised my children the American way -- choose your destiny, stick to it and be proud of your heritage. They all succeeded.\par \par \uc2 Consider this: If you don't want to speak the language of your new country and don't wish to adjust to its customs, it may be harder for you to be recognized as one of them. This makes common sense and has nothing to do with inhumanity.\par \par \uc2 Liane Fossland\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 A big market in the wrong place\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 15 article "Neighbors opposing height of Fry's store."\par \par \uc2 We are original homeowners of 38 years in the subdivision and street directly on the north perimeter of this newly proposed development. This is not simply about a decrease in property values, hundreds of cars coming and going all day and night, and some outrage about the impact to our everyday lives.\par \par \uc2 Many of us feel this opens the door to developers to scrape the desert and bulldoze closer and closer to Saguaro National Park. We have empty supermarkets here within a 2-mile radius. It is foolish to build the biggest supermarket in Pima County on only 17 acres.\par \par \uc2 Representatives for the developer focus on those who accept this total disregard for the Houghton East Neighborhood Plan and Plan Tucson requirements. This is our home.\par \par \uc2 Vicki Senter Sheley\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Young should take responsibility and vote\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 11 Sarah Garrecht Gassen column "Clinton's tact with young women voters needs fresh approach."\par \par \uc2 I read your opinion piece about \uc2 Hillary Clinton\uc2  where you say she has become "The Man." I'm 68 and don't know many young women. I am glad to see young men and women getting invested in politics. I think it is great that Bernie Sanders is exciting the democratic youth. \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2 's excitation of the Republican base is frightening to me.\par \par \uc2 But to me, your statement that it doesn't matter that \uc2 Hillary Clinton\uc2  speaks from experience is unfortunate. I think that \uc2 Hillary Clinton\uc2  is probably the most qualified candidate who has ever run for president. I'm impressed that she has laid out thoughtful and detailed plans with workable implementation.\par \par \uc2 I will embrace young people and say it is your time. You don't have to know or recognize what old women have done for women's rights so far.\par \par \uc2 The future is yours and I hope that young people accept their right and responsibility of casting their vote.\par \par \uc2 Barbara Moore\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Another failure for the mental health system\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 16 article "New mental health goals place strain on agencies."\par \par \uc2 We react with horror every time we experience another mass shooting and predictably we lament the failures of the mental health system. Your article describes another horror we have been avoiding for years: the total refusal of our society to fund and support basic public mental health services.\par \par \uc2 Mental health workers often work for low wages in dangerous conditions trying to help the most damaged and neglected members of our society. When a corporation such as Cenpatico has the ability to decide that "agencies who don't bill for at least 75 percent of that funding allocation won't get paid at all for the month," these workers and these clients are the ones who suffer. In the bigger picture we all suffer from the failure to fund and support a reasonable, efficient public mental health system.\par \par \uc2 Anne Gooden\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Obama headline stated the obvious\par \par \uc2 Your Feb. 16 headline on Obama's possible choice for Antonin Scalia's replacement was hilarious: "Obama could lean to the left on court nominee." What a shock. I suggest you follow up with an equally startling story with the headline "Pope could possibly be Catholic."\par \par \uc2 Jim Reinertson\par \par \uc2 SaddleBrooke\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020161026ec2i0012d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\bkmkstart toc25}{\*\bkmkend toc25}\b \uc2 Bill would disallow counting of illegal immigrants in census\b0\par\par\uc2 Howard Fischer \par \uc2 580 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 January 2016\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 ISSN:0888546X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2016 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 The legislation crafted by Sen. John Kavanagh, R-Fountain Hills, would allow cities, towns and counties to count only those who are U.S. citizens, nationals of U.S. territories, or are legally admitted to the United States. More to the point, SB 1044 would forbid counting anyone who is an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "If a city that has that problem wants to perhaps pressure the federal government to do their job and remove these people, then this will encourage that," Kavanagh said.\par \par \uc2 "People said, 'What criminal in their right mind would incriminate themselves after you read them Miranda (rights)?'" he said. "They do it every day."\par \par \uc2 PHOENIX -- A veteran state lawmaker wants to block communities trying to boost their revenues through a special interim census from counting residents who are not in this country legally.\par \par \uc2 The legislation crafted by Sen. John Kavanagh, R-Fountain Hills, would allow cities, towns and counties to count only those who are U.S. citizens, nationals of U.S. territories, or are legally admitted to the United States. More to the point, SB 1044 would forbid counting anyone who is an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Kavanagh's move come as several Arizona cities are conducting mid-decade counts to get a more accurate figure of how many people are present. That can have immediate financial consequences as some state dollars are doled out to communities based on population.\par \par \uc2 There's a lot of money involved.\par \par \uc2 This past budget year the state distributed nearly $609 million in "urban revenue sharing." State transportation dollars also are allocated to communities at least in part based on population.\par \par \uc2 In general, the larger the community, the bigger the slice.\par \par \uc2 How many people are here illegally remains a guess at best.\par \par \uc2 Pew Hispanic estimated there are 11.3 million undocumented individuals in the country. And its most recent figures for Arizona put the figure at about 300,000.\par \par \uc2 Where they are within the state, however, is one of those unknowns that Kavanagh hopes to determine through his legislation.\par \par \uc2 The question remains, though, whether it's fair to cut aid based on whether someone who is living in a city or town is legally present.\par \par \uc2 Kavanagh, whose wife, Linda, is the mayor of Fountain Hills, sees the issue from a different perspective.\par \par \uc2 "Why should the people in Fountain Hills get less state-shared revenue because there are more illegal immigrants in Phoenix?" he asked.\par \par \uc2 Nor is he dissuaded by arguments that communities have to provide services to all in their borders, here legally or not.\par \par \uc2 "If a city that has that problem wants to perhaps pressure the federal government to do their job and remove these people, then this will encourage that," Kavanagh said.\par \par \uc2 He conceded there are flaws to the plan.\par \par \uc2 One is that, no matter what happens in a mid-decade tally, the Census Bureau's official decennial count will include all residents, legal or not. So the new revenue sharing figures after 2020 would be reset based on total population.\par \par \uc2 Then there's the simple question of why anyone would admit to someone who shows up at the door there are people present who are not here legally. But Kavanagh said his 20 years as a police officer suggests otherwise.\par \par \uc2 "People said, 'What criminal in their right mind would incriminate themselves after you read them Miranda (rights)?'" he said. "They do it every day."\par \par \uc2 Credit: Howard Fischer Capitol Media Services\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020161026ec170005d\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc26}{\*\bkmkend toc26}\b \uc2 Letters to the editor\b0\par\par\uc2 836 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 December 2015\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A17\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Extra holiday adds\par \par \uc2 to city's budget burden\par \par \uc2 Re: the Dec. 5 article "City to cut jobs, offer buyouts."\par \par \uc2 I read about the city's plan to make "painful cuts" to the budget, yet this city council voted unanimously a few years ago to add another holiday for city employees. This additional holiday was predicted to add hundreds of thousands of extra dollars to the city budget in the very first year alone. Is that being fiscally responsible?\par \par \uc2 Michael Colbert\par \par \uc2 Northwest side\par \par \uc2 Glad to see RichRod stay in Tucson\par \par \uc2 Re: the Dec. 6 article "RichRod 'happy' to stay with UA."\par \par \uc2 Media, social and otherwise, were blowing up about whether or not Rich Rodriguez would stay or go. It all makes me think about whatever happened to playing and coaching purely for the love of the game? If you ask eight out of 10 boys what they want to be when they grow up, most say "play in the NFL/NBA", etc. It's not because they are thinking about what their contract may look like in 15 years, it's because they love the game.\par \par \uc2 At a certain point, it goes from the love of the sport to the money,