 published an eloquent and rational editorial this past weekend urging the adoption of some obviously wise criteria for regulation of guns.\par \par \uc2 If even one-third of America's newspapers would endorse the proposals of the Times, we might be able to get Congress off the dime to develop rational national gun regulations. Too many members of Congress presently seem to shiver in terror of the \uc2 NRA\uc2 , which was founded and funded by gun manufacturers. The \uc2 NRA\uc2  is more interested in their profits than in preventing murder.\par \par \uc2 I support the adoption of the laws and processes developed in Australia. Will the Star do likewise?\par \par \uc2 Patricia McKnight\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Brown, Obama attended same 'Blame School'\par \par \uc2 Re: the Dec. 7 article "Ducey strikes back at Gov. Brown's AZ gun- law criticism."\par \par \uc2 California Gov. Jerry Brown attacks Arizona's laws? This attack comes from a man whose state's left-wing immigration policies allow \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  felons to be set free and kill innocent U.S. citizens, as happened in San Francisco not long ago. And the guns used in San Bernardino were purchased in Brown's California.\par \par \uc2 Looks like Brown went to the same "Blame School" as our president who, after using executive actions to loosen immigration rules, now says it's up to Congress to tighten them. How about using executive action to tighten the visa rules, Mr. President? The credo of the "Blame School" these guys attended is "It's not my fault, someone else needs to do something."\par \par \uc2 They should both be ashamed.\par \par \uc2 Matthew Scully\par \par \uc2 Sahuarita\par \par \uc2 Obama plays losing game vs. terrorism\par \par \uc2 President Obama's strategy on fighting terrorism reminds me of the football coach who has the ball first-and-goal on the 1-foot line. Then the coach decides to run the same play four times in a row, fails to score and loses the game, and then wonders why he lost the game and his job.\par \par \uc2 Roger Provost\par \par \uc2 SaddleBrooke\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020151210ebca0000g\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc27}{\*\bkmkend toc27}\b \uc2 Letters to the editor\b0\par\par\uc2 908 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 September 2015\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A15\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Ducey's co-pay plan will mean higher costs\par \par \uc2 Re: the Aug. 24 article "Ducey's new plan draws ire."\par \par \uc2 I read Gov. Doug Ducey's plans to "modernize" Medicaid (\uc2 AHCCCS\uc2 ) in Arizona. This is really code for cutting the program back by invoking co-payments proven to discourage patients in the greatest need of treatment from seeking care. That results in more serious illnesses and increases in overall costs.\par \par \uc2 If the governor really wishes to save unnecessary medical dollars, he may wish to review the law requiring mandatory urine drug testing for illicit substances in people receiving assistance from the state.\par \par \uc2 These programs have universally failed to impact anything across the United States, at an extremely high cost to the taxpayer.\par \par \uc2 Alan Barreuther\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 McCain doesn't care about those near border\par \par \uc2 Wow, with all the visits John McCain has been making to Tucson, he must be up for re-election next year. The only thing missing is his once-every-six-years photo op on the border where he pretends to care about us before going back to D.C. and throwing more money at the Border Patrol.\par \par \uc2 Guess that is easier than putting effort into our problems. Thanks also to McCain for treating those of us who live within 100 miles of our border like low-life, third-class citizens, without the liberties enjoyed by others who live farther away.\par \par \uc2 Dave Rollins\par \par \uc2 Patagonia\par \par \uc2 Put striking drivers\par \par \uc2 in bus riders' shoes\par \par \uc2 This solution should have been implemented on day two of the bus strike: Take away all household vehicle keys for the strikers, especially drivers.\par \par \uc2 They can call and pay for a taxi if they want, but they are not allowed to get a ride from any family member or friends. They must depend on whatever few buses run, or their feet, just like their passengers.\par \par \uc2 They should be forced to walk in 107-degree heat. They should walk in the rain and get totally drenched. They should be forced to be exposed to the pervs and perps out there by walking home at night.\par \par \uc2 They should not be able to go to work, like many passengers. They should not be able to pick up a prescription because there are no buses in their neighborhood. They should be lucky enough to break a sandal beginning a long walk home and have to hobble the entire way.\par \par \uc2 After the first busless weekend, I guarantee the strike would have ended on day five.\par \par \uc2 Jen Jersey\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Bus strike will be\par \par \uc2 a loss for everyone\par \par \uc2 Though I'm not sure how it could be calculated, it would be interesting (or depressing) to see a dollar figure of the lost wages, lost jobs (and the economic impact on families), reduced shopping revenue, and so on, compared to amount of the extra salaries Sun Tran drivers want.\par \par \uc2 I suspect the drivers would be gaining much less than Tucsonans are losing during the strike, as well the amount that families of fired workers will continue to lose after the strike is over.\par \par \uc2 Jerry Peek\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Obama and Trump are alike on immigration\par \par \uc2 Am I the only one who recognizes the essential sameness of Barak Obama's and Donald Trump's \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  policies? Obama wants to stop deportations except of recent arrivals and criminals (Trump's "bad ones"). Trump wants to deport all illegals and then "expedite" readmission and legalization of "the good ones."\par \par \uc2 They end up at the same place, only Trump, the tremendous manager, wouldn't use deportation hearings to identify the good ones and keep them here instead of sending them through a revolving door.\par \par \uc2 There is logic to Trump's proposal to end birthright citizenship. The twin purposes of the citizenship clause of the 14th Amendment, to reverse "Dred Scott" and protect freed slaves, have been accomplished.\par \par \uc2 What would be so terrible if the U.S. joined other liberal democracies and, for example, began to deny citizenship to people whose parents were here illegally or on short-term work or tourist visas?\par \par \uc2 Peter Strong\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Congratulations due\par \par \uc2 for 22nd-Kino work\par \par \uc2 Congratulations to the city of Tucson Department of Transportation, the Regional Transportation Authority and The Ashton Co. on the completion of the city's first grade-separated intersection at 22nd Street and Kino Boulevard.\par \par \uc2 Anyone driving through this on a daily basis can appreciate that this project has substantially improved traffic flow.\par \par \uc2 The RTA, Pima County and the participating communities and contractors have not received sufficient credit for all the work they have done revitalizing many of our seriously deficient roadways.\par \par \uc2 Morgan E. North\par \par \uc2 Tucson\par \par \uc2 Climate change fallout will be self-punishment\par \par \uc2 Re: the Aug. 30 article "Katrina's wrath, rebuilding marked on anniversary."\par \par \uc2 It's hurricane time again, thus time to read and hear of nature as our enemy. If it's not "wrath" it might be "fury," or it might be a volcano or wildfire. And Katrina wasn't just huge, she was "monstrous." A storm as an infuriated female monster?\par \par \uc2 Naming and imputing animal emotions to natural phenomena such as weather events, even though not literally intended, is animistic and tends to reinforce the hoary notion of nature being "out there," a separate, often hostile entity.\par \par \uc2 If destructive natural events must continue to be portrayed as punishment, the climate change headed our way over the coming decades should provoke a more accurate understanding: self- punishment.\par \par \uc2 Walter Hurley\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020150902eb920000m\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc28}{\*\bkmkend toc28}\b \uc2 How Arizona's members of Congress voted\b0\par\par\uc2 920 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 July 2015\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A11\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Voterama in Congress\par \par \uc2 WASHINGTON -- Here's how Arizona's members of Congress voted on major issues in the week ending July 24.\par \par \uc2 HOUSE\par \par \uc2 SANCTUARY CITIES, IMMIGRATION ENFORCEMENT\par \par \uc2 The House on July 23 voted, 241 for and 179 against, to deny certain law-enforcement grants to so-called "sanctuary cities" that decline to act as an arm of federal immigration enforcement. The GOP- drafted bill (HR 3009) is a response to a recent murder in San Francisco, a sanctuary city, in which an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  with felony convictions allegedly gunned down Kathryn Steinle after city authorities released him from custody. Officials in sanctuary cities say that to assist with federal immigration enforcement would undercut community-policing efforts that depend on rapport with immigrant populations. Backers of the bill said cities are required by law to comply with federal requests that they detain illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to send the bill to the Senate.\par \par \uc2 Yes: Martha McSally, R-2, Paul Gosar, R-4, Matt Salmon, R-5, David Schweikert, R-6, Trent Franks, R-8, Kyrsten Sinema, D-9\par \par \uc2 No: Ann Kirkpatrick, D-1, Raul Grijalva, D-3, Ruben Gallego, D-7\par \par \uc2 SANCTUARY CITY CRIME RATES\par \par \uc2 Voting 181 for and 239 against, the House on July 23 defeated a bid by Democrats to block any funding cuts under HR 3009 (above) that would reduce a city's deployment of police on the beat or raise its crime rate with respect to domestic violence, sex crimes or crimes against children.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to adopt the motion, which, had it prevailed, would have immediately amended the bill.\par \par \uc2 Yes: Kirkpatrick, Grijalva, Gallego, Sinema\par \par \uc2 No: McSally, Gosar, Salmon, Schweikert, Franks\par \par \uc2 STATE REGULATION OF COAL ASH\par \par \uc2 Voting 258 for and 166 against, the House on July 22 passed a GOP- drafted bill (HR 1734) that would give states rather than the \uc2 Environmental Protection Agency\uc2  primary authority to regulate the coal ash discharged as waste by the nation's 500-plus coal-fired power plants. The bill would put states in charge of permitting and enforcement under a new \uc2 EPA\uc2  rule for regulating coal ash impounded in ponds or landfills near these plants. The federal rule takes effect Oct. 19. Addressing factors such as the structural integrity and location of storage sites, it is designed to protect drinking water, groundwater and air quality from ash containing elements such as arsenic, cadmium, chromium, lead and selenium.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 EPA\uc2  began its rulemaking process in response to a December 2008 spill at a \uc2 Tennessee Valley Authority\uc2  facility at Kingston, Tenn., which spread coal-ash sludge over 300 acres and into the Emory and Clinch rivers.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to send the bill to the Senate.\par \par \uc2 Yes: Kirkpatrick, McSally, Gosar, Salmon, Schweikert\par \par \uc2 No: Grijalva, Gallego, Sinema\par \par \uc2 Not voting: Franks\par \par \uc2 DRINKING WATER\par \par \uc2 FROM NEARBY WELLS\par \par \uc2 Voting 192 for and 231 against, the House on July 22 refused to require operators of coal-ash impoundment sites to provide notification and alternative sources of safe drinking water to properties within one-half mile whose wells show signs of coal-ash contamination. The Democratic-sponsored amendment was offered to HR 1734 (above).\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to adopt the amendment.\par \par \uc2 Yes: Kirkpatrick, Grijalva, Gallego\par \par \uc2 No: McSally, Gosar, Salmon, Schweikert, Sinema\par \par \uc2 Not voting: Franks\par \par \uc2 VOLUNTARY GMO LABELING\par \par \uc2 Voting 275 for and 150 against, the House on July 23 passed a bill (HR 1599) that would establish a system of voluntary, state- administered labeling requirements for foods that contain genetically modified organisms (GMOs). In addition, the bill pre- empts any existing or future state or local laws that establish mandatory labeling of genetically engineered foods. At present, there are no federal requirements for GMO labeling.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote favored a voluntary state-by-state approach to labeling GMO foods.\par \par \uc2 Yes: Kirkpatrick, McSally, Gosar, Salmon, Schweikert, Sinema\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Grijalva, Gallego, Franks\par \par \uc2 MANDATORY GMO LABELING\par \par \uc2 Voting 123 for and 303 against, the House on July 23 defeated an amendment to HR 1599 (above) that sought to require mandatory, federally administered labeling of foods containing genetically modified organisms. This would replace the underlying bill's voluntary state-level approach.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to establish federally mandated labeling of foods containing GMOs.\par \par \uc2 Yes: Grijalva, Gallego\par \par \uc2 No: Kirkpatrick, McSally, Gosar, Salmon, Schweikert, Franks, Sinema\par \par \uc2 'NATURAL' GMO FOODS\par \par \uc2 Voting 163 for and 262 against, the House on July 23 refused to prohibit food labeled as "natural" from containing generically modified ingredients. The vote affirmed wording in HR 1599 (above) that allows the \uc2 Food and Drug Administration\uc2  and \uc2 U.S. Department of Agriculture\uc2  definitions of "natural" to include GMO foods.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to prohibit foods containing GMOs from being labeled as "natural."\par \par \uc2 Yes: Grijalva, Gallego\par \par \uc2 No: Kirkpatrick, McSally, Gosar, Salmon, Schweikert, Franks, Sinema\par \par \uc2 SENATE\par \par \uc2 SIX-YEAR TRANSPORTATION BILL\par \par \uc2 Voting 62 for and 36 against, the Senate on July 22 agreed to start debate on a bill (HR 22) that would authorize $317 billion over six years for highway and mass-transit construction projects. Because the Highway Trust Fund is projected to raise only $240 billion over the next six years to finance these projects, the bill faces a shortfall of $77 billion that would be funded by revenue increases or spending cuts yet to be fully determined. If the bill clears the Senate, it would have to be reconciled with a House- passed measure to fund transportation programs only through Dec. 18.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to advance the transportation bill.\par \par \uc2 Yes: \uc2 John McCain\uc2 , R, Jeff Flake, R\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020150726eb7q0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc29}{\*\bkmkend toc29}\b \uc2 Facebook\uc2  comments from our readers\b0\par\par\uc2 290 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 July 2015\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A15\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Re: Sign-posting effort marks anniversary of sanctuary case. Some 5,000 signs with "We Stand with Rosa" will be distributed across Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Antonia Carrera: I have one of these signs in front of my house.\par \par \uc2 Gayla Fancher: Research shows she entered this country illegally. And only when she risked deportation did she 