defining an intersection should be made, but the evidence that they prevent crashes is compelling.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 Federal Highway Administration\uc2  analyzed more than 130 red- light camera intersections across the country and found that "the average number of right-angle or 'T-bone' crashes went down 25 percent after cameras were installed."\par \par \uc2 The study also found the "average number of rear-end crashes went up 15 percent, but it is very important to put that into perspective; while rear-ends do increase, the overall crash harm to the victims is reduced with the installation of red-light cameras. Right-angle crashes are simply much more dangerous than rear-end collisions."\par \par \uc2 The study says this increase is not surprising. "When a new signal is installed on a roadway, the same pattern is seen -- the more severe angle crashes are decreased while the less severe rear- end crashes usually increase to some extent." Let's improve and keep photo-radar.\par \par \uc2 Phil Lopes\par \par \uc2 West side\par \par \uc2 Conservative policies hurt economic recovery\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 7 article "Tucson is No. 9 on distressed communities list, report says."\par \par \uc2 In this article the reporter tells us that Tucson is No. 9 and Phoenix is No. 11 on this list. We have not recovered from the recession, and I lay the responsibility for that failure directly on the conservative governor's and state legislators' collective desks, past and present.\par \par \uc2 The article quotes the study's spokesman, "... they are desperately in need of more private sector investment and entrepreneurship to grow their way out of the economic crisis."\par \par \uc2 Our conservative state does not promote jobs or business. We discourage business and employees from coming to Arizona because of our deep cuts to education, our reputation as a "right-wing, crazy state," and our employee-unfriendly stance.\par \par \uc2 We are held hostage by the governor and his minions and their business unfriendly policies.\par \par \uc2 Karen Clifton\par \par \uc2 Midtown\par \par \uc2 Mother's life cut short by \uc2 illegal immigrant\par \par \uc2 On Oct. 10, 2010, my mother, who was from Indianapolis, was struck and killed by a drunk driver. The perpetrator fled the scene. He was apprehended three hours later and still had two times the legal limit of serum alcohol.\par \par \uc2 It was his second DUI, and he was in the country illegally from Guatemala after having been deported once already. His attorney argued for mercy because he is a "family man."\par \par \uc2 My mother volunteered at a children's hospital for 25 years. She daily visited an Alzheimer's unit, she knit scarves and hats for women at a "battered women's" shelter, she delivered Meals on Wheels, and she likely did much more. She was the most benevolent, selfless person I've ever known. Her life was cut short by the reckless behavior of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , combined with faulty U.S. policies and the inability to control our U.S borders.\par \par \uc2 I'm so tired of only reading the "feel good stories" about immigrants tragically separated from their families. How about the tragic separation of my family?\par \par \uc2 Shelley Herman\par \par \uc2 North side\par \par \uc2 Social sciences hold key to long-term survival\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 7 column "\uc2 NSF\uc2  should stop paying for stupid social- science research."\par \par \uc2 As an anthropologist I can testify that in academia it is common for members of the so-called hard sciences-- physics, chemistry, mathematics, engineering -- to view the social sciences as somehow inferior. Miller's article is a prime example of that bias.\par \par \uc2 Yet, to take one historical example, it was the psychology of Hitler and Stalin, not physics, that led to the deaths of millions. It was the culture of the German Army, not chemistry, that led them to follow Hitler. It was the sociology of the German people, 