lifornia is poised to take Arizona's share of the Colorado and that environmentalists are to blame require clarification.\par \par \uc2 To sum up the water problems in California and Arizona: First, our supplies were designed to support a population far smaller than the one we have today. Second, federal agricultural water is so darn cheap (average $32.39/acre-foot in California) that corporate farmers plant crops requiring huge amounts of water all year long. Lastly, there is the changing water picture. No longer is the winter snowpack large enough to recharge the rivers and reservoirs.\par \par \uc2 Until we understand and address the issues, developing sustainable paths forward will be elusive.\par \par \uc2 David Wegner\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Golfer Nallen is great on, off the course\par \par \uc2 Re: the July article "Nallen's consistency makes him Cats' ace."\par \par \uc2 I have known Chris Nallen since he was 13. Even then you could see he was headed for great things. I introduced him to Payne Stewart, who told me Chris is a fantastic golfer. I caddied for Chris in a number of tournaments and have been around the game for many years. A more determined, dedicated golfer you will never find. Off the course he is a perfect gentleman and represents Arizona and the game of golf as well as a Hogan, Palmer or Nicholas. It is an honor to know Chris Nallen.\par \par \uc2 Donald Brauer\par \par \uc2 Downtown\par \par \uc2 Tucson's giving heart helps ease a big loss\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 5 article "I am more than cancer."\par \par \uc2 As the grandparents who lost our granddaughter, Kelsey Taylor Luria, at 18, we are saddened for those who have lost a child or adolescent with so much life and experiences before them. Many thanks to the Star for the front- page article on Kelsey. We are proud of her concerns for others and our memories of Kelsey, our sweet fashion princess, will live with us forever.\par \par \uc2 Kelsey's too-short life demonstrates