ts. But remember that without exception, injuries and deaths incurred while illegally crossing the fence or the desert are 100 percent preventable and essentially the result of bad decisions made by the individuals themselves.\par \par \uc2 Much more tragic are the deaths of U.S. citizens at the hands of illegal immigrants such as occurred recently in San Francisco. These deaths are the result of bad decisions made by "feel good" politicians who allow \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  felons to remain in the country and, in San Francisco's case, be protected by "safe haven" and "sanctuary" policies.\par \par \uc2 All politicians who support these types of policies should be deported.\par \par \uc2 Matthew Scully\par \par \uc2 Sahuarita\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020150709eb790000c\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc32}{\*\bkmkend toc32}\b \uc2 Letters to the editor\b0\par\par\uc2 629 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 February 2015\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A09\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Babeu's concerns are justified\par \par \uc2 Re:the Feb. 4 article "Babeu likens detainee releases to 'massive prison break.'"\par \par \uc2 Sheriff \uc2 Paul Babeu\uc2  strongly complains about the dangers of the Obama administration's policies regarding the release of illegal immigrants that began in 2013.\par \par \uc2 As proof that Babeu's complaints are valid, we need only look at the Star's page A8 article on Jan. 29. That article points out the January 2013 release of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who had been convicted of burglary. Allowed to stay and await deportation hearings since that time, he had two injunction orders issued against him, and is now accused of murdering a store clerk over a pack of cigarettes.\par \par \uc2 This death of a U.S. citizen at the hands of a released \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  is not the first. Unfortunately, due to Obama's lenient policies that encourage more illegal immigration by rewarding those who do so, it will probably not be the last.\par \par \uc2 Matthew Scully\par \par \uc2 Sahuarita\par \par \uc2 Spreading Fitz's beliefs a dangerous disservice\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 5 David Fitzsimmons cartoon.\par \par \uc2 Having a military combat and intelligence background, I can assess with high probability that Fitzsimmons has never served his country in a military capacity during war. Therefore, his ignorance regarding extremist Islamist terrorism is somewhat understandable.\par \par \uc2 However, spreading his uneducated beliefs and misinformation via this cartoon, only provides a disservice to the citizens of this country: When he depicts those knowledgeable about the terrorist threat as hysterical "Islamaphobes," he destroys his own credibility with a portion of your readers.\par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, he also convinces the remaining readers to believe his ignorance. And that is dangerous.\par \par \uc2 Marla Closen\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Support horse racing or Tucson will lose it\par \par \uc2 It was so nice to read the short article on Rillito Park racing by Patrick McNamara. I expected to see more information in the Sports section including the entries/jockeys/trainers etc. But the only additional information was two short paragraphs under Sports Shorts.\par \par \uc2 If we are going to support this track and not lose it like we did spring training, PGA Match Play and the LPGA, let's have some follow through on what is a very nice tourist attraction.\par \par \uc2 Let us not forget that Southern Arizona has given horse racing the two best trainers in the country and have sent several jockeys to higher-profile race tracks.\par \par \uc2 For tourists to continue coming to the Old Pueblo vs. that other city northwest of here, they need things to see and do. I hope you will make the effort.\par \par \uc2 Gary Freeman\par \par \uc2 Northeast side\par \par \uc2 Neither crosses or rainbows on Old Glory\par \par \uc2 Re: the Feb. 6 article "Rainbow-themed flag at Davis-Monthan draws vet's serious objection."\par \par \uc2 I can empathize with the concern about the "rainbow flag" at D- M. Some years ago I was surprised to see a strange flag in California that resembled the Stars and Stripes, but with a Christian cross instead of the 50 stars. This "cross flag" implied that there is a special Christian claim to our country, which of course is false historically.\par \par \uc2 It makes me feel better that neither the "cross flag" nor the "rainbow flag" are legally considered to be versions of Old Glory.\par \par \uc2 Nickolas Waser\par \par \uc2 Foothills\par \par \uc2 Info on foster parenting, arrives late, postage due\par \par \uc2 Some time back I contacted the Department of Economic Security to get information on foster parenting. When I was finally contacted after leaving several messages, I was quickly rushed to provide my mailing address and told that I would receive information that would answer my questions. Approximately two weeks later I received a mailing with postage due and an expired calendar of events.\par \par \uc2 I gave up and never contacted again. No wonder the system is in trouble.\par \par \uc2 Linda Henderson\par \par \uc2 East side\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020150210eb2a0000p\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc33}{\*\bkmkend toc33}\b \uc2 Parents of US citizen kidsoften deported, report says ; Few foreign dads, moms in custody get to plead case\b0\par\par\uc2 Perla Trevizo   \par \uc2 Perla Trevizo Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 1,340 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 January 2015\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A01\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Parents of children who are U.S. citizens were arrested at the border more than 100,000 times in fiscal years 2011 and 2012 -- and very few of them were able to plead their case before a judge before being deported, a human-rights organization found.\par \par \uc2 Keeping a family together should at least be considered before deporting someone, said \uc2 Clara Long\uc2 , a U.S. researcher with \uc2 Human Rights Watch\uc2 . Instead, at the border and after a criminal conviction, "deportations are just automatic," Long said.\par \par \uc2 On Nov. 20, the administration announced an effort to keep families together by deferring deportation for some parents of children who are U.S. citizens or legal permanent residents, focusing the government's resources on deporting certain people, including convicted felons and recent border crossers.\par \par \uc2 But Long said it's contradictory to say the administration wants to "deport felons, not families" when it continues to prioritize deportation of anyone caught at the border.\par \par \uc2 Parents of U.S. citizen children are nearly twice as likely to be processed under a previous deportation order and 1.35 times more likely to be charged with illegal entry or illegal re-entry than nonparents, \uc2 Human Rights Watch\uc2  said in the report, which is based on Customs and Border Protection apprehension data from fiscal years 2011 and 2012.\par \par \uc2 "When someone is separated from their family and they don't see any way out, they continue to cross and continue to cross," Long said. "Someone can be a felon simply by trying to rejoin their family multiple times."\par \par \uc2 ALMOST A FELON\par \par \uc2 Aurora Olivares almost became a felon herself. She now sits in a Nogales, Sonora, women's shelter trying to decide what to do.\par \par \uc2 The Puebla native, who lived in Utah for 11 years, is the mother of three girls, ages 8 through 12, who are all U.S. citizens.\par \par \uc2 "I was happy. I was working and I had my three girls," she said. But she hadn't seen her parents in 11 years and she feared her mother, who was very ill, would die before they were able to see each other again. So she returned to Mexico and brought her daughters with her.\par \par \uc2 They spent a few months in Puebla and, on April 18, 2012, she put them on a direct flight to Utah from Mexico City, while she took another plane to Hermosillo. In Sonora, she thought, she would cross illegally as she had done 12 years ago.\par \par \uc2 While her daughters arrived safely in Utah, Olivares was caught by the Border Patrol at the border and deported back to Mexico.\par \par \uc2 She tried crossing again in 2013 but was detained, and this time she was charged criminally with illegal re-entry, a felony, plus a misdemeanor of illegal entry. She was processed in Tucson through Operation Streamline -- a federal program in which immigrants enter pleas en masse -- and accepted a deal to plead guilty to the misdemeanor charge.\par \par \uc2 She received a 75-day sentence, but was in a detention center for more than a year as she sought asylum and went through appeals. Before a final decision on her case came down, she was deported through Nogales on Dec. 30, 2014.\par \par \uc2 "I didn't care about being detained as long as it meant one last shot at being with my daughters again," she said, tears streaming down her cheeks.\par \par \uc2 "A LINE HAS TO BE DRAWN"\par \par \uc2 She hasn't seen her daughters in nearly three years. While they could travel to Mexico, her former partner won't let them do so and is limiting communication between them.\par \par \uc2 What \uc2 Human Rights Watch\uc2  wants the government to do is an overreach, said \uc2 Jessica Vaughan\uc2 , director of policy studies for the D.C.-based \uc2 Center for Immigration Studies\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "It's their choice to keep trying to come back here, exposing themselves to potentially being prosecuted," she said. "It's important to recognize there is some responsibility for repeatedly ignoring the law rather than waiting it out for an opportunity to come back legally in the future if the son or daughter sponsors them."\par \par \uc2 Having family members here, she said, should not trump a criminal history or another factor that makes someone ineligibile.\par \par \uc2 "If we are going to have regulated legal immigration, a line has to be drawn somewhere, and the government has to be ready to enforce it," Vaughan said.\par \par \uc2 There are already more qualified potential legal immigrants waiting in line than the country can accommodate every year, she said.\par \par \uc2 Olivares said she just wants an opportunity to come back.\par \par \uc2 "There are many mothers like me, who are crying, who are pleading for an opportunity," she said.\par \par \uc2 She would stay in Mexico if she didn't have children or she could bring them with her, she said, but that's not an option.\par \par \uc2 She misses their hugs, their kisses. Waking them up in the morning, taking them to the park and helping them with their homework.\par \par \uc2 It breaks her heart, she said, when they do get to talk and they ask when she's coming back.\par \par \uc2 The little one tells her, "Mommy, I'm afraid I'm not going to remember your face anymore." Olivares just tells her she'll send her photographs to make sure that doesn't happen.\par \par \uc2 A PERILOUS JOURNEY\par \par \uc2 She walked through the desert by herself, guided by a smuggler using a cellphone. She wandered lost, with only the sounds of the coyotes and snakes in the background. She has jumped the iron border fence more than once.\par \par \uc2 All with one goal: being back with her daughters. But now she weighs all her options. She knows if she tries to cross back and gets caught, the punishment will be more severe. She already has a 20-year bar from returning to the United States.\par \par \uc2 All of her legal troubles relate to trying to cross the border, but some immigrants lose their legal status and get deported after criminal convictions like for certain drug offenses.\par \par \uc2 "We live in a world in which we've had harsh criminal immigration laws since 1996 that continue to punish immigration harshly for what are some times old or minor crimes that many people in this country are discussing to reduce punishments for," Long said.\par \par \uc2 The 1996 \uc2 Illegal Immigrant\uc2  Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act expanded the definition of "aggravated felonies" to include nonviolent theft offenses, nonviolent drug offenses, forgery and fraud, for example.\par \par \uc2 What's really needed is a permanent solution, Long said, "to take a look at those laws and the kinds of stories we highlight that show who can be swept up in the system," Long said. "People who are veterans, people who paid their dues in prison and now are left with really severe consequences that tear them apart from their families."\par \par \uc2 Some key findings:\par \par \uc2 Based on data of 700,000 Customs and Border Protection apprehensions at the border, out of which 15 percent were of parents of U.S. citizen children:\par \par \uc2 60 percent of parents with U.S. citizens who were caught at the border by Customs and Border Protection were processed under expedited removal or reinstatement of removal, meaning they had a prior deportation order.Few, the report found, were processed in a way that would let them explain their case to an immigration judge.They were nearly twice as likely (1.77 times) to be processed under a previous deportation order or reinstatement of removal.And 1.35 times more likely than non-parents of U.S. citizens to be charged with an illegal entry or re-entry crime.In fiscal years 2011 and 2012, only .2 percent of parents of U.S. citizens were charged as deportable by CBP because they were convicted of an aggravated felony.In 2012, 24 percent of "criminal aliens" deported had immigration crimes like illegal entry and re-entry as their most serious conviction.\par \par \uc2 Source: \uc2 Human Rights Watch\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020150109eb190002x\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc34}{\*\bkmkend toc34}\b \uc2 Facebook\uc2  comments from our readers\b0\par\par\uc2 347 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 October 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A11\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 These are excerpts from online reader comments on one of this week's most talked-about stories. Join the conversation at \uc2 Facebook.com\uc2 /ArizonaDailyStarOpinion.\par \par \uc2 Re: Arivaca residents group finds racial profiling at Amado border checkpoint.\par \par \uc2 OK, let me see if I have this straight. They are looking for illegal aliens that are of Latino descent, most likely. So they stop Latino descent people at their checkpoints and ask them more questions, and this constitutes racial profiling?\par \par \uc2 Jason Lee Riddell\par \par \uc2 "Latinos are more likely to encounter prolonged stops and secondary inspection than white people." Well, yes, you check most in areas where crimes happen most.\par \par \uc2 The Arivaca corridor has long been a sort of highway for \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  trafficking -- that's a simple, well-known fact. I'm willing to bet that this "Arivaca residents group" is actually just a handful of rabble rousers.\par \par \uc2 Kevin Myers\par \par \uc2 I am very much reminded of a "Animal Farm" quote, "all animals are equal but some animals are more equal than others."\par \par \uc2 It's not the problem of stopping people because they look Mexican, but that we think people look more American than others. That is the shameful part.\par \par \uc2 Amber Wells\par \par \uc2 Every time we go to Mexico we get stopped by a checkpoint, which in order to get out of getting a ticket for doing nothing wrong, we are expected to pay dollars.\par \par \uc2 Sherri Barrett\par \par \uc2 I'm not white; I'm American and have been able to move on. They've never been disrespectful. I have the most respect for these men and women and canines out there. Keep up the awesome job guys!\par \par \uc2 Karla Fourcade Alvarado\par \par \uc2 It's unfortunate but necessary.\par \par \uc2 Sherry Fredrickson Palmer\par \par \uc2 And if they could stop the helicopters at night, that would be good, too.\par \par \uc2 Laurie Plaster-Miranda\par \par \uc2 Does it matter? Will any of it help?\par \par \uc2 Marie Gannon Ribbens\par \par \uc2 There are also citizens of the United States that look Mexican and are treated differently than us white folk.\par \par \uc2 Because they are citizens, they should not be treated differently than me.\par \par \uc2 Jacquie Brubaker\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020141024eaao00005\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Metro\par {\*\bkmkstart toc35}{\*\bkmkend toc35}\b \uc2 Only litigants, local cops watch the border watchers\b0\par\par\uc2 Tim Steller   \par \uc2 Tim Steller Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 1,079 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 October 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par C01\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 On Friday it will be two years since a Border Patrol agent in Nogales emptied his pistol across the border, firing through a high fence of metal poles, down a steep hill and across a Mexican street, killing 15-year-old Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez.\par \par \uc2 The federal investigation into the killing began immediately, but today it remains, in the customary term of the \uc2 FBI\uc2 , "ongoing."\par \par \uc2 When I interviewed Jose Antonio's mother, Araceli Rodriguez, in December 2012, she complained about the slow pace of the American investigation. She hadn't seen anything yet. What she didn't know is that such prolonged probes are typical of federal investigations into shootings by Border Patrol agents.\par \par \uc2 Still, even I naively thought this investigation would come to a faster resolution. There are eyewitnesses to the shooting, one of whom told my colleague Perla Trevizo last year that Jose Antonio was walking along the sidewalk when shot, not throwing rocks as the Border Patrol originally alleged. There's also video from a mounted camera along the border. And there's a growing sense of public concern about this and other cases.\par \par \uc2 That hasn't made a difference. Federal prosecutors would not explain the delay, but defense attorney Sean Chapman, who represents the agent who shot Jose Antonio, told me prosecutors are waiting for Mexican officials to hand over evidence related to the autopsy.\par \par \uc2 The lack of a decision doesn't mean there hasn't been action. Elena's killing and more recent cases of alleged misconduct by Border Patrol agents have shown that going around the feds is the only way to ensure justice is done in a timely manner. In cases of possible misconduct by federal agents, local law enforcement and civil attorneys are the ones who can force the wheels of justice to turn for victims.\par \par \uc2 As for the accused agents, they're pretty much forced to wait, in limbo, for the feds to make up their minds.\par \par \uc2 "My clients would rather that they didn't take a long time, because they have it hanging over their heads forever," said Chapman, himself a former federal prosecutor.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps the clearest recent example of federal reticence came to light last month. The Santa Cruz County Attorney's Office filed a felony assault charge against a Nogales Border Patrol agent, Aldo Arteaga, who slugged a teenage detainee in the stomach.\par \par \uc2 The Jan. 30 incident was clearly visible on a video camera mounted in the detention cell. The video shows Arteaga, with no visible provocation, punching the teen once in the stomach, and the teen staggering back onto the floor. The blow isn't exceptionally vicious -- what jumps out from the video is the casual nature of the punch. It makes you wonder how many times this happens and nobody finds out.\par \par \uc2 Federal prosecutors watched the video Feb. 12 and decided a month later that the punch "did not appear egregious enough to warrant prosecution," The Associated Press reported Friday.\par \par \uc2 The agency didn't act to discipline Arteaga either. But in late September the agency's Office of Professional Responsibility asked the Santa Cruz County Attorney to review the case. It was the local prosecutors who quickly made the simple decision that it was an assault, though they were forced to refile the charge as a misdemeanor because the victim was not younger than 15, as they had thought.\par \par \uc2 In yet another case this year, friction arose between Pima County sheriff's deputies and Border Patrol agents after the May 30 killing in Green Valley by Border Patrol agent Daniel Marquez of smuggling suspect Jose Arambula. Marquez had been chasing Arambula on foot, when, Marquez said, Arambula turned and made punching out motions with his hands, as if he was firing a gun. But he was unarmed when Marquez opened fire.\par \par \uc2 At the scene, agents grew angry, according to Pima County Sheriff's Department reports, because they felt the investigators were treating them like criminals. As my colleague Carmen Duarte reported, one deputy's report offered this eyebrow-raising description of the federal agents' reaction. "Some of the comments I heard included: 'We are all cops; why are you treating us like this? This is ridiculous, and there is no need for this.' "\par \par \uc2 Chapman, the Tucson attorney who represents Agent Marquez, told me the friction also arose because investigators did not allow Marquez to speak with Chapman for 2ae hours.\par \par \uc2 Eventually, the Pima County Attorney's Office declined to press charges, deciding that the shooting was justified, but the unsympathetic posture of the sheriff's investigators on the scene encourages me, because it gives at least the impression of an unbiased investigation. In the end, it also gives more confidence in the prosecutor's decision not to file charges. And the quicker decision removes the agent from limbo.\par \par \uc2 No local law enforcement has been willing to take up the investigation of Jose Antonio's killing, in part because of the jurisdictional difficulties caused by the cross-border shooting. But his family ran out of patience, got legal help and filed suit July 29. The \uc2 American Civil Liberties Union\uc2  joined the family's Nogales attorney, Luis Parra, in filing the wrongful-death suit, giving it a little extra oomph.\par \par \uc2 I know from speaking with Parra in 2012 that he had planned to file suit only after hearing first whether the government decided to pursue charges.\par \par \uc2 In retrospect, it's no surprise that they haven't yet decided. There seems to be a reticence permeating the federal government to hold agents accountable for shootings. The Border Patrol's acting internal-affairs chief acknowledged that the agency has not internally disciplined any of the agents responsible for 46 killings that have occurred since 2004, the Arizona Republic reported Sept. 14.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps the agency's internal disciplinarians have been deferring to federal prosecutors' decisions. But then, who are the \uc2 FBI\uc2  and federal prosecutors deferring to? Don't forget: They're not deciding whether the agent's guilty -- they're deciding whether a jury should decide guilt.\par \par \uc2 Until federal investigators show some sense of urgency in resolving these cases, expect more civil suits and local-police investigations of Border Patrol agents' actions. These are the only ways the public can know for sure that agents are being held accountable.\par \par \uc2 Online:\par \par \uc2 View the video of an agent punching an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  at Tucson.com/video\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020141005eaa500006\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Metro\par {\*\bkmkstart toc36}{\*\bkmkend toc36}\b \uc2 Immigration activists convicted of disorderly conduct for protest\b0\par\par\uc2 Patrick McNamara   \par \uc2 Patrick McNamara Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 448 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 October 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par C07\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Activists who blocked the entry to the parking lot of Tucson's federal courthouse in a 2013 effort to halt the prosecutions of illegal immigrants have been found guilty of disorderly conduct.\par \par \uc2 Wendy Bedoya, Sandra Garnica, Katherine Sinclair, Walter Stanton, Ryan Tombleson and Rachel Winch were convicted of disorderly conduct on federal property and failure to follow the direction of a federal police officer in connection with the October 2013 protest.\par \par \uc2 In the incident, the group rushed the parking lot gate of the Evo A. DeConcini Federal Courthouse downtown. They chained themselves together and to either side of the gate to prevent federal officials from deporting illegal immigrants under "Operation Streamline."\par \par \uc2 "We're deeply disappointed," defense attorney Jeffrey Rogers said.\par \par \uc2 Rogers represented Bedoya and Garnica at the bench trial in late September.\par \par \uc2 They were among the demonstrators on hand to protest the \uc2 U.S. government\uc2 's policy that requires criminal prosecutions and imprisonment for unlawful border crossers.\par \par \uc2 Other demonstrators blocked a bus carrying \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  defendants.\par \par \uc2 The policy, begun in 2005, has been cited as the cause of vastly increased caseloads at federal courthouses in the border region. The federal court here hears an estimated 70 such cases a day. The protest halted the prosecutions for one day.\par \par \uc2 In a ruling dated Friday, 