r the Pima County Sheriff's Department.\par \par \uc2 Bellemare had severe burns and was taken to the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2  Medical Center before being flown to at the Maricopa Burn Center in Phoenix.\par \par \uc2 The investigation is ongoing.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140926ea9q00002\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc38}{\*\bkmkend toc38}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 599 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 July 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A07\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 News from around state shows crAZiness\par \par \uc2 With the insane news pouring out of Arizona, why would anyone come?\par \par \uc2 There was the SB1070 "anti-immigrant bill" encouraging racial profiling, and SB1062, "the anti-gay bill" meant to refuse service to gays and lesbians.\par \par \uc2 Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio is profiling, pursuing and jailing "illegals" but neglecting to investigate 400 cases of child abuse.\par \par \uc2 Tom Horne, Arizona's Attorney General accused of using staff and state resources to promote his election and violations of campaign law.\par \par \uc2 Andrew Thomas\uc2 , former Maricopa County Attorney, disbarred for unwarranted criminal charges and investigations against his political enemies.\par \par \uc2 John Huppenthal, the Superintendent of Schools blogging under "Falcon9" posting racist comments and calling people on public assistance "lazy pigs."\par \par \uc2 Paul Babeu\uc2 , the Pinal County Sheriff, informing the citizens of \uc2 Oracle\uc2  that a bus with \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children was coming through town. No bus arrived but the crowd, including Arizona Representative from Oro Valley, Adam Kwansman, followed a \uc2 YMCA\uc2  bus with American kids, with Kwansman reporting he saw the fear on their faces.\par \par \uc2 Can't spell "crazy" without AZ.\par \par \uc2 Vicki Hart\par \par \uc2 Counselor, Tucson\par \par \uc2 Sun Tran is providing exceptional service\par \par \uc2 I am fortunate enough to be able to afford a car, gas, and insurance. Sometimes however that car is in the shop and alternative transportation options are necessary.\par \par \uc2 I took advantage of our Sun Tran bus system today and I was pleasantly surprised. I purchased a bus pass from my local grocery store, and caught a cross-town express during rush hour.\par \par \uc2 The bus arrived on time, and along with 12 other cross-town riders, we boarded a clean, efficient, quiet and cool bus. The driver and my fellow riders were courteous and helpful. The entire ride took 35 minutes and seemed much shorter.\par \par \uc2 People complain about the new Sun Link system and its cost, but we are blessed to have such a clean efficient system here and options for those without personal transportation. Thank you Sun Tran for your exceptional service.\par \par \uc2 Doug Burke\par \par \uc2 Publisher, Oro Valley\par \par \uc2 'Small gov't' legislators\par \par \uc2 desire to control us\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 24 article "Hundreds of new AZ laws kick in today."\par \par \uc2 I read about the Arizona Legislature "gifting" us with a set of new laws to live by. These are the same folks who believe in "small government" yet tell us we can't be trusted with decongestants and cough syrups, but at the same time, guns are OK almost everywhere. Is anyone following the logic behind this other than their endless desire to control people?\par \par \uc2 Alan Barreuther\par \par \uc2 Pharmacist, Tucson\par \par \uc2 Releasing fixed cats not a good idea\par \par \uc2 Re: the July 25 article "Fix-and-release program for feral cats is proposed."\par \par \uc2 Trapping, sterilizing, and vaccinating feral and "free-roaming" cats is wonderful and I certainly hope it is supported by everyone.\par \par \uc2 However, releasing these cats back to their homeless environment is not good.\par \par \uc2 I have two rescue cats that went through this process and I found each of them outside my apartment complex at separate times starving and looking for food.\par \par \uc2 I fed each of them twice a day outside until I humanely trapped them. Both cats came from the same area but there was nothing for them to hunt. The article says that the cats are problem critters. The cats aren't the problem; it is the people who let their cats have kitten after kitten with no responsibility towards the animals who are the problem. It is the people who throw these animals away like trash who are the problem.\par \par \uc2 Elayne Fasman\par \par \uc2 Program assistant, Tucson\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140727ea7r00038\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc39}{\*\bkmkend toc39}\b \uc2 Bickering recedes for a day; maybe we've come round the bend\b0\par\par\uc2 David Fitzsimmons   \par \uc2 David Fitzsimmons Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 756 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 July 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A15\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 We crammed so many of ourselves into the streetcar yesterday it looked like a Tokyo subway train at rush hour. The rail line was so popular with gawkers you'd think Woody Guthrie had been inspired to write "This train is bound for glory" by the round trip from the maintenance facility to the Mercado District west of I-10.\par \par \uc2 Look at their mugs, smiling at the sight of our modern streetcar the way Mister Rogers smiled at "Trolley" every time it returned from the Barrio of Make-Believe, humming, "it's a beautiful day in the neighborhoods" from midtown to downtown.\par \par \uc2 It's as if Tennessee Williams wrote "a streetcar named desire for a viable downtown" in steel and asphalt, and downtown, like a sweaty Brando shouting "Stella" at the top of his aching lungs, was shouting "I'm back" at Southern Arizona.\par \par \uc2 The streetcar is the ark by which the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2  and its children are colonizing and invigorating downtown. By shuttling frisky Wildcats into downtown for wilding sprees with their parent's debit cards, the ancient urban planner's prophecy shall be fulfilled.\par \par \uc2 Verily, I say unto thee, thy streetcar shall run to and fro and verily, unto downtown, it shall beget students who shall beget student housing which shall beget fine dining which shall beget clubs which shall beget retail which shall beget who knows? Maybe even a Trader Joe's? And verily thy aging boomers shall buy lofts and sip Manhattans and downtown will be rocking as unto a shining city on a hill.\par \par \uc2 The economic benefits of the streetcar are clear: permanent jobs, thriving revenue-generating enterprises springing up along the line like seedlings next to a river, and a notable boost in the incomes of personal injury lawyers representing maladroit bicyclists.\par \par \uc2 I'm excited about the plans to expand the streetcar line. Take it up Campbell Avenue to Wisconsin, and out west to Southern California, link it up with the monorail at Disneyland, offering inebriated students a chance to sober up on Mr. Toad's Wild Ride long after the fireworks have ended.\par \par \uc2 It's the little electric engine that could, making it over countless hills thanks to the many obsessed and possessed Tucsonans clinging to their "I think we can, I think we can" attitude.\par \par \uc2 Here's to the founders of Old Pueblo Trolley, \uc2 Gene Caywood\uc2  and Dick Guthrie, a pair of trolley pushers who were promoting a streetcar for Tucson before Rice-A-Roni was the San Francisco treat. Clang, clang, clang, went the trolley. Hum, hum, hum came the streetcar.\par \par \uc2 Here's to the group of trolley huggers full of sense and sensibility called Tucsonans for Sensible Transportation who kick- started it all in 2001.\par \par \uc2 Here's to Steve Farley, public artist, state senator and light- rail evangelist, who preached the word of the electric shuttle to the heathens until he was hoarse, amen.\par \par \uc2 Nudged by a coalition of similar light rail-o-philes, homebuilders and auto dealers, the voters in 2006, approved a half- cent sales tax, funding the \uc2 Regional Transportation Authority\uc2  Plan. The RTA plan purchased buses, bikeways, blimps, gondolas, enough asphalt to pave the moon, the streetcar system and two wicker rickshaws pulled by javelinas.\par \par \uc2 Mayor Bob Walkup got the remaining funding for the blue ride from a federal economic stimulus grant by twisting arms in Washington, D.C., with such insistent cheer the \uc2 U.S. Department of Transportation\uc2  coughed up $63 million to make Bob go away and return their arms to their sockets.\par \par \uc2 I was told the streetcar required extensive testing in order to meet federal guidelines.\par \par \uc2 The ugly truth is, week after week, the streetcar kept failing the multiple-choice math portion of the exam. With the help of tutors, the streetcar finally passed, which brings us to yesterday's "Dia de los Mass Transit Mania," a day that was not marred by anti- immigration protesters attempting to block a northbound streetcar, demanding to search it for \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children bound for "El Norte."\par \par \uc2 It was a day when partisan carping and empty-headed mewling was drowned out by the sweet rumbling hum of urban progress with a small carbon footprint -- a day when we celebrated bipartisan teamwork and persistent citizen engagement, a day when Tucson celebrated the inaugural run of its modern streetcar like a kid, wide-eyed and breathless, on Christmas morning celebrating his first Lionel train.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140726ea7q0002t\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Metro\par {\*\bkmkstart toc40}{\*\bkmkend toc40}\b \uc2 US attorney says border shooting just ; Defense contends agent struck man on head with lasso\b0\par\par\uc2 Patrick McNamara   \par \uc2 Patrick McNamara Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 644 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 July 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A02\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  shot by a Border Patrol agent in the deserts of Southern Arizona in 2010 provoked the agent, according to the U.S. Attorney.\par \par \uc2 "This was the result of poor choices he made," Johanna Hamburger, with the U.S. Attorney's Office for the District of Colorado, said of Jesus Castro Romo, the man the agent shot.\par \par \uc2 Hamburger said Romo was uncooperative with a Border Patrol agent who apprehended him and other illegal immigrants west of Nogales. She said Romo picked up a rock and motioned as if he intended to throw it at the agent, leaving the officer no choice but to fire on Romo.\par \par \uc2 Hamburger's statements came Monday in a civil trial in U.S. District Court in Tucson before Judge James A. Soto, in a case Romo filed against the federal government.\par \par \uc2 Romo seeks unspecified monetary damages from the government for the shooting, which greatly impaired his ability to walk because the bullet struck his spine.\par \par \uc2 In court documents, Romo's attorney, William Risner, accused the Border Patrol agent of shooting Romo as he attempted to flee back toward Mexico.\par \par \uc2 "Our confident position is that this was not justified," Risner said in his opening statements.\par \par \uc2 A complaint Risner filed in January 2012 says an unnamed Border Patrol agent on horseback intercepted Romo among a group of people attempting to enter the United States illegally, and that the agent, identified Monday as Abel Canales, repeatedly struck Romo over the head with a lasso after Romo had surrendered.\par \par \uc2 The documents say Romo 