need to focus on the economy and not get sidetracked on various promises of what a new governor might be able to do about immigration, Smith said.\par \par \uc2 "We've only recovered half of the jobs we lost during the recession," he said. He added that Arizona is lagging far behind even California, also hard-hit during the downturn, but which has recovered all its lost jobs despite having what might be "the worst business tax and regulatory environment in the country."\par \par \uc2 But Smith said the problem in Arizona goes deeper.\par \par \uc2 "We're not only recovering jobs at a slower rate," he said. "But the quality of jobs we are recovering are basically minimum-wage jobs. They're not the high-quality jobs that we lost."\par \par \uc2 Ducey promised to sign a moratorium on new state regulations the first day he takes office, not withstanding the fact there already is one in place, put there by incumbent \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Riggs promised new incentives for business, including the ability to take an immediate tax write-off on the cost of new equipment in the year it was purchased. Now, larger purchases must be amortized as deductions over multiple years.\par \par \uc2 Riggs was undeterred by questions of lower state tax revenues, saying the change "will pay for itself, in stimulation and job creation."\par \par \uc2 While that helps manufacturers, Smith noted it leaves out service- oriented businesses that do not make large capital purchases.\par \par \uc2 Jones was a bit less specific, promising to "streamline" the state tax code.\par \par \uc2 And Thomas reiterated his contention that border security "dwarfs all other issues."\par \par \uc2 The question of how to get any of this done had each of the contenders claiming some unique experience.\par \par \uc2 Smith noted his time as both mayor of Mesa and head of the U.S. Conference of Mayors.\par \par \uc2 Ducey and Jones both cited their experience in the private sector, him as head of the Cold Stone Creamery ice cream chain and her as an executive of GoDaddy website hosting.\par \par \uc2 Bennett said he was state Senate president the last time Arizona had a balanced budget, while Thomas said he took on the powerful as a county attorney -- at least before he was disbarred.\par \par \uc2 And Riggs said his three terms in the U.S. House, albeit from California, give him instant credibility in working with \uc2 Congress\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 All of the candidates said the emergence of the tea party is good for the Republican Party, each insisting that he or she believes in many of the same things. But Thomas, who was disbarred for abusing his prosecutorial discretion, went farther.\par \par \uc2 "The liberal media attack the tea party for the same reason they attack any real conservative: They don't like the principles they stand for and they see that they're effective,'' he said.\par \par \uc2 Online:\par \par \uc2 Find more election news at tucson.com/politics\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140722ea7m00005\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Metro\par {\*\bkmkstart toc42}{\*\bkmkend toc42}\b \uc2 Babeu provokes migrant protests for own benefit\b0\par\par\uc2 Tim Steller   \par \uc2 Tim Steller Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 943 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 July 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A02\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 You don't have to concern yourself with Pinal County Sheriff \uc2 Paul Babeu\uc2 's personal life to grasp that he has a love-hate relationship with illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Babeu, as you may know, has made a national name for himself over the last four years by taking a hard line against border insecurity and illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 What's less well-understood is that border crises are the lifeblood of Babeu's political career. Without them, his hopes for the next, bigger office wither.\par \par \uc2 To grasp that, ask yourself where he has been since 2012, when the revelation of his romance with an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  helped end his quest for a congressional seat. The border crisis diminished, and so did Babeu's political prominence.\par \par \uc2 This dynamic goes a long way toward explaining why two groups of protesters and a posse of reporters, deputies and "militia" members gathered in and near \uc2 Oracle\uc2  Tuesday morning. I joined them for a couple of hours.\par \par \uc2 During the current illegal-migrant wave, groups of Central Americans have been detained in Nogales, Tucson and other places in Arizona, but only when they were scheduled to arrive in Pinal County did a protest erupt. This is not a coincidence.\par \par \uc2 Babeu learned last week of the scheduled use of the Sycamore Canyon Academy south of \uc2 Oracle\uc2  in the Catalinas as a place to detain juvenile Central American migrants. He promptly informed the citizens of Pinal County, taking special pains to alert \uc2 Oracle\uc2  resident Robert Skiba.\par \par \uc2 Skiba was one of Babeu's early financial supporters in 2008, when the upstart Republican Babeu challenged Democratic hegemony in Pinal County offices and won. Told by Babeu when and where to expect buses carrying 40 or 50 Central American minors, Skiba took the initiative and got the protest rolling.\par \par \uc2 After he announced the protest, and even after protesters declared their plans to block the buses from going up Mount Lemmon Road to the academy, Babeu presented himself as the law-and-order man who would keep the peace. He handed protesters fliers on the Constitution Tuesday morning. He acted as if he was simply responding to the protests when he was actually their creator.\par \par \uc2 "Our job here today is to provide the First Amendment freedoms of speech, the right to assembly and to protest. I'm doing that for everybody who is here, as long as they're not violating the law," Babeu said Tuesday morning.\par \par \uc2 This sleight of hand is nothing new for Babeu. His political career is built on a double game: He uses border and immigration issues to arouse the passions of hard-right conservatives while at the same time building strong relationships with the GOP establishment. He gave primary-election endorsements to \uc2 John McCain\uc2  in 2010, \uc2 Mitt Romney\uc2  in 2012 and Andy Tobin for \uc2 Congress\uc2  this year, all of whom were the establishment Republican favorites.\par \par \uc2 The double game can also be seen in his relationship with the self-appointed "militias" who occasionally show up at border- related events. Babeu's repeated denunciations of smuggling activity in the Vekol Valley of western Pinal County in 2010 prompted neo- Nazi J.T. Ready to begin independent patrols of the valley with a heavily armed group of fellow travelers.\par \par \uc2 Babeu's response was to issue a tepid statement discouraging Ready and Co. "I do not ask or encourage them to come here," it read, going on to say: "It will only complicate our concerns to have untrained and armed citizens, who are not from Pinal County, patrolling our desert areas."\par \par \uc2 What kind of person had Babeu inspired? Two years later, Ready massacred his ex-girlfriend and three family members in Gilbert before killing himself.\par \par \uc2 On Tuesday, members of the self-anointed Arizona Citizens Militia taped off a perhaps 75-foot stretch of the shoulder of Mount Lemmon Highway. Looking official in tan-and-black uniforms with dark sunglasses, and wearing communications radios in their ears, the men told me they were saving the space for a VIP to arrive later in the day. Pinal County deputies did not interfere with their seizure of public land or discourage them in any way.\par \par \uc2 These are the dangerous forces Babeu unleashes when he whips up anti-illegal-immigration fever. But necessity clearly demands that he do it. The new political action committee he has launched, \uc2 Paul Babeu\uc2  for Arizona, raised a relatively small $26,385 between Jan. 1 and May 31 this year, $15,000 of it from three individual donors who gave $5,000 apiece. He's also supporting a gubernatorial candidate, Christine Jones, who could well name Babeu the state's director of public safety if elected. They need this wave of anger.\par \par \uc2 Babeu adviser Sean McCaffrey, a one-time state GOP director who now works in Texas, explained a relevant principal in political fundraising in an online blog post earlier this year, and I think it helps explains the whole \uc2 Oracle\uc2  circus on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Over the years he'd discovered a universal rule of fundraising by mail, he wrote: "To get donors to give the most and the most often you either needed to really scare them, or really piss them off," McCaffrey wrote on the Beast Digital web site. "Fear and loathing of the unknowable or unthinkable remains a powerful motivator."\par \par \uc2 For a couple of years, Babeu has needed to revive his beloved old nemesis, border-crossing illegal immigrants. A simple planned transfer of detainees to a site just inside the Pinal County line let him do it, as I'm sure his next campaign-finance report will show.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140716ea7g0000o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc43}{\*\bkmkend toc43}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 784 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 June 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A09\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Entire migrant-kids\par \par \uc2 situation is intolerable\par \par \uc2 Re: June 13 letter "Such cruelty toward children."\par \par \uc2 So the writer is outraged at the way the government is treating the \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children. Has she offered to host a few children in her own home? Has she made donations to ease the overwhelming burden? Has she volunteered her time at the shelters to help these kids?\par \par \uc2 I wonder where the families of these poor, underprivileged children are getting the money to send their offspring to the United States. I wonder how they get across the southern Mexican border. If the Mexicans thought these immigrants would stay in Mexico, they would have been turned back.\par \par \uc2 The whole situation is intolerable. The government's shame is that \uc2 Congress\uc2  would rather fight against each other than work on a viable solution to illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 Marilyn Forstot\par \par \uc2 Retired, Sahuarita\par \par \uc2 A candidate's party\par \par \uc2 is a vital consideration\par \par \uc2 Congress\uc2  is America's legislature. What it does depends on its makeup. The majority party in \uc2 the Senate\uc2  or House, organizes that body.\par \par \uc2 The Senate\uc2  Majority leader has power to determine what matters that body will consider. The House speaker is similarly empowered. Each has lieutenants, prescribed by rules and chosen by majority vote to assist in running that body.\par \par \uc2 Voters often say (apparently with pride) that they vote for the person, not the party. They should recognize, though, that their vote is often more significant for the winning candidate's party than for the candidate, determining, as it may, the party in control.\par \par \uc2 Both parties' goals are known, but achievable only with congressional majorities. A successful "minority" candidate can accomplish little.\par \par \uc2 Voters should bear in mind that a candidate's party is vital in deciding which party will organize and control one of the houses of our national legislature.\par \par \uc2 Charles Tillinghast\par \par \uc2 Retired lawyer, Tucson\par \par \uc2 Gun-control people\par \par \uc2 miss the real problem\par \par \uc2 Re: the June 8 column " 'Guns everywhere' movement brings NRA to heel."\par \par \uc2 Let me start by saying