\par \par \uc2 Research, Tucson\par \par \uc2 How is my tax money\par \par \uc2 spent, exactly?\par \par \uc2 I'm just curious why Arizona and Pima County residents haven't asked where our tax money is going. I'd like a budget breakdown of where my money is spent. Schools are being cut. I spend more money for my kids to go to public school for supplies everybody uses, because the state has cut the budget.\par \par \uc2 First, where does the lottery money go? Second, the county has all these vehicles just sitting, not being used. How about selling off some ? Third, why do taxpayers pay for these employees to go to work or provide them with transportation? Will the taxpayer pay for me to get to work, please? It's sorry that they expect us to pay their way while they sit back, get rich and do nothing .\par \par \uc2 As a engine mechanic in the \uc2 Air Force\uc2 , if you don't do your job people die. I'm tired of my money being wasted on their bad decisions. Either show me where my money goes or allow me to not pay taxes.\par \par \uc2 Larry Boze\par \par \uc2 Maintenance, Vail\par \par \uc2 Don' paint entire GOP\par \par \uc2 with right-wing brush\par \par \uc2 I agree with Buddy Gill and Fran Martinez in principle, in their condemnation of the whiny far right, whose mission seems to be to bring down Obama at any price regardless of the needs of the country. But I wouldn't be so quick to paint the entire party with the same brush, particularly at this time when it appears that the Republicans may finally be coming to the understanding that the frothing-at-the-mouth lynch mob of the far right really doesn't deserve the shelter offered by the Republican tent.\par \par \uc2 Robert Epstein\par \par \uc2 Retired, Green Valley\par \par \uc2 Hot-weather needs\par \par \uc2 should be obvious to UA\par \par \uc2 In the June 9 letter "UA will learn from its mistakes," the letter writer, who identifies himself as an educator, says don't criticize the university for conditions that existed during the last graduation such as lack of adequate water and people having to stand in line in the heat.\par \par \uc2 He implies the university now has a high-level committee trying to figure out how to improve things for future ceremonies. The UA was established in 1885. After more than 100 years, they now need a committee to figure out that a couple of basic hot-weather needs are shade and water?\par \par \uc2 Richard R. Gallimore\par \par \uc2 Retired civil engineer, SaddleBrooke\par \par \uc2 Big money will be\par \par \uc2 ruination of sports\par \par \uc2 Re: the June 10 article "Ex-UCLA star takes stand in \uc2 NCAA\uc2  suit."\par \par \uc2 Big money will eventually destroy sports. Here is another athlete who did not apply himself to the educational part of college. At least he is selling cars and not working for \uc2 McDonald's\uc2 . Now these athletes want to be paid for screwing up their lives. At least this one is not on welfare.\par \par \uc2 Most of us played sports for fun. We were not gifted athletes and never gave the pros a second thought. Today kids are recruited from junior high school, and Mom and Dad are all for it.\par \par \uc2 I see, in the future, sports taking a dive just as the housing market did seven years ago.\par \par \uc2 Ted Gemoets\par \par \uc2 Retired, Tucson\par \par \uc2 We can't care for all\par \par \uc2 these immigrant kids\par \par \uc2 I am angry and distraught that Arizona has been chosen to be the "drop-off" point for all of the \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children from south of the border. We are not prepared to care for these kids, and from all accounts this will go through September.\par \par \uc2 Child abuse, maybe? Anybody wonder what kind of parents send their children across multiple countries in the summer?\par \par \uc2 Your article Wednesday said an 18-year-old boy was taken to the hospital for seizures. Last I knew, 18 is an adult. Process him and return him to his country.\par \par \uc2 If immigration is to be fixed, reward the people who have filled out the forms and waited patiently for years, and make them citizens first. Then look into a guest worker program and start simplifying the process to allow people into the country to work and return home with proper documentation.\par \par \uc2 One thousand kids in two weeks? Get a grip, federal government. You have lost all credibility with the people who live here.\par \par \uc2 Gillian Borden\par \par \uc2 Office manager, Tucson\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140612ea6c0000z\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc45}{\*\bkmkend toc45}\b \uc2 AZ candidate says mass shooters are Dems ; Republican primary debate contenders speak on gun rights\b0\par\par\uc2 Becky Pallack   \par \uc2 Becky Pallack Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 715 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 May 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A02\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 FLORENCE -- Congressional District 1 candidate Gary Kiehne made extreme comments about gun rights at a Republican primary debate Saturday.\par \par \uc2 Asked how he would protect gun rights, Kiehne said he owns more guns and ammunition than the other candidates and said everyone should own a gun.\par \par \uc2 When it comes to mass shootings, "if you look at all the fiascos that have occurred, 99 percent of them have been by Democrats pulling their guns out and shooting people," Kiehne said to an audience of about 60 people. "So I don't think you have a problem with the Republicans."\par \par \uc2 No one at the debate challenged Kiehne's remark, and Kiehne provided no evidence to support the claim.\par \par \uc2 When it was his turn to answer the question, candidate Adam Kwasman said he supports gun rights and said, "it's a God-given, natural right to keep and bear arms."\par \par \uc2 Tim Sifert, Arizona Republican Party spokesman, declined to comment on Kiehne's remarks, but said the party encourages voters to interact with candidates and vote for the candidate who best represents their views.\par \par \uc2 Candidate Andy Tobin did not attend the event, which was hosted by the Pinal County Republican Committee.\par \par \uc2 The primary election is Aug. 26. The winner of the Republican primary will face incumbent Democrat Ann Kirkpatrick in November. Kirkpatrick did not respond Saturday to a request for comment.\par \par \uc2 Here are a few more issues Kiehne and Kwasman addressed at Saturday's event:\par \par \uc2 VA HOSPITAL PROBLEMS\par \par \uc2 Kiehne and Kwasman agree Veterans Affairs leaders must be held accountable, and Kwasman said Veterans Affairs Secretary Eric Shinseki should resign.\par \par \uc2 Kiehne said Congress should give whistleblowers protection.\par \par \uc2 Kwasman said the government should get rid of the VA healthcare system and replace it with a voucher system that would let veterans choose their own doctors.\par \par \uc2 IMMIGRATION\par \par \uc2 Kwasman said he's against "any type of legal status or amnesty for those who are here illegally." He supports guest work programs and enforcing employer compliance with the I-9 forms, which state an employee is legally allowed to work in the U.S.\par \par \uc2 He also supports a "double-layer border fence" with National Guard support, he said.\par \par \uc2 "I'm a big fan of people coming in the front door and signing the guest book, not going through the back door and raiding the refrigerator," Kwasman said.\par \par \uc2 Kiehne said deporting every \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  isn't realistic.\par \par \uc2 "I don't believe you can just grab every one of them and send them back to Mexico or wherever they came from," he said. Instead, he would take an inventory of the people who already are here and place them in work programs if they're not criminals.\par \par \uc2 Many illegal immigrants are contributing to society and aren't asking for citizenship, he said. He would allow those people to apply for work-visa programs that allow them to work here for a limited time. Those programs currently require people to apply from their home country.\par \par \uc2 "If you really want to look at the cold, hard facts, I challenge you to go to a construction site anywhere around the Phoenix/Tucson/ Maricopa area and find a framing crew that can speak English," he said. "If you like $100-a-square-foot homebuilding costs, you're gonna love $200-a-square-foot homebuilding costs if you package all of 'em up and send 'em home. The truth is they're here, they're working."\par \par \uc2 Illegal immigrants who are criminals must be deported, he said, and securing the border will help stop smuggling "and the potential terrorists that have been coming across there."\par \par \uc2 BALANCING FEDERAL BUDGET\par \par \uc2 Kwasman said he supports a balanced-budget amendment to the Constitution, including a spending limit. He said the states could act as a board of directors, requiring a supermajority of states to approve any debt ceiling increase.\par \par \uc2 Kiehne said the government should be run more like a business, with Congress offering incentives and bonuses to departments that are efficient and frugal with taxpayers' money.\par \par \uc2 Both candidates said they oppose the expansion of Medicaid and the Common Core school curriculum.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet:\par \par \uc2 Hear an audio clip from the debate at azstarnet.com/multimedia\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140518ea5i0000t\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc46}{\*\bkmkend toc46}\b \uc2 No action taken on most BP charges ; Migrants' complaints of abusehave little effect, review finds\b0\par\par\uc2 Perla Trevizo   \par \uc2 Perla Trevizo Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 1,343 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 May 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A01\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 An unauthorized immigrant complained that a Border Patrol agent hit his head against a rock, causing a hematoma.\par \par \uc2 A minor said an agent physically forced him to sign a document.\par \par \uc2 Another border crosser complained agents denied him water and touched female immigrants inappropriately.\par \par \uc2 Those were among the 279 complaints filed in the Border Patrol's Tucson Sector between January 2009 and January 2012.\par \par \uc2 Only the first resulted in counseling for the agent -- one of 13 complaints where an action was taken out of 809 cases reviewed by the \uc2 American Immigration Council\uc2 , a D.C.-based immigrant advocacy group.\par \par \uc2 Many complaints were pending, but among the cases in which a formal decision was made, 97 percent resulted in "no action taken," the researchers found.\par \par \uc2 Through a Freedom of Information Request, the group reviewed complaints filed against Border Patrol agents and supervisors from the three-year period.\par \par \uc2 Since there is no unified system through which the agency receives complaints, the report provides only a snapshot of those that were passed along to Customs and Border Protection's office of internal affairs.\par \par \uc2 The agency released this statement Tuesday: "CBP is committed to ensuring that the agency is able to execute its challenging missions while preserving the human rights and dignity of those with whom we come in contact.\par \par \uc2 "The men and women of CBP strive to treat each of the over 1 million people we come into contact with each day with the respect they deserve. All allegations of misconduct are taken seriously, and if warranted, referred for appropriate investigative and/or disciplinary action to be taken."\par \par \uc2 Mike Nicley, retired chief of the Border Patrol's Tucson Sector, said the agency had issues with the level of experience in the past when it went through a hiring surge, and agents make mistakes. But overall, the number of complaints filed are a small percentage of total apprehensions and many are not substantiated.\par \par \uc2 It might be that the agent's action is justified, he said, but the person involved doesn't see it that way.\par \par \uc2 More than one in three complaints filed against Border Patrol were directed at agents in the Tucson Sector -- the highest among the nine Southwest border sectors. But when apprehensions were taken into account, Tucson fell to sixth place, with 69.5 complaints filed per 100,000 apprehensions.\par \par \uc2 During the time of the review, Tucson still had the highest number of apprehensions, with more than 200,000 in fiscal years 2009 and 2010. Since, the number has dropped to about 120,000 and Tucson was surpassed last fiscal year by the Rio Grande Valley Sector in Texas, which recorded 154,453 apprehensions.\par \par \uc2 Researchers are just scratching the surface of how complex the system is, said Daniel Martinez, co-author and assistant professor of sociology at The \uc2 George Washington University\uc2  and head of the binational migrant border-crossing study.\par \par \uc2 He said many people don't file formal complaints, especially if they get deported or are afraid due to their legal status.\par \par \uc2 Among the complaints reviewed, 40 percent were still "pending investigation." As of January 2012, one case reviewed had been pending more than two years.\par \par \uc2 Seventy-eight of the cases filed were allegations of physical abuse, or excessive force, the data show. A much smaller number pertained to improper searches or inappropriate touching.\par \par \uc2 CBP, the parent agency of the Border Patrol, has been under increasing scrutiny from Congress, nonprofits and community members for what they consider a lack of accountability and transparency.\par \par \uc2 With more than 4,000 agents, the Border Patrol is one of the largest employers in the region.\par \par \uc2 "The buildup has not been matched with adequate accountability," said Vicki Gaubeca, director of the American Civil Liberties Union's regional center for border rights in New Mexico, during a conference call with reporters Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Just last week, Mario Alvarado, a Pima County resident and U.S. citizen, filed a lawsuit against a group of Border Patrol agents for what he considered wrongful stops and abuse on multiple occasions during the summer and fall of 2012.\par \par \uc2 He was stopped and referred to secondary inspection at the I-19 checkpoint several times . On at least two occasions, he was detained for eight hours, court documents show.\par \par \uc2 During one of those stops, an agent accused him of being an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , buying his citizenship and being in possession of drugs.\par \par \uc2 Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents also arrested him in September at the port of entry after a code alerted them that Alvarado was armed and dangerous. When the agent looked at the computer system again, it showed a different code. He was released an hour later.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol never charged Alvarado as a result of any of the multiple detentions, the lawsuit said.\par \par \uc2 Over the last several years, local nonprofits, including No More Deaths, and researchers with the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2  have published reports that point to physical and verbal abuse of immigrants while in Border Patrol custody.\par \par \uc2 In March, an alliance of immigration advocacy groups launched the website holdcbpaccountable.org to catalog lawsuits and administrative complaints brought against the agency.\par \par \uc2 The ACLU in Arizona recently filed a lawsuit to get records regarding Border Patrol checkpoints amid allegations of civil rights violations and unlawful stops.\par \par \uc2 Representatives of the ACLU and the Women's Refugee Commission, which in 2012 published a report on unaccompanied children crossing the border, said during the conference call they have filed administrative complaints regarding CBP since 2012 and still have not gotten a response.\par \par \uc2 "We need a more effective, meaningful complaint system," said Gaubeca, of the ACLU. "There's no one way to file a complaint. And when we do file a complaint, there's no adequate response."\par \par \uc2 A bill introduced in March aims to do just that.\par \par \uc2 Rep. Beto O'Rourke, a Democrat from El Paso, and Steve Pearce, a Republican from New Mexico, introduced legislation that would create a new complaint system for CBP and an independent oversight commission.\par \par \uc2 "When the results of an investigation are not released timely or the public perceives there's not transparency, that does more damage to the standing of the agency," Nicley said.\par \par \uc2 Often it's not up to the Border Patrol to release the information, he said. "The Border Patrol suffers when information is not made available."\par \par \uc2 Info box\par \par \uc2 HOW TUCSON RANKED?\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 American Immigration Council\uc2  reviewed 809 complaints filed along the southwest border between Jan. 22, 2009 through Jan. 5, 2012. Out of those:\par \par \uc2 - The Tucson Border Patrol sector had 279 complaints filed, the highest number among the nine southwest sectors; followed by the Rio Grande Valley in Texas with 167 complaints and San Diego in California, with 132 requests.\par \par \uc2 - When the number of Border Patrol agents in the sector are taken into account, Tucson still ranked first with 30.7 complaints per 1,000 agents; followed by the Rio Grande Valley, with 27.5 complaints and San Diego, with 22.6 complaints.\par \par \uc2 - But when apprehensions are taken into account, the Tucson sector falls to sixth place, with 69.5 complaints filed per 100,000 apprehensions. The Rio Grande Valley sector was second with 114.3 complaints, followed by San Diego with 107.2 complaints. Del Rio, also in Texas, was first, with 116.7 complaints per 100,000 apprehensions.\par \par \uc2 Source: "No action taken," special report by the \uc2 American Immigration Council\par \par \uc2 Info box\par \par \uc2 RECOMMENDATIONS:\par \par \uc2 - The Department of Homeland Security could streamline the complaint process into a unified procedure.\par \par \uc2 - Individuals who file complaints, or organizations that file complaints on their behalf, should be informed of the status throughout the review process.\par \par \uc2 - Complaints should be used as an opportunity to inform training and promotion of employees as well as improve the performance of its personnel.\par \par \uc2 - Lessons from the complaints review should be shared with key CBP personnel to foster a change of culture within the agency.\par \par \uc2 - CBP should become more transparent.\par \par \uc2 Source: "No action taken," special report by the \uc2 American Immigration Council\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140507ea5700009\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc47}{\*\bkmkend toc47}\b \uc2 Letters to the editor\b0\par\par\uc2 593 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 March 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A11\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Programs help those of all political views\par \par \uc2 I regularly come into contact body insurance, the G.I. Bill and Civil Rights legislation.\par \par \uc2 The elderly and poor would go without adequate medical care, the unemployed and their families would struggle to put food on the table, Jim Crow would still be law in eleven states and college attendance would still be primarily for the wealthy.\par \par \uc2 I am at a loss to explain why so many Americans support a political point of view that opposes many of the programs from which they benefit.\par \par \uc2 Stuart Sellinger\par \par \uc2 Retired school administrator, Tucson\par \par \uc2 Healthy eaters fund obesity-related issues\par \par \uc2 Re: the March 28 letter to the editor "Why must business fund birth control?"\par \par \uc2 To the letter writer who wondered why Americans should be "forced" to pick up the insurance costs for birth control, I would extrapolate this:\par \par \uc2 Why should those of us who are careful about diet and exercise be forced to pick up the insurance costs for medications to treat high blood pressure, high cholesterol or other obesity-related health issues?\par \par \uc2 Obesity is largely the result of a decision by a person to overeat the wrong foods and remain sedentary. Not my problem, right?\par \par \uc2 Nancy Arora\par \par \uc2 Retired, Tucson\par \par \uc2 Why invite children here illegally to TUSD?\par \par \uc2 RE: the March 28 article "TUSD a 'destination district' for children here legally or not."\par \par \uc2 So, local taxpayers are now funding the Tucson Unified School District's welcoming of \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children.\par \par \uc2 Think of the classroom funds being diverted from those children who are U.S. citizens or are here legally.\par \par \uc2 TUSD has already had to close some schools, lay off teachers, et cetera, because of budget constraints.\par \par \uc2 At a time when public school funds are scarce and at a premium, why overtly invite those illegally in the country to attend our local schools?\par \par \uc2 This is one of the primary reasons that fosters illegal immigration, for parents to place their children into the public school system at the taxpayer's expense.\par \par \uc2 Between the TUSD, the county and city now being "immigrant" welcoming communities, as a U.S. citizen I feel left out.\par \par \uc2 David Burford\par \par \uc2 Retired, Tucson\par \par \uc2 Court ruling shows college sports are too big\par \par \uc2 Re: the March 27 article "College athletes can unionize, federal agency says."\par \par \uc2 The article concerning the \uc2 Na