uc2 Schenectady city school district officials say the series of mistakes began Wednesday morning when the 5-year-old girl boarded the wrong bus, which was driven by a substitute driver.\par \par \uc2 At the school, teachers were expecting a new first-grader and asked the girl if she was that student. The girl said she was and spent the day answering to the no-show first-grader's name.\par \par \uc2 California\par \par \uc2 Hollywood reporting icon Thomas dies\par \par \uc2 LOS ANGELES -- He was the institutional memory for the movies at The Associated Press and a passage for the world to a Hollywood both longed for and long gone.\par \par \uc2 Bob Thomas\uc2 , who died Friday at his Encino, Calif., home at 92, started reporting when Clark Gable was a middle-aged king, Bette Davis was in her big-eyed prime and Kirk Douglas and Lauren Bacall were emerging stars.\par \par \uc2 "Independent" movies were a rarity during the studio-controlled era, and celebrity gossip was dispensed by rival columnists Hedda Hopper and Louella Parsons rather than Internet sites.\par \par \uc2 Thomas worked well into his 80s, covering a record 66 consecutive Academy Awards shows, beginning in 1944.\par \par \uc2 During his nearly seven decades writing for the AP, Thomas reviewed hundreds of films and television shows and wrote numerous retrospective pieces on Hollywood and how it had changed.\par \par \uc2 R&B singer \uc2 Brown\uc2  held without bail\par \par \uc2 LOS ANGELES -- \uc2 Chris Brown\uc2  was arrested Friday and will be held without bail on a warrant issued by probation officials in the latest legal entanglement for the R&B singer who has struggled to put his 2009 attack on Rihanna behind him.\par \par \uc2 The warrant was issued by the judge overseeing \uc2 Brown\uc2 's case after he was informed Friday morning that the singer had been discharged from rehab "for failure to comply with rules and regulations ."\par \par \uc2 Brown\uc2  had been ordered to remain in rehab for anger management treatment. A January letter from the facility stated that the singer was also being treated for bipolar disorder, post-traumatic stress disorder and past substance abuse.\par \par \uc2 Connecticut\par \par \uc2 No charges for man who unknowingly killed son\par \par \uc2 NEW HAVEN -- A popular fifth-grade teacher will not face prosecution for fatally shooting a knife-wielding prowler in a ski mask who turned out to be his 15-year-old son, a prosecutor announced Friday.\par \par \uc2 Jeffrey Giuliano reasonably believed the masked person "presented him with the threat of imminent death or great bodily harm" and that he needed to use deadly force to defend himself, State's Attorney Stephen Sedensky III wrote.\par \par \uc2 Investigators were unable to determine why the boy, Tyler Giuliano, was outside after midnight wearing a ski mask and carrying a flip-style knife with the blade open and a roll of duct tape under his arm.\par \par \uc2 Texas\par \par \uc2 3 who were attacked reportedly surrendered\par \par \uc2 MISSION -- An \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  woman, her daughter and another girl who said they were kidnapped and assaulted by a Border Patrol agent were in the process of surrendering to the agent when their ordeal began, another Border Patrol agent and a federal law enforcement official said Friday.\par \par \uc2 Agent Esteban Manzanares, who officials say committed suicide early Thursday morning, was accused of driving the three away from the Rio Grande after they had surrendered and assaulting them. The other agent said Manzanares cut the wrists of the adult woman, assaulted one teenager in the group, and then fled the area with a second teenage girl.\par \par \uc2 The Honduran Embassy in Washington, D.C., said the three are a mother, her underage daughter and another girl not related to them. The \uc2 FBI\uc2  has said the three were in the U.S. illegally.\par \par \uc2 After the attack, the woman walked upriver and tripped a camera at the border fence shortly after 5 p.m. Wednesday, the agent and law enforcement official said.\par \par \uc2 They said in the camera image a woman can be seen walking toward a gap in the fence.\par \par \uc2 The border agent said there was blood covering her wrists. Within 10 minutes of the camera image being taken, agents responded to the woman and began the search.\par \par \uc2 Arkansas\par \par \uc2 Judge tosses ban on abortion at 12 wks.\par \par \uc2 LITTLE ROCK -- A federal judge Friday struck down Arkansas' attempt to ban most abortions beginning 12 weeks into a pregnancy, saying viability, not a heartbeat, is the key factor in determining whether abortions should be allowed.\par \par \uc2 U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright last year had stopped enforcement of the law while she reviewed it, and on Friday she declared that it was unconstitutional. She cited previous court decisions that said abortions shouldn't be restricted until after a fetus reaches viability, which is typically at 22 to 24 weeks.\par \par \uc2 By adopting a ban based on a fetal heartbeat, and not the ability to survive, the Legislature had adopted the nation's toughest abortion law last March. Two weeks later, North Dakota lawmakers passed a bill restricting abortions at six weeks, before some women would know they're pregnant. That law is on hold.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140315ea3f0000u\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc49}{\*\bkmkend toc49}\b \uc2 Brewer's leaving, but conservatives retain stranglehold on state\b0\par\par\uc2 Sarah Garrecht Gassen   \par \uc2 Sarah Garrecht Gassen Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 730 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 March 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A09\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2  isn't going to run for a third term as Arizona governor.\par \par \uc2 Excuse me while I pause for a moment.\par \par \uc2 There, all finished. Let's hope I didn't bother any neighborhood dogs with my delighted yodel.\par \par \uc2 But any celebration is premature.\par \par \uc2 Brewer's conclusion that wielding power and influence with her more than a million bucks in campaign cash will be more rewarding than 1) wrangling over the tenuous legalities of getting on the ballot for a third term; 2) fighting in the Republican primary and 3) hashing through the general election isn't a surprise.\par \par \uc2 We should hardly be stunned that \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2  has made a decision to advance \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 She cemented her conservative mark by signing the anti-\uc2 illegal- immigrant\uc2  SB 1070 and cultivating an image as a fighter ready to battle the invading hordes of \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  headless bodies in the desert. (Much of the law has been struck down, and the portion that remains is unevenly enforced, and she keeps at the illegal immigration, knowing it's a right-wing-crowd favorite.)\par \par \uc2 Brewer pushed Medicaid expansion and an education sales tax, two decisions that advanced good public policy, incidentally, but gave her a degree of credibility with the far-too-silent moderate Republicans and some Democrats.\par \par \uc2 And yes, we all know that she wagged her finger in the face of President Obama. We've seen the photo.\par \par \uc2 Oh, and she vetoed a pro-discrimination bill -- SB 1062 -- after her staff worked on its language. Businesses and sports officials objected to the measure, and she paid attention. In a sad show of how low our expectations have dropped, Democrats even thanked her for her veto of a bill that never should have gotten to her desk.\par \par \uc2 We know that Brewer is ultimately pragmatic. Self-interest in a politician is nothing new, and it's no surprise that she's decided to take her influence on the road.\par \par \uc2 It's what she leaves behind that the rest of us have to worry about.\par \par \uc2 Brewer told Capitol Media Services' Howard Fischer that she plans to use the money she's raised through Jan PAC and her Arizona's Legacy PAC to support pragmatic, not ideological, candidates for national office as well as the state Legislature.\par \par \uc2 Brewer is another Republican who decries the direction of her party -- yet she remains in it, as do many who deplore the current incarnation of the GOP. She told Fischer, "If you didn't agree with 100 percent of those who say they are the leaders, then you weren't a Republican anymore.\par \par \uc2 "They have closed the gates to the tent," Brewer said.\par \par \uc2 "If you don't agree with them, you're not allowed in," she continued. "And if you're in, they want to kick you out."\par \par \uc2 This is where that warning about premature celebration pops up. Because for all the moderates and liberals who are glad to see Brewer leave office -- and there are many -- people who think of themselves as true conservatives are just as pleased.\par \par \uc2 Ultraconservatives have lost no love for Brewer. Her Medicaid and tax positions didn't hew to the Republican ideological line -- the cardinal sin of any fundamentalist regime. She's been skewered by her Republican colleagues for her perceived betrayals.\par \par \uc2 This is evidence of how off-kilter Arizona has fallen. Anyone who can't be counted on as a puppet of the so-called religious conservatives is, at least temporarily, hailed as a common-sense leader by the left and derided as a Judas by the right.\par \par \uc2 What a state.\par \par \uc2 The field of nine Republican primary gubernatorial hopefuls don't offer many glimmers of hope for a new direction. The group is anti- reproductive-choice, pro-gun and against full equal rights for gay and lesbian Americans -- all of which is pro forma for an Arizona Republican.\par \par \uc2 Each will have to fight for any scrap of attention available, and that means months of trying to out-conservative each other with platitudes and proclamations. It won't be pretty.\par \par \uc2 And that's just for the primary in August.\par \par \uc2 Then comes the general election, where the person at the top of that Republican pile faces off against Democrat Fred DuVal.\par \par \uc2 This is just the beginning.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140313ea3d000ft\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc50}{\*\bkmkend toc50}\b \uc2 Enforce SB 1070 in reasonable, legal, proportional fashion\b0\par\par\uc2 624 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 March 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A09\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A lengthy Star investigation published last week revealed the highly disparate approach Arizona law enforcement agencies take to enforcing state immigration law SB 1070.\par \par \uc2 Much of the original SB 1070 law was struck down by the \uc2 U.S. Supreme Court\uc2 . But the remaining provision requires officers to inquire about the immigration status of people they stop in the course of other suspected infractions, if they believe the individuals to be in the country illegally. That provision went into effect in September 2012.\par \par \uc2 We opposed SB 1070, and the findings of the Star's news investigation do not change our view.\par \par \uc2 While the 13 Southern Arizona law enforcement agencies queried for data about immigration stops and work with the Border Patrol revealed a troubling dearth of data, some themes emerged:\par \par \uc2 Crime victims and witnesses must be shielded from checks on their immigration status. The same should apply to passengers in vehicles that have been pulled over. This can be done through statute or agency policy. Stops must be prompted by suspicion of a criminal or civil infraction, not an officer's assessment that a person appears to be an undocumented immigrant. A person's likelihood of being reported to the Border Patrol depends on where he's stopped. Agencies differ greatly in how they view and handle immigration stops. Know your rights. Police have struck up conversations with people who are not crime suspects and asked for identification. You don't have to speak with an officer, but most people don't know that they can walk away. Law enforcement should track stops, calls to Border Patrol and criteria used to determine suspicion that a person is undocumented. In response to the Star's investigation, some agencies are already taking those steps.\par \par \uc2 Because of the mismatched enforcement among law enforcement, there's no way to know if SB 1070 is serving as the deterrent to illegal immigration that supporters hoped it would be; and there's no systematic data to show if people are being improperly targeted, stopped or detained.\par \par \uc2 The lack of information is purposeful, because when lawmakers passed it in 2010, they decided requiring agencies to keep such data could be seen as a burden, and cost them "yes" votes in the Legislature.\par \par \uc2 What is clear from the Star's "State of Confusion" investigation is that some officers are doing immigration enforcement. They call Border Patrol to do the processing, but local officers start the ball rolling by approaching a suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , even when no infraction is identified in case reports.\par \par \uc2 These facts are troubling. Every dubious stop corrodes the already often tenuous relationship between law enforcement and vulnerable communities.\par \par \uc2 A powerful voice of reason comes from the South Tucson Police Department. Officer Yvonne Billotte told the Star that fears police are working with immigration authorities has had an effect on the community she has served for 12 years.\par \par \uc2 "My biggest concern with 1070 is that it takes someone who is not documented and makes him the perfect victim because they are now afraid to report crime, and it destroys that relationship with us," she said.\par \par \uc2 "I always tell people: 'I don't care about your immigration status,'" Billotte said. "What I care about is people not being victimized."\par \par \uc2 The best fix to problems with SB 1070 is comprehensive immigration reform that creates a fair and realistic path to legal status for those now in the country illegally -- but it's highly unlikely that will happen any time soon.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, SB 1070 will remain. Changes must be made to make the enforcement reasonable, legal and proportional. Protection of local communities, not immigration violations, should be the top priority of law enforcement.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020140314ea3900039\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc51}{\*\bkmkend toc51}\b \uc2 Border chief: Security requires new approach ; Johnson, during AZ tour, says US needs to be creative, agile\b0\par\par\uc2 Joseph Trevino   \par \uc2 Joseph Trevino Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 559 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 January 2014\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par A01\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The new secretary of homeland security stressed alertness along the U.S.-Mexico border, but during his first official visit to Southern Arizona he did not address recent cartel-related violence in Sonora.\par \par \uc2 "We have to remain vigilant in the face of evolving challenges to border security," Jeh Johnson, homeland security secretary, said during an afternoon stop at the Customs and Border Protection building on South Swan Road.\par \par \uc2 He said border security is a priority along with making sure the agencies he oversees remain open to using new methods.\par \par \uc2 Under strict security and flanked by Border Patrol agents, Johnson said that while he believes the Homeland Security Department is doing a good job, 