TAR\par \uc2 837 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 June 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Despite fewer people migrating illegally through Southern Arizona, the number of border-crosser remains found during the last decade has not dropped below 140 a year, according to a new report.\par \par \uc2 Also, Central Americans are now making up a bigger share of the deaths each year, the new report from the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2  found. Economic conditions in Central America, coupled with increasing violence there, is pushing more Central Americans to migrate north, said Daniel Martinez, assistant professor in the department of sociology at \uc2 George Washington University\uc2  and co- author of the report, which was released Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Illegal immigrants from countries other than Mexico - mostly Central Americans - have increased from 9 percent of all deaths between 2000 and 2005 to 17 percent between 2006 and 2012.\par \par \uc2 unknowns about deaths\par \par \uc2 Since 1990, more than 2,000 remains have been examined by the Pima County Office of the Medical Examiner.\par \par \uc2 But when it comes to migrant deaths, there still are a lot of unknowns.\par \par \uc2 "Nobody has the real number of people who have died while crossing illegally," said Dr. Gregory Hess, Pima County's chief medical examiner and one of the authors of the report. "Part of the goal is to try to provide a national model to do that."\par \par \uc2 The way his office counts illegal immigrants' deaths is by using the date when the remains are found, but the people could have perished weeks, months or even years before they were discovered.\par \par \uc2 Nearly 800 remains, or 34 percent, haven't been identified. The Pima County office now handles more unidentified remains per capita than any other medical examiner's office in the country.\par \par \uc2 More in remote areas\par \par \uc2 People are also being discovered in more remote areas and in more decomposed conditions, the report states.\par \par \uc2 The leading cause of death between 2006 and 2012 is "undetermined," but Robin Reineke, co-author and doctoral candidate of the UA School of Anthropology, said there's a big possibility many of those deaths are a result of exposure to the elements.\par \par \uc2 "Keep in mind with these studies we are dealing with a brand new phenomenon with deaths in this country," said Raquel Rubio- Goldsmith, adjunct professor in Mexican-American Studies at the UA and a co-author.\par \par \uc2 "We don't call this a disaster in a legal sense," she said, "but in a sense we are dealing with a national disaster."\par \par \uc2 The increase in border deaths has coincided with intensified enforcement efforts across the border.\par \par \uc2 When border enforcement efforts first began in the early 1990s, remote areas along the California-Baja California border experienced significant increases in \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  deaths.\par \par \uc2 In the first few years of the 2000s, the increase in deaths appeared to shift east into Southern Arizona, the report said. The number of remains found in Southern Arizona jumped from 19 in 1999 to 71 in 2000 - and doubled by 2002.\par \par \uc2 Now counties close to the south Texas-Tamaulipas border have begun reporting higher numbers of \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  deaths. For example, the number of remains found in Brooks County, a rural county in south Texas, went from 20 in 2010 to 129 in 2012.\par \par \uc2 With the proposed comprehensive immigration reform bill calling for even more border security measures, the number of illegal immigrants dying could continue rising, especially as the economy recovers, Martinez said.\par \par \uc2 Answers to illegal immigration "don't lie in more border security," he said.\par \par \uc2 Sen. Flake's viewpoint\par \par \uc2 Arizona Sen. Jeff Flake "believes that the lack of a workable legal framework for foreign labor to enter and leave the country is more responsible for migrant deaths than an increase in border security, and that's a problem that the Senate immigration reform bill addresses," Flake's spokeswoman, Genevieve Rozansky, said in an email.\par \par \uc2 The current bill revamps guest-worker programs for high- and lower-skilled jobs and seeks to better match labor demands with supply, but it would also add up to $6.5 billion to securing the border.\par \par \uc2 Researchers said they hope policymakers consider the findings as they debate "what is arguably the single most important piece of immigration legislation in nearly three decades."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Perla Trevizo at ptrevizo@azstarnet.com or at 573-4213. On \uc2 Twitter\uc2 : @Perla_Trevizo\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Search the border-death database at azstarnet.com/ borderdeaths for the names of those who have died attempting to cross from Mexico.\par \par \uc2 KEY FINDINGS\par \par \uc2 * When comparing the number of \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  deaths per 100,000 apprehensions, in 2011 it was nearly double what it was in 2009, from 79 to 147.\par \par \uc2 * The typical deceased illegal border crosser between 1990 and 2012 was male, around the age of 30 and from central or southern Mexico.\par \par \uc2 * 13 percent of deaths between 1990 and 2012 were of individuals between 10 and 19 years old.\par \par \uc2 Source: "A Continued Humanitarian Crisis at the Border: Undocumented Border Crosser Deaths Recorded by the Pima County Office of the Medical Examiner, 1990-2012."\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130718e96600006\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc65}{\*\bkmkend toc65}\b \uc2 GCU still interested despite El Rio rebuff\b0\par\par\uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO   \par \uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,375 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 June 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 'Dreamers,' religious leaders, UA all would welcome Phoenix school\par \par \uc2 In higher education, everyone loves a high achiever.\par \par \uc2 Students with lofty grade-point averages are coveted by universities. In Tucson, competition for them may be heating up as Phoenix-based \uc2 Grand Canyon University\uc2  seeks to build a local campus it hopes will attract 5,000 or more area students.\par \par \uc2 The for-profit Christian school isn't interested in just any students - only those with grade-point averages of 3.0 or higher. And it plans to sweeten the deal by offering cut-rate tuition tied to academic performance.\par \par \uc2 "Our long-term goal is to make higher education more affordable," said GCU spokesman \uc2 Bill Jenkins\uc2 . He said the school's tuition structure was designed to be "very, very competitive with public universities."\par \par \uc2 GCU still hasn't found a metro Tucson location after city leaders nixed a proposal for the west-side El Rio Golf Course. But school officials say they're still keen to have a presence here.\par \par \uc2 Many local churches are eager to see it happen. And the Christian school also may appeal to so-called Dreamers, who were brought to this country as the children of illegal immigrants. They can earn four-year degrees at GCU for a fraction of what they'd pay at the state's three public universities because GCU doesn't charge higher out-of-state tuition.\par \par \uc2 For now, at least, all Dreamers must pay out-of-state tuition to attend the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2 , \uc2 Arizona State University\uc2  or Northern Arizona University.\par \par \uc2 At the UA, where the minimum grade-point average for freshmen is 2.0 although 83 percent last year had a 3.0 or higher, officials say they'd welcome the new player on the local higher-education scene.\par \par \uc2 "I'm a proponent of \uc2 Grand Canyon University\uc2 . I think they're doing great things," said John Nametz, UA's director of student financial aid.\par \par \uc2 "Are they competing with us? Yes and no," he said.\par \par \uc2 Strengths, challenges\par \par \uc2 While GCU has strengths, such as its popular nursing and teacher- training programs, it can't rival UA's extensive research opportunities and doesn't offer degree programs for those looking to become doctors, engineers and many other types of professionals.\par \par \uc2 GCU has relatively few master's and doctoral programs - 38, compared to 223 at UA. That stands to benefit UA's graduate school, which can offer many more choices to GCU grads who want to continue their educations, Nametz said.\par \par \uc2 Spokesman Jenkins said GCU - accredited by the same outfit that accredits UA - uses profits from its extensive online programs to reduce the cost of attendance on-campus.\par \par \uc2 While its current tuition rate is $16,500 a year, "the average student is paying $7,800 a year," Jenkins said, because the school provides hefty scholarships that increase in value as a student's grade-point average rises. That would continue in Tucson, he said.\par \par \uc2 The UA also offers scholarships and other help. Nametz said about half of UA freshmen don't pay anything out of pocket their first year once aid is factored in.\par \par \uc2 GCU has some substantial challenges to overcome.\par \par \uc2 Most of its students - 69 percent - didn't graduate within six years of starting a four-year degree program, according to federal Education Department statistics citing 2011 data, the most recent available, on its website.\par \par \uc2 By comparison, 39 percent of UA students didn't graduate within the same period.\par \par \uc2 GCU's dropout rates are also much higher that UA's. About 41 percent of GCU freshmen didn't come back for their sophomore year, compared to 23 percent of UA freshmen, statistics show.\par \par \uc2 Jenkins said GCU has made improvements in recent years, such as tightening admissions standards from a minimum 2.5 to a minimum 3.0 GPA.\par \par \uc2 The school's current graduation rate is above 50 percent, and its retention rate is 87 percent, he said.\par \par \uc2 "Not a church"\par \par \uc2 Though billed as a Christian university, GCU isn't especially heavy on religion. In fact, it may be less religious now than at any point in its 64-year history.\par \par \uc2 Before it became a for-profit, GCU was run for decades by the Southern Baptist Convention. That ended in 2003, when private investors stepped in to rescue the struggling school from possible bankruptcy.\par \par \uc2 Some GCU staffers still lament that the change watered down the school's Christian focus, said Vincent Jones of Tucson, who graduated from GCU in 2011 with a degree in physical education.\par \par \uc2 Students no longer are required to attend chapel services, for example, and "some of the staff weren't happy about that," said Jones, 29, a 2003 graduate of Salpointe Catholic High School.\par \par \uc2 Jones said GCU gave him a good education, and said class sizes there were much smaller than they would have been at UA . His largest class had 20 students, he said, and the smallest had four. He said he's now studying online at GCU for a master's degree in special education.\par \par \uc2 For those so inclined, there is no shortage of Bible-based courses at GCU. Only one is required for all students. It's called "Christian World View," but those of other faiths can share their beliefs in comparison to Christianity, Jenkins said.\par \par \uc2 "You do not have to be Christian to attend \uc2 Grand Canyon University\uc2 ," he said. "We are not a church."\par \par \uc2 The school's mission statement says it aims to produce global citizens who "avoid ethnocentrism and embrace the reality that people are different with different perspectives on history, religion, value systems, and many other aspects of life and living."\par \par \uc2 Many local Christian leaders are enthused about the prospect of a GCU campus in the Tucson area.\par \par \uc2 "I think it would be great," said Jay George, pastor for the past 20 years at Tucson Mountain Baptist Church, 5757 W. Ajo Way.\par \par \uc2 He said many of his flock have attended GCU in Phoenix over the years and went on to become successful in teaching, nursing and other fields.\par \par \uc2 George also is involved with the Catalina Baptist Association, which represents dozens of churches in Pima County. Many of them also are looking forward to having GCU in town, he said.\par \par \uc2 Noncitizen scholars\par \par \uc2 In Phoenix, GCU's tuition setup has attracted hundreds of high- performing high school students who lack U.S. citizenship because their parents brought them here illegally as children.\par \par \uc2 Arizona's public universities all charge much higher tuition to such students. At UA, for example, American students who live in- state pay tuition of just over $10,000 a year, while non-citizens pay more than $26,000.\par \par \uc2 GCU doesn't have different rates based on citizenship. As a result, its Phoenix campus attracted about 300 noncitizen students last term -about 5 percent of the student body.\par \par \uc2 A Tucson group that aids young immigrants estimates Pima County is home to as many as 4,000 \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  students, though it isn't clear how many would have grade-point averages high enough to qualify for admission to GCU.\par \par \uc2 Jenkins said interest in Phoenix has been so strong that GCU has started a college-readiness program there at a high school whose student body is 98 percent Latino and includes many noncitizens.\par \par \uc2 "These are kids who never really thought they'd have a chance to go to college," he said. "We're providing them with that opportunity."\par \par \uc2 Contact repor