news conference from Washington Thursday.\par \par \uc2 From 2010 to 2012, a binational group of researchers interviewed more than 1,000 Mexican nationals who had been deported to six Mexican cities, including Nogales.\par \par \uc2 More than half of those surveyed said they were going to try to cross again. The figure rises to 70 percent when counting only those who consider the United States home.\par \par \uc2 The portrait of the average \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  had been that of seasonal laborers and young single men with no real ties to the United States. But as enforcement and the cost of crossing illegally has increased, experts say many have decided to build their lives here instead of going back and forth.\par \par \uc2 Among those who were interviewed, one-fourth said they had U.S.- born children and 28 percent considered the United States home.\par \par \uc2 As lawmakers continue to debate what should be in an immigration reform bill, a guest-worker program and more highly skilled immigrants have gained consensus, but Martinez said it's time to think outside the box.\par \par \uc2 "We need to look at the root causes of immigration to really understand," he said. Seeing a guest-worker program as the only solution is 10 to 15 years too late.\par \par \uc2 And "high-skilled immigration is an important component of immigration reform, but what's missing from the current debate is the issue of family values," Scott Whiteford, professor at the Center for Latin American Studies, said at the UA news conference.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol shifted to a "consequence delivery system" in 2011, where basically illegal immigrants are put through different programs with the goal that they won't try to cross again.\par \par \uc2 As a result, Customs and Border Protection officials have said, the recidivism rate along the Southwest border dropped from 24 percent in fiscal year 2010 to 17 percent in 2012.\par \par \uc2 But Jeremy Slack, also an author of the study and a doctoral student at the UA, said programs like Operation Streamline or lateral repatriation, in which people are dropped off at a different location from where they initially crossed, are not having the desired effect.\par \par \uc2 "The only thing it does is put people in harm's way," he said. "It separates groups and sends them to places like Tamaulipas and Coahuila, which are extremely dangerous."\par \par \uc2 Researchers also highlighted what they called "systematic abuses" by U.S. authorities.\par \par \uc2 About 10 percent of respondents said they had been physically abused by U.S. authorities, which researchers said is consistent with recent reports by groups such as No More Deaths and the Kino Border Initiative.\par \par \uc2 CBP did not respond to a request for comment, but in the past officials have said agents are required to treat all of those they encounter with respect and dignity, and to make every effort to make sure people in their custody are given the attention they need.\par \par \uc2 The issue deserves further attention because more than 400,000 people were deported to Mexico in 2011, Martinez said.\par \par \uc2 "Funds to the border should go towards oversight and accountability," he said.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Perla Trevizo at ptrevizo@azstarnet.com or at 573-4213. On Twitter: @Perla_Trevizo\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of immigration issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 ABOUT THE STUDY\par \par \uc2 * From 2010-12, about 60 researchers from both sides of the border interviewed 1,113 Mexican nationals who had been deported to Tijuana, Mexicali, Nogales, Juarez, Nuevo Laredo and Mexico City.\par \par \uc2 * They were given a 250-question survey and a face-to-face interview that lasted about 45 minutes.\par \par \uc2 By the numbers\par \par \uc2 31\par \par \uc2 average age of the deportee\par \par \uc2 $280\par \par \uc2 average monthly income before trying to cross into the U.S.\par \par \uc2 74%\par \par \uc2 had previously lived or worked in the U.S.\par \par \uc2 Seven\par \par \uc2 the median number of years the deportees had spent in the U.S.\par \par \uc2 25%\par \par \uc2 had a U.S.-born child\par \par \uc2 Source: "In the Shadow of the Wall: Family Separation, Immigration Enforcement and Security" by the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130620e93t0003e\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc67}{\*\bkmkend toc67}\b \uc2 AZ moves to improve gun-check reporting\b0\par\par\uc2 CARLI BROSSEAU   \par \uc2 CARLI BROSSEAU, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 817 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 March 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Commission pushes for review of police access to health files\par \par \uc2 In Arizona, police officers have no way to know whether a person has been found by a judge to have a seriously incapacitating mental illness.\par \par \uc2 They don't know when they are approaching a vehicle during a traffic stop, and they don't know when they hand a seized gun back to its owner inside police headquarters.\par \par \uc2 Under state law, those mental health records can be shared with the federal government for the purpose of background checks during gun purchases at federally licensed dealers, but they cannot be shared with local law enforcement.\par \par \uc2 That fact - and the desire to change it - helped ensure continued political support Thursday for efforts to improve Arizona's reporting into the background check system used when a person tries to buy a gun from a federally licensed dealer. That system is known as the National Instant Criminal Background Check System, or more commonly, NICS.\par \par \uc2 The Arizona Criminal Justice Commission voted unanimously Thursday to support recommendations to bolster the state's NICS reporting, but only after adding a review of laws pertaining to local law enforcement's access to mental health records to the long list of the project consultants' to do's.\par \par \uc2 The vote by the group of statewide criminal justice officials was also conditioned on a clarification of how to ensure that felons who have had their Second Amendment rights restored at the state level can pass the federal background check.\par \par \uc2 But perhaps the most important caveat to the vote was that it did not involve the allocation of any money. Funds were not dedicated to the effort in Gov. \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2 's state budget plan, a fact that threatened to topple the effort altogether.\par \par \uc2 Commission program manager Pat Nelson had earlier estimated the cost of implementing the recommendations at about $28 million, but board members clarified and re-clarified at Thursday's meeting that no cost breakdown had been made and no state funds had been promised.\par \par \uc2 "There is no money in this," said David Byers, the state's administrative director of the courts, by way of introducing the measures.\par \par \uc2 The burden of many of the recommended process changes falls to the courts.\par \par \uc2 The recommendations approved Thursday include:\par \par \uc2 * Establishing specific data stewardship guidelines to make each law enforcement agency responsible only for the charges it establishes or adjudicates.\par \par \uc2 * Modifying the state's disposition reporting system to show what phase of the process the charges are in.\par \par \uc2 * Creating scorecards that would reflect how well counties are updating their records with outcomes.\par \par \uc2 * Improving the database systems used for protective orders, mental health records and warrants.\par \par \uc2 * Providing technical assistance for systems upgrades.\par \par \uc2 Among the acknowledged holes in records reporting that have not so far received much scrutiny is how to include negative drug-test records.\par \par \uc2 Under federal rules, a person is not eligible to own a gun if they have failed a drug test in the past year or have been arrested within the last year on a drug charge or multiple times in the past five years on drug charges.\par \par \uc2 "It is our understanding now that Jared Lee Loughner failed a drug test when he was trying to enter the military," said project consultant Anthony Coulson, referring to the gunman in the Jan. 8, 2011, mass shooting in Tucson. "He technically would have been a prohibited possessor."\par \par \uc2 Arizona currently reports only a portion of the mental health records required. It sends records related to people who are involuntarily committed for mental health reasons, but not those found by a judge to be an "incapacitated person" or "not competent" for mental health reasons.\par \par \uc2 Coulson estimates that only about one-tenth of Arizona's relevant mental health records are entered into the federal repository.\par \par \uc2 The next step, he said, is to create action plans for each of the recommendations.\par \par \uc2 The project has so far received about $1.5 million in federal funding, Nelson said. To keep the project going, administrators are hoping to secure more federal grants.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Carli Brosseau at cbrosseau@azstarnet.com or 573- 4197. On Twitter @carlibrosseau\par \par \uc2 Legal reasons preventing gun ownership\par \par \uc2 * Convicted of a felony or a state misdemeanor and sentenced to two or more years in prison.\par \par \uc2 * Fugitive on an active warrant.\par \par \uc2 * Medical marijuana cardholder.\par \par \uc2 * Arrested within the last year on a drug charge or multiple times in the past five years on a drug charge.\par \par \uc2 * Failed a drug test in the past year.\par \par \uc2 * Adjudicated to be mentally defective or involuntarily committed or incompetent to manage own affairs.\par \par \uc2 * \uc2 Illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 * Dishonorably discharged from the U.S. armed forces.\par \par \uc2 * Renounced U.S. citizenship.\par \par \uc2 * Subject of a protective order after having received notice and a hearing.\par \par \uc2 * Convicted of misdemeanor domestic violence.\par \par \uc2 * Under indictment.\par \par \uc2 Source: \uc2 U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130619e93m00040\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc68}{\*\bkmkend toc68}\b \uc2 Universities back tuition breaks\b0\par\par\uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO   \par \uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 599 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 March 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 3 Ariz. school presidents support reduced rates for some immigrant students\par \par \uc2 The presidents of Arizona's three public universities are voicing support for tuition breaks for immigrants who entered the country illegally as children and now are protected from deportation.\par \par \uc2 If such a measure is approved, it would follow similar changes made by the state's two largest community college districts.\par \par \uc2 "I am aware of and sympathetic to the difficulties faced by young people brought to the U.S. as children who have studied hard and worked to prepare themselves for success in college," University of Arizona President Ann Weaver Hart told the Arizona Daily Star on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 "All of us will benefit if these students have the opportunity for a high-quality, affordable university education in Arizona, and I am supportive of efforts to make that access more affordable," she said.\par \par \uc2 On Wednesday, a day before Hart's comments, Arizona State University President \uc2 Michael Crow\uc2  was quoted in the Arizona Republic saying he supports "some kind of tuition reduction" for such students.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 Arizona Board of Regents\uc2 , which oversees the state's public universities, "will be considering a range of options at their next several gatherings," Crow said.\par \par \uc2 Also on Thursday, Tom Bauer, a spokesman for President \uc2 John Haeger\uc2  of \uc2 Northern Arizona University\uc2  in Flagstaff, said in an email that Haeger "agrees in principle with charging in-state tuition for certain qualified undocumented students."\par \par \uc2 Both \uc2 Pima Community College\uc2  in Tucson and the Maricopa Community College system in the Phoenix area have opted to give in-state tuition discounts to illegal immigrants enrolled in a new federal program that provides them with work permits and renewable, two- year reprieves from deportation.\par \par \uc2 Under Arizona law, a federal work permit is acceptable as proof of lawful status when applying for in-state tuition at colleges and universities. In-state rates are much lower than those for out-of- state residents.\par \par \uc2 At the UA, for example, in-state tuition is about $10,000 a year for basic full-time tuition and mandatory fees, compared with more than $26,000 for nonresidents.\par \par \uc2 The Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program, announced by the White House in June, aims to help those brought into the U.S. illegally before age 16. Candidates also must be in school or have a high school diploma or GED, have no felony convictions and meet several other requirements.\par \par \uc2 When the new federal program began, Arizona Gov. \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2  issued an executive order declaring that the young people it covers are still in the country illegally and should not receive driver's licenses or "any taxpayer-funded public benefits." A number of other Arizona laws also prevent tuition discounts and other benefits for illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 But in January, the Department of Homeland Security announced on a federal website that those covered by the new program "are considered to be lawfully present" in the country.\par \par \uc2 While community colleges have lowered tuition for such students, the Board of Regents has taken a hands-off approach until now. Its lawyers have interpreted state laws on tuition differently from legal advisers for colleges.\par \par \uc2 Matthew Benson, a spokesman for the Arizona governor, said Brewer won't comment until the regents actually propose a change and details are available.\par \par \uc2 Immigrant advocates say Pima County is home to as many as 4,000 \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  students, though it isn't clear how many qualify for the new federal program.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Carol Ann Alaimo at calaimo@azstarnet.com or at 573-4138.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130615e9380004n\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc69}{\*\bkmkend toc69}\b \uc2 PCC slashes tuition for some immigrants\b0\par\par\uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO   \par \uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 658 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 February 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Those who qualify under new US policy are joyous at news\par \par \uc2 Dreams of an affordable higher education are about to come true for some young illegal immigrants who live in Pima County.\par \par \uc2 Dozens of them cheered Wednesday night as Pima Community College's Governing Board agreed to steep tuition discounts for those who enroll in a new federal immigration program and can prove they've lived in the county for at least a year.\par \par \uc2 The change slashes the cost of a full-time college education from more than $9,000 to about $2,000 a year for such students. It is expected to take effect in time for the fall semester.\par \par \uc2 The higher rate is what nonresidents of Arizona must pay to attend PCC. Until now, the college also has charged \uc2 illegal- immigrant\uc2  students at the higher rate, even if they've lived in the state for years.\par \par \uc2 That left many unable to pursue a college degree on a full-time basis, if at all - no matter how well they had done in high school.\par \par \uc2 "This will change my life," said a beaming Ana Rodriguez, 20, after the vote witnessed by 150 or so people who packed the meeting.\par \par \uc2 Rodriguez, who came to Tucson from Nogales, Sonora, as an 8-year- old, told a story similar to many heard by PCC's board.\par \par \uc2 She graduated from Amphitheater High School in 2011 with a 4.3 grade-point average - equivalent to an A-plus - and was offered about $10,000 in scholarships to attend PCC full-time for two years. She couldn't accept because she lacked a Social Security number, she said.\par \par \uc2 Until now, part-time classes were all her family could afford, and at that rate, it would have taken five years to graduate from a two-year program. Many young illegal immigrants in that situation end up dropping out in frustration, she said.\par \par \uc2 Local educators were among those who urged the college's board to adopt the change.\par \par \uc2 "I truly believe this is a defining moment for our community," said Manuel Isquierdo, superintendent of the Sunnyside Unified School District.\par \par \uc2 He predicted lower drop-out rates and higher academic achievement in his district if college becomes more affordable for immigrant children.\par \par \uc2 Saul Ostroff, a career counselor for Pueblo Magnet High School in the Tucson Unified School District, said the whole county would benefit economically from having more educated workers paying higher taxes.\par \par \uc2 Wednesday's vote makes PCC the second community college district in Arizona to offer in-state tuition to young illegal immigrants covered by a federal program that offers them work permits and renewable, two-year reprieves from deportation.\par \par \uc2 Maricopa County's 10-college system was the first to adopt the approach. The state's three public universities, including the \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2 , are interpreting the law differently and do not give tuition discounts to such students.\par \par \uc2 The Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program, announced by the White House in June, aims to help those who entered the country before age 16. Candidates also must be in school or have a high school diploma or GED, have no felony convictions and meet a number of other requirements.\par \par \uc2 Immigrant advocates say Pima County is home to as many as 4,000 \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  students, though it isn't clear how many qualify for the new federal program.\par \par \uc2 PCC's board voted 4-1 in favor of the change. Board member Scott Stewart, who cast the lone vote against the measure, said PCC should seek more information about the potential impact before agreeing to the move.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Carol Ann Alaimo at calaimo@azstarnet.com or at 573-4138.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of immigration issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 "I truly believe this is a defining moment for our community."\par \par \uc2 Manuel Isquierdo, superintendent of the Sunnyside Unified School District\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130613e92s00013\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc70}{\*\bkmkend toc70}\b \uc2 Discoveries of crossers' bodies now at lowest level in 10 years\b0\par\par\uc2 PERLA TREVIZO   \par \uc2 PERLA TREVIZO, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 765 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 February 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 CORRECTION RAN MARCH 1, 2013, A2\par \par \uc2 "Discoveries of crossers' bodies now at lowest level in 10 years," on Page A1 Feb. 21, should have said "exposure to the elements" is the most \uc2 common cause\uc2  of death after those classified as "undetermined."\par \par \uc2 172 sets of remains were found in Tucson Sector during fiscal '12\par \par \uc2 The number of illegal immigrants' bodies found last year in the Arizona desert was the lowest in a decade.\par \par \uc2 During federal fiscal year 2012, 172 bodies were found in the Border Patrol's Tucson Sector, the Arizona Daily Star's border death database shows. That's down from the record in 2010, when 252 bodies were found.\par \par \uc2 The federal fiscal year ended Sept. 30.\par \par \uc2 For about 70 percent of the bodies found in the Tucson Sector in fiscal 2012, the cause of death was undetermined, mostly because they were badly decomposed. In the Tucson area, the Pima County medical examiner is responsible for conducting autopsies on and trying to identify the bodies found.\par \par \uc2 So far this fiscal year, there have been 42 bodies of illegal border crossers found in the Tucson Sector.\par \par \uc2 One was that of Gerardo Lopez de Leon, a 41-year-old Mexican national traveling with some relatives through an area near Pena Blanca Lake and Arivaca, said Sheriff Tony Estrada of Santa Cruz County.\par \par \uc2 He died of hypothermia, the most \uc2 common cause\uc2  of death after "undetermined." His body was found Feb. 12.\par \par \uc2 Estrada said his office has found three remains this calendar year compared with about eight or nine last year.\par \par \uc2 "The numbers went down tremendously from 20 or so, give or take on average we used to have," he said. "It's been declining, and it has a lot to do with numbers coming through."\par \par \uc2 The number of Border Patrol apprehensions in the Tucson Sector has decreased from nearly 500,000 in 2001 to 120,000 last fiscal year.\par \par \uc2 The number of apprehensions is generally used as an indicator of the \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  flow.\par \par \uc2 Since 2001, more than 2,200, men, women and children have been found dead trying to cross illegally into the United States through Arizona's desert.\par \par \uc2 "Who is Dayani Cristal?"\par \par \uc2 The death toll in the border desert has for years caught the attention of journalists, filmmakers and photographers.\par \par \uc2 It is now the topic of a new film titled "Who is Dayani Cristal?" by Mexican actor Gael Garcia Bernal and director Marc Silver, about a decomposing body found in the Arizona desert in August 2010. It screened at this year's Sundance Film Festival and is scheduled to be shown in Tucson later this year.\par \par \uc2 The film unravels the mystery about the dead man, who had "Dayani Cristal" tattooed across his chest.\par \par \uc2 He was found by two ranchers, who called the \uc2 Pima County Sheriff's Department\uc2 , said Dr. Greg Hess, the county medical examiner. The man was identified two months later as Dilcy Sanders Martinez, 29.\par \par \uc2 The film blends interviews and conventional documentary segments with Bernal's travels through Honduras, Guatemala and Mexico to reveal the circumstances that led Sanders Martinez on a 2,000-mile trek that ended in the desert, The Associated Press reported.\par \par \uc2 The film crew had the rare opportunity to follow the process of identifying the man to completion while it was in Tucson, said Robin Reineke, a \uc2 University of Arizona\uc2  graduate student who coordinates the Pima County Missing and Unidentified Persons Project and appears in the film.\par \par \uc2 Bernal and Silver said the intent was to put a face on one of the thousands - many anonymous - who have died in the Arizona desert, according to the AP.\par \par \uc2 "It allows you to understand the force that leads him to cross the border and shows you how it's not an individual choice," Reineke said.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Perla Trevizo at ptrevizo@azstarnet.com or at 573-4213. On Twitter: @Perla_Trevizo.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Go to azstarnet.com/databases for a database of deaths on the border.\par \par \uc2 BORDER DEATHS\par \par \uc2 Humane Borders, a local organization that provides water to illegal immigrants crossing through the Arizona desert, collaborates with the the Pima County medical examiner to develop detailed maps of the region that mark the location of every body discovered. John F. Chamblee, a Humane Borders volunteer and head of its mapping project, will discuss the project at a public meeting.\par \par \uc2 The event is 6 p.m. Friday at Grace St. Paul Episcopal Church, 2331 E. Adams St. For information online, go to borderaction.org\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130606e92l0001r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSON\par {\*\bkmkstart toc71}{\*\bkmkend toc71}\b \uc2 Colegio Pima analiza dar tarifa de residentes a sonadores\b0\par\par\uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO   \par \uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO, LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSoN; Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 1,352 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 February 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par 18\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Puede que el Colegio Comunitario Pima (Pima Community College) pronto siga los pasos de otro colegio al Norte, al hacer la educacion mucho mas accesible para algunos inmigrantes indocumentados.\par \par \uc2 Aquellos que ingresaron a los Estados Unidos de forma ilegal cuando eran ninos y que les ha sido perdonada la deportacion bajo un nuevo programa federal de inmigracion, estan recibiendo grandes descuentos en matriculas en 10 colegios en Phoenix.\par \par \uc2 Localmente, el PCC no ofrece descuentos por el estilo, ya que para cuestiones de matriculas categoriza a dichos estudiantes como no residentes, aunque hayan vivido en Arizona por anos.\par \par \uc2 Pero eso podria cambiar este mes, cuando la Mesa Directiva del PCC considere dar el mismo descuento en matriculas que el sistema de colegios del Condado Maricopa ofrece a los estudiantes que tienen permiso de trabajo bajo el programa de Accion Diferida para los Llegados en la Infancia, anunciado por la Casa Blanca en junio pasado.\par \par \uc2 Si se aprueba el cambio, el ahorro seria bastante grande para dichos estudiantes, porque los no residentes pagan una matricula mucho mas alta que los estudiantes que si son residentes.\par \par \uc2 El PCC cobra a los estudiantes de tiempo completo que son residentes 63.50 dolares por cada credito academico, y 319 a los no residentes.\par \par \uc2 El nuevo programa federal esta abierto a los inmigrantes indocumentados que ingresaron al pais antes de los 16 anos y que tenian menos de 31 anos cuando el programa comenzo. Los candidatos tambien deben estar matriculados en una escuela o tener un diploma de preparatoria o un GED, y no haber sido condenados por un delito mayor, entre otros requisitos.\par \par \uc2 Los que hayan sido aprobados para el programa pueden recibir un perdon de deportacion de dos anos renovable, y son elegibles ademas para un permiso federal de trabajo.\par \par \uc2 La propuesta para cambiar la matricula del PCC esta siendo impulsada por Sylvia Lee, una nueva integrante de la Mesa Directiva quien apoya mas flexibilidad en las leyes de inmigracion.\par \par \uc2 "Yo veo esto como un asunto de desarrollo economico y de calidad de vida", dijo Lee en una entrevista. "Entre mas eduquemos a un individuo, mejor para todos nosotros y nuestra economia".\par \par \uc2 Por lo menos una docena de estados proporcionan descuentos en matriculas con solo mostrar prueba de residencia, sin importar el estatus migratorio, dijo Matt Matera, director de Scholarships-A-Z, una organizacion sin fines de lucro de Tucson que ayuda a personas en busca de una educacion superior.\par \par \uc2 El estima que hay hasta cuatro mil estudiantes indocumentados que viven en el Condado Pima, aunque no esta claro cuantos califican para el nuevo programa federal.\par \par \uc2 Las opiniones legales contradictorias del estado han derivado en las diversas politicas de matriculas que tiene Arizona.\par \par \uc2 Por ejemplo, el Consejo de Regentes de Arizona (\uc2 Arizona Board of Regents\uc2 ), el cual supervisa las universidades publicas, interpreta que como los inmigrantes indocumentados bajo el nuevo programa federal aun no tienen un "estatus migratorio legal", no son elegibles para el descuento en la inscripcion.\par \par \uc2 Casi todos los colegios comunitarios han seguido lo que dicen los regentes, excepto por el sistema de colegios de Maricopa, que es el mas grande en el estado.\par \par \uc2 Las autoridades de Maricopa dicen que la ley estatal claramente permite el descuento en matricula para estudiantes con permiso de trabajo que comprueben que hayan vivido en Arizona por lo menos un ano.\par \par \uc2 Si el PCC adopta la politica de Maricopa, algunos temen una represalia financiera por parte de los legisladores estatales que estan opuestos a la ayuda publica para los inmigrantes indocumentados. El PCC recibe unos 7 millones de dolares de ayuda estatal al ano.\par \par \uc2 Scott Stewart, miembro de la Mesa Directiva del PCC, dijo en un junta reciente que le preocupa que "la Legislatura actual les de un contragolpe" que podria causar mas recortes a los fondos.\par \par \uc2 "Ese riesgo existe, absolutamente", aunque no es probable que ocurra, le contesto Michael Racy, el cabildero del PCC en la Legislatura, quien tambien estaba en la junta.\par \par \uc2 "Aunque definitivamente habra algunos (legisladores estatales) que tendran ese punto de vista, no creo que vaya a ser el punto de vista predominante", dijo Racy.\par \par \uc2 La Mesa Directiva del PCC considerara el asunto en la reunion del 27 de febrero.\par \par \uc2 Contacta a Carol Ann Alaimo en calaimo@azstarnet.com o al 573- 4138.\par \par \uc2 Following in the footsteps of its counterpart to the north, Pima Community College may soon make education much more affordable for some illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Those who entered the United States illegally as children and now are spared deportation under a new federal immigration program are getting steep in-state tuition discounts at 10 community colleges in the Phoenix area.\par \par \uc2 Locally, there are no such bargains at PCC, which classifies such students as nonresidents for tuition purposes even if they've lived in Arizona for years.\par \par \uc2 That could change this month when PCC's Governing Board will consider giving the same tuition breaks as Maricopa County's college system to students issued federal work permits under the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program announced by the White House in June.\par \par \uc2 The move would mean big savings for such students, because nonresidents pay much higher tuition than in-state students.\par \par \uc2 PCC charges $63.50 per credit-hour to full-time students who live in state and $319 to those who don't.\par \par \uc2 The new federal program is open to illegal immigrants who entered the country before age 16 and were no older than 31 when the program began. Candidates also must be in school or have a high school diploma or GED, have no felony convictions and meet a number of other requirements.\par \par \uc2 Approved applicants can get a renewable, two-year reprieve from deportation and also are eligible for federal work permits.\par \par \uc2 The proposed tuition change at PCC is being pushed by new board member Sylvia Lee, a supporter of easing immigration laws.\par \par \uc2 "I see this as an economic-development issue and a quality-of- life issue," Lee said in an interview. "The more we educate any individual, the better it is for all of us and for our economy."\par \par \uc2 At least a dozen states give in-state tuition breaks based solely on proof of residency, regardless of immigration status, said Matt Matera, director of Scholarships- A-Z, a Tucson nonprofit that aids those seeking higher education.\par \par \uc2 He estimates as many as 4,000 \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  students are living in Pima County, though it isn't clear how many would qualify for the new federal program.\par \par \uc2 In Arizona, conflicting legal opinions have led to a patchwork of tuition policies.\par \par \uc2 For example, the \uc2 Arizona Board of Regents\uc2 , which oversees public universities, interprets existing laws to mean that illegal immigrants covered by the new federal program still don't have "lawful immigration status" and thus aren't eligible for reduced tuition.\par \par \uc2 Nearly all the state's community colleges have been following the regents' lead except for Maricopa's college system, the largest in the state.\par \par \uc2 Maricopa officials said state law clearly allows tuition breaks for students with federal work permits who can prove they've lived in Arizona for at least a year.\par \par \uc2 If PCC adopts Maricopa's approach, some fear financial retaliation by state lawmakers opposed to any type of public aid for illegal immigrants. PCC now gets about $7 million a year in state aid.\par \par \uc2 PCC board member Scott Stewart said at a recent meeting that he's concerned about a "backlash from the current Legislature" that could prompt more funding cuts.\par \par \uc2 "There is absolutely a risk of that," though it isn't likely, replied Michael Racy, PCC's contract lobbyist at the Legislature, who also was at the meeting.\par \par \uc2 "While there will definitely be (state lawmakers) who take that point of view, I don't think it will be the prevailing point of view," Racy said.\par \par \uc2 PCC's board is due to take up the issue at its Feb. 27 meeting.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Carol Ann Alaimo at calaimo@azstarnet.com or at 573-4138.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130601e9210000h\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc72}{\*\bkmkend toc72}\b \uc2 PCC board weighs tuition discount\b0\par\par\uc2 CAROL ANN ALAIMO   \par \