ember \uc2 Sylvia Lee\uc2 , a supporter of easing immigration laws.\par \par \uc2 "I see this as an economic-development issue and a quality-of- life issue," Lee said in an interview. "The more we educate any individual, the better it is for all of us and for our economy."\par \par \uc2 At least a dozen states give in-state tuition breaks based solely on proof of residency, regardless of immigration status, said Matt Matera, director of Scholarships- A-Z, a Tucson nonprofit that aids those seeking higher education.\par \par \uc2 He estimates as many as 4,000 \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  students are living in Pima County, though it isn't clear how many would qualify for the new federal program.\par \par \uc2 In Arizona, conflicting legal opinions have led to a patchwork of tuition policies.\par \par \uc2 For example, the \uc2 Arizona Board of Regents\uc2 , which oversees public universities, interprets existing laws to mean that illegal immigrants covered by the new federal program still don't have "lawful immigration status" and thus aren't eligible for reduced tuition.\par \par \uc2 Nearly all the state's community colleges have been following the regents' lead except for Maricopa's college system, the largest in the state.\par \par \uc2 Maricopa officials said state law clearly allows tuition breaks for students with federal work permits who can prove they've lived in Arizona for at least a year.\par \par \uc2 If PCC adopts Maricopa's approach, some fear financial retaliation by state lawmakers opposed to any type of public aid for illegal immigrants. PCC now gets about $7 million a year in state aid.\par \par \uc2 PCC board member Scott Stewart said at a recent meeting that he's concerned about a "backlash from the current Legislature" that could prompt more funding cuts.\par \par \uc2 "There is absolutely a risk of that," though it isn't likely, replied Michael Racy, PCC's contract lobbyist at the Legislature, who also was at the meeting.\par \par \uc2 "While there will definitely be (state lawmakers) who take that point of view, I don't think it will be the prevailing point of view," Racy said.\par \par \uc2 PCC's board is due to take up the issue at its Feb. 27 meeting.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Carol Ann Alaimo at calaimo@azstarnet.com or at 573-4138.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find more education and PCC news and resources at azstarnet.com/education\par \par \uc2 Learn more\par \par \uc2 For details on the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program, go to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dhs.gov/news"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.dhs.gov/news}}}\par \par \uc2 Then click on the "blog" link and scroll down to an Aug. 15, 2012, entry about the program.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130502e91l000jd\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc73}{\*\bkmkend toc73}\b \uc2 AZ tries to patch holes on gun info\b0\par\par\uc2 CARLI BROSSEAU   \par \uc2 CARLI BROSSEAU, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,236 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 January 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par B1.B2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Background checks now rely on database that is incomplete\par \par \uc2 Being a medical marijuana cardholder is among the many reasons a person can be denied gun ownership under federal rules.\par \par \uc2 Tracking down who is a medical marijuana cardholder, however, is almost impossible because of the Arizona law's stringent confidentiality protections.\par \par \uc2 The state Department of Health Services keeps a database of registered patients, but the records can't be accessed by name, only by card number.\par \par \uc2 The result is that background checks done to ensure weapons are sold only to those legally eligible draw on incomplete information, leaving gaps for those prohibited from buying guns to make it through the system without a snag.\par \par \uc2 Firearms dealers only know someone is a cardholder if the person presents a medical marijuana card as ID, which they say happens occasionally.\par \par \uc2 Most times, though, dealers rely on buyers' statements on their federal applications that they do not use marijuana or other federally controlled substances. They couldn't do a follow-up check, even if they wanted to.\par \par \uc2 The wrinkle in records reporting is one of many that is complicating efforts to keep guns out of the hands of those banned from owning them.\par \par \uc2 That gap in the system and scores of others like it were highlighted Thursday when a statewide group of law enforcement agencies agreed on a set of recommended fixes ranging from short- term training measures to a long-term data stewardship overhaul.\par \par \uc2 The recommendations - while yet without funding - cemented Arizona's place as one of few states actively working to plug reporting holes.\par \par \uc2 Recent studies from the Arizona Criminal Justice Commission show that state reporting to the federal databases used in firearm background checks, which only affects weapons sold by licensed dealers, is badly in need of reform.\par \par \uc2 Many records that are supposed to be included never make it into the federal repositories maintained by the \uc2 Federal Bureau of Investigation\uc2 . Some records that should be cleared remain in place.\par \par \uc2 Commission figures show that only about two-thirds of the more than 470,000 arrests entered into the Arizona Computerized Criminal History database in 2009 were complete with information about dispositions by the end of the next year.\par \par \uc2 Many convictions aren't entered into the database because they can't be matched with an arrest record or fingerprints, and that repository feeds into a federal one, the Interstate Identification Index.\par \par \uc2 The other two databases the \uc2 FBI\uc2  searches when it does a check for a gun dealer - the National Crime Information Center and the National Instant Criminal Background Check System, or NICS among other things - have similar problems.\par \par \uc2 Different jurisdictions collect, process and report information differently, and sometimes quirks in the compatibility of state and federal databases lead to records being dropped in transfer.\par \par \uc2 With only about 3,300 mental health adjudications reported a year, the state is reporting an estimated one-tenth of the records it should be sending into federal repositories, said Anthony Coulson, the consultant on the project and former head of the \uc2 Drug Enforcement Administration\uc2 's Tucson office.\par \par \uc2 Arizona does not even report in one category required to funnel into NICS, which tracks mental health adjudications. Right now, no information about active indictments or charges being reviewed by a judge is flowing into the federal system.\par \par \uc2 Law enforcement experts consider background checks an important piece of gun regulation, but many sales don't require one. Gun sales that take place between private individuals or at gun shows and flea markets are exempted, as are sales to people who already have a concealed weapons permit.\par \par \uc2 About 40 percent of gun sales fall into that category, according to the most recent data from the \uc2 National Institute of Justice\uc2 . The Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence, one of the nation's leading gun-control groups, has said its top priority is to close loopholes that exempt gun-show sales from the background check requirement.\par \par \uc2 Still, Arizona criminal justice experts found it worthwhile to improve the state's reporting.\par \par \uc2 About 40 people representing courts, prosecutor's offices and front-line law enforcement volunteered to serve on the NICS task force.\par \par \uc2 The project is coordinated by the Arizona Criminal Justice Commission, a group created by the Legislature to coordinate criminal justice efforts among state, county and municipal agencies.\par \par \uc2 Among the nearly 30 recommendations approved Thursday were efforts to standardize fingerprinting procedures and distribute fingerprinting equipment to courthouses to ensure that cases are opened in the state's criminal history database.\par \par \uc2 Felony convictions that can't be linked back to a set of fingerprints aren't entered into the NICS system.\par \par \uc2 "That could be literally tens of thousands of people in Arizona who could walk in and buy a handgun because they're not in the system," Coulson said.\par \par \uc2 The recommendations would also add findings of "not competent" and "not restorable" and court orders of dismissal based on a finding that a person was not competent to assist in their defense to the mental health adjudications that flow into the federal system.\par \par \uc2 None of the recent mass shootings would have been prevented even if these recommended improvements of mental health reporting into the NICS system had been in place. The shooters' mental health histories did not include records that are required to be reported.\par \par \uc2 Even so, participants say the Jan. 8 shooting helped propel Arizona to move forward with recommendations.\par \par \uc2 The estimated cost of implementing the recommendations is about $28 million, program manager Pat Nelson said. The group hopes to get at least some of that from the Legislature this session. It has also applied for federal grants.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, background checks in Arizona hit an all-time high.\par \par \uc2 Firearms dealers requested nearly 49,000 checks in December, far more than the previous record of 34,000, which was set the month before, \uc2 FBI\uc2  data show. The December figure was 65 percent higher than the same month last year.\par \par \uc2 Tommy Rompel of Black Weapons Armory cited fears of gun-control legislation because of President Obama's re-election and the Newtown mass shooting as the motivation for heightened gun sales, along with a traditional boost in holiday sales.\par \par \uc2 Dec. 19 was a record-breaking day that topped the store's previous record, set on Black Friday, he said.\par \par \uc2 "We've seen a huge increase in demand and sales," Rompel said. "None of our distributors, even of revolvers, have anything right now."\par \par \uc2 Vice President \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2  has said the gun-control task force he leads plans to make its recommendations to the president on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Carli Brosseau at cbrosseau@azstarnet.com or 573- 4197. On Twitter @carlibrosseau\par \par \uc2 Legal reasons preventing gun ownership\par \par \uc2 * Convicted of a felony or a state misdemeanor and sentenced to two or more years in prison.\par \par \uc2 * Fugitive on an active warrant.\par \par \uc2 * Medical marijuana cardholder.\par \par \uc2 * Arrested within the last year on a drug charge or multiple times in the past five years on a drug charge.\par \par \uc2 * Failed a drug test in the past year.\par \par \uc2 * Adjudicated to be mentally defective or involuntarily committed or incompetent to manage own affairs.\par \par \uc2 * \uc2 Illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 * Dishonorably discharged from the U.S. armed forces.\par \par \uc2 * Renounced U.S. citizenship.\par \par \uc2 * Subject of a protective order after having received notice and a hearing.\par \par \uc2 * Convicted of misdemeanor domestic violence.\par \par \uc2 * Under indictment.\par \par \uc2 Source: \uc2 U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130502e91d000e2\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc74}{\*\bkmkend toc74}\b \uc2 GAO: Border plan missing key parts\b0\par\par\uc2 PERLA TREVIZO   \par \uc2 PERLA TREVIZO, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 832 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 January 2013\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Agency urges Patrol to define goals, needs in a timely manner\par \par \uc2 Key elements of the Border Patrol's strategic plan to secure the border with Mexico are not in place, including specific timelines and resources needed by the agency to provide the security, according to a new federal report.\par \par \uc2 The report by the \uc2 Government Accountability Office\uc2  is recommending the agency develop a time frame for assessing its needs along the Southwest border - including where to station agents and technology - and to develop a timeline for meeting security goals.\par \par \uc2 U.S. Rep. Ron Barber, a Democrat from Tucson, along with U.S. Rep. Bennie Thompson of Mississippi, asked the GAO to review how the Border Patrol manages its resources on the Southwest border.\par \par \uc2 "To ensure the border is secure, we must define our goals and deploy resources where they are needed most," Barber said in a news release. "I call upon the Border Patrol and the Department of Homeland Security to develop smarter strategies and tactics and a better way to measure border security."\par \par \uc2 He plans two public meetings on the report later this month in Douglas and Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Officials with \uc2 U.S. Customs and Border Protection\uc2 , which includes the Border Patrol, could not be reached for comment, but Department of Homeland Security officials said in the report that it agreed with the recommendations and it would come up with specifics by November.\par \par \uc2 Barber said Border Patrol agents are doing an "exemplary job," but "if you can't measure progress, you can't talk about progress."\par \par \uc2 In fiscal year 2011, 18,500 agents apprehended more than 327,000 illegal immigrants and made more than 17,150 drug seizures along the Southwest border, including the Tucson Sector.\par \par \uc2 The Tucson Sector, which covers all of the Arizona border with Mexico except for the Yuma area, includes 13 percent of the U.S.- Mexico border but accounts for about 38 percent of all drug seizures and 37 percent of all apprehensions across the entire Southwest border.\par \par \uc2 But border apprehensions in the Tucson Sector, as in all the Southwest, have been decreasing. From fiscal 2006 to 2011, they declined by 68 percent in the Tucson Sector. The GAO attributed those declines not only to enhanced efforts by the Border Patrol but also to the downturn in the U.S. economy.\par \par \uc2 Over the last several years the Border Patrol has received funding that has helped it increase the number of agents and increase the use of technology to thwart smugglers.\par \par \uc2 Customs and Border Protection spent more than $4 billion to secure the U.S. border with Mexico in fiscal 2011, according to the report. From fiscal 2004 to 2011, the number of Border Patrol agents on the Southwest border nearly doubled from 9,500 to 18,500.\par \par \uc2 While progress is being made, Barber thinks there's still room for improvement.\par \par \uc2 "When I speak to the ranchers who live east of Douglas and they tell me drug flow and \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  flow has not changed significantly, why aren't we putting resources in those areas?" Barber asked.\par \par \uc2 GAO officials talked with 13 ranchers in the Tucson Sector who said the number of illegal immigrants coming across their properties had declined but the level of drug smuggling had remained constant. They were also concerned that illegal trafficking had affected land values and driven up costs in the ranching industry.\par \par \uc2 The biggest concern for ranchers is drug trafficking because of the weapons used by smugglers, said Ray Borane, former mayor of Douglas.\par \par \uc2 The U.S. economy, coupled with enforcement and anti-illegal- immigration laws like Arizona's SB 1070, have helped bring the number of illegal crossers down, he said, but hasn't affected drug trafficking in the same way. "I don't know that there's more, but it's constant because there's a much greater monetary demand than for workers," he said.\par \par \uc2 Barber said he would like to see more resources shifted to the Tucson area.\par \par \uc2 More resources are needed, said Art Del Cueto, president of the National Border Patrol Council's union local in Tucson, adding that the agents in the field are the ones who need to be asked what they should be.\par \par \uc2 "If I'm going to find out how to bake a cake, I'm going to ask the cook of the restaurant, not the owner of the building. And I think that's the issue," he said.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Perla Trevizo at ptrevizo@azstarnet.com or at 573-4213. On Twitter: @Perla_Trevizo.\par \par \uc2 IF YOU GO\par \par \uc2 * What: U.S. Rep. Ron Barber's office briefings on GAO report on Border Patrol operations.\par \par \uc2 * When: 5:30-7 p.m. Jan. 28 in the city of Douglas Visitors Center, and Jan. 29 at Pima Community College East Campus, 8181 E. Irvington Road.\par \par \uc2 * Information: Those who want to attend the briefings can RSVP to AZ02.RSVP@mail.house.gov\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130502e91a000b9\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSON\par {\*\bkmkstart toc75}{\*\bkmkend toc75}\b \uc2 La impunidad de los 'legales'\b0\par\par\uc2 TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 TIM STELLER, LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSoN; ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 3,763 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 December 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Impera la opacidad en asesinatos a manos de la Patrulla Fronteriza\par \par \uc2 Apenas dos meses despues de que un agente de la Patrulla Fronteriza le hubiera disparado al hijo de 16 anos de Araceli Rodriguez Salazar en Nogales, Sonora, la madre comenzo a notar que el silencio invade este caso.\par \par \uc2 "Estoy cansada de llorar. Estoy cansada de esperar. Quiero que se haga justicia", dijo en una tarde reciente, al frente de su humilde hogar en la ladera de una colina en el centro de la ciudad.\par \par \uc2 Si el mismo patron se mantiene, tendra que esperar mucho mas.\par \par \uc2 Una investigacion de la Estrella de Tucson y el Arizona Daily Star ha revelado que aunque los disparos por parte de los agentes hayan estado incrementando, el sistema para la rendicion de cuentas continua siendo complicado y opaco, dejando a los ciudadanos sin informacion sobre el estatus de los casos. \uc2 Un\uc2  caso de Arizona ha sido secreto y ha estado "en curso" por casi tres anos.\par \par \uc2 Las preguntas se han agudizado, ya que en Arizona por lo menos en dos ocasiones en los ultimos dos anos agentes les dispararon a personas que aparentemente no los estaban amenazando.\par \par \uc2 En las pocas ocasiones en que se ha procesado a agentes en Arizona, los oficiales han ganado. Quiza los disparos estaban justificados, pero el secretismo del proceso provoca que tal vez la gente nunca lo sepa.\par \par \uc2 A medida que aumentan las preguntas, los disparos de los agentes de la Patrulla Fronteriza continuan incrementandose - principalmente en Arizona. En los ultimos tres anos, los agentes les han disparado por lo menos a 22 personas a nivel nacional. Nueve de esos casos han sucedido en el Sur de Arizona -cuatro en los ultimos dos meses y dos de ellos en tan solo la ultima semana.\par \par \uc2 El 2 de diciembre, un agente de la Patrulla Fronteriza mato a un presunto inmigrante indocumentado en las montanas Baboquivari. La agencia dijo que el guatemalteco Margarito Lopez Morelos, quien tenia 19 anos, lucho con el agente.\par \par \uc2 Dos dias despues, el 4 de diciembre, un agente al suroeste de Gila Bend hirio a un hombre quien, segun la agencia, blandio un arma.\par \par \uc2 Desde enero del 2010 han habido por lo menos seis balaceras transfronterizas con agentes, incluyendo el tiroteo en el que murio el hijo de Rodriguez-Salazar, Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez. Cuando murio, el estaba en la acera al otro lado de la calle que corre a lo largo de la frontera, y que mide 36 pies de ancho.\par \par \uc2 Dos personas estaban en la cerca fronteriza cuando los agentes llegaron mas o menos a las 11 p.m. Alguien comenzo a tirar piedras, aunque los reportes de la policia no aclaran quien fue, y por lo menos un agente disparo hacia Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Los disparos le dieron a Elena Rodriguez por lo menos siete veces - dos veces en la cabeza y cinco veces en la espalda. Los muros detras de el quedaron salpicados con balazos.\par \par \uc2 "?Que pasaria si un policia de Sonora hubiera disparado y le hubiera dado a un joven de 16 anos que estuviera caminado en la calle en Arizona?", pregunto Kat Rodriguez, de la Coalicion de Derechos Humanos, un grupo en Tucson que aboga por esta causa. "Todos sabemos que la reaccion seria muy distinta, y no deberia de ser asi".\par \par \uc2 Los agentes de la Patrulla Fronteriza estan entrenados para utilizar fuerza letal solo cuando ellos o alguien mas este corriendo peligro mortal, dijo Bill Brooks, un vocero de la agencia. Sin embargo, los oficiales siempre deben dispararle solamente a la persona amenazante, dijo Dave Klinger, profesor adjunto de Criminalistica en la Universidad de Missouri-St. Louis.\par \par \uc2 "Si tengo a un tipo que me esta disparando, no tengo el derecho de simplemente disparar en esa direccion en general", explico Klinger, quien dijo haber matado a un hombre cuando era policia en Los Angeles.\par \par \uc2 Lo mismo ocurre cuando se tiran piedras, anadio Klinger, junto con otros. Entre mas cerca este la persona tirando piedras, mas probabilidades hay de que sea una amenaza inminente.\par \par \uc2 El 21 de marzo del 2011, en Douglas, un agente mato a Carlos LaMadrid, quien tenia 19 anos. La policia local persiguio a LaMadrid hasta la cerca fronteriza, donde un vehiculo de la Patrulla Fronteriza choco con el que LaMadrid estaba manejando, segun los reportes del sheriff del Condado Cochise.\par \par \uc2 LaMadrid y uno de los pasajeros comenzaron a subirse por una escalera que sus amigos habian puesto contra la cerca, y al mismo tiempo alguien montado en la cerca comenzo a tirarle piedras a los agentes. El agente les disparo y mato a LaMadrid mientras se subia por la escalera. Los que estaban tirando piedras se escaparon hacia Mexico.\par \par \uc2 El procurador del Condado Cochise, Ed Rheinheimer, dijo que ya ha decidido si va a procesar al agente en el caso de LaMadrid, pero esta esperando a que las autoridades federales tomen una decision tambien, para no influenciarlas.\par \par \uc2 El FBI, el inspector general del Departamento de Seguridad Nacional de Estados Unidos, el equipo de incidentes criticos de la Patrulla Fronteriza y la rama de Asuntos Internos de Proteccion Fronteriza, todos pueden responder a cualquier balacera de un agente de la Patrulla Fronteriza.\par \par \uc2 La Oficina del Fiscal de Estados Unidos supervisa la investigacion, y las agencias policiacas locales tambien pueden investigar si se violaron leyes estatales. En el caso de Elena Rodriguez, la policia estatal de Sonora respondio al otro lado de la frontera.\par \par \uc2 Lento y opaco\par \par \uc2 Pero, ?quien esta a cargo y que pasa despues? Esta pregunta es mas dificil.\par \par \uc2 Ni siquiera Jim Calle, un abogado de Tucson cuyo trabajo es defender a los agentes de la Patrulla Fronteriza involucrados en balaceras o acusados de mala conducta, puede determinar con precision el proceso.\par \par \uc2 "He estado haciendo esto por mas de una decada y todavia es confuso para mi", dijo Calle. "Asi es como opera el gobierno federal. Todo es lento. Todo es opaco (y las investigaciones) son siempre muy dificiles".\par \par \uc2 "Olvidate del proceso. Hay veces que el publico ni se entera de que hubo una balacera", agrego.\par \par \uc2 A los familiares de los que mueren se les hace dificil creer que los casos se investigan bien, porque no lo ven. Una de las familias que esta atascada en el proceso es la de Ramses Barron Torres, quien murio al otro lado de la cerca fronteriza en Nogales, Sonora, baleado por un agente de la Patrulla Fronteriza el 5 de enero del 2011.\par \par \uc2 Un\uc2  vocero del \uc2 FBI\uc2  dijo en ese entonces que los agentes de la Patrulla Fronteriza estaban tratando de arrestar a narcotraficantes cuando unas personas les empezaron a tirar piedras. La policia de Sonora dijo que Barron Torres se estaba subiendo en el lado Sur de la cerca cuando se le disparo. No esta claro si el estaba tirando piedras.\par \par \uc2 Ahora, 23 meses despues, el \uc2 FBI\uc2  dice que la investigacion todavia esta en marcha.\par \par \uc2 Hay otro caso que ha estado abierto aun mas tiempo. Jorge Solis Palma fue baleado el 4 de enero del 2010 despues de que, segun agentes, el les tirara piedras. La Oficina del Procurador del Condado Pima absolvio al agente dos meses despues, pero el \uc2 FBI\uc2  aun esta considerando el caso, casi tres anos despues.\par \par \uc2 En los dias siguientes a la muerte de Barron Torres, "vinieron periodistas de aqui, periodistas de alla", comento su madre Zelma. "Despues de unos dias, se desaparecieron. Hasta la fecha, no se nada".\par \par \uc2 Cuando un policia de Tucson o un colaborador del sheriff del Condado Pima mata a alguien, el proceso por lo general es transparente y tipicamente rapido. Ambas agencias se autorresponsabilizan de informar al publico sobre el incidente de forma expedita e incluyen el nombre del oficial.\par \par \uc2 Sin embargo, la Patrulla Fronteriza no revela los nombres de los agentes involucrados en las balaceras. La familia LaMadrid tuvo que obtener una orden judicial para forzar al gobierno federal a revelar el nombre del agente que le disparo al joven, para que se le pudieran despachar documentos legales.\par \par \uc2 Los agentes del \uc2 FBI\uc2  deben de ser imparciales en los casos de balaceras de la Patrulla Fronteriza. Pero la manera en que algunos casos han procedido ha causado que algunos testigos entren en duda.\par \par \uc2 El 7 de junio del 2010, unos agentes de la Patrulla Fronteriza en San Diego mataron a Anastasio Hernandez-Rojas mientras lo expulsaban del pais a Tijuana. En un comunicado de prensa, los agentes policiales de San Diego dijeron que le habian quitado las esposas a Hernandez-Rojas y que se puso violento, por lo cual un agente utilizo un arma de electrochoque.\par \par \uc2 Pero los testigos y unas grabaciones de video del incidente muestran que las manos de Hernandez-Rojas estaban sujetadas detras de su espala. Se encontraba tendido en el piso, gritando y pidiendo ayuda, rodeado por una docena de agentes mientras le daban choques electricos, y murio.\par \par \uc2 Un\uc2  poco mas reciente, el residente de Nogales, Arizona, que llamo al 911 y que desato la cadena de eventos que resultaron en la muerte de Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez al otro lado de la frontera, dijo que nadie lo ha llegado a entrevistar. Marco Gonzalez, un locutor de radio que vive en la frontera, llamo al 911 el 10 de octubre por la noche para informarle a la policia que unas personas se habian cruzado la cerca fronteriza y estaban en su patio y en una calle vecina. \uc2 Un\uc2  poco despues, vio que unos agentes de la Patrulla pasaron en sus vehiculos y luego escucho los disparos. Ni la policia de Nogales, ni la Patrulla Fronteriza, ni el \uc2 FBI\uc2  lo contactaron.\par \par \uc2 Es poco probable que un agente que le dispare a alguien sea procesado o disciplinado internamente.\par \par \uc2 La Patrulla Fronteriza se rehuso a comentar si los agentes en los seis casos de balaceras recientes del sur de Arizona habian sido reprendidos.\par \par \uc2 "Las acciones administrativas y disciplinarias de nuestros empleados no se hacen publicas", dijo el vocero Brooks en un correo electronico.\par \par \uc2 Los agentes se benefician de la suposicion que existe de que actuaron correctamente, y el umbral de procesamiento es mas alto para ellos en comparacion al del resto de los ciudadanos.\par \par \uc2 "A los oficiales se les da el beneficio de la duda, no solamente por el jurado y los ciudadanos americanos sino tambien dentro de las oficinas del Fiscal de Distrito y el Fiscal de Estados Unidos", dijo Johnny Sutton, quien fue fiscal de Estados Unidos para el distrito Occidental de Texas del 2001 al 2009.\par \par \uc2 Como fiscal de Estados Unidos, Sutton declaro varias balaceras de agentes como justificadas, comento, pero su oficina tambien encarcelo a dos agentes de la Patrulla Fronteriza. En el 2005, los agentes Ignacio Ramos y Jose Compean le dispararon a un narcotraficante desarmado que estaba huyendo. Su procesamiento y sentencia causaron un reproche a nivel nacional hasta por personalidades de la television. El presidente Bush les redujo sus sentencias en su ultimo dia de gobierno.\par \par \uc2 Aparte del beneficio de la duda que se les da, es menos probable que sean acusados, en primer lugar por el simple hecho de que son oficiales. Es mas dificil ganar un caso contra un policia.\par \par \uc2 Rheinheimer, procurador del Condado Cochise, presento una demanda contra el agente de la Patrulla Fronteriza Nicholas Corbett en el 2008. Argumento que la muerte en el 2007 de un inmigrante indocumentado por el agente era injustificada y un crimen, y por lo tanto un homicidio de segundo grado.\par \par \uc2 Se realizaron dos juicios, en ambos el jurado quedo sin veredicto y finalmente Rheinheimer abandono el caso.\par \par \uc2 El sindicado de los agentes de la Patrulla Fronteriza critico a Rheinheimer por procesar al agente, y dijeron que "se dejo influenciar por el gobierno mexicano y por los grupos radicales con intereses especiales".\par \par \uc2 Isabel Garcia, una abogada y activista de los derechos civiles, le echo la culpa a la falsa idea que tiene el publico de que la frontera es una zona de guerra.\par \par \uc2 "Aun cuando se hace lo que se deberia -un procesamiento completo- , verdaderamente es dificil eliminar esa impunidad", comento. "El publico es muy ignorante. Cree todo lo feo, entonces, obviamente les dan a los agentes una inmunidad total".\par \par \uc2 Contacte a \uc2 Tim Steller\uc2  al 520 807-8427 o en tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 ENGLISH\par \par \uc2 Just two months after a Border Patrol agent shot her 16-year-old son in Nogales, Sonora, Araceli Rodriguez Salazar sensed silence spreading over the case.\par \par \uc2 "I'm tired of crying. I'm tired of waiting. I want justice," she said on a recent afternoon, standing outside her humble home on a downtown hillside.\par \par \uc2 If the pattern holds, she'll be waiting much longer.\par \par \uc2 Even as the number of shootings by agents increases, the system for holding them accountable remains complicated and opaque, leaving the public in the dark about the status of the cases, an Arizona Daily Star investigation has found. One Arizona case has remained secret and "ongoing" for almost three years.\par \par \uc2 Questions have sharpened after agents shot people who apparently weren't threatening them at least twice in Arizona over the last two years.\par \par \uc2 In the few cases when agents have been prosecuted in Arizona, they've won. That may be because the shootings were justified, but the secrecy of the process means the public may never know.\par \par \uc2 As questions of accountability grow louder, shootings by Border Patrol agents continue - primarily in Arizona. In the last three years agents have shot at least 22 people nationwide. Nine of those cases have been in Southern Arizona - four in the last two months and two just last week.\par \par \uc2 On Dec. 2, a Border Patrol agent in the Baboquivari Mountains killed an apparent \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  - 19-year-old Guatemalan Margarito Lopez Morelos - who, the agency said, struggled with an agent. Two days later, Dec. 4, an agent southwest of Gila Bend shot and wounded a man who, the agency said, brandished a weapon.\par \par \uc2 Since January 2010, there have been at least six cross-border shootings by agents, including the one that killed Rodriguez- Salazar's son, Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez. When killed, he was on a sidewalk across the 36-foot-wide street along the border.\par \par \uc2 Two people were on the border fence when agents arrived at about 11 p.m. Rocks flew, though police reports leave it unclear who threw them, and at least one agent fired into Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Elena Rodriguez was hit at least seven times - twice in the head and five times in the back. The walls next to him were pocked with bullet holes.\par \par \uc2 "What would have happened if a Sonoran police officer had opened fire and shot a 16-year-old walking along the street in Arizona?" asked Kat Rodriguez of the Coalicion de Derechos Humanos, a human- rights advocacy group in Tucson. "We all know the response would be very different, and it shouldn't be."\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents are taught to use deadly force only when they or someone else are threatened with death, agency spokesman Bill Brooks said. However, officers everywhere must always have "target discrimination" and fire only at the person posing the threat, said Dave Klinger, an associate professor of criminal justice at the University of Missouri-St. Louis.\par \par \uc2 "If I've got a guy shooting at me, I don't get to send rounds downrange at the general area," said Klinger, who himself shot and killed a man when he was a Los Angeles police officer.\par \par \uc2 The same rules apply to rock-throwing, Klinger and others said. The closer the thrower, the more likely it poses an imminent threat.\par \par \uc2 On March 21, 2011, an agent shot and killed 19-year-old Carlos LaMadrid in Douglas. Local police had chased LaMadrid to the border fence, where a Border Patrol vehicle collided with the one LaMadrid was driving, Cochise County sheriff's reports show.\par \par \uc2 LaMadrid and a passenger began climbing a ladder friends had put against the fence, and at the same time someone atop the fence began throwing rocks at the agent. The agent fired and killed LaMadrid as he climbed the ladder. The rock throwers escaped into Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Cochise County Attorney Ed Rheinheimer said he has made a decision about whether to prosecute the agent in the LaMadrid case, but he is waiting until federal authorities make their call so as not to influence their decision.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 FBI\uc2 , Department of Homeland Security inspector general, the Border Patrol's critical incident team and the Customs and Border Protection Internal Affairs branch all may respond to any shooting by a Border Patrol agent.\par \par \uc2 The U.S. Attorney's Office oversees the investigation, and local police agencies may also investigate whether state laws were broken. In Elena Rodriguez's case, the Sonoran state police responded on their side of the border.\par \par \uc2 Who's in charge, and what happens from there? That's a tougher question.\par \par \uc2 Even Jim Calle, a Tucson attorney whose job is to defend Border Patrol agents involved in shootings or accused of misconduct, can't pinpoint the process.\par \par \uc2 "I've been doing this for more than a decade, and it's still confusing to me," Calle said. "That's how the federal government operates. They're slow. It's opaque, and they (the investigations) are always difficult."\par \par \uc2 "There are times when the public never learns about the shooting, never mind the process," he added.\par \par \uc2 The families of those killed and others find it hard to believe the cases are well-investigated because they can't see it. One of the families stuck in the process is that of Ramses Barron Torres, killed on the Mexican side of the border fence in Nogales, Sonora, by a Border Patrol agent on Jan. 5, 2011.\par \par \uc2 An FBI spokesman said at the time that Border Patrol agents were trying to arrest drug smugglers when people started throwing rocks at them. Sonoran police said Barron Torres was climbing on the south side of the border fence when shot. It's unclear whether he was a rock thrower.\par \par \uc2 Now, 23 months later, he \uc2 FBI\uc2  says the investigation is ongoing.\par \par \uc2 Another case has been open even longer: Jorge Solis Palma was shot on Jan. 4, 2010, after, agents said, he threw rocks at them. The Cochise County Attorney's Office cleared the agent two months later, but the \uc2 FBI\uc2  still considers it "an ongoing matter" almost three years later.\par \par \uc2 In the days after Barron Torres was shot, "there were reporters from here, reporters from over there," his mother, Zelma, said in Spanish. "After a few days, they disappeared. Up till now, I don't know anything."\par \par \uc2 When a Tucson police officer or a Pima County sheriff's deputy shoots and kills somebody, the process is mostly transparent and typically quick.\par \par \uc2 Both agencies make it a rule to inform the public of the incident quickly and include the officer's name. The Border Patrol keeps the names of agents involved in shootings secret. The LaMadrid had to obtain a court order to force the federal government to reveal the name of the agent who shot the boy so they could serve him with legal papers.\par \par \uc2 FBI\uc2  agents enter Border Patrol shooting cases impartially. But the way some cases proceeded left witnesses with doubt.\par \par \uc2 On June 7, 2010, Border Patrol agents in San Diego killed Anastasio Hernandez-Rojas as they were expelling him from the country into Tijuana. In a press release, San Diego police said agents had uncuffed Hernandez-Rojas and he became violent, causing an agent to use a taser to subdue him.\par \par \uc2 But witnesses say, and video recordings of the incident show, Hernandez-Rojas's hands were restrained behind his back and he was lying on the ground, screaming for help, as about a dozen agents stood over him, when he was tased and died.\par \par \uc2 More recently, a Nogales, Ariz., resident whose 911 call started chain of events that led to the killing of Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez across the border, said no one has interviewed him.\par \par \uc2 Marco Gonzalez, a radio announcer who lives along the border, called 911 the night of Oct. 10 to tell police that people had jumped the border fence and were moving through his yard and a neighboring street. Soon after, he saw border agents drive by, then heard gunshots.\par \par \uc2 Neither Nogales police nor Border Patrol agents nor the \uc2 FBI\uc2  contacted him.\par \par \uc2 An agent who shoots somebody is unlikely to face prosecution or even internal discipline.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol declined to say whether the agents in any of the six recent Southern Arizona shooting cases were reprimanded. "Administrative and disciplinary actions of our employees are not made public," agency spokesman Brooks said in an email.\par \par \uc2 Agents enjoy an assumption that they're in the right, and they face a higher threshold for prosecution than the average citizen.\par \par \uc2 "Law enforcement officers are given the benefit of the doubt, not only by juries and American citizens, but inside DAs' and U.S. attorneys' offices," said Johnny Sutton, who was U.S. attorney for the western district of Texas from 2001 to 2009.\par \par \uc2 As U.S. attorney, Sutton ruled many shootings by agents justified and denied prosecution, he said, but his office also put two Border Patrol agents in prison. In 2005, agents Ignacio Ramos and Jose Compean shot an unarmed drug trafficker who was running away. Their conviction and sentencing prompted a nationwide outcry led by television personalities. President Bush commuted their sentences on his last day in office.\par \par \uc2 Beyond the benefit of the doubt officers receive, their jobs make them less likely to be charged in the first place. It's simply harder to win a case against a cop.\par \par \uc2 Cochise County Attorney Rheinheimer brought a second-degree murder case against Border Patrol Agent Nicholas Corbett in 2008, arguing Corbett's January 2007 killing of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  was unjustified and a crime. There were two trials, two hung juries and finally Rheinheimer dropped the case.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol agents union lambasted Rheinheimer for prosecuting, saying "he let undue influence from the Mexican government and the radical special-interest groups taint his decision-making ability."\par \par \uc2 Longtime Tucson civil-rights activist Isabel Garcia, an attorney, laid the blame for the loss on the public's misconception of the border area as a war zone.\par \par \uc2 "Even when we get what we should get - full prosecution - it's really hard to break that impunity," she said. "The public is very ignorant. They believe all the ugly stuff, so of course they give the agents full immunity."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter \uc2 Tim Steller\uc2  at 807-8427 or tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130502e8cl0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc76}{\*\bkmkend toc76}\b \uc2 Shootings and lawsuits go together\b0\par\par\uc2 TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 564 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 December 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A19\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 When border agents pull the trigger, lawyers are nearly sure to get involved\par \par \uc2 When agents shoot, lawsuits follow.\par \par \uc2 It's a rule of thumb that Border Patrol agents know and even families deep in Mexico come to learn.\par \par \uc2 Sometimes attorneys seek out the victim's family. Other times, the Mexican government offers the family legal help through a network of attorneys.\par \par \uc2 Among the survivors and their families now suing the federal government:\par \par \uc2 * The mother of Carlos LaMadrid, a U.S. citizen shot by a Border Patrol agent as he climbed a ladder over the border fence in Douglas on March 21, 2011.\par \par \uc2 * Jesus Enrique Castro-Romo, a Nogales, Sonora, resident who survived being shot by an agent on Nov. 16, 2010.\par \par \uc2 * The family of Sergio Hernandez-Guereca, killed along the international line in Ciudad Juarez, Chihuahua, on June 7, 2010.\par \par \uc2 In that case, the U.S. government argued that constitutional protections don't apply to Hernandez-Guereca, a 15-year-old Mexican national because he was shot in Mexico. U.S. District Judge David Briones accepted that argument and dismissed the case in February. The family is appealing.\par \par \uc2 In the largest recent settlement, the federal government agreed to pay $850,000 to survivors of Mexican \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  Francisco Dominguez-Rivera. That's even though two juries failed to convict Border Patrol Agent Nicholas Corbett in Dominguez-Rivera's killing.\par \par \uc2 Frequently, however, the shooting victims' families get nothing.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol Agent Denin Hermosillo killed an unarmed marijuana smuggler west of Rio Rico in 2005, in what investigators believed was an accidental discharge of Hermosillo's gun. The victim's father in Mexico sued in U.S. District Court, but the late Judge John Roll threw out the suit because it was filed too late.\par \par \uc2 Zelma Barron Torres, the mother of a 15-year-old killed near the border fence in Nogales, Sonora, in January 2011, received visits from several attorneys after the shooting. She signed a contract with one of them, Ezequiel Reyna Jr. of Weslaco, Texas.\par \par \uc2 But after a while, the lawyer stopped returning her calls, and eventually she had missed the deadline for filing suit. Reyna did not return a call from the Star seeking comment.\par \par \uc2 Attorney Luis Parra is representing the family of Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez, a 16-year-old killed in Nogales, Sonora, by a Border Patrol agent firing across the border on Oct. 10. The agency said the gunfire was in response to rock throwing from the Mexican side.\par \par \uc2 "We're maintaining that Jose Antonio was not involved with rock throwers. He was not involved with crossing into the United States," Parra said.\par \par \uc2 The family plans to file a claim within the six months required by law, he said.\par \par \uc2 Suits can provide some accountability, said Esha Bhandari of the ACLU's Immigrant Rights Project.\par \par \uc2 She pointed to the Hernandez-Guereca case from El Paso as an example. Almost two years after the June 2010 shooting, in April this year, the Justice Department announced it would not pursue charges against the agent who shot him, despite witnesses and video evidence that raised questions about the necessity of the shooting.\par \par \uc2 "It's basically case closed," she said, "unless the Hernandez family gets their day in court."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Tim Steller at 807-8427 or tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130407e8c900008\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc77}{\*\bkmkend toc77}\b \uc2 Border Patrol faces little accountability\b0\par\par\uc2 TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 2,587 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 December 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 STAR INVESTIGATION: FEW ANSWERS WHEN AGENTS SHOOT\par \par \uc2 Shootings by agents are up, but few are held responsible; families and the public rarely learn the outcome of secret, complex investigations\par \par \uc2 Just two months after a Border Patrol agent shot her 16-year-old son in Nogales, Sonora, Araceli Rodriguez Salazar sensed silence spreading over the case.\par \par \uc2 "I'm tired of crying. I'm tired of waiting. I want justice," she said on a recent afternoon, standing outside her humble home on a downtown hillside.\par \par \uc2 If the pattern holds, she'll be waiting much longer.\par \par \uc2 Even as the number of shootings by agents increases, the system for holding them accountable remains complicated and opaque, leaving the public in the dark about the status of the cases, an Arizona Daily Star investigation has found. One Arizona case has remained secret and "ongoing" for almost three years.\par \par \uc2 Questions have sharpened after agents shot people who apparently weren't threatening them at least twice in Arizona over the last two years.\par \par \uc2 Still, agents get the benefit of the doubt from the public and prosecutors, and are rarely criminally charged. In the few cases when agents have been prosecuted in Arizona, they've won.\par \par \uc2 That may be because the shootings were justified, but the secrecy of the process means the public may never know.\par \par \uc2 As questions of accountability grow louder, shootings by Border Patrol agents continue - primarily in Arizona. In the last three years agents have shot at least 22 people nationwide. Nine of those cases have been in Southern Arizona - four in the last two months and two just last week.\par \par \uc2 Last Sunday, a Border Patrol agent in the Baboquivari Mountains killed an apparent \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  - 19-year-old Guatemalan Margarito Lopez Morelos - who, the agency said, struggled with an agent. On Tuesday, an agent southwest of Gila Bend shot and wounded a man who, the agency said, brandished a weapon.\par \par \uc2 Since January 2010, there have been at least six cross-border shootings by agents, including the one that killed Rodriguez- Salazar's son, Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez. When killed, he was on a sidewalk across the 36-foot-wide street along the border.\par \par \uc2 Two people were on the border fence when agents arrived at about 11 p.m. Rocks flew, though police reports leave it unclear who threw them, and at least one agent fired into Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Elena Rodriguez was hit at least seven times - twice in the head and five times in the back. The walls next to him were pocked with bullet holes.\par \par \uc2 "What would have happened if a Sonoran police officer had opened fire and shot a 16-year-old walking along the street in Arizona?" asked Kat Rodriguez of the Coalicion de Derechos Humanos, a human- rights advocacy group in Tucson. "We all know the response would be very different, and it shouldn't be."\par \par \uc2 agent ivie's death\par \par \uc2 Early on Oct. 2, Border Patrol Agent Nicholas Ivie cautiously approached a site east of Bisbee where a ground sensor had gone off. Two fellow agents approached from another direction.\par \par \uc2 In an apparent accident, Ivie fired at the other agents, striking one, the \uc2 FBI\uc2  and Cochise County Sheriff's Department reported. The agent who was struck fired back, killing Ivie.\par \par \uc2 Amid an outpouring of support for Ivie's family, some found a key aspect of the case troubling: Here was a case where an agent apparently didn't know what he was shooting at.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents are taught to use deadly force only when they or someone else are threatened with death, agency spokesman Bill Brooks said.. However, officers everywhere must always have "target discrimination" and fire only at the person posing the threat, said Dave Klinger, an associate professor of criminal justice at the University of Missouri-St. Louis.\par \par \uc2 "If I've got a guy shooting at me, I don't get to send rounds downrange at the general area," said Klinger, who himself shot and killed a man when he was a Los Angeles police officer.\par \par \uc2 The same rules apply to rock-throwing, Klinger and others said. The closer the thrower, the more likely it poses an imminent threat.\par \par \uc2 On March 21, 2011, an agent shot and killed 19-year-old Carlos LaMadrid in Douglas. Local police had chased LaMadrid to the border fence, where a Border Patrol vehicle collided with the one LaMadrid was driving, Cochise County sheriff's reports show.\par \par \uc2 LaMadrid and a passenger began climbing a ladder friends had put against the fence, and at the same time someone atop the fence began throwing rocks at the agent. The agent fired and killed LaMadrid as he climbed the ladder. The rock throwers escaped into Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Cochise County Attorney Ed Rheinheimer said he has made a decision about whether to prosecute the agent in the LaMadrid case, but he is waiting until federal authorities make their call so as not to influence their decision.\par \par \uc2 who's in charge?\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 FBI\uc2 , Department of Homeland Security inspector general, the Border Patrol's critical incident team and the Customs and Border Protection Internal Affairs branch all may respond to any shooting by a Border Patrol agent.\par \par \uc2 The U.S. Attorney's Office oversees the investigation, and local agencies - such as a sheriff's department - may also investigate whether state laws were broken. In Elena Rodriguez's case, the local agency was Sonoran state police, who responded on their side of the border.\par \par \uc2 Who's in charge, and what happens from there? That's a tougher question. Even Jim Calle, a Tucson attorney whose job is to defend Border Patrol agents involved in shootings or accused of misconduct, can't pinpoint the process.\par \par \uc2 "I've been doing this for more than a decade, and it's still confusing to me," Calle said. "That's how the federal government operates. They're slow. It's opaque, and they (the investigations) are always difficult."\par \par \uc2 "There are times when the public never learns about the shooting, never mind the process," he added. "The one thing I am sure of is that every time an agent pulls a trigger, their conduct is critically reviewed, and it is really, really scrubbed hard for all the details to see if they've done anything wrong."\par \par \uc2 The families of those killed and others find it hard to believe the cases are well-investigated because they can't see it. One of the families stuck in the process is that of Ramses Barron Torres, killed on the Mexican side of the border fence in Nogales, Sonora, by a Border Patrol agent on Jan. 5, 2011.\par \par \uc2 An FBI spokesman said at the time that Border Patrol agents were trying to arrest drug smugglers when people started throwing rocks at them. Sonoran police said Barron Torres was climbing on the south side of the border fence when shot. It's unclear whether he was a rock thrower.\par \par \uc2 Now, 23 months later, he \uc2 FBI\uc2  says the investigation is ongoing.\par \par \uc2 Another case has been open even longer: Jorge Solis-Palma was shot on Jan. 4, 2010, after, agents said, he threw rocks at them. The Cochise County Attorney's Office cleared the agent two months later, but the \uc2 FBI\uc2  still considers it "an ongoing matter" almost three years later.\par \par \uc2 In the days after Barron Torres was shot, "there were reporters from here, reporters from over there," his mother, Zelma, said in Spanish. "After a few days, they disappeared. Up till now, I don't know anything."\par \par \uc2 names are secret\par \par \uc2 When a Tucson police officer or a Pima County sheriff's deputy shoots and kills somebody, the process is mostly transparent and typically quick.\par \par \uc2 Both agencies make it a rule to inform the public of the incident quickly and include the officer's name. The Border Patrol keeps the names of agents involved in shootings secret - to the point that LaMadrid's family got a court order to force the federal government to reveal the name of the agent who shot him so they could serve him with legal papers.\par \par \uc2 On the local level, two investigations of shootings occur.\par \par \uc2 In one, the local homicide department looks into whether the officer broke the law. Investigators pass their findings to the county attorney's office for a ruling on whether charges should be filed.\par \par \uc2 In the other investigation, internal affairs decides whether the officer followed department rules and regulations.\par \par \uc2 Those cases are typically wrapped up in two to six months, attorney Calle said.\par \par \uc2 The different ways the two levels of government respond is typical, said Klinger, the University of Missouri professor.\par \par \uc2 "The further away from the populace the seat of power is, the less accountability there is," he said. "For whatever reason, people haven't been making a big stink about federal use of deadly force."\par \par \uc2 In Border Patrol shooting cases, the investigation may be in an "ongoing" status long after FBI special agents have completed their work, said James Turgal, special agent in charge of the agency's Phoenix division. That may be because prosecutors from the county to the U.S. Attorney's Office to the Justice Department in Washington, D.C., are considering their options.\par \par \uc2 "Just because the \uc2 FBI\uc2  walks down to the U.S. Attorney's Office and presents a case, it doesn't mean we get an answer the next day," he said.\par \par \uc2 doubtful witnesses\par \par \uc2 FBI\uc2  agents enter Border Patrol shooting cases impartially, Turgal said. But the way some cases proceeded left witnesses with doubt.\par \par \uc2 On June 7, 2010, Border Patrol agents in San Diego killed Anastasio Hernandez-Rojas as they were expelling him from the country into Tijuana. In a press release, San Diego police said agents had uncuffed Hernandez-Rojas and he became violent, causing an agent to use a taser to subdue him.\par \par \uc2 But witnesses say, and video recordings of the incident show, Hernandez-Rojas's hands were restrained behind his back and he was lying on the ground, screaming for help, as about a dozen agents stood over him, when he was tased and died. The PBS program "Need to Know" revealed the videotapes and some witness accounts in two shows this year.\par \par \uc2 On June 7, 2010, a Border Patrol agent shot and killed 15-year- old Sergio Hernandez-Guereca in a concrete canal that separates Ciudad Juarez, Chihuahua, from El Paso. In a news release, the \uc2 FBI\uc2  said the agent fired when a group "surrounded the agent and continued to throw rocks at him."\par \par \uc2 Witness accounts and videos show that the agent was not surrounded and that apparently no more than one person threw a rock at him. Nevertheless, the \uc2 FBI\uc2  labeled the incident as an "assault on a federal officer."\par \par \uc2 In some cases, the aftermath of the shootings does not inspire witnesses' confidence in investigators. In both the San Diego and El Paso cases, witnesses who were crossing border bridges when the shootings occurred said they were hustled away and not questioned.\par \par \uc2 One American woman who watched the agent shoot Hernandez-Guereca said in a deposition that she refused to leave the bridge despite a security guard shouting at her, and she spoke to investigators only after she insisted on calling 911 and later called the \uc2 FBI\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "No one approached me and said, 'Listen, can you tell us what happened?'" Bobbie James McDow said in a sworn deposition taken as part of a civil lawsuit. "It was basically, 'Get off the bridge, get off the bridge, get out of here.' "\par \par \uc2 More recently, a Nogales, Ariz., resident whose 911 call started chain of events that led to the killing of Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez across the border, said no one has interviewed him.\par \par \uc2 Marco Gonzalez, a radio announcer who lives along the border, called 911 the night of Oct. 10 to tell police that people had jumped the border fence and were moving through his yard and a neighboring street. Soon after, he saw border agents drive by, then heard gunshots.\par \par \uc2 Neither Nogales police nor Border Patrol agents nor the \uc2 FBI\uc2  contacted him.\par \par \uc2 Sanctions unlikely\par \par \uc2 An agent who shoots somebody is unlikely to face prosecution or even internal discipline.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol declined to say whether the agents in any of the six recent Southern Arizona shooting cases were reprimanded. "Administrative and disciplinary actions of our employees are not made public," agency spokesman Brooks said in an email.\par \par \uc2 Calle, the Border Patrol union's lawyer, said in shootings it's "exceedingly rare that an agent faces disciplinary consequences for their conduct."\par \par \uc2 That's partly because most shootings are legally justified, agents and attorneys said. They argue there are more shootings now largely because more border jumpers resist arrest.\par \par \uc2 Also, they say, agents enjoy an assumption that they're in the right, and they face a higher threshold for prosecution than the average citizen.\par \par \uc2 "Law enforcement officers are given the benefit of the doubt, not only by juries and American citizens, but inside DAs' and U.S. attorneys' offices," said Johnny Sutton, who was U.S. attorney for the western district of Texas from 2001 to 2009. "You're always loath to prosecute a cop because you understand they're putting their lives on the line every day."\par \par \uc2 As U.S. attorney, Sutton ruled many shootings by agents justified and denied prosecution, he said, but his office also put two Border Patrol agents in prison. In 2005, agents Ignacio Ramos and Jose Compean shot an unarmed drug trafficker who was running away. Their conviction and sentencing prompted a nationwide outcry led by television personalities. President Bush commuted their sentences on his last day in office.\par \par \uc2 Beyond the benefit of the doubt officers receive, their jobs make them less likely to be charged in the first place. Prosecutors must consider the likelihood of winning a conviction when taking on a case, and it's simply harder to win a case against a cop.\par \par \uc2 Cochise County Attorney Rheinheimer brought a second-degree murder case against Border Patrol Agent Nicholas Corbett in 2008, arguing Corbett's January 2007 killing of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  was unjustified and a crime. There were two trials, two hung juries and finally Rheinheimer dropped the case.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol agents union lambasted Rheinheimer for prosecuting, saying "he let undue influence from the Mexican government and the radical special-interest groups taint his decision-making ability."\par \par \uc2 Longtime Tucson civil-rights activist Isabel Garcia, an attorney, laid the blame for the loss on the public's misconception of the border area as a war zone.\par \par \uc2 "Even when we get what we should get - full prosecution - it's really hard to break that impunity," she said. "The public is very ignorant. They believe all the ugly stuff, so of course they give the agents full immunity."\par \par \uc2 If there's a next time, Rheinheimer said, he would factor in his failure to convict Corbett when deciding whether it's worth bringing charges against another agent.\par \par \uc2 That reality, he said, "is balanced against doing whatever is the right thing to do."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter \uc2 Tim Steller\uc2  at 807-8427 or tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of border-related issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 Continued from previous page\par \par \uc2 Continued on next0 page\par \par \uc2 the investigation continues inside\par \par \uc2 Shootings by agents\par \par \uc2 Map details 20 incidents in the past two years involving Border Patrol agents. Page A18\par \par \uc2 Seeking justice by lawsuit\par \par \uc2 Families, often frustrated by a lack of information after a loved one is killed, increasingly look to the courts for relief.\par \par \uc2 Page A19\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020130407e8c900007\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc78}{\*\bkmkend toc78}\b \uc2 Border agent slain; partner wounded\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS; TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS AND TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,186 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 October 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Unknown gunmen flee shooting scene east of Bisbee\par \par \uc2 NACO - U.S. Border Patrol Agent Nick Ivie usually got home from his overnight shift at about 4 a.m., but on Tuesday about that time other agents knocked on the door of his Sierra Vista home.\par \par \uc2 They came to tell Ivie's wife, Christy, Nick had died.\par \par \uc2 Ivie and two other agents responded early Tuesday morning to an area where a ground sensor had been tripped, about eight miles east of Bisbee and five miles north of the border. They were on foot in the hilly area when unknown gunmen opened fire.\par \par \uc2 Ivie, a 30-year-old father of two young girls, died of his wounds, another agent was wounded and the third agent was not hit. The wounded agent was in stable condition Tuesday after surgery at a Tucson hospital.\par \par \uc2 The agents were assigned to the Naco Border Patrol station, which was renamed in honor of slain agent Brian Terry just two weeks ago. Ivie's death put a new name on the dismaying list of victims of border violence.\par \par \uc2 "It just goes to show that whether you are an armed Border Patrol agent on duty or a simple rancher like Rob Krentz out working his ranch - if you're in border country you are in peril," said Rod Rothrock, acting sheriff of Cochise County.\par \par \uc2 Residents of the area midway between Naco and Douglas, about 100 miles southeast of Tucson, said the number of illegal immigrants has plummeted since 2008 when a fence across the border was completed and the economy tanked. The twist: Drug-smuggling traffic has remained about the same.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, the killing took place in an area that has been a drug- smuggling corridor for 30 to 40 years, said Lee Morgan II, who retired as a U.S. Customs Service special agent in 2006 after decades in the area.\par \par \uc2 "It's a historically bad area," said Morgan. "Over the years we've had numerous armed confrontations, shootings, pursuits."\par \par \uc2 Tripped sensors routine\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol has buried sensors in many spots along border trails in Southern Arizona. Responding to a tripped sensor is a routine part of an agent's shift, said Art Del Cueto, president of the National Border Patrol Council local 2544 in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Agents learn over time which sensors tend to signal \uc2 illegal- immigrant\uc2  groups, and which usually mean drug smugglers are moving through, Del Cueto said. But whenever they respond, they're in a heightened state of alertness.\par \par \uc2 The agents who responded early Tuesday radioed that they had come under fire from three or four people, Cochise County sheriff's Cmdr. Marc Denney told the Los Angeles Times. It is not known whether the agents returned fire, sheriff's spokeswoman Carol Capas told The Associated Press.\par \par \uc2 By the time deputies responded, the gunmen had disappeared, apparently on foot, Denney told the Times. "Whether they were picked up in another vehicle is unknown," he said. "They had a bit of a jump on us." Border agents were sent to try to cut off escape routes to Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Two suspects were detained by Mexican officials south of the border Tuesday, Denney told the L.A. Times. Rothrock, the acting sheriff, told the Star he had heard that but couldn't confirm it.\par \par \uc2 Rothrock's agency and the FBI are investigating the case jointly, but they declined to give any details of the shooting or investigation at a news conference Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 In Mexico, soldiers and federal and state police were sent to the area, but a spokesman for the Mexican military said no arrests were made, the Times reported.\par \par \uc2 President Obama called Ivie's family Tuesday to offer condolences and to express his gratitude for the agent's "selfless service to his nation," the White House said. Obama said the administration "was doing everything it could to locate those responsible."\par \par \uc2 "It's changed a lot" recently\par \par \uc2 Dan Oldfield's dogs started barking about 2 a.m. Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Oldfield, 66, has lived on property along Arizona 80 for 25 years, just southeast of the Bisbee-Douglas highway in the southeastern foothills of the Mule Mountains.\par \par \uc2 "I got up and there were three cop cars with automatic weapons in my driveway," Oldfield said.\par \par \uc2 The officers told him an agent had been killed, and helicopters began circling the area, swooping over the house all night, he said.\par \par \uc2 The late-night action in the area has calmed in recent years as the groups of illegal border-crossers dwindled, he and other residents said. Much of the change happened after 2008, when the fence was completed between Naco and Douglas, said rancher Fred Giacoletti. Yet he and others said the drug-smuggling traffic has not gone down.\par \par \uc2 Ironically, the potential for trouble seems higher, said Tony Coulson, who retired as the agent in charge of the \uc2 Drug Enforcement Administration\uc2 's Tucson office in 2010. "The drug smuggling has been historically very aggressive in that area," Coulson said, adding: "The nature of trafficking has so changed, in the sense of the violence and the shooting."\par \par \uc2 Yet some residents feel quite safe compared to border agents, whose job puts them in harm's way. "It's actually pretty quiet down here," said Cynthia Binyon, who lives east of Naco.\par \par \uc2 A Dedicated dad and mormon\par \par \uc2 Ivie was a loving husband and father who cherished spending time with his daughters, ages 3 and 1, said Kevin Goates, president of the Sierra Vista stake of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. Originally from Provo, Utah, Ivie served his Mormon mission in Mexico City and became a border agent assigned to the Naco station in January 2008.\par \par \uc2 He was a dedicated member of the Mormon church, serving as second counselor to the bishop of his local congregation. In that role, he conducted meetings and spoke to the congregation on Sundays.\par \par \uc2 Ivie loved taking the girls to the park and riding bikes with them, Goates said. "His family life was the center of everything that he did," Goates said.\par \par \uc2 On Monday evening, Ivie spoke with Dr. Jarrett Hamilton about the tithe Hamilton's young son had offered at the previous day's service. Ivie wanted to be sure the boy got proper credit for it, Hamilton said. And before starting his shift on Monday night, Ivie went to his wife's soccer practice, Goates said. While the mothers were practicing, Ivie rounded up all the kids and played with them.\par \par \uc2 "We believe that families are eternal," Goates said. "So, they have the hope of being able to be with Nick again. That gives them tremendous hope and comfort."\par \par \uc2 To contact reporters: Brady McCombs, 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com; Tim Steller, 807-8427 or tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: See more photos at azstarnet.com/gallery\par \par \uc2 you can help\par \par \uc2 A foundation has been established to help the Ivie family pay for its expenses. People can make donations to the Nicholas Ivie Memorial Fund at any branch of \uc2 National Bank of Arizona\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020121110e8a300004\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc79}{\*\bkmkend toc79}\b \uc2 Cochise County Sheriff Dever dies at 60 in rollover crash\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS; TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS AND TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,564 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 September 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Longtime Cochise County Sheriff Larry Dever was killed Tuesday evening when his truck went off a road in Northern Arizona while on a family hunting trip. He was 60.\par \par \uc2 His death left his family, friends and colleagues shocked and saddened. And it ended Dever's 16-year run as the Republican sheriff of Cochise County - a period in which he rose to national prominence as an advocate for stronger border enforcement.\par \par \uc2 Dever's tenure coincided with Arizona becoming the busiest stretch of U.S.-Mexico border for illegal immigration and drug smuggling after a mid-1990s security push beefed up enforcement in Texas and California and funneled traffic to Arizona. Cochise County has 83.5 miles of Mexican border in Southeastern Arizona.\par \par \uc2 During his numerous appearances at congressional hearings and in his comments to the national media, Dever became known for having a measured response to the border issue. But he sharpened his tone in 2010 after his friend, rancher Robert Krentz, was killed on his land northeast of Douglas.\par \par \uc2 Dever blamed the killing on the unsecured border, deducing that it was probably carried out by a cross-border criminal. The crime has yet to be solved.\par \par \uc2 The Krentz killing triggered a wave of concern about border- related crime in Arizona and helped get Arizona's immigration enforcement law, SB 1070, passed by the Legislature and signed into law by Gov. \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2 . Dever asked to legally defend the state's controversial law in federal court.\par \par \uc2 Dever also joined the chorus of Republicans slamming the Obama administration over a botched federal operation that lost track of weapons sold to suspect straw purchasers for Mexican drug gangs, known as "Fast and Furious."\par \par \uc2 His chief deputy, Rod Rothrock, takes over as interim sheriff and may also become his successor. (See box at right.)\par \par \uc2 No matter who replaces him, though, Dever's boots will remain forever unfilled, said Pima County Sheriff Clarence Dupnik, a Democrat who didn't always share the same opinions as Dever but respected him.\par \par \uc2 "He's going to be irreplaceable," Dupnik said. "He was an expert on border law-enforcement issues. He was always cooperative."\par \par \uc2 Santa Cruz County Sheriff Tony Estrada, also a Democrat, called Dever a friendly, professional and knowledgeable lawman. Both Dupnik and Estrada agreed that Dever's death leaves a major gap in the Southern Arizona law-enforcement community.\par \par \uc2 "We're going to miss him," Estrada said. "He's been a great ambassador for law enforcement and for the sheriffs of Arizona."\par \par \uc2 The accident\par \par \uc2 Dever died near Williams, west of Flagstaff, where he was on a family hunting trip.\par \par \uc2 He was driving a 2008 Chevrolet truck on a well-traveled dirt forest road about two miles north of White Horse Lake when the truck went off the road, said Gerry Blair, Coconino County Sheriff's Office spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Investigators don't know why, but Dever apparently lost control of the truck, going off the road and rolling at least once, coming to rest upright.\par \par \uc2 Dever, who was still in the truck when investigators arrived, was pronounced dead at the scene. They don't know yet if he was wearing a seat belt, Blair said.\par \par \uc2 There are no signs that he was drinking or impaired, he said. He was the only person in the truck.\par \par \uc2 He was on his way to meet several members of his family at a campsite, where they were set to go hunting, Blair said.\par \par \uc2 Dever is survived by his wife, Nancy, six sons and 11 grandchildren. The sheriff died just four days after his 86-year- old mother, Annie Mae Dever, died of cancer.\par \par \uc2 Cochise County lifer\par \par \uc2 Dever spent his entire life in Cochise County. He was born and raised in the town of St. David, southeast of Benson. In 1976, he began his career with the Cochise County Sheriff's Office as a deputy.\par \par \uc2 Dever was one of several sheriff's deputies wounded in an October 1982 clash at Miracle Valley, near Palominas. A radical church group from Chicago had taken up residence at the Hereford-area religious compound, and when deputies moved in to arrest some members, fighting and gunfire broke out.\par \par \uc2 Dever, then a sergeant, was hit by shotgun pellets and suffered minor wounds. In the aftermath, Dever was criticized for allegedly escalating the standoff, but he always defended his conduct.\par \par \uc2 During his first 20 years with the agency, Dever rose as high as chief deputy before retiring in early 1996 to run for sheriff. He changed his party affiliation - from Democrat to Republican - the year before to run against one-term incumbent John Pintek, a Democrat.\par \par \uc2 In an acrimonious campaign, Dever accused Pintek of wrongdoing, and Pintek said a win by Dever would represent the return of a good- old-boys network. Pintek had defeated Dever's cousin, Jimmy Judd, a four-term sheriff, in the 1992 Democratic primary. Dever defeated Pintek, the first of four victories.\par \par \uc2 Border sheriff\par \par \uc2 In the late 1990s and early 2000s, Dever became a proponent for more resources from the state and federal governments to combat the problems caused by crossings of \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  and drug smugglers that had become a constant in the rural county.\par \par \uc2 In 2000, he called on then-Gov. Jane Hull to deploy the Arizona National Guard to provide more non-enforcement support.\par \par \uc2 "I have a responsibility to preserve the peace, and I'm trying to meet it. It is one of the greatest challenges I've faced in my life," Dever said in 2000.\par \par \uc2 Dever said his deputies were spending as much as 40 percent of their time on border crime in the early 2000s. The traffic continued throughout the decade, and a massive buildup of Border Patrol agents, fences and technology followed. Only recently has the flow of illegal immigration slowed.\par \par \uc2 In the aftermath of the Krentz slaying and Brewer's signing of SB 1070 into law, Dever supported placing National Guard troops on the border. He also openly called for using the moment of crisis to bring more resources to the border.\par \par \uc2 "While we have the nation's attention, it's important that we strike now and that we get these suggestions implemented now," Dever said in April 2010. "I really feel that the window of opportunity will close very quickly."\par \par \uc2 After the \uc2 American Civil Liberties Union\uc2  filed suit to stop the implementation of SB 1070, Dever and Pinal County Sheriff Paul Babeu joined forces in a group called the Border Sheriffs. The group was formed to raise money to defend SB 1070 against the ACLU lawsuit, which named the state's sheriffs and county attorneys as defendants.\par \par \uc2 His legacy\par \par \uc2 Residents are in shock about Dever's death, said Cochise County Attorney Ed Rheinheimer.\par \par \uc2 "When you hear about something like this, it's the kind of thing that makes you go weak in the knees," he said.\par \par \uc2 Dever will be remembered personally as a trustworthy man, and professionally as a sheriff who spoke up for border ranchers whose lands were being trampled by illegal crossers and drug smugglers, ranchers and colleagues said.\par \par \uc2 Cochise County Recorder Christine Rhodes, a Democrat originally from St. David, lauded Dever as a "wonderful family man."\par \par \uc2 "Larry Dever will be sorely missed. He was extremely well-liked, so well-liked that nobody was bothering to run against him," she said.\par \par \uc2 Dever's death is a huge loss to ranchers fighting the border issue, said Ed Ashurst, who manages a ranch in Cochise County.\par \par \uc2 "He wasn't afraid to speak out about it," Ashurst said. "He was a real patriotic American."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com.\par \par \uc2 Dever's replacement\par \par \uc2 The replacement for Cochise County Sheriff Larry Dever on the Nov. 6 ballot will likely be chosen today at a Cochise County Republican Party meeting.\par \par \uc2 Dever was running unopposed for his fifth term in office before his death in a vehicle crash Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 The law allows the Republican Party to select a substitute candidate to take his ballot spot, but it must make that decision by 2 p.m. today to ensure ballots can be printed Saturday as planned.\par \par \uc2 The Cochise County Republican Party has called a meeting for noon today for the 83 precinct committee members, said Matt Creegan, Cochise County Republican chairman. They will take a vote to choose from three candidates:\par \par \uc2 * Rod Rothrock, the chief deputy of the Cochise County Sheriff's Office who became the acting sheriff upon Dever's death.\par \par \uc2 * Mark Dannels, a retired Cochise County sheriff's commander who worked under Dever.\par \par \uc2 * Billy Cloud, the Tombstone marshal who lost to Dever in the 2008 Republican primary.\par \par \uc2 The winner will have until 2 p.m. to turn in his paperwork at county headquarters, Creegan said. If the Cochise County GOP cannot make a decision, or if the person it chooses fails to get his proper paperwork in on time, the next sheriff would be chosen in a write- in election Nov. 6, said Cochise County Attorney Ed Rheinheimer.\par \par \uc2 Rothrock, Dever's chief deputy, has assumed the sheriff position now as constituted by law. The Cochise County Board of Supervisors will select a replacement to complete the remaining 3 1/2 months of Dever's current term, Rheinheimer said. That may be Rothrock, he said.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020121017e89k00013\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc80}{\*\bkmkend toc80}\b \uc2 Man convicted in two slayings, could get death\b0\par\par\uc2 KIM SMITH   \par \uc2 KIM SMITH, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 378 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 September 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A Pima County jury has convicted a Texas man of first-degree murder and kidnapping in the May 2009 killing of a Marana couple, and decided that his crimes justify consideration of the death penalty.\par \par \uc2 The jury deliberated about eight hours over three days before returning its guilty verdict Friday morning. It took another 30 minutes to decide that Michael Carlson, 56, is eligible for the death penalty, finding he was guilty of killing multiple people, was on parole at the time and has prior convictions for serious offenses.\par \par \uc2 Carlson's attorneys will begin presenting mitigating evidence on Wednesday in hopes it will persuade jurors to spare his life.\par \par \uc2 Carlson, 56, was arrested in June 2009, on an outstanding Texas parole violation warrant two weeks after Kenneth "KR" Alliman, 49, and Rebecca Lofton, 52, were reported missing.\par \par \uc2 Shortly thereafter, Carlson was indicted on two counts of first- degree murder and two counts of kidnapping after he told a Tucson TV reporter he had killed the couple and burned their bodies in trash pits.\par \par \uc2 At the time, Alliman, Carlson and Lofton were living rent-free on five acres of land belonging to the Menden family.\par \par \uc2 Carlson told the TV reporter he killed the couple because they were stealing and were methamphetamine-addicted \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  smugglers. He also said he believed Alliman was peeping on a 17- year-old girl and endangering other children by recklessly firing weapons.\par \par \uc2 Carlson's defense attorneys, Harley Kurlander and Darlene Edminson-O'Brien, told jurors that Carlson falsely confessed to avoid going back to prison in Texas, where he had been beaten, raped and stabbed. They also suggested Larry Menden had a motive to kill the couple and that Carlson confessed to protect him.\par \par \uc2 Prosecutors Nicol Green and Carolyn Nedder told jurors the physical evidence corroborated Carlson's confession, and that the defense's explanation for the "false" confession didn't make sense. Jurors were not aware of the fact Carlson also confessed to Pima County sheriff's detectives, but it was thrown out of court because his Miranda rights were violated.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Kim Smith at 573-4241 or kimsmith@azstarnet.com. On Twitter: KimSmithStar\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120919e89100009\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc81}{\*\bkmkend toc81}\b \uc2 Double-murder case goes to jurors\b0\par\par\uc2 KIM SMITH   \par \uc2 KIM SMITH, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 597 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 August 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Jurors are now deliberating the fate of a 56-year-old Texas man accused of killing a Marana couple three years ago and burning their bodies in trash pits.\par \par \uc2 If convicted, Michael Carlson could face the death penalty in the deaths of Kenneth "KR" Alliman, 49, and Rebecca Lofton, 52.\par \par \uc2 Alliman, Lofton and Carlson were all living rent-free on a five- acre piece of land owned by Larry Menden when Lofton and Alliman disappeared on May 25, 2009. Carlson was indicted a month later after telling a TV reporter he killed the pair.\par \par \uc2 His attorneys told jurors he falsely confessed to avoid going back to the Texas prison system on a parole violation and to protect Menden, who they said had a motive to kill the pair.\par \par \uc2 During closing arguments Wednesday, Deputy Pima County Attorney Nicol Green told jurors neither reason makes sense.\par \par \uc2 If Carlson, 56, was so terrified about going back to Texas, why was he driving a stolen car and why did he give police his real name during a traffic stop around the time of the slayings? Green asked.\par \par \uc2 The truth is, Carlson wasn't terrified about going back, Green said. During his 25 years in prison, he was assaulted only twice, and the incidents took place decades ago, Green said. His prison records also show he wasn't shy about lodging complaints against the very guards he was supposedly terrified of, she said.\par \par \uc2 In addition, Carlson confessed after the Menden family abandoned him, Green said. The Mendens did not visit him in jail after his arrest, they didn't put money into his commissary account, and they didn't acknowledge his birthday.\par \par \uc2 Most people would have been angry at being shunned and wouldn't try to protect them, Green said.\par \par \uc2 The fact Carlson also described how he killed eight other people in gruesome detail - when he had not - shows he had been fantasizing about killing people for a long time, Green said.\par \par \uc2 "He fancied himself a killer," Green said.\par \par \uc2 Defense attorney Harley Kurlander told jurors the evidence points to Menden as the real killer. Menden had pointed a gun at Alliman at least once before, spoke about wanting to kill Alliman and Lofton after allegedly catching them stealing, and believed Alliman was peeping on his 17-year-old granddaughter. He also suspected the two of being methamphetamine-addicted \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  smugglers.\par \par \uc2 Kurlander reminded jurors that Menden told them he didn't know human remains were found in his trash pits until after the trial started, but told police Carlson confessed to him after he raked up Lofton's leg on May 26, 2009.\par \par \uc2 Menden didn't tell police about Carlson's alleged confession until a month after the slayings, Kurlander said. Fear couldn't have been the reason, because Menden and his family continued to associate with Carlson, Kurlander said.\par \par \uc2 The defense attorney also told jurors to ask themselves why Menden bought lye or lime around the time of the slayings. Menden didn't have livestock, so he didn't need to mask the smell of dead animals, Kurlander said.\par \par \uc2 "I think we can figure that one out," Kurlander said.\par \par \uc2 If Carlson is convicted, the same jury will decide whether he should be eligible for the death penalty.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Kim Smith at 573-4241 or kimsmith@azstarnet.com. On Twitter: KimSmithStar\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Follow the news and events at Pima County's courthouses in Kim Smith's blog, At the Courthouse, at azstarnet.com/ courthouse\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120912e88u00034\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc82}{\*\bkmkend toc82}\b \uc2 POLITICAL NOTEBOOK: Self-deport spoof speaks to Brewer's notoriety\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 786 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 August 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par C2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Say what you will about Gov. \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2 , but you gotta give her credit - she keeps Arizona in the national spotlight.\par \par \uc2 The latest to mock our right-wing governor is the popular skit- comedy website, Funny or Die. In a two-minute video that made the rounds on \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and Twitter this week, actress Mary Steenburgen does her best Brewer impersonation in a skit inspired by the governor's string of anti-\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  policies.\par \par \uc2 "I'm no-nonsense Arizona governor \uc2 Jan Brewer\uc2 . Part of my duties as governor is to make sure that Arizona is a great to place to live," she says. "Right now, Arizona is just an OK place to live, and it's getting more not OK because of illegals."\par \par \uc2 The satirical skit depicts Brewer touting plywood "self- deportation stations" that people can use to send home people who look like they're illegal immigrants. The best part might be the cameo from George Lopez at the end.\par \par \uc2 This likely won't be the last time Brewer inspires parody. She'll be in office until 2014, which leaves her plenty of time to give comedians across the country plenty more material.\par \par \uc2 To see what the ersatz website has to offer on the governor, or a variety of other topics, try {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.funnyordie.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.funnyordie.com}}}\par \par \uc2 Baja Arizona for obama\par \par \uc2 Democrats would be a whole lot more optimistic heading into November's presidential election if "Baja Arizona" had its own number of electoral votes.\par \par \uc2 As it is, Republican \uc2 Mitt Romney\uc2  is looking more and more like a the front-runner to capture Arizona's 11 electoral votes. Not only does the GOP have a 180,000 advantage in registered voters and the lead in polls, but Romney's fund-raising lead here is widening.\par \par \uc2 Through July, Romney has brought in $3.2 million from Arizona - nearly $726,000 more than President Obama's $2.5 million.\par \par \uc2 Not surprisingly, Romney's advantage comes mainly from the Valley of the Sun. The former Massachusetts governor has pulled in $1.1 million more than Obama in the ZIP codes covering the Phoenix metro area, according to new finance reports from the \uc2 Federal Election Commission\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Down here in the area some would like parceled off into Baja Arizona, Obama has outraised Romney by nearly $278,000. In Tucson ZIP codes, Obama raised $681,000 - nearly as much as he raised in the main Phoenix ZIP codes, $706,500.\par \par \uc2 But Obama's stranglehold on Southern Arizona means little so long as Romney and Republicans control Arizona's political epicenter.\par \par \uc2 Heard this one before?\par \par \uc2 Like sports, politics is brimming with old, tired cliches. Here are a few of our favorites that have been popping up again this season:\par \par \uc2 * "I've never seen such a dirty campaign."\par \par \uc2 This one is always accompanied by outrage from the candidate who swears he's never witnessed the nasty tactics his rival is using. Such declarations are usually accompanied by a sound bite about how the opposite party has stooped to new lows. As if politics was ever a gentleman's sport.\par \par \uc2 * "They must be worried."\par \par \uc2 This one always comes after an opponent gets a key endorsement from a powerful political figure or group. Instead of accepting reality that it's a sign he or she is going to get beat, the challengers loves to spin it as a sign that he or she must be a threat, and has the front-runner worried.\par \par \uc2 Wouldn't it be refreshing to hear a candidate say, "Yeah, I'll be honest, I would have really, really loved to have received that endorsement. ... It stings a bit."\par \par \uc2 * "The only poll that matters is on election day."\par \par \uc2 A poll shows less than ideal numbers for a politician? No problem. Just pull out this tried and true line. But, when the polls show a good number for your candidate, send the results out to the world and tout it as a sign that the race is in your favor.\par \par \uc2 And, finally my favorite:\par \par \uc2 * "I'm not a politician."\par \par \uc2 Oh, how candidates love to throw this one around. We've got news for every single one of you who has ever said that - yes you are. The day you decided to get in the race, you became a politician.\par \par \uc2 If you truly weren't a politician, you would have just stayed out of the race.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com Twitter: @BradyMcCombs\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Brady McCombs will keep you aware of all of the political news with the Pueblo Politics blog at azstarnet.com/ pueblopolitics\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120912e88q0000x\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc83}{\*\bkmkend toc83}\b \uc2 Latino evangelicals find political voice\b0\par\par\uc2 JOSEPH TREVInO   \par \uc2 JOSEPH TREVInO, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 514 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 August 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 South-side church emerges as go-to place for election activities\par \par \uc2 Every Sunday, Gina Islas dances, sings and has a personal relationship with God at Vida Nueva, the church with the largest Latino evangelical congregation in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 But during the rest of the week, besides working in an office, taking care of her children and her home, Islas has other chores: her political duties.\par \par \uc2 Come November, she will vote for one of the presidential candidates - she is still undecided - and she wants to encourage others to do the same.\par \par \uc2 Islas, 48, a mother of three and a Tucson native, embodies the new Latino evangelical who - besides being committed to her church - follows politics closely.\par \par \uc2 According to a 2007 poll done by the Pew Hispanic Center, 15 percent of Latinos in the U.S. are evangelicals, the second-biggest religious group among Hispanics.\par \par \uc2 Samuel Rodriguez, a pastor and the head of the National Hispanic Christian Leadership Conference, an organization that claims 40,118 affiliated churches, said that in Arizona alone the group has managed to register 98,000 Latinos to vote.\par \par \uc2 Last year, political representatives from across the nation - including White House officials - held an immigration reform summit at Vida Nueva.\par \par \uc2 In recent months some local candidates have already paid the church a visit, and in November the church will make room for polling booths, and also hold voter-registration drives.\par \par \uc2 All of this is in striking contrast to barely 25 years ago, when mostly everything to do with politics was seen by Latino evangelicals as sinful. But change came from an event no one could predict: The 1986 immigration amnesty.\par \par \uc2 "Now the silent giant has awoken, and nothing can make it go to sleep again," Rodriguez said.\par \par \uc2 Latino evangelicals tend to hold the following political views: They are anti-abortion, pro-family, against same-sex marriages, for religious liberty and are committed to defending immigrant rights, Rodriguez said.\par \par \uc2 Their political quest is leading Latino evangelicals to hold hands with an unlikely group: Catholics.\par \par \uc2 The Obama administration's health-care mandate, which requires companies' insurance plans to provide contraceptives, has managed to unite the two faith groups, Rodriguez said.\par \par \uc2 "We are seeing a great collaboration, where the barriers of the past have been overcome", Rodriguez said. "It is a beautiful day."\par \par \uc2 For Luis Rodriguez (no relation to Samuel Rodriguez), Latino evangelicals face a choice. Rodriguez said both President Obama and \uc2 Mitt Romney\uc2  are good candidates, but Obama's support for gay marriage rights, access to birth control and abortion, which evangelicals oppose - and Romney's anti-\uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  rhetoric - are disturbing.\par \par \uc2 In the past, Latino evangelicals tended to vote Republican, but lately more have been registering as independents, Samuel Rodriguez said.\par \par \uc2 "I don't want Hispanics to be married to a political party," he said. "I want the Hispanic community to be exclusively married to the Lamb's (Jesus Christ's) agenda. To me, that is much more important."\par \par \uc2 Contact Joseph Trevino at jtrevino@azstarnet.com or at 807-8029.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120829e88m00015\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc84}{\*\bkmkend toc84}\b \uc2 Murder defendant texted he 'took out trash,' witness says\b0\par\par\uc2 KIM SMITH   \par \uc2 KIM SMITH, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 495 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 August 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A11\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 On the night Pima County sheriff's detectives believe Kenneth Alliman and Rebecca Lou Lofton were killed and tossed into a trash pit, a Marana resident says she saw a text from the suspect saying he had "taken out the trash."\par \par \uc2 Mae Menden testified that can't remember if she saw the text on her phone or those belonging to her husband or father-in-law, but the incoming text definitely came from Michael "Tex" Carlson's phone number, she said.\par \par \uc2 Carlson, 56, is on trial in Pima County Superior Court for the deaths of Alliman, 49, and Lofton, 52, in May 2009. If he is convicted of first-degree murder, prosecutors plan to seek the death penalty.\par \par \uc2 In May 2009, Carlson, Alliman and Lofton were all living rent- free on five acres owned by Menden's father-in-law, Larry Menden, in Marana.\par \par \uc2 Prosecutors told jurors the evidence will show Carlson killed the couple on May 25, 2009, while the Menden family was in Tucson. They also believe Carlson burned the couple in three fire pits while most of the family was camping near the town of Cochise between May 26 and May 30.\par \par \uc2 The couple was reported missing by their respective family members on June 2 and Carlson was arrested on an outstanding Texas warrant June 16.\par \par \uc2 After his arrest, Carlson told a Tucson TV station reporter he killed the couple and burned their remains because he believed they were stealing from the Mendens.\par \par \uc2 His attorneys accused members of the Menden family of killing Alliman and Lofton and told jurors Carlson falsely confessed to protect them.\par \par \uc2 They also said he didn't want to return to the Texas prison system where he has been repeatedly beaten, stabbed and raped.\par \par \uc2 Mae Menden testified that the Menden family went to Tucson on May 25, 2009, to visit her mother's boyfriend.\par \par \uc2 The men spent the entire day getting drunk and eventually passing out. Some time after that, she said she saw a text from Carlson saying he had taken out the trash.\par \par \uc2 The family returned to their property the next day, but she didn't see Carlson, Alliman or Lofton, Menden said.\par \par \uc2 Menden recalled smelling a fire that day, but didn't see it. Since the family always burned their trash, she didn't think anything of it.\par \par \uc2 The next day, Menden said she, her husband and three daughters left for Cochise, southeast of Benson, where they stayed for about four days.\par \par \uc2 Menden spoke disparagingly of Alliman and Lofton, accusing them of being methamphetamine addicts, \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  smugglers and "pains in the butt" who were asked to leave the property several times.\par \par \uc2 Judge Richard Nichols is presiding over the trial. The state is expected to rest by the end of the week.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Kim Smith at 573-4241 or kimsmith@azstarnet.com. On Twitter: KimSmithStar\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120829e88m00011\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc85}{\*\bkmkend toc85}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 434 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 August 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A8\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Father admits guilt in abuse of infant son\par \par \uc2 A Tucson man accused of breaking bones of his 4-month-old son pleaded guilty to one count of child abuse in a plea agreement that leaves him eligible for probation.\par \par \uc2 Leonard Dorame, 29, was indicted in January on two counts of child abuse, death or serious physical injury likely, after the child's mother took the baby to a hospital for a swollen leg.\par \par \uc2 Doctors discovered bones in the boy's upper and lower legs were broken, as were his ribs and bones in his left arm. They also observed bleeding in the baby's retinas and brain.\par \par \uc2 Dorame pleaded guilty to one count, saying he didn't seek medical care for the boy's injuries.\par \par \uc2 Pima County Superior Court Judge Christopher Browning could place Dorame on probation for up to a lifetime or he could send him to prison for up to 12 1/2 years at the Sept. 11 sentencing.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Rescue helicopter plucks illegal migrant from cliff\par \par \uc2 An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  was rescued by a Customs and Border Protection helicopter from the Cerro Colorado Mountains near Arivaca on Tuesday after he was stranded on a near-vertical cliff.\par \par \uc2 The man, who was from Mexico, called 911 on Monday. A \uc2 U.S. Customs and Border Protection\uc2  helicopter crew spotted him at about 10 p.m. Monday and called the Border Patrol's search and rescue team, which began its rescue operation at 5 a.m. Tuesday attempting to reach the man by using a rope system. However, because of the man's position on the cliff and a lack of anchor points for the rope, the agents decided a helicopter was needed. A CBP Blackhawk helicopter rescued the man, using a rope suspension technique.\par \par \uc2 He was treated for mild dehydration and taken to the Tucson Border Patrol station for processing for return to Mexico.\par \par \uc2 See a video of the rescue at azstarnet.com/video\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Fedora-decked man who robbed 5 banks is sought\par \par \uc2 Tucson police are asking for the public's help to identify a man linked to five local bank robberies.\par \par \uc2 The latest was at about 2:30 p.m. Tuesday at the \uc2 Wells Fargo Bank\uc2  inside \uc2 Safeway\uc2 , 8740 E. Broadway, said Sgt. Chris Widmer, a Tucson police spokesman. The robber is described as Hispanic, in his 20s, between 5 feet 5 inches and 5 feet 7 inches tall, and wearing a black fedora when last seen. Anyone with information should call 911 or 88-CRIME (882-7463).\par \par \uc2 Veronica M. Cruz\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120815e8890000o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc86}{\*\bkmkend toc86}\b \uc2 Traffic stop leads to bales of marijuana in Ajo, 4 arrests\b0\par\par\uc2 JAMAR YOUNGER   \par \uc2 JAMAR YOUNGER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 279 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 July 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par C8\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Pima County sheriff's deputies arrested four people in Ajo this week on suspicion of smuggling marijuana.\par \par \uc2 Mashelle Womack, 39; Jesus Tereso De Lopez-Zavala, 34; and a 17- year-old boy are all facing charges of possession of marijuana for sale, transportation of marijuana for sale and possession of drug paraphernalia, said Deputy Tom Peine, a Sheriff's Department spokesman.\par \par \uc2 The teen's name was not released because he is a juvenile, Peine said.\par \par \uc2 Another woman, Kristy Ann Fejarang-Blake, 37, was arrested on suspicion of possession of dangerous drugs, Peine said in a news release.\par \par \uc2 Authorities arrested the suspects late Thursday after finding 25 bales of marijuana, weighing more than 430 pounds, inside a shed at an Ajo home. Ajo is about 100 miles west of Tucson.\par \par \uc2 The discovery came after a deputy made a traffic stop in front of the home. The deputy smelled marijuana in the car, reportedly driven by Womack, and called for additional deputies and a drug-sniffing dog.\par \par \uc2 The dog did not smell drugs in the car but alerted deputies to the fence line of a nearby house.\par \par \uc2 Deputies eventually searched a shed at the home and found the marijuana, along with an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  identified as Lopez- Zavala.\par \par \uc2 Several people were inside the home, including a woman who had a small amount of methamphetamine, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 Womack, Fejarang-Blake and Lopez-Zavala were booked into Pima County jail. The 17-year-old was booked into the juvenile detention center.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Jamar Younger at jyounger@azstarnet.com or 573- 4115.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120801e87m0001s\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc87}{\*\bkmkend toc87}\b \uc2 Weapons stashes share dark purpose\b0\par\par\uc2 TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 900 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 July 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Point to clandestine border crime, may even be tied to agent's killing\par \par \uc2 When a hiker in Madera Canyon discovered three AK-47-type rifles wrapped in plastic last month, it may have seemed like a random occurrence.\par \par \uc2 It wasn't.\par \par \uc2 Across Southern Arizona's borderlands, workers, residents or visitors occasionally come across weapons that apparently have been stashed or ditched by criminals. In two cases this year, people in areas managed by the \uc2 Bureau of Land Management\uc2  have found stashed, plastic-wrapped rifles.\par \par \uc2 And in a fourth incident this year, a young border-crosser said the two guides of his large group stashed plastic bags of weapons in a cave southwest of Tucson. Inside, the 17-year-old told a Pima County Sheriff's investigator, were guns like the kind you see in action movies - and grenades.\par \par \uc2 Each incident may have its own explanation, but there are common reasons for the stashes, said Santa Cruz County Sheriff Tony Estrada.\par \par \uc2 "They'll put them in a strategic place, and when they're going to rip somebody off or going to protect a load, they go retrieve them," Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 The phenomenon may also be relevant to the killing of U.S. Border Patrol Agent Brian Terry near Rio Rico in December 2010. Federal prosecutors have said the six defendants in the case crossed the border from Mexico early that month and picked up weapons that were cached north of the line.\par \par \uc2 They declined to detail how or where the defendants got the guns, which were bought in January 2010 by a young man named Jaime Avila, now a defendant in the notorious Operation Fast and Furious case. But Terry's cousin, Robert Heyer of San Diego, said he would like to see investigators uncover whoever stored the weapons for his cousin's alleged killers.\par \par \uc2 "Where did they go once Jaime Avila walked out of the Lone Wolf Gun Store on Jan. 10, 2010?" Heyer asked.\par \par \uc2 connection to migrant\par \par \uc2 The story of the long guns and grenades would never have emerged if a woman hadn't died while crossing the border in May. Mariana Chaverri Pina entered the United States May 5 with her 17-year-old nephew and a group of about 40 illegal immigrants, the nephew told a Pima County sheriff's investigator.\par \par \uc2 Three days into their journey, the group began to climb a mountain ridge, apparently in the Baboquivari Mountains southwest of Tucson, and arrived at a cave, the report says.\par \par \uc2 "Once they got to the cave, both the guide and his assistant put their bag of guns into the cave," the report said. The teen "stated that he did not get a good look at what the guns and grenades looked like because once the guides had removed the packs from their backs, they told the rest of the group to go wait downhill a little bit and he walked away."\par \par \uc2 The group stayed that night in the area, and the next day, the teen's aunt was bit by a rattlesnake. The group left her behind, and she eventually died and was found by area residents. The boy was later captured by the Border Patrol, and it was May 13 by the time a sheriff's deputy heard hisstory.\par \par \uc2 Neither the sheriff's department nor the Border Patrol acknowledged following up by searching for the weapons.\par \par \uc2 In a written statement, Border Patrol spokesman Brent Cagen said, "Occasionally, abandoned weapons are recovered in the desert. Firearms seized by \uc2 U.S. Customs and Border Protection\uc2  agencies in Arizona are then test-fired for cross-matching through the National Integrated Ballistic Information Network to determine whether any of the weapons were used in the commission of a crime."\par \par \uc2 Rifle uncovered\par \par \uc2 On Feb. 29, volunteers from Friends of the Ironwood Forest were cleaning up a wash where \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  or smuggling groups had left trash near the Silver Bell Mountains, northwest of Marana, said Jon Young, state chief ranger for the \uc2 Bureau of Land Management\uc2  in Arizona. One of them saw the corner of a plastic bag sticking out from the sand and pulled on it. Out came a plastic bag wrapped in a T-shirt and containing a Mac-90 rifle.\par \par \uc2 A similar discovery happened three days later. On March 2, about 300 yards south of Interstate 8 in an area west of Casa Grande, a ranger found a plastic bag wrapped in a T-shirt underneath a pile of brush. Inside was an AK-47-style assault rifle and a 30-round magazine loaded with 28 rounds.\par \par \uc2 Young said he isn't sure why rangers find weapons in the monuments, but he thinks smugglers' concerns offer an explanation.\par \par \uc2 "A lot of the scouts or cartel members tend to work the same areas. They come and go out of these remote areas," Young said. "I think it's probably riskier for them to be traveling with a weapon. They store the weapon in an area where they know they're either going to use them or keep them in the future."\par \par \uc2 If members of the public find weapons, they should call 911 or a local law-enforcement office, he said.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Tim Steller at 807-8427 or tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of immigration and border issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120801e87m0001n\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc88}{\*\bkmkend toc88}\b \uc2 PBS explores Border Patrol conduct\b0\par\par\uc2 PHIL VILLARREAL   \par \uc2 PHIL VILLARREAL, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 193 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 July 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A10\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Show examines treatment of illegal immigrants in US\par \par \uc2 Tonight's episode of PBS's "Need to Know" focuses on U.S. Border Patrol abuse in detention centers, and several local humanitarian agencies are said to be featured in the episode. The show airs at 10 p.m.\par \par \uc2 Dubbed "Crossing the Line, Part 2," the investigative show is a follow-up to the show's first "Crossing the Line" feature, which aired in April and told the story of Border Patrol agents' alleged abuse of suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  Anastasio Hernandez Rojas in 2010. The case led to a federal grand jury probe.\par \par \uc2 Tonight's episode includes an interview with a former Border Patrol agent who says suspected illegal immigrants suffer unacceptable conditions, including torture, sexual assault, overcrowding and food and water deprivation.\par \par \uc2 Local groups No More Deaths, Samaritans and Green Valley Samaritans contributed videos and testimonies to the show, according to No More Deaths volunteer John Fife.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Phil Villarreal at 573-4130 or pvillarreal@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 IF YOU WATCH\par \par \uc2 "Need to Know"\par \par \uc2 * When: 10 tonight\par \par \uc2 * Channel: KUAT\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120801e87k0000m\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc89}{\*\bkmkend toc89}\b \uc2 Samaritans marking 10th year of their work helping migrants\b0\par\par\uc2 JOSEPH TREVInO   \par \uc2 JOSEPH TREVInO, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 993 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 July 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par C9\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 She had to find him.\par \par \uc2 Dr. Kristin Olson-Garewal and her 27-year-old son, Raj, were looking for the body of a young man, an immigrant border crosser between 16 and 20 years old, who had died in the desert in Santa Cruz County.\par \par \uc2 Olson-Garewal, 62, had recently joined the Samaritans, a Tucson- based group dedicated to taking water and food to weary migrant trekkers, and she was determined not to leave the desert without finding the body.\par \par \uc2 It was her third try, following two expeditions that had failed after an immigrant crosser had told the group about spotting the body as he crossed the desert.\par \par \uc2 The man, an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who had tipped off the Samaritans instead of the Border Patrol for fear of being caught and deported, told the group the body was in a wash.\par \par \uc2 The Samaritans said they informed the Santa Cruz Sheriff's Department, which, in turn, said it would inform the Border Patrol. The Border Patrol said via a statement it was unaware of the incident, but that "The group did, in fact, do the right thing by contacting the local authorities."\par \par \uc2 After two days of hearing nothing from officials, the Samaritans moved into action.\par \par \uc2 not a casual consideration\par \par \uc2 Olson-Garewal's volunteer work for the Samaritans is far from a casual pastime. She said that for years, her late husband, Dr. Harinder Garewal, the one-time chief of medical oncology at Southern Arizona VA medical center, had spoken of taking some time off from work and volunteering for a humanitarian group like the Samaritans.\par \par \uc2 Garewal passed away in 2010 before the couple could realize their humanitarian goals, his widow said. In a way, helping dehydrated border crossers was, for Olson-Garewal, a sort of a homage to the memory of her husband.\par \par \uc2 Thus Olson-Garewal joined the Samaritans as they hopped into their off-road SUVs and drove to the desert, where they searched on foot.\par \par \uc2 On Saturday, May 19, Olson-Garewal, following a hunch, decided to go back out alone with her son.\par \par \uc2 "Then it dawned on me that because of the rain, the body had washed in a certain direction," Olson-Garewal says.\par \par \uc2 Her son announced, "'I know where it is.' There was a vulture ... that was what tipped him off."\par \par \uc2 Only after helping sheriff's deputies remove the body did Raj, a literature student who is heading to England this fall to continue his studies, realize how shocked he was by the gruesome sight of the bloated and decomposed body partially devoured by animals.\par \par \uc2 He threw up.\par \par \uc2 "He said, 'Mom, this is terrible. This is so wrong,' " Olson- Garewal said.\par \par \uc2 Decade-long commitment\par \par \uc2 The Samaritans, who are based out of the \uc2 Southside Presbyterian Church\uc2  and go out to the desert every day, have pro-immigrant roots that stretch back more than 10 years.\par \par \uc2 The group was formed by volunteers including the Rev. \uc2 John Fife\uc2  and many former members of the Sanctuary Movement, which aided Central American refugees and attracted worldwide attention during the 1980s. The Samaritans also immediately attracted international attention and sparked controversy.\par \par \uc2 The group, one of several humanitarian border organizations, claims to have about 300 members. This weekend, it will commemorate its 10th anniversary, but instead of calling it a cause for celebration, they say it is a tragedy, since they believe the border issue should have been resolved long ago.\par \par \uc2 "We note with sadness the 10th year of a humanitarian disaster at our border," said Kathryn Ferguson, the group's spokeswoman. "The migration north of individuals across the U.S.-Mexico border continues to cause an appalling level of mortality, morbidity and loss of human dignity."\par \par \uc2 Brent Cagen, spokesman for the Tucson Border Patrol, said his office shares the concern of the Samaritans and other humanitarian groups regarding border crossers and tries to reduce fatalities by disseminating "a forthright message regarding the many dangers associated with illegally crossing our borders."\par \par \uc2 "This message is delivered to communities throughout Mexico, Central and South America through public service announcements, pamphlets and with the assistance of the Mexican, Central and South American governments."\par \par \uc2 In addition, Cagen said, the Border Patrol strives to build relationships with local humanitarian groups. Its border community liaison "continues to meet and discuss integrated messaging and efforts to prevent illegal migrants from crossing, thus reducing deaths."\par \par \uc2 Ira Mehlman, from the Federation for Immigration Reform, a national, nonprofit group that wants to limit immigration, said he believes the Samaritans have good motives.\par \par \uc2 But he said their actions actually endanger border crossers by encouraging them to cross the desert.\par \par \uc2 "The best way to avoid having people die out there in the desert is not to have them coming across that desert in the first place," Mehlman said.\par \par \uc2 "The idea that if you put out water stations, that somehow people are going to come across it, that's kind of risky ... You are unnecessarily risking people's lives and that is something that they ought to be concerned about."\par \par \uc2 Situation saddens her\par \par \uc2 The fact that Arizona, especially Tucson and the border areas, have garnered international attention in recent years as an immigration battleground, chagrins Samaritans like Ferguson, a filmmaker and dance instructor.\par \par \uc2 A Tucson native, Ferguson says the state has been known for centuries for its charity and hospitality and that the solitude of the desert landscape invites everyone to practice higher forms of spiritual and self-help by practicing contemplation and meditation.\par \par \uc2 She says: "I find it personally offensive that we have all these little men in uniforms running around in a place made for solitude."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Joseph Trevino at 807-8029 or jtrevino@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Saturday event\par \par \uc2 The Samaritans were to commemorate their 10th anniversary on Saturday with a "Flood the Desert Weekend." A caravan to the border was to begin at \uc2 Southside Presbyterian Church\uc2 , 17 W. 23rd St.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120714e8710000z\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSON\par {\*\bkmkstart toc90}{\*\bkmkend toc90}\b \uc2 Resolucion de la Corte Suprema deja inconsistencias\b0\par\par\uc2 CARMEN DUARTE; BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 CARMEN DUARTE Y BRADY MCCOMBS, LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSoN; ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 3,616 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 June 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par 16\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Agencias del orden aun no saben como podran cumplir con la disposicion\par \par \uc2 Los activistas de los derechos civiles y los defensores de la inmigracion estan enfurecidos con el fallo de la Corte Suprema que se realizo el Lunes 25 de Junio, el cual permite que en Arizona los policias revisen el estatus migratorio de los detenidos.\par \par \uc2 Algunos dicen que el fallo ocasionara discriminacion por perfil racial hacia los hispanos y generara temor entre los inmigrantes indocumentados de Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Ese mismo dia, el Departamento de Seguridad Nacional dijo que no enviara oficiales para recoger a los inmigrantes que hayan sido detenidos por la policia local de Arizona y que se sospeche que son ilegales, al menos que cumplan el criterio de prioridad de la agencia.\par \par \uc2 Se cuestiona si la decision del Departamento de Seguridad Nacional realmente cambiara las actividades del dia a dia de los oficiales cuando finalmente se les requiera, bajo la disposicion sobreviviente de la SB 1070, revisar el estatus migratorio de las personas a las que detengan.\par \par \uc2 Los criticos de la ley SB 1070 dijeron que continuaran trabajando para desmantelar la ley controversial, a pesar de la incertidumbre generada por el fallo de la Corte Suprema y la decision del Departamento de Seguridad Nacional.\par \par \uc2 Unas 50 personas se reunieron junto con oradores en una conferencia de prensa que se realizo el 25 de Junio por la tarde en el edificio estatal situado en West Congress Street y North Granada Avenue.\par \par \uc2 "Continuaremos trabajando para revocar la SB 1070, porque es una ley injusta", dijo Alison Harrington, quien es pastora de la Southside Presbyterian Church en el Sur de la ciudad.\par \par \uc2 "Esta ley promueve el miedo en nuestra comunidad, a la gente le da miedo ir al supermercado, a la iglesia, a los hospitales", agrego.\par \par \uc2 Alma Hernandez, de 28 anos, dijo que entiende el miedo que sienten los inmigrantes indocumentados.\par \par \uc2 "Soy una madre de tres ninos, y estoy luchando contra la deportacion para poderme quedar con mi familia", explico Hernandez, quien ha vivido en Tucson de manera ilegal desde los 8 anos.\par \par \uc2 "Mis padres se mudaron aqui desde Guadalajara en busca de una mejor vida. Tucson es mi hogar. No conozco otro lugar", expreso Hernandez. Ella intenta que le cancelen su deportacion con la orden ejecutiva que dio el presidente Obama el 15 de Junio.\par \par \uc2 La orden permite que aquellos que fueron traidos a Estados Unidos ilegalmente cuando ninos puedan permanecer en el pais bajo ciertas condiciones.\par \par \uc2 Hernandez explico que en Junio del 2010, un agente del Condado Pima la paro cuando manejaba. Dijo que no la detuvo por una infraccion de transito, sino que el alguacil llamo a la Patrulla Fronteriza cuando ella no pudo comprobar su residencia legal.\par \par \uc2 Dijo que estuvo encarcelada en diferentes centros de detencion durante tres semanas.\par \par \uc2 Hernandez ahora es miembro de Corazon de Tucson, un grupo que educa a sus participantes sobre sus derechos civiles y las leyes estatales y federales.\par \par \uc2 El supervisor del Condado Pima, \uc2 Richard Elias\uc2 , dijo que "la Corte Suprema codifico la parte de SB 1070 que ataca las libertades civiles y los derechos humanos de las personas.\par \par \uc2 "... La discriminacion por perfil racial es inevitable si se promulgan las disposiciones de la SB 1070 que fueron aprobadas hoy por la Corte".\par \par \uc2 Elias anuncio que exigira que se realicen foros comunitarios para que el alguacil Clarence Dupnik y el jefe de Policia de Tucson, Roberto Villasenor, o sus administradores, puedan discutir como las agencias del orden van a cumplir con la ley.\par \par \uc2 La Concejal de la Ciudad de Tucson, \uc2 Regina Romero\uc2 , estuvo de acuerdo con Elias respecto a los foros. Dijo que ella pedira que haya una discusion abierta con el abogado municipal y el jefe de la Policia sobre el refuerzo de la ley y sus efectos.\par \par \uc2 "Me da miedo que los inmigrantes ya no reporten los crimenes y que desconfien de la policia", dijo Romero. "Todos los avances del pasado se borraran. Eso me preocupa".\par \par \uc2 Aun si la policia local continua entregandoles individuos a los oficiales de inmigracion, muchos de ellos no seran recogidos dados los nuevos reglamentos que anuncio el Departamento de Seguridad Nacional tan solo horas despues del fallo de la Corte.\par \par \uc2 En Arizona, los oficiales de inmigracion ha sido instruidos para que no recojan a inmigrantes indocumentados que hayan sido detenidos por la policia local, al menos que el individuo sea:\par \par \uc2 * Un criminal condenado\par \par \uc2 * Alguien que haya sido deportado en el pasado\par \par \uc2 * O alguien que haya cruzado la frontera recientemente.\par \par \uc2 El Departamento de Seguridad Nacional continuara cumpliendo con el requisito legal de recibir las llamadas de los agentes del orden local para verificar el estatus migratorio de personas, dijeron los oficiales federales.\par \par \uc2 El Departamento de Seguridad Nacional tambien anuncio que ha revocado algunos acuerdos que tenia bajo el programa conocido como el 287(g). Los acuerdos se habian hecho con fuerzas operacionales de siete agencias del orden en Arizona, incluyendo el Departamento de Seguridad Publica de Arizona, el Departamento del Alguacil del Condado Pima y la Oficina del Alguacil del Condado Pinal.\par \par \uc2 Los oficiales del Departamento de Seguridad Nacional dicen que las fuerzas operacionales, en las que los oficiales de inmigracion trabajaban con la policia local para realizar investigaciones en el campo, no son utiles en los estados donde se han adoptado politicas migratorias como la SB 1070.\par \par \uc2 Los acuerdos de las carceles del programa 287(g) aun permanecen con ocho agencias, incluyendo el Departamento del Alguacil del Condado Pima. En el programa de las carceles, los oficiales de inmigracion trabajan con la policia local para investigar a las personas que ingresan a ellas.\par \par \uc2 Los lideres de las agencias del orden que estaban tratando de entender lo que significaria para ellos el fallo de la Corte Suprema, se vieron aun mas perdidos frente a las directivas del Departamento de Seguridad Nacional.\par \par \uc2 El jefe de Policia de Tucson, Roberto Villasenor; el alguacil del Condado Pima, Clarence Dupnik, y el alguacil del Condado Santa Cruz, Tony Estrada, dijeron que planean pedirle apoyo a la Patrulla Fronteriza para llegar a un entendimiento mejor de las implicaciones.\par \par \uc2 Las tres agencias entregan con regularidad a la Patrulla Fronteriza a los inmigrantes indocumentados que se encuentran durante sus patrullajes.\par \par \uc2 "Hemos tratado de contactar a la Patrulla Fronteriza hoy, sin exito, para determinar que quieren decir exactamente con eso", dijo Dupnik. "Si quiere decir lo que parece, que no van a responder, eso significa que no podemos reforzar la ley cuando hay violaciones migratorias".\par \par \uc2 La pregunta de los lideres de las agencias del orden es: ?que deben de hacer ellos si los oficiales de inmigracion no vienen a recoger a una persona que se cite por un delito menor y que se haya verificado por telefono que esta aqui ilegalmente?\par \par \uc2 Villasenor esta bajo la impresion de que sus oficiales habran cumplido con la ley si llaman a los oficiales de inmigracion respecto al estatus de una persona que se sospeche que este aqui ilegalmente.\par \par \uc2 Si la Patrulla Fronteriza no puede, o simplemente no recoge al individuo, ellos liberaran a la persona, comento.\par \par \uc2 "Todo va a depender de la capacidad de la Patrulla Fronteriza o del ICE para respondernos rapidamente", dijo Villasenor.\par \par \uc2 Pero no hay uniformidad entre agencias, o segun la ley, sobre cuanto un oficial debe de esperar.\par \par \uc2 La policia de Tuccson le instruye a sus oficiales que espere "tanto como sea necesario para cumplir el objetivo de la detencion inicial", dijo Villasenor.\par \par \uc2 Los agentes del alguacil en el Condado Pima y Santa Cruz liberan a la persona si la Patrulla Fronteriza no llega en un periodo de tiempo razonable, dijeron Dupnik y Estrada.\par \par \uc2 Como habra miles de llamadas adicionales que los oficiales locales le tendran que hacer a los de inmigracion, va a ser aun mas dificil que respondan las agencias federales de inmigracion.\par \par \uc2 "No estoy seguro de que puedan adaptarse a esa cantidad de trabajo ahora mismo", dijo Villasenor.\par \par \uc2 Aun antes de que el Departamento de Seguridad Nacional hiciera su anuncio, los lideres de las agencias del orden y los abogados municipales estaban buscando como lidiar con el fallo de la Corte Suprema.\par \par \uc2 La Ciudad y el Departamento de Policia de Tucson estan repasando el fallo de la Corte Suprema y recibiran un asesoramiento legal durante una sesion ejecutiva en la junta del Concejo de la Ciudad, dijo el alcalde de Tucson, Jonathan Rothschild.\par \par \uc2 Villasenor juro reforzar la ley "que ha aprobado la Corte Suprema", pero dijo que su departamento esta esperando para ver que pasa cuando la ley se mande de vuelta a la juez Superior de Distrito, Susan Bolton.\par \par \uc2 "Hasta que eso ocurra, nosotros vamos a continuar con nuestras politicas actuales", dijo Villasenor. "?Cuando tomara lugar eso? No lo se".\par \par \uc2 Dupnik dijo el Lunes 25 por la tarde que no sabra con seguridad como el fallo de la Corte Suprema afectara al departamento hasta que los abogados del condado examinen la decision.\par \par \uc2 Pero aun sin recibir direccion, Dupnik considero que el fallo no afectara la forma en que sus comisarios realizaran sus patrullajes. El Alguacil, quien se opuso radicalmente a la SB 1070 cuando se introdujo en el 2010, dijo que el departamento ya esta reforzando la politica migratoria federal al referirle a la Patrulla Fronteriza a quienes sospechan que estan aqui ilegalmente.\par \par \uc2 El departamento tambien trabaja estrechamente con los agentes de la Patrulla Fronteriza asignados a la unidad Border Crimes (Crimenes Fronterizos) del Departamento.\par \par \uc2 Villasenor reflejo los comentarios de Dupnik, al decir que los oficiales de la Policia de Tucson siempre han podido llamar a la Patrulla Fronteriza si sospechan que un individuo esta aqui ilegalmente, y lo hacen con frecuencia. Los oficiales utilizan su criterio y consideran que tan ocupados estan, entre otros factores, comento.\par \par \uc2 "El problema con la SB 1070 es que nos prohibe usar nuestro criterio", dijo Villasenor.\par \par \uc2 Contacta a Carmen Duarte en cduarte@azstarnet.com o al 573-4104.\par \par \uc2 Contacta a Brady McCombs en bmccombs@azstarnet.com o al 573- 4213.\par \par \uc2 La reportera Veronica Cruz contribuyo a este reportaje.\par \par \uc2 English version\par \par \uc2 Civil rights and immigration advocates were angered by the Supreme Court's ruling Monday that Arizona can require police to check the immigration status of those they stop.\par \par \uc2 The ruling, said speakers, will lead to racial profiling of Hispanics and create fear for illegal immigrants in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 The same day Homeland Security said it will not send its officers to pick up any suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  snared by local police in Arizona unless the person meets the agency's priority criteria.\par \par \uc2 The decision by Homeland Security brings into question whether much will actually change on the ground in Arizona when law officers are finally required, under the surviving provision of SB 1070, to check the immigration status of those they have stopped.\par \par \uc2 Opponents of SB 1070 said they will continue to work to dismantle the controversial law, regardless of the uncertainty created by the Supreme Court's ruling and decision by Homeland Security. Some 50 people joined speakers at an afternoon news conference June 25 at the downtown state building on West Congress Street and North Granada Avenue.\par \par \uc2 "We will continue to work to repeal SB 1070 because it is an unjust law," said Alison Harrington, pastor of Southside Presbyterian Church on Tucson's south side.\par \par \uc2 "This law promotes fear among our community where people are scared to go to the grocery store, church and hospitals.\par \par \uc2 Alma Hernandez, 28, said she understands the fear undocumented immigrants feel.\par \par \uc2 "I am a mother of three children, and I am fighting deportation so I can stay home with my family," explained Hernandez who has lived in Tucson as an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  since she was 8 years old.\par \par \uc2 "My parents moved our family here from Guadalajara for a better life. Tucson is my home. I know no other one," said Hernandez, who is seeking a cancellation of deportation under President Obama's June 15th executive order allowing those brought to the United States illegally as children to remain under certain conditions.\par \par \uc2 Hernandez said on June 2010 a Pima County sheriff's deputy pulled her over while she was driving. She said she was not cited for a traffic violation. Rather the deputy called Border Patrol agents when she could not prove legal residency.\par \par \uc2 She said she was locked up in detention centers for three weeks.\par \par \uc2 Hernandez said she now is a member of Corazon de Tucson, an advocacy group that educates members about their civil rights, and state and federal laws.\par \par \uc2 Pima County Supervisor \uc2 Richard Elias\uc2 , said the "Supreme Court codified the portion of SB 1070 that attacks people's civil liberties and human rights.\par \par \uc2 "... racial profiling is inevitable if the provisions of SB 1070 approved today by the court are enacted."\par \par \uc2 Elias said he will call for community forums so that Sheriff Clarence Dupnik and Tucson police Chief Roberto Villasenor, or their administrators, can discuss what actions will be taken by local law enforcement to comply with the ruling.\par \par \uc2 Tucson City Councilwoman \uc2 Regina Romero\uc2  agreed with Elias about the forums. She said she will call for open discussion with the city attorney and police chief about the law's enforcement and its effects.\par \par \uc2 "I fear that the immigrant population will no longer report crime, and they will distrust police," said Romero. "All the inroads made in the past will be erased. This worries me."\par \par \uc2 Even if local police continue to turn people over to immigration officials, many of them will not be picked up under the guidelines announced just hours after the Supreme Court's ruling, by the \uc2 Department of Homeland Security\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In Arizona, immigration officers have been instructed not to pick up an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  stopped by local police, unless the person is:\par \par \uc2 * A convicted criminal\par \par \uc2 * Someone who has been deported in the past\par \par \uc2 * Or a recent illegal border crosser.\par \par \uc2 Homeland Security will continue to comply with its legal requirement to take phone calls from local law enforcement to verify a person's immigration status, federal officials said.\par \par \uc2 Homeland Security also announced it has revoked task-force agreements it had under a program known as 287(g) with seven Arizona law enforcement agencies, including the \uc2 Arizona Department of Public Safety\uc2  , the Pima County Sheriff's Department and the Pinal County Sheriff's Office.\par \par \uc2 Homeland Security officials say the task forces, in which immigration officers and local police worked together on investigations in the field, are no longer useful in states that have adopted immigration enforcement laws such as SB 1070.\par \par \uc2 The 287(g) program's jail agreements remain in place with eight agencies, including the Pima County Sheriff's Department. In the jail programs, immigration officers work with local police to help screen people booked into the jails.\par \par \uc2 For local law enforcement leaders already trying to make sense of what the Supreme Court's ruling means for them, the Homeland Security directives created even more confusion.\par \par \uc2 Tucson Police Chief Roberto Villasenor, Pima County Sheriff Clarence Dupnik and Santa Cruz County Sheriff Tony Estrada said they plan to reach out to the U.S. Border Patrol to better understand the implications. All three agencies regularly turn over illegal immigrants they encounter during their patrols to the Border Patrol.\par \par \uc2 "We've tried to get in touch with the Border Patrol today, unsuccessfully, to determine exactly what they mean by that," Dupnik said. "If it means what you think it means, that they're not going respond, that puts us in the position of not being able to enforce immigration violations under the federal law."\par \par \uc2 One question that lingers for law enforcement leaders is what they'll be required to do if immigration officers don't come to pick up a person cited for a misdemeanor whom they've verified by phone is here illegally.\par \par \uc2 Villasenor is under the impression his officers will have met the law's requirement if they call immigration officers about the status of a person they suspect may be here illegally. If a Border Patrol can't, or won't, pick the person up, they'll release the person, he said.\par \par \uc2 "It's all going to hinge on Border Patrol or ICE's ability to respond quickly to us," Villasenor said.\par \par \uc2 But there is no uniformity among agencies, or set by the law, as to how long an officer should wait. Tucson police instruct their officers to wait "as long as it takes to accomplish what the original stop was for,"' Villasenor said. Sheriff's deputies in Pima and Santa Cruz counties release a person if Border Patrol doesn't arrive in a reasonable amount of time, said Dupnik and Estrada.\par \par \uc2 With thousands of additional calls that will need to be made by local officers to immigration officers, it's only get going to get more difficult for federal immigration agencies to respond.\par \par \uc2 "I'm not sure that they are set up to accommodate that workload right now," Villasenor said.\par \par \uc2 Even before Homeland Security made its announcements, law enforcement leaders and city attorneys were grappling with how to move forward based on the Supreme Court ruling.\par \par \uc2 The city of Tucson and the Tucson Police Department are reviewing the Supreme Court's ruling and will receive legal advice during an executive session at today's City Council meeting, said Tucson Mayor Jonathan Rothschild.\par \par \uc2 Villasenor vowed to enforce the law "as upheld by the Supreme Court" but said the department is waiting to see what happens when the law is sent back to U.S. District Judge Susan Bolton.\par \par \uc2 "Until that takes place, we are continuing with our policies as is," Villasenor said. "What the timeline for that will be, I don't know."\par \par \uc2 Dupnik said Monday afternoon he won't know for sure how the Supreme Court's ruling affects the department until county attorneys examine the decision.\par \par \uc2 But, even without that guidance, Dupnik said the ruling will have no bearing on how his deputies go about their patrols. The sheriff, who vehemently opposed SB 1070 when it was introduced in 2010, said the department already enforces federal immigration law by referring people it suspects are here illegally to the Border Patrol. The department also works closely with Border Patrol agents assigned to the department's Border Crimes Unit.\par \par \uc2 Villasenor echoed Dupnik's remarks, saying Tucson police officers have always been able to call the Border Patrol if they suspect a person is here illegally and do so regularly. Offi