eys examine the decision.\par \par \uc2 But, even without that guidance, Dupnik said the ruling will have no bearing on how his deputies go about their patrols. The sheriff, who vehemently opposed SB 1070 when it was introduced in 2010, said the department already enforces federal immigration law by referring people it suspects are here illegally to the Border Patrol. The department also works closely with Border Patrol agents assigned to the department's Border Crimes Unit.\par \par \uc2 Villasenor echoed Dupnik's remarks, saying Tucson police officers have always been able to call the Border Patrol if they suspect a person is here illegally and do so regularly. Officers use their discretion based on how busy they are and other factors, he said.\par \par \uc2 "The problem with SB 1070 is that it takes away that discretion," Villasenor said.\par \par \uc2 Star Reporter Veronica Cruz contributed to this story. Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120713e86q0000r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc92}{\*\bkmkend toc92}\b \uc2 Upset immigration advocates to work on repeal of SB 1070\b0\par\par\uc2 CARMEN DUARTE   \par \uc2 CARMEN DUARTE, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 533 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 June 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Ruling will result in racial profiling of Hispanics, they say\par \par \uc2 Civil rights and immigration advocates were angered by the Supreme Court's ruling Monday that Arizona can require police to check the immigration status of those they stop.\par \par \uc2 The ruling, said speakers, will lead to racial profiling of Hispanics and create fear for illegal immigrants in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Some 50 people joined speakers at an afternoon news conference at the downtown state building on West Congress Street and North Granada Avenue.\par \par \uc2 "We will continue to work to repeal SB 1070 because it is an unjust law," said Alison Harrington, pastor of Southside Presbyterian Church on Tucson's south side.\par \par \uc2 "This law promotes fear among our community where people are scared to go to the grocery store, church and hospitals.\par \par \uc2 "Our doors and our hearts are open to you. We will serve the people of this community regardless of their immigration status," said Harrington, who ministers at a church that was in the forefront of the nationwide underground Sanctuary Movement for Central Americans in the 1980s.\par \par \uc2 Alma Hernandez, 28, said she understands the fear undocumented immigrants feel.\par \par \uc2 "I am a mother of three children, and I am fighting deportation so I can stay home with my family," explained Hernandez who has lived in Tucson as an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  since she was 8 years old.\par \par \uc2 "My parents moved our family here from Guadalajara for a better life. Tucson is my home. I know no other one," said Hernandez, who is seeking a cancellation of deportation under President Obama's recent executive order allowing those brought to the United States illegally as children to remain under certain conditions.\par \par \uc2 Hernandez said in June 2010 a Pima County sheriff's deputy pulled her over while she was driving. She said she was not cited for a traffic violation. Rather the deputy called Border Patrol agents when she could not prove legal residency.\par \par \uc2 She said she was locked up in detention centers for three weeks.\par \par \uc2 Hernandez said she now is a member of Corazon de Tucson, or Heart of Tucson, an advocacy group that educates members about their civil rights and state and federal laws.\par \par \uc2 Pima County Supervisor Richard Elias, said the "Supreme Court codified the portion of SB 1070 that attacks people's civil liberties and human rights. ... Racial profiling is inevitable if the provisions of SB 1070 approved today by the court are enacted."\par \par \uc2 Elias said he will call for community forums so that Sheriff Clarence Dupnik and Tucson Police Chief Roberto Villasenor, or their administrators, can discuss what actions will be taken by local law enforcement to comply with the ruling.\par \par \uc2 Tucson City Councilwoman Regina Romero agreed with Elias about the forums. She said she will call today for open discussion with the city attorney and police chief about the law's enforcement and its effects.\par \par \uc2 "I fear that the immigrant population will no longer report crime, and they will distrust police," said Romero. "All the inroads made in the past will be erased. This worries me."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Carmen Duarte at 573-4104 or cduarte@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020120713e86q0000q\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc93}{\*\bkmkend toc93}\b \uc2 Rothschild joins call to give in-state tuition to crossers Rothschild says crossers merit in-state tuition\b0\par\par\uc2 DARREN DARONCO   \par \uc2 DARREN DARONCO, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 422 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 June 2012\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 President Obama wasn't the only politician passing resolutions over the status of illegal immigrants this week.\par \par \uc2 While politicians battle over the DREAM Act in Washington, D.C., Mayor Jonathan Rothschild says students across the country are suffering.\par \par \uc2 So he is joining other mayors from around the nation in petitioning the federal government to temporarily allow \uc2 illegal- immigrant\uc2  students to qualify for in-state tuition and other benefits until the act is passed.\par \par \uc2 Rothschild, along with Phoenix Mayor Greg